<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITERARY-LEGEND:MONIF     12-11 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITERARY-LEGEND:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH OF JUBILEE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.) 
 By AKILAH MONIFA 
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa, African American, is a freelance writer and
journalist living in Oakland, Calif. She is a contributor to the
forthcoming book ``Seductions of Justice: Lesbian Legal Theories
and Practices.'' (1999) Routledge Press.)
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    To the very end, Margaret Walker Alexander believed her book
``Jubilee'' was the main source of material for Alex Haley's
acclaimed work ``Roots.''
 &HT;    Although she sued Haley for copyright infringement, the courts
dismissed her lawsuit. She died Nov. 30, at the age of 83,
unrequited.
 &HT;    Walker was born in Birmingham, Alabama and she and her family
went to live in New Orleans when she was 10. She moved to Chicago
in 1932 to complete her undergraduate education. While in Chicago
she became a member of the South Side Writers' Group initiated by
Richard Wright. Walker was later to address Richard Wright as the
`Daemonic Genius.'
 &HT;    She first came to literary attention with the publication of her
poem, ``For My People'' in 1942. It marked the first poetry
publication by an African American woman in 24 years.
 &HT;    Walker married Firnist Alexander in 1943 and gave birth to and
raised three children. In 1949, she and her family moved to
Mississippi.
 &HT;    From 1955 to 1962 Walker published nothing, and some of her more
cynical `friends' suggested she wasn't even a has-been, but only a
might-have-been. But Walker carried on. In Mississippi she had a
full time teaching position at Jackson State University where she
established the Institute for the Study of Black Life and Culture,
the first in the south. With the exception of four years _ three of
the Writers' Project and a one year sabbatical from teaching _
Walker wrote and was published while working full time and raising
a family. She published eight more books after completing
``Jubilee.''
 &HT;    But it was ``Jubilee,'' published in 1966, that put Walker on
the literary map. A historical fiction novel, it was loosely based
on her own `roots.'
 &HT;    ``Jubilee'' told the story of the daughter of a slave and a
white plantation owner. The New York Times Book Review said it
``chronicled the triumph of a free spirit over many kinds of
bondage.'' Walker acknowledged that it was based on the lives of
her grandmother and great-grandmother.
 &HT;    She alleged, albeit unsuccessfully that Haley had copied
voluminously from her book, and sued him for plagiarism _ with
disheartening results. Her law suit was dismissed. Haley only
conceded he admired Walker but claimed he had never read her book.
Despite what the courts ruled, Walker was convinced that ``Roots''
would not have been Roots if not for ``Jubilee.''
 &HT;    She was overshadowed in life and death not only by Haley but by
the more renowned Mississippian, William Faulkner. She critiqued
Faulkner especially about race.
 &HT;    Maryemma Graham, the editor of Walker's ``How I Wrote `Jubilee'
and Other Essays on Life and Literature'' noted that despite ``the
abundance of talent emerging from the South, no black writer has
ever achieved recognition by remaining there. Richard Wright is
identified with Chicago, New York, and Paris, and certainly not
with Mississippi or Tennessee. Ernest Gaines writes about Louisiana
exclusively, but it is California that claims him. The story is the
same with modern and contemporary black writers from Ralph Ellison
to Toni Morrison. Thus, in addition to being victimized by the
critical neglect that has affected black writing historically until
very recently, Walker seems to have suffered because of her
conscious decision to live as a black woman artist in the
20th-century South.''
 &HT;    I met Walker in the late 1970s at the State University of New
York at Binghamton. She was lecturing and was one of the first
literary personalities I had met. I was barely 20 years old and in
total awe.
 &HT;    Walker was a literary giant but also very real and approachable.
After her lecture she greeted everyone with a hug. She reminded me
of a grandmother to dream of.
 &HT;    Perhaps her death will spark new interest in her writings.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Akilah Monifa 
