<HEADER>
A4458 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTO-RICO:STATEHOOD     12-11 1837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-RICO:STATEHOOD-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICO AND THE ECONOMICS OF STATEHOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``f''
financial and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By VIVIENNE HEINES 
 c. 1998 Hispanic Business 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Business is booming for homebuilder Ivar Pietri in his native
Puerto Rico, and the prospect of the island becoming the 51st state
of the union lends an even rosier glow to the Caribbean landscape.
 &HT;    ``Statehood would have a dramatic positive impact. Absolutely,''
says Pietri. ``Among the most important things when it comes to
economic development is certainty. And by its very nature, our
present political status is a transitory one. Statehood would give
the island certainty and full integration into the most prosperous
economy in the world.''
 &HT;    In the past five years, Puerto Rico's economy has been growing
slowly and construction has experienced a boom thanks in part to a
number of government initiatives. The number of people employed in
the island's construction industry has risen from 55,000 in 1992 to
71,000 in 1997, and the total value of construction projects
doubled in the same time period _ from $2.5 billion in 1992 to $5
billion in 1997, according to figures from the Puerto Rico Planning
Board.
 &HT;    Pietri, president of Peregrine Development Co. and a former
investment banker with the New York-based Lehman Brothers, is not
alone in his belief that statehood would only enhance the island's
growth.
 &HT;    In March, the U.S. House of Representatives voted 209-208 to set
Puerto Rican self-determination in motion. The 10-year process
would begin with the Dec. 13 referendum that offers Puerto Ricans
the choice of four options: statehood; independence; independence
with a vaguely defined ``free association'' with the United States;
or continuing their unusual commonwealth status. However, that bill
is currently held up in the Senate.
 &HT;    The Dec. 13 referendum is non-binding: Puerto Ricans' decision
on the future status of the island must receive the approval of the
U.S. Congress.
 &HT;    Supporters of statehood say the time is ripe because of several
factors, among them, the support of prostatehood Gov. Pedro
Rossello, who is calling for an end to the island's existence as
``a disenfranchised ghetto.''
 &HT;    Puerto Rico, located in the northern Caribbean about 1,000 miles
southeast of Miami, is about the same size as Connecticut (3,492
square miles). It has a population of 3.7 million, approximately
equal to that of Kentucky. Nearly half a million residents live in
its capital, San Juan. The climate is temperate, with an average of
75 degrees in the winter and 81 in the fall.
 &HT;    The main industry is manufacturing (41.5 percent of Puerto
Rico's gross domestic product), followed by service (38.2 percent)
and government (10.4 percent).
 &HT;    The island also has a strong and thriving entrepreneurial class
of local business owners, says Pietri. In addition, most of the
multinational corporations hire Puerto Rican managers to head up
their operations on the island.
 &HT;    If the island's residents choose statehood, then the issue will
come before the U.S. House of Representatives and the U.S. Senate,
where two bills are currently pending.
 &HT;    Under the commonwealth agreement worked out in 1952, Puerto
Rico's residents are U.S. citizens and eligible for limited federal
aid, but they cannot vote for president unless they live on the
mainland and their sole representative in Congress, Carlos Romero
Barcelo, has no vote.
 &HT;    Jaime Morgan-Stubbe, executive director of the Puerto Rico
Industrial Development Co., says doubters should look to the past
if they want to see how statehood would affect Puerto Rico's
business climate. Morgan-Stubbe's job includes stimulating
investment and creating jobs in Puerto Rico, tasks that he says
will become easier if the island becomes a state.
 &HT;    ``Historically, none of the states were worse off after they
became states and gained economic integration into the union,'' he
says. ``Based on history alone, what we expect is a more profitable
economic environment _ without affecting the ability of Puerto Rico
to compete for investment and jobs.'' Gov. Pedro Rosello's push for
statehood pits local patriotism againt the convenience and
prosperity offered by the United States. It also confronts
Americans with the prospect of a U.S. state _ the 26th largest in
the nation _ where the predominant language is Spanish and the
people consider themselves a distinct nation.
 &HT;    Business owners have a lot at stake. Puerto Rico has long been a
haven for corporations seeking the benefits of the island's
tax-exempt status, and many Fortune 500 entities such as General
Electric, Intel Corp., Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., HewlettPackard Co.
and Sara Lee Corp. are long-established in Puerto Rico.
 &HT;    Changes have already been implemented. In 1996, Congress ended
Section 936, the income tax exemption for U.S. companies operating
in Puerto Rico. Section 936 offered those companies an income-based
tax credit and a wage-based tax credit. About 550 companies
operated under Section 936, employing more than 110,000 workers and
saving an estimated $3 billion annually, according to the Institute
for Puerto Rican Policy in New York.
 &HT;    Those tax credit benefits will be phased out over a 10-year
period, and some predict many corporations will abandon ship,
draining bank deposits and contributing further to the island's 14
percent unemployment rate.
 &HT;    Morgan-Stubbe says that hasn't happened, nor does he expect it
to. The government this year launched a series of economic
incentives to foster investment and development in Puerto Rico. The
1998 tax package includes a flat corporate income tax of between 2
percent and 7 percent, a 200 percent deduction for research and
development and job training, a special deduction for investment in
buildings, machinery, and equipment, and a 90 percent exemption on
property taxes. The package, Morgan-Stubbe says, makes Puerto Rico
even better than Singapore for manufacturing companies.
 &HT;    Jose Villamil, president of Estudio Tecnicos in San Juan, Puerto
Rico, says that the issue is not whether Puerto Rico becomes a
state; it is how the island navigates the transition to a new and
different status.
 &HT;    ``Puerto Rico is dealing with many things that have impacted its
economic development. But I don't think the statehood discussion
has had any impact at this time,'' he says.
 &HT;    Puerto Rico voters have faced the question of statehood before
(in 1967 and 1993) and turned it down. Villamil, however, predicts
that statehood will win this time and ticks off the reasons.
 &HT;    ``One, the opposition is disorganized with basically no
leadership. Second, the pro-statehood government has a huge amount
of resources and they're well organized. Third, the governor is a
pretty popular guy,'' Villamil says.
 &HT;    He adds, ``Becoming a state would probably take anywhere from 10
to 15 years and we would have to map out what those years would
look like.'' Villamil says that the key to Puerto Rico's economic
prosperity lies not with which path its voters choose, but with the
process of change.
 &HT;    ``Basically, the (possible) political statuses are equally
viable in the long run. But what we need to do very much is
negotiate the transition from what we have now to whatever the
alternative status would be. Negotiating the transition is the real
challenge,'' he says.
 &HT;    Those who favor statehood disagree, saying that statehood would
bring a wealth of economic opportunities to the island.
 &HT;    ``The fact alone of Puerto Rico becoming a state will attract a
lot of interest from the mainland,'' says Morgan-Stubbe.
``Statehood would do away with misunderstandings about the
(island's) actual political standing ... and would foster a more
stable climate in the minds of most business people.''
 &HT;    Currently, the island of Puerto Rico is a commonwealth, a local
self-governing territory under the U.S. Constitution. Its
government contains executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
General elections are held every four years; its residents have
been statutory U.S. citizens since 1917.
 &HT;    Commonwealth supporters say that the current arrangement is ``Lo
Mejor de Dos Mundos'' (The Best of Both Worlds). However, Puerto
Ricans have no voting representation in Congress and can't vote for
president. They receive lower levels of federal benefits, such as
welfare and Medicaid, but pay no federal income taxes. And their
future U.S. citizenship and nationality is not guaranteed.
 &HT;    Analysts say that the issue of federal income tax is key to the
upcoming referendum and approval by U.S. leaders of Puerto Rico's
statehood. David Lewis, deputy executive director of Caribbean
Latin-American Action, says an issue for American political leaders
is how Puerto Rico would fit with the other 50 states. Largely
Spanish-speaking, it has a per capita income of $8,000 annually.
That's half of the nation's poorest state, Mississippi, and a
fourth of the average U.S. per capita income.
 &HT;    In addition, Puerto Rico as a state would have two senators and
seven representatives in Washington, D.C.
 &HT;    ``That's more representation than many states have now. It would
also be eligible for more U.S. aid,'' Lewis said. ``For some,
that's a reason to have statehood; for others, it's a reason to
oppose it.''
 &HT;    Pietri believes that statehood would ``unleash tremendous
productive forces in Puerto Rico.''
 &HT;    ``We have tremendous competitive advantages in Puerto Rico. We
have a bilingual environment, a bicultural environment, a large and
trainable work force, a long affiliation with the United States ...
you take those conditions and you put them together with the
political power, the certainty and the full integration into the
U.S. economy.''
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Hispanic Business 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
