<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (These ``separate buy'' articles from this week's New America News
Service moved today.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish a NEWAM article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448; fax: 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RETIRED, BUT NOT FROM WORK. St. Petersburg, Fla., notes
columnist Bill Maxwell, is still sometimes known as the city where
old people go to die _ in droves. But 79-year-old William Dixon
Southworth disputes this notion. ``I don't mind my age at all,'' he
told Maxwell. ``The thought of being a teenager again _ being young
again _ is something that not only is impossible but it's
unattractive. I like my age. I have a good marriage. I'm healthy.
All of my vital organs are good. I'm enjoying life and loving God.
I get along with people, and I get along with myself.'' And, though
retired, he has not stopped working. Maxwell tells the remarkable
story of how he published his first novel.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-RETIRED-ACTIVELY:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTIONS AND AFFAIRMATIVE ACTION: THE PLAYING FIELD IS UNEVEN.
While everyone knows the results of recent national elections,
writes columnist Tim Giago, what about those in Indian country?
``Selection of leaders by a democratic vote in the Indian nations
of America will have a profound impact,'' he says, ``and new
leadership in the Apache, Navajo, and Lakota nations, for examble,
will hopefully change the course of recent difficult times.'' But
Indians in the Northwest, he adds, worry how Washington state's new
legislation to stop affirmative action will affect them in higher
education and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-INDIAN-ELECTIONS:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   THE CONSTITUTION AS A SHIELD AGAINST THE MANY. Why did
California do a such a thing as pass a law making English the
official language of California, wonders columnist Raoul Lowery
Contreras. ``English is not `officially' the language of the United
States and there is no mention of that in the Constitution,'' he
writes. Yet, a majority of white and black citizens in California
voted to force an official language on all Californians. ``They
must have forgotten the words in the Constitution about not
abridging free speech,'' he adds. He hasn't, he declares, and he
will defend that argument in English _ and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-SPANISH:FREE-SPEECH:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH OF JUBILEE. To the very end, Margaret Walker Alexander
believed her book ``Jubilee'' was the main source of material for
Alex Haley's acclaimed work ``Roots.'' Although she sued Haley for
copyright infringement, the courts dismissed her lawsuit. She died
Nov. 30, at the age of 83, unrequited. Columnist Akilah Monifa
remembers Walker, the writer of ``For My People'' in 1942 _ the
first poetry publication by an African American woman in 24 years _
as well as ``Jubilee,'' 20 years later, about her own `roots' _ the
story of the daughter of a slave and a white plantation owner, and
based on the lives of her grandmother and greatgrandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-LITERARY-LEGEND:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTO RICO AND THE ECONOMICS OF STATEHOOD. On Dec. 13, Puerto
Ricans will decide the future of their island. It will be the third
time they will vote on the issue of statehood since 1967.
``Statehood would have a dramatic, positive impact,'' builder Ivar
Pietri told Vivienne Heines of HISPANIC BUSINESS magazine. ``Among
the most important things when it comes to economic development is
certainty. And by its very nature, our present political status is
a transitory one. Statehood would give the island certainty and
full integration into the most prosperous economy in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-PUERTO-RICO:STATEHOOD-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``f'' financial file.
</P>
