<SLUG> BC-PARAMOUNT-PAYOFF-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAMOUNT SCALING NEW HEIGHTS WITH BILLION-DOLLAR BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: ``Today'' in story is Friday, Dec. 11.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ No studio is hotter than Paramount, right now, and
the company that brought the ``Star Trek'' and ``Godfather'' series
to movie screens can thank an unsinkable boat and a bunch of
toddlers for its success.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount passed the $1 billion mark in domestic box office last
week, becoming only the third studio in Hollywood history to
achieve the milestone in one calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' delivered close to half of that total _ $443.2
million, to be exact _ while other key contributors were ``Deep
Impact,'' ``The Truman Show,'' ``The Rugrats Movie'' and ``Snake
Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney and Sony are the only other studios to crack the
billion-dollar barrier, according to box office tracker Exhibitor
Relations Co. And Paramount films likely will add an additional
$100million to $150million during the year's last four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Its ``Rugrats'' has been a surprise hit and ``Star Trek:
Insurrection,'' which opens today in 2,620 theaters, should perform
solidly if the studio's eight other ``Star Trek'' films are any
guide.
</P>
<P>
   If Paramount's final total for the year hits $1.15 billion, it
will represent an impressive gain of 51 percent over 1997's $761
million total, which included $157.5 million from the first 13 days
of ``Titanic.'' What's particularly notable is that Paramount has
only released 11 movies so far this year, with five of those _
including ``Twilight,'' ``Hard Rain'' and ``The Odd Couple II'' _
grossing under $20 million each.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been amazing how well Paramount has done,'' said Paul
Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor Relations Co., which
estimates the studio has achieved a 16.21 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
   This year will be the first in which two studios top the $1
billion mark. Disney crossed the $986 million mark Monday and could
take in as much as $150 million more by the end of the year if ``A
Bug's Life,'' ``Enemy of the State,'' ``The Waterboy'' and two
entries due out Dec. 25 _ ``Mighty Joe Young'' and ``A Civil
Action'' _ perform at the high end of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   So despite currently trailing Paramount by nearly $50 million,
Disney conceivably still could finish in first place for the fourth
time in five years. Either way, this year has solidified Disney's
status as Hollywood's most reliable performer. It topped $1 billion
in 1994, 1995 and 1996 before falling to $880 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Paramount is the surprise story as Hollywood's hottest
studio. In fact, Paramount easily would have broken Sony's record
$1.26 billion, set last year, if it had kept domestic rights to
``Saving Private Ryan,'' which grossed $190 million in the United
States and more than $200 million overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But, as with many of its high-profile projects, Paramount split
the financing. For ``Saving Private Ryan,'' a deal was struck with
DreamWorks SKG, giving Steven Spielberg's studio the domestic
distribution while Paramount retained foreign rights.
</P>
<P>
   In the best-known example of co-financing, Paramount invested
$65 million in ``Titanic'' in exchange for an estimated 40 percent
of the profits. 20th Century Fox picked up the rest of the $200
million cost and handled distribution overseas, where grosses
topped $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount, under ownership by Viacom Inc. since 1994, has become
the most aggressive of Hollywood's seven major studios in pursuing
the sharing production costs. During 1998, it handled domestic
distribution on two co-produced projects _ ``Deep Impact'' with
DreamWorks and ``Snake Eyes'' with Disney _ and it split costs with
Disney on ``A Civil Action'' and will handle overseas distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Dergarabedian said such co-financing deals are becoming
increasingly popular as a way to deal effectively with soaring
production and marketing expenses. ``As costs rise, studios will
look to risk-sharing so the impact of a picture that doesn't
perform is not so devastating,'' he added. ``It's proven to be a
good business decision because these are such enormous
undertakings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Association of America estimated last year
that the average cost to make and market a movie had reached $75.6
million, up 30 percent from 1996. ``You're going to see more and
more co-financing,'' Dergarabedian promised.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street likes the practice, according to Prudential
Securities analyst Kathy Styponias. ``Co-financing does limit the
upside, but as (an) analyst I like to see it because the movie
business is so unpredictable,'' she said. ``It worked out pretty
well on `Titanic' and I think we'll see more of it. It's a function
of costs escalating, so I don't see what choice the studios have.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Cesinger, an analyst with investment bank Grief &AMP; Co.,
noted that co-financing prevents the major studios from creating a
glut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios are tired of driving prices into the
stratosphere,'' Cesinger said. ``With co-financing, you increase
the quality of your slate and decrease the competitive frenzy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
