<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HIT ROADBLOCK IN PITCHING SEARCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ As baseball's winter meetings begin today in
Nashville, the Angels' search for a No.1 starter has hit a road
block. Randy Johnson is signed in Arizona and the possibility of
landing Kevin Brown or Roger Clemens is becoming more and more
remote.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a free agent seeking a six-year deal worth about $80
million, spoke with the Angels and Dodgers this week, but he is
believed to be favoring the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who has asked the Blue Jays to trade him, is likely
headed to the Indians or Rockies, though Blue Jays general manager
Gord Ash won't specify what team is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an offer from a club that from a player point of view
satisfies our needs,'' Ash said. ``What I've suggested to that club
is that they get guidance from Roger's representatives on how they
should proceed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, Astros and Rangers had been the top contenders for
Clemens, but Ash implied that the ``mystery club'' wasn't one of
them and would need Clemens' approval to trade for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what I'm directing that club to do is make sure they
qualify,'' Ash said. ``They had a lot of questions for me that I
couldn't answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have a surplus of outfielders that can be used to
acquire a starting pitcher in a trade, but it seems unlikely that
any team would be willing to give up a No.1 starter.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Angels trying to trade for a No.3-type starter,
or signing an available free agent. Among the free agents available
are Tim Belcher, Doug Drabek, Jimmy Key, Steve Avery, Ricky Bones,
Orel Hershiser and even Jim Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' policy is to not discuss the players they are
targeting, although it is certain they have made contingency plans
in the event they do not land Brown or Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   With the recent addition of Mo Vaughn, the Angels lineup looks
good. But the starting pitching is a concern because their top two
starters are Chuck Finley, who is 36, and Ken Hill, who is coming
off elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Knuckleballer Steve Sparks is coming off a surprisingly
productive season, but Allen Watson is not expected to be offered
arbitration and would be let go. Jarrod Washburn and Jason Dickson,
provided they are not traded, are expected to compete for starting
spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last two weeks are why I never want to become a general
manager,'' said Angels manager Terry Collins. ``(Angels general
manager) Billy (Bavasi) has put some time in. We're going to try to
get better, but it's not easy. There are not a lot of options right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, an Angel since 1986, says the signing of Vaughn leaves
the Angels with no option other than getting pitching help, however
they have to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to put someone like Mo Vaughn out there, you'd
better make sure his RBIs hold up for you,'' Finley said. ``You
don't try to fill holes by putting Double-A and Triple-A guys out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean Finley would endorse a trade of one of the
outfielders?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only nine spots out there to play,'' he said. ``It's
getting a little crowded out there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
