<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STERN: LEAGUE WANTS DEAL, NOT BROKEN UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ From his Manhattan office on a brisk December day, NBA
commissioner David Stern is watching a horror flick.
</P>
<P>
   The silence of not playing NBA games because of a labor impasse
is screeching in the din of constant lockout lingo. In the backdrop
is a ``drop-dead'' date to cancel the season, which indicates that
this grim picture might soon earn the title of ``The Lost Season.''
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview with the Post-Intelligencer
Thursday, Stern hinted that this will be the last collective
bargaining agreement he will mediate as commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledged that it will be virtually impossible to put
together a season if there is no agreement when the calendar turns
to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And Stern said he recognizes that the NBA will be ``mortally
wounded'' if the 1998-99 season does not commence at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' Stern said, ``but I'm not making any ultimatums.
... We'll get the owners together at the appropriate time and ask
them what they want to do. We're starting to think about that now.
I don't mean to say it's tomorrow, but it certainly is looming.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take a little more than a monh to get the league up and
running again whenever a deal is done.
</P>
<P>
   Stern does not know when he will negotiate with the players'
union again. Talks have been on-again and off-again _ mostly off _
this month. His relationship with the players is more strained than
it has ever been, but he disputes the notion he is attempting to
break their union.
</P>
<P>
   The intention, says Stern, is to strike a deal with this union
leadership so that both sides can continue to prosper long after
his reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal has to be long enough so that the person negotiating
its successor is my successor,'' Stern said. ``If it's a six-year
deal, it could very well be (my last). I would like to leave the
league in good shape. That's why I'm leading this negotiating
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern remains miffed that player agents appear to carry great
influence over the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something holding our players back, and that is
they're being told by their experts that they don't want to make a
deal that's too good for the owners,'' Stern said. ``In other
words, they're not saying, `Is this a good deal for the players?'
What they're saying is this conceivably could be too good a deal
for the owners. And the owners are saying, `Show us.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The players have been told, `Stern said this isn't his last
offer so therefore he's got another offer. He's hiding from us.' I
don't know what that offer is. ... The owners' views have to be
softened and the players' views have to be softened, then a deal
has to emerge. That's the way it's always worked. It's just not
working this time.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the squabble over percentages and basketball-related
income (BRI), it is clear that the labor dispute is a power
struggle that has been derailed by blanket mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of whether the basketball-related income that is
divided among the owners and players is calculated fairly, Stern
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``When they said let's reconstitute the BRI, we said that's
easy. Let's do it. That was weeks ago,'' Stern said, adding that
the ``mistrust issue is one that has been utilized by those who are
exhorting the players so that they can keep them unified under the
certainty that the owners would yield. We trust the players and
it's become convenient for them to say they don't trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the league's assertion that teams are losing money is
correct, Stern is adamant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players have the books. Their own expert says the trend is
down,'' he said. ``I say call Charles Bennett (a forensic
accountant who works for the players). Ask him whatever you want to
ask him. I have a great deal of confidence in his assessment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett told the P-I last month that he was comfortable with the
BRI figures as compiled by the owners.
</P>
<P>
   The league contends that close to 10 teams received revenue
assistance last year. The most handed out was $2.9 million,
according to deputy commissioner Russ Granik.
</P>
<P>
   The players' argument is that the issue of financial losses does
not account for what they see as mismanagement prevalent in certain
franchises. They cite the Milwaukee Bucks _ and owner Herb Kohl _
as an example.
</P>
<P>
   His payroll was roughly $25 million last season. Kohl, who is
worth an estimated $200 million, is reportedly paying three
coaches. Former Sonic coach George Karl was recently hired for $20
million over four years. His predecessors, Chris Ford and Mike
Dunleavy, were fired before their contracts ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owners are obviously taking money out of their pockets to
subsidize their teams,'' Stern said. ``But collective bargaining is
where you stop that. Is the question whether Herb Kohl can afford
to lose a couple of million dollars a year? Sure. But this is where
you get the chance to say, `I don't want to do it anymore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The owners reopened the collective bargaining agreement after
player salaries accounted for 57 percent of basketball-related
income. Despite the fact that league revenue has quadrupled since
1984, Stern's analogy is that now whenever the league generates $2,
the players are making $4.
</P>
<P>
   The owners' latest proposal is a seven-year structured plan in
which the average salary is projected to go from $3 million to $4.9
million. The percentage of BRI devoted to salaries would start at
57 percent for the 1998-99 season and curtail to 53.5 percent in
2004-05, with a low of 52 in the middle year of the deal. The
players want a 60-percent cut and an open-ended pay scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always leeway. But there are so many different issues,
there has to be some trading going on,'' Stern said. ``When we say
that, they say we're holding back an offer. The only way the two
parties can get together is to say we really need this but we're
prepared to give a little on that. But you need to do this and
we'll do that. That's the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   There is just this one major snag: Nothing is going on right
now. This is the 164th day of the lockout. There is no end in
sight, and Stern remains firm in his seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players will lose in excess of a billion dollars if the
season is canceled. They're telling us that they're willing to give
that up so the owners can't make another 50 or 60 or 70 million a
year?'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never asked them to take less absolute dollars. We've
always assured them salaries would grow. We just wanted to adjust
the percentage. If we have a fundamental economic model that works,
the amount of money that we and the players can make collectively
is so much larger than the amount we're fighting about, it's
frightening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
