</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-NEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS UP TO CHALLENGE OF DETHRONING CAMPAS  
 OPEN-AND-SHUT TYSON  
 HAMED AND INGLE SPLIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Nev., N.J., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By TIMOTHY SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fernando Vargas will be the second member of the 1996 U.S.
Olympic boxing team to go for a world championship when he faces
Yory Boy Campas, the International Boxing Federation junior
middleweight champion, Saturday night at the Trump Taj Mahal in
Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question is whether this fight is too big a step for
Vargas. Yes, Vargas is the No. 1 contender; yes, he is 14-0 and has
knocked out all of his opponents. But he will be giving away 59
fights worth of experience to Campas (71-2).
</P>
<P>
   The bout will be the co-feature with the rematch of two
lightweights, Arturo Gatti and Ivan Robinson, to be broadcast on
HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas is not worried about being in over his head. ``It's not
about having 50 or 60 fights to be a great fighter,'' he said.
``Yory Boy Campas is there to be taken. I feel like I'm the man to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Campas' only two losses in his career have been against Felix
Trinidad and Jose Luis Lopez _ two tough welterweights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Trinidad, I lost because I went into the bout with a
fractured nose,'' Campas said. ``Against Lopez, I had to lose six
to seven pounds in the final days to make weight. By fight time, I
had nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Diaz, Campas' trainer, said Campas is comfortable now
that he has moved up to 154 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in better shape than he was when he won the title against
Raul Marquez,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   OPEN-AND-SHUT TYSON
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson was more unbridled in his opinions in two interviews
he had in Phoenix on Monday than he was during his Los Angeles news
conference Tuesday to announce his fight against Francois Botha on
Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference Tuesday, Tyson would not address the
prospect of his probation being revoked and his having to return to
prison in Indiana, except to make a quick joke about it. But in
interviews on Monday, Tyson said he is not afraid to return to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went back to prison, it wouldn't be because I violated
anyone,'' Tyson said. ``I didn't do anything to go back. If they
send me back to prison, I can handle it. I'm not a wimp. I'm no
chump. I'm not afraid of anything, except God.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has apologized to Evander Holyfield for biting his ears
during their bout on June 28, 1997. But after his workout on
Monday, Tyson wasn't so conciliatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was butting me,'' Tyson said. ``Yeah, I bit his ears. He's
lucky I didn't bite his throat. He's a boxer. He knew what he did
was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson thinks the Nevada State Athletic Commission set up a
battery of psychological and psychiatric exams by doctors at
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston hoping that he would fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put me through that test thinking I wasn't going to pass
it,'' Tyson said. ``They probably thought I would blow up during
the hearing, do something crazy and they wouldn't have to give it
to me. One of the doctors told me before the tests that these are
the same tests that they give to astronauts. I'm no astronaut. I'm
an 11th-grade dropout.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson explained his occasional outbursts by saying: ``I don't
think I have any rage. I think I'm like anybody else. I get upset.
I just think I have a different way of showing it.''
</P>
<P>
   HAMED AND INGLE SPLIT
</P>
<P>
   Prince Naseem Hamed, the flamboyant featherweight, has dismissed
his longtime trainer, Brendan Ingle, and is looking for a new
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed dropped Ingle, the only trainer he has had, because Ingle
professed loyalty to the promoter Frank Warren, whom Hamed also
split from. . . . Roy Jones, Jr., will fight Richard Frazier, a New
York City police officer, in Pensacola, Fla., on Jan. 9. Frazier is
the WBC's No. 1 contender for Jones' light heavyweight title and
jumped in front of David Telasco when Jones could not reach a deal
with Telasco. Shane Mosley, the IBF lightweight champion, will be
on the undercard, possibly against Justin Rowsell of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Gil, the manager for Diobelys Hurtado, is protesting
Hurtado's loss to Kostya Tszyu on Nov. 28 to the WBC, because the
bout took place in a 17-foot ring, instead of the contracted
20-foot ring. Gil wants a rematch before Tszyu fights Miguel Angel
Gonzalez. . . . Ron Scott Stevens, a Brooklyn promoter, has joined
Cedric Kushner Promotions as a matchmaker.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
