<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LOCKOUT DISPLAYS LITTLE SHOP OF HORRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Should you or anyone you know become part of the
swirling, snarling mass of shoppers in Manhattan this Christmas
season, here's my handy survival tip:
</P>
<P>
   Find the famed Fifth Avenue shopping district and slip into the
NBA Store at 52nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   It's peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of room. Lots of bored sales personnel. Lots of weird
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Such as a large vase made of Waterford crystal, etched with a
figure of Larry Bird. A fine stocking stuffer for just $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps your taste runs to $150 Hugo Boss shirts, $500 gold
cuff links or $1,800 leather jackets _ all emblazoned with the logo
and icons of an epically dysfunctional industry. In light of
current events, the store felt like a welcome-back party for the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning after the Seahawk game in New Jersey, I wandered
through the quiet store, blinking in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Who would buy this stuff, I wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich foreigners,'' came an answer from nearby.
</P>
<P>
   That was a relief. I was worried there might be an American
sports fan possessed of more credit cards than brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   At almost the same time I was fingering a $300 logo-festooned
sweater, the NBA players, led by agent/viper David Falk, were
making an announcement about a charity game Dec. 19 in Atlantic
City, proceeds from which would go, in part, to benefit their
brethren suffering from the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the worst-off player in the NBA last year made
$272,500, or 36 percent more than the president.
</P>
<P>
   If this were England, the gesture would be equivalent to having
the royal family hold a bake sale to help out the Rolling Stones
between concert tours.
</P>
<P>
   After considering the greedy, preening indulgence of the NBA
Store and the stupendous arrogance of the players with the charity
game, a thought occurred:
</P>
<P>
   I have never seen a sports enterprise so nakedly and publicly
disconnected from its fan base.
</P>
<P>
   And it happened barely more than a decade after the league was
begging for the sporting public's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishing. Absolutely astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   Is the NBA situation worse than the labor problems that have
shut down other pro sports? Yes, because it comes after all the
mistakes made by other leagues and unions, and because there was no
discernible reason for the stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did neither side in the NBA dispute learn from the
disasters of its sports predecessors, there was no obvious evidence
that pro basketball was in serious trouble. In the cases of the
other labor travails, a labor-management imbalance at least could
be argued.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several years, the biggest NBA economic news was
almost always good: Successful expansion, massive globalization,
Olympic glory, full houses and improving ratings, big TV contracts
and widespread acknowledgment as the hippest, hottest mainstream
sport going.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly, Commissioner David Stern stood before the sports
world with his pockets inside out, declared a crisis and shut down
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   While continuing to sign players to unfathomable contracts, the
owners and Stern flat failed to make the public case that the
building was on fire.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, they failed to make believers of the players.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing to market glamorous individuals instead of teams or
the game itself, the NBA created a Frankenstein monster.
</P>
<P>
   The players believe, as the charity fiasco attests, that they
are more important than the game. Surrounded by sycophants,
entourages and the NBA's ravenous marketing machine, the players'
profoundly distorted sense of worth fairly screams.
</P>
<P>
   When Nick Anderson says he may have to sell one of his eight
luxury vehicles to make ends meet, when Gary Payton suggests that
the lockout isn't hurting players as much as fans, when the lockout
``victims'' arrive in stretch limos to union events held only in
Vegas or Atlantic City in order to assure attendance, it's plain
they have no idea how insulting they appear.
</P>
<P>
   They've never been told no in their adult lives. They don't know
how to act.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the negotiating posture: They reduce the economic
issues to a childish pout of macho competitiveness in which they
fear disrespect more than defeat. They allow the negotiations to be
done by ruthless agents who fear for their careers if they either
let down a rich player or allow the NBA to implement a salary scale
that reduces the need for agents.
</P>
<P>
   The belief in entitlement that is corrupting the union position
is a far cry from 1984, when the league and union created a
landmark collective bargaining agreement that was the foundation of
the NBA's remarkable success. The league then was in serious
trouble, made the case clearly to players and agents, who then
joined with the league in an unprecedented partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Half a generation later, the partnership has vanished, players
lost in self-absorption, owners deluded by rapid success.
</P>
<P>
   The season no longer is worth saving. The disconnection is
severe enough to wonder whether the league and its players ever
will be worth bringing back from their parallel universe.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 0028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
