<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT FLYERS IN OVERTIME, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The New Jersey Devils had spent the past few days
wondering where the defensive prowess that had carried them in
recent years had gone. In the opening minutes of Thursday night's
game, little changed as they found themselves in a three-goal hole.
But the Devils' recently discovered offensive prowess came to the
rescue and they posted a dramatic 5-4 overtime victory over the
Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite surrendering 14 goals in their past three games, the
Devils have managed a pair of victories and a tie amid a six-game
unbeaten streak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The decisive goal came 1 minute 18 seconds into overtime when
Dave Andreychuk finally pounded in a rebound after the Devils
pelted four shots at a bewildered Ron Hextall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After surrendering four goals on the first 14 shots by the
Flyers, spanning the first 20:40, Martin Brodeur closed the
revolving door to the Devils' net. He stopped the final 15 shots of
regulation, although a pair of blasts by Eric Lindros hit the post,
and Brodeur was lucky to survive another Lindros slap shot from
just inside the blue line that hit his chest and bounded into his
face, knocking him off his feet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Brodeur finally stopping the Flyers' onslaught, the Devils
rallied from the sizable deficit, tying the score with 7:21
remaining in the third period when Randy McKay stole the puck from
Luke Richardson behind the Flyers' net and slid the puck to Bobby
Holik, who was stopped by Hextall on his first attempt but stuffed
the rebound into the right side of the net. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, just to get into overtime the Devils had to survive a
late flurry that included a bullet by John LeClair, a point-blank
chance by Lindros and then LeClair circling in front of the net as
time expired. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Stevens, who missed Tuesday night's game with the flu,
joined the Devils for the morning skate on Thursday and felt well
enough to take the ice on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But getting their captain back did little to stop the flood of
goals that the Devils have been letting in of late. After
surrendering five goals on Saturday to the Islanders and five more
in the tie with the Flyers on Tuesday, the Devils were pelted for
13 shots and 3 goals in the first period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took a 1-0 lead with a power-play goal by Petr Sykora
just 4:12 into the game on a pretty pass between his legs by Jason
Arnott. But just as they had squandered leads of 3-2 and 5-3 on
Tuesday to the Flyers, they gave this lead up quickly _ 1:04 later.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair slipped a pass from behind the net to Lindros near the
right circle, and Lindros drilled the puck past Brodeur for his
15th goal of the season and sixth against the Devils. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Flyers got a power-play opportunity at 8:16, it took
them just five seconds to take advantage, after winning the
face-off in front of the Devils' net. LeClair took a pass in front
from Eric Desjardins and tried one backhand that was stopped before
he banged in his own rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers added a short-handed goal with 2:54 left in the
period, taking advantage of a lackluster effort by the Devils.
First Arnott fanned on the puck while trying to keep it in along
the boards. Then the Flyers' Rod Brind'Amour beat Vadim
Sharifijanov to the puck as it crossed the blue line into the
Devils' defensive zone, centering the puck to Petr Svoboda, who
outraced Scott Niedermayer to the net and slipped the puck past
Brodeur's glove. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things did not improve immediately for the Devils after the
intermission, with the Flyers getting their fourth goal just 40
seconds into the second period when Lindros beat Lyle Odelin,
flicking a shot into the near side of the net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 0127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
