<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BRYANTAWARD-SNYDE     12-11 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BRYANTAWARD-SNYDER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEAL FARMER  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
There was another high for Kansas State football coach Bill Snyder
in a season of highs and lows after he was announced Thursday as
the recipient of the 1998 Paul ``Bear'' Bryant Coach of the Year
Award at the Westin Galleria.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``They were virtually all highs until the last play of the last
ballgame,'' Snyder said. ``We've been fortunate to work in that
realm.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was honored to take home the hardware during such an
emotional time for him and his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are an awful lot of far better football coaches than I
am in this country,'' said Snyder, who was a Bryant finalist in '93
and '95. ``I've been humbled (to be in Houston) three times for
this award. When you think about Paul `Bear' Bryant, that is
special. Just to be mentioned in the same breath as him is very
dynamic for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had coached better, we would be here with a 12-0 record
instead of 11-1. And we've been 11-1 before, so it is not new. I
think the fact that a lot of very positive things have happened at
Kansas State, and this year just happened to be part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State's 36-33 double-overtime loss to Texas A&AMP;M in the
Big 12 Championship Game on Saturday in St. Louis resulted in the
team not only missing the Bowl Championship Series but the Cotton
and Holiday bowl berths as well. The Wildcats are matched against
Purdue on Dec. 29 in the Alamo Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder had a short answer when asked if winning the Bryant award
would ease the hurt of losing to Texas A&AMP;M and all that it
entailed: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with it, because the wounds I am able
to handle with time,'' Snyder said. ``It has been devastating, I
think, but my concerns are not with me as they are with the
players, the direction they go and how they respond to this. So,
no, this does not soothe those wounds. I am honored by it, but
that's a whole different agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder's record at K-State is 77-38-1 in 10 years, impressive
since the Wildcats lost with regularity in the 1950s through 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of what has taken place and have some positive
feelings for it,'' Snyder said. ``But who I am excited for and
proud of are all those young people who came into our program 10
years ago and had no success whatsoever at Kansas State. They
toiled every bit as much as the young people we have now and didn't
have the opportunity to reap the benefits we have now.''
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists were Tennessee's Phil Fulmer, Tulane's Tommy
Bowden, Ohio State's John Cooper, Arkansas' Houston Nutt and UCLA's
Bob Toledo. The voting was a two-tiered process by the 800-member
National Sportscasters and Sportswriters Association.
</P>
<P>
   Only Snyder came to Houston, as the other schools sent
assistants in the place of their head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the head coaches who were finalists in Houston also were
finalists for the Eddie Robinson Coach of the Year Award ceremony
in Orlando, Fla., and they chose to go to the Florida event
Thursday. Houston organizers said they are not concerned about what
the other coaches did, as this year's banquet was highly
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to raise more than $150,000 _ net _ for the
American Heart Association,'' event chairman Jerel T. Humphrey
said. ``We always like to get as many of the finalists as possible,
but obviously, circumstances being what they may, is difficult. But
people come here to support the American Heart Association. Having
more coaches here is just icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   American Heart Association officials said that coaches who went
to Orlando were asked to sign a contract saying that they would
attend that banquet. No such contract is required in Houston,
according to Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kicked that around,'' Humphrey said. ``Each year we have an
evaluation that we go through and ask what can we do differently?
That is something we have not decided to do. Some of the events
want the coaches to agree to come before they are considered, and
that's not the way we have gone. We felt we wanted the
sportswriters to pick who is the most deserving candidates and we
take it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey said they will explore dates that will not overlap with
other banquets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
