<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4559 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLPLAYOFFS-HNS &LR;      12-11 1838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
 PLAYOFFS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WITH three games remaining in the season, the NFC playoff
picture is not difficult to figure, but it takes a mathematician to
sort through the possibilities in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   If everything goes as expected in the NFC, Minnesota and Atlanta
will get first-round byes. San Francisco will host Green Bay in one
wild-card game. Dallas will entertain the wild-card team with the
worst record.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, Tampa Bay and New Orleans are competing for the last
wild-card spot in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the AFC, take a deep breath. The only thing for certain
is that the undefeated Denver Broncos have earned the home-field
advantage and a first-round bye.
</P>
<P>
   The home advantage in the AFC hasn't meant much in the past
three years. Kansas City blew it in 1996 and 1998. Denver gave it
away in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville has a three-game lead in the AFC Central. If the
Jaguars win the division, as expected, they have the inside track
to getting a first-round bye and a second-round game at home.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a miracle, a big portion of the AFC will have to be
settled with tiebreakers.
</P>
<P>
   The AFC East, the most competitive division in the league, could
send four teams to the playoffs, a feat achieved only once in NFL
history. That happened last year when the NFC Central had Green
Bay, Tampa Bay, Minnesota and Detroit reach postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   Miami and the New York Jets are tied for first place in the AFC
East with 9-4 records. They play at Miami on Sunday night. New
England and Buffalo are 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have made the playoffs once in 11 years. They should
have made it last season, but a bad call in the last game against
Detroit ruined their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's more on the line now for all these teams,''
Jets coach Bill Parcells said. ``We were sitting here six weeks ago
talking about the exact same thing, and not much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our division aside, some of the competition is not in as good
a position as they were in. Certainly, Pittsburgh (7-6) is not in
as good as position, and Tennessee (7-6) and Seattle (6-7) and
Kansas City (5-8). And Oakland (7-6) has certainly had a tough
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, some of the 10 teams we were competing with are in a lot
worse situation than us. That's the good news. The bad news is that
in our division, there's not much separation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos (13-0) are trying to join the 1972 Dolphins as the
only undefeated and untied champion. They are trying to become the
first 19-0 team. Because of their quest for perfection, the Broncos
have remained focused, unlike two years ago when they clinched
home-field advantage early, rested players and were shocked in the
second round by Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of the season, the only teams that might even give
Denver and Minnesota trouble in the playoffs are Jacksonville in
the AFC and Atlanta or possibly San Francisco or Green Bay in the
NFC. Injuries have contributed to the 49ers and Packers
relinquishing their strangleholds on the NFC West and NFC Central
titles.
</P>
<P>
   AFC East
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who are trying to make the playoffs for the first time
since 1991, won the first game against the Dolphins. A victory
Sunday would actually give New York, which has a 4-1 division
record, a two-game lead over Miami because of the head-to-head
tiebreaker. Last season, Parcells' first, the Jets lost three their
last four to finish 9-7 and miss the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' last three games are against the three division teams
competing for the playoffs. After visiting Miami and Buffalo, they
host New England.
</P>
<P>
   If you think the Jets' schedule is tough, check out Miami. The
Dolphins have the best defense in the league, but coach Jimmy
Johnson's conservative style has set offensive football back to the
'50s. After hosting the Jets, they entertain Denver and finish at
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are the hottest team in the division. They have a
three-game winning streak and games at St. Louis and the Jets
sandwiched around a home game against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills have Doug Flutie, the miracle worker, at quarterback
and Eric Moulds, the hottest receiver in the league, to catch his
passes. The Bills host Oakland and the Jets and end at New Orleans.
All of their opponents are competing for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Keys &QC; 
 &UR; Coach &LR; : Jimmy Johnson, Dolphins. No one knows if he will take the
shackles off quarterback Dan Marino or continue to rely too heavily
on the running game and defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Player &LR; : Vinny Testaverde, Jets. A veteran quarterback with a
reputation for inconsistency down the stretch. He hasn't played in
many December games this important.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Question &LR; : Will Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe continue to
play better than any time in his six-year career and continue to
pull out last-minute victories despite a fractured index finger on
his throwing hand?
</P>
<P>
   AFC Central
</P>
<P>
   Barring a monumental collapse, the Jaguars are going to dethrone
the Steelers and win their first title. Pittsburgh's five-year
streak should end. The Jaguars better get a playoff game at home.
The last time they beat a winning team on the road was the 1997
second-round game at Denver, where they pulled the stunning upset.
</P>
<P>
   After hosting Tennessee this weekend, they travel to Minnesota
and end at home against Pittsburgh in the last Monday night game.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers and Oilers have been disappointing. The Steelers
are capable of losing at Tampa Bay. After hosting Cincinnati, they
could crater in the finale against the Jaguars. The Oilers have the
most difficult schedule. They visit Jacksonville and Green Bay and
host Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Keys &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coach &LR; : Bill Cowher, Steelers. This is his seventh season, and
his team has never missed the playoffs. It will be a test of
Cowher's coaching and motivation to see if he can rally his team
over the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Player &LR; : Fred Taylor, Jaguars. The rookie running back has
scored 14 touchdowns and rushed for 1,005 yards despite nagging
injuries. With quarterback Mark Brunell nursing an ankle injury,
Taylor must take the pressure off backup Jamie Martin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Question &LR; : How long will Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell be
out? Coach Tom Coughlin wishes he knew.
</P>
<P>
   AFC West
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, who won Super Bowl XXXII as a wild card, are trying
to win an NFL-record 19th consecutive game Sunday when they play a
road game against the Giants. Unless they suffer a colossal upset,
they will be 14-0 when they travel to Miami in the next game.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland looked as if it was going to make a serious run at the
playoffs, but the Raiders have lost three in a row. With road games
at Buffalo and San Diego and a home finale against the Chiefs, they
probably need to win out for a shot. Don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   Keys &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coach &LR; : Mike Shanahan, Broncos. He must keep his players
focused on the Giants and not allow them to look ahead to the
Monday night game at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Player &LR; : John Elway, Broncos. The veteran quarterback has
thrown nine touchdown passes in his last three games and is healthy
for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Question &LR; : If the Broncos beat the Giants, will they also win
at Miami in the most important regular-season game in years?
</P>
<P>
   NFC East
</P>
<P>
   Although the Cowboys are coming off one of the most embarrassing
losses in franchise history, only a total collapse would keep them
from winning the NFL's worst division.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is easy. After playing at Kansas City, they host
Philadelphia and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is woefully inconsistent. The Cardinals had the inside
track to the last wild-card spot and blew it with a home loss to
the Giants. If they had won, they would have trailed Dallas by one
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals also have an easy schedule. After visiting the
Eagles, they host the Saints and Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Keys &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coach &LR; : Chan Gailey, Cowboys. He has to show he's not Barry
Switzer and keep the Cowboys from gagging down the stretch against
three disappointing teams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Player &LR; : Jake Plummer, Cardinals. Arizona's quarterback is a
miracle worker or a disaster. The coaches just never know who is
going to show up: Jake Plummer or Jake the Snake.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Question &LR; : Will the Cardinals rally to win their first
non-strike playoff berth since 1975, and if they do, will they win
their first playoff game since 1947?
</P>
<P>
   NFC Central
</P>
<P>
   How the mighty hath fallen. The injury-plagued Packers are
reduced to a wild-card berth after reaching the last two Super
Bowls. The Vikings have dominated the division and earned a
first-round bye for the first time in coach Dennis Green's seven
years. They have a schedule so soft (at Baltimore, Jacksonville, at
Tennessee) they should finish 15-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers' skill-position players have spent more time in the
hospital than on the field, except for Brett Favre. There's good
news, though. They play two games against Chicago. Barring a
dramatic change, they will play the first-round game at San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   After shocking the Packers, Tampa Bay has vaulted back into
wild-card contention. If the Bucs can upset the Steelers at Tampa,
the last two on the road are against the Redskins and Bengals, two
of the league's worst teams.
</P>
<P>
   Keys &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coach &LR; : Dennis Green, Vikings. With one playoff victory in six
seasons, he must prove that he can win the big games in January.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Player &LR; : Brett Favre, Packers. Without healthy receivers, he
has to perform almost inhuman feats for his team to avoid a
first-round loss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Question &LR; : Will Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren's job status
become such a distraction that the Packers make a quick exit from
the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   NFC West
</P>
<P>
   There is a changing of the guard. Atlanta should win its second
division title and finish with the best record in franchise
history. The Falcons are expected to earn a second-round game at
the Georgia Dome. Although they have been very good, don't mark
them down for the division title yet. After road games against New
Orleans and Detroit, they finish at home against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers can't believe they are going to be a wild-card team.
Thank heaven for an easy schedule because their defense is
mediocre. After hosting Detroit and traveling to New England, they
finish at home against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints surprised Dallas to move into contention for the last
wild-card spot. Their schedule is brutal the last three weeks. They
host Atlanta, visit Arizona and entertain Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Keys &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coach &LR; : Mike Ditka, Saints. Without much talent and a lot of
injuries, his motivational skills are paramount if his team is
going to survive a schedule that has five of the last six against
teams with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Player &LR; : Chris Chandler, Falcons. If he stays healthy, they
have a chance to reach the NFC Championship Game. If he is injured,
they're dead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Question &LR; : If the 49ers host a wild-card game against Green
Bay, will their defense be good enough to finally beat the Packers
in a playoff game?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
