<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4560 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAYLOR-STALLINGS-     12-11 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-STALLINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
GRANBURY _ While speaking at the historic Granbury Opera House on
Thursday, Gene Stallings sounded like a man who wanted to make a
little more history coaching college football.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The former Alabama head coach said he met with Baylor officials
Wednesday and talked about the school's coaching job, which became
vacant Sunday when Dave Roberts was reassigned after back-to-back
2-9 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visited with them (Baylor athletic director Tom Stanton and
Baylor president Robert Sloan),'' Stallings said. ``But they have a
number of people they want to talk to. That's basically where it
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made a decision one way or the other, and neither
have they.''
</P>
<P>
   But sources close to the program say the job is Stallings' if he
wants it. And for a man who said he hasn't made a decision,
Stallings sounded a lot like a man planning to take on a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said there are two things that could get me back in
coaching,'' Stallings said. ``One is if there was a team that I
thought was good enough to win the national championship. The other
is a team that needs help. Baylor needs some help. That's the
reason Baylor got my attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Stallings, 63, said he had followed Baylor closely this season
and attended two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were within a point or two of winning five or six
games,'' Stallings said. ``They were in the Texas game, the
Colorado game and the Texas Tech game. They just needed someone to
make a play or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any level of coaching, you win with players, not schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton said Thursday he expects to name a new head coach by the
end of next week. That would appear to fit Stallings' schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Stallings will be in Birmingham, Ala., today to take part in a
fund-raiser for the Stallings Center, a home for children with Down
syndrome. Stallings has a son with Down syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Stallings, who has a ranch in Paris, Texas, will return home
Sunday, then he will be in Washington from Monday through Thursday
participating in events for Special Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having dinner at the White House with the president
Thursday night for Special Olympics,'' Stallings said. ``Then, I'm
coming home on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   The one problem for Baylor is that waiting another week would be
a big blow to recruiting, but sources said school officials are
willing to wait if it means getting Stallings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to do it as quickly as they can,'' Stallings said.
``By the same token, they want to make sure they get the person
that they want, but they can't wait too long. I would say they need
to do something within a week or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about getting back in touch. There's going to come a
time when they have to make a decision, and there's going to come a
time when I have to make a decision. But right now is not the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping the situation with Dave Roberts would work out.
I've been where is he right now, and I feel bad for him.''
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Stallings said he does not want to accept the
job too quickly, because he doesn't want it to look like it was a
done deal before Roberts was reassigned.
</P>
<P>
   Stallings, who retired at Alabama after the 1996 season, was in
Granbury on Thursday to announce plans for the USA World Cup
football team, which will train in Granbury this summer before
going to Palermo, Sicily, for the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Stallings is the head coach for the college all-star team, but
that could change if he takes the job at Baylor. NCAA rules say no
active coach can be involved with the World Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I retired, I said I was closing the chapter but I was not
closing the book,'' Stallings said. ``When I got involved with the
World Cup team, I told them there was a possibility that I might
coach again, either in the pros or in college. I know of two or
three people that would be very capable of taking over (the World
Cup team).''
</P>
<P>
   While Stallings was holding a news conference in Granbury,
Stanton was holding a hastily called news conference at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton said he had talked to Stallings, along with Dallas
Highland Park coach Scott Smith, a former Baylor player and
assistant coach under Grant Teaff.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Baylor is interested in Smith as a defensive
coordinator who could be groomed under Stallings. But Stallings
said he didn't know Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really think they would tell me what coaches I had to
take?'' Stallings said. ``We didn't discuss (Smith), but we did
discuss some of the coaches that are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's important that some of the coaches remain. I
think there are some good coaches there, and I think it's good to
have as much stability as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those coaches is Keith Gunn, Stallings' son-in-law. Gunn
coached tight ends this season. When asked if Gunn would be part of
the staff if he took the job, Stallings grinned and said, ``I would
say that would be a sure thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton said he has other candidates he wants to interview. Two
of the names on Stanton's short list include Southern Mississippi
coach Jeff Bower and Arkansas defensive coordinator Keith Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Bower, the son-in-law of Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, is
reputed to be one of the best coaches in the country at molding
quarterbacks. He coached Green Bay Packers quarterback Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   But Stallings is the top choice if he decides he wants to return
to coaching. Stallings was asked if he was flattered that Baylor
saw him as a man who could resurrect the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just because of my age,'' he said. ``I managed to go
through the pro game and the college game and still survive. If I
was looking for a coach, I would look for me, too. I make no
apologies about knowing something about coaching football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 0225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4562 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-REYNOLDS-H     12-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-REYNOLDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
While the Astros wait to see if one highly coveted pitcher is
coming to town, they made sure another is staying.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds, whose name had been mentioned in trade talk
involving five-time Cy Young Award winner Roger Clemens, agreed
Thursday to a $21.5 million, three-year contract extension that
could keep him with the Astros through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the extension, the 30-year-old righthander has a
no-trade provision for the 1999 season and a limited no-trade
provision for the remainder of the contract, which includes a club
option for a fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the contract extension was casually discussed, this
literally happened in the last few days and accelerated,'' Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The no-trade (clause) was something they asked for. We had no
problem with that. In fact, we thought it was even more important
given the speculation out there that Shane was potentially part of
any discussions involving Roger Clemens _ to come out and put that
to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds will make $3.5 million in 1999 in the final season of
an $8.5 million, three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Under the extension, he gets a $3.5 million signing bonus
payable over three years, and salaries of $5.5 million in 2000, $6
million in 2001 and $6.5 million in 2002. The Astros have an $8
million option for 2003 that would become guaranteed if Reynolds
makes 32 starts or pitches 215 innings in 2002, or has 64 starts
and 430 innings combined in 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds would have been eligible for free agency after next
season. Instead of waiting to test the high-dollar market, he chose
to remain with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not have another year and go for free agency with the way
the money is going?'' Reynolds said. ``Everybody wants to go to a
winner. I like it here. I've been with the Houston Astros
organization my whole career, and they have treated me fairly
throughout. They are the ones to give me the chance to succeed, and
they've been very loyal, and I think I've been loyal to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I can finish my career here. I think the Astros
have done their part to make that possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm worth exactly what I got here _ no more, no
less, because it's where I wanted to be. They wanted me. That was
very important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds battled back from 1997 knee surgery to go 19-8 with a
3.51 ERA as the Astros repeated as National League Central
champions in 1998. The 19 wins were a career high for Reynolds _
his previous high was 16 in 1996 _ and tied for second in the NL
with Chicago's Kevin Tapani.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Tom Glavine, the Cy Young Award winner, led the league
with 20 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds also tied for the league lead in starts (35) and ranked
in the top 10 in winning percentage (.704), innings pitched (233),
strikeouts (209), strikeouts per nine innings (8.06) and fewest
walks per nine innings (2.04).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best-kept secrets in major-league baseball,''
Hunsicker said. ``Shane has been one of the anchors of our staff
over the last four years and, over that four-year period, is among
the most consistent starting pitchers in all of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at all the important statistical categories that
evaluate starting pitchers, I think you'll find Shane's name in
most of those lists. In each of the last three years, he has been
our opening-day starting pitcher. That is further evidence of what
he means to this franchise and our baseball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Reynolds became the first three-year veteran ever
guaranteed a multiyear contract by the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a relatively easy contract to do,'' said the
pitcher's agent, Tommy Tanzer. ``The club was very motivated. We
were very motivated. After some of the departures they had, they
stepped up. This got done in three or four conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said the rush to complete a deal was mostly because he
wanted to remain a part of a contending club, although speculation
of his possible departure played a small role.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros remain a contender for Clemens, who has asked the
Toronto Blue Jays to trade him to a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this organization, a lot of ballplayers and this city
would love to have Roger,'' said Reynolds. ``I didn't want it to be
at my expense. You just don't ever know. That's another reason this
was a case for me to sign this deal, to kind of know I'm here and
have the stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball, you're here one year and gone the next. When you
find a club you really like _ and like the people and management _
you'll pretty much do whatever you can to stay. Seeing my name
(among trade rumors) is something you have to go through being an
athlete these days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 0225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4564 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     12-11 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Astros deserve extra points for not trying to be coy. They told
us straight up, before the fact, that their hastily called
Thursday-afternoon news conference concerned only Shane Reynolds,
not Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some of us felt let down. But that didn't mean the
announcement of a three-year contract extension for Reynolds,
currently the Astros' ace, was a trivial development.
</P>
<P>
   With Randy Johnson come and gone and Clemens still a mere
Christmas wish _ albeit one tantamount to that new pony _ Reynolds
is, until further notice, The Man. You want to keep him happy. And
happy Shane should be, even if he didn't squeeze every nickel out
of a free-spending system that he might have after winning 19 games
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds got security. The Astros also got security, with just a
modicum of risk.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are now on the hook to Shane for an additional
$21.5 million, the club has every reason to believe he will do
whatever is humanly possible to earn the sum total of the windfall.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Reynolds appears to have no latent Mark Portugal or
Greg Swindell tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   While that's a lot of money to guarantee a pitcher, and
organizational policy frowns on such largess, Reynolds' file
indicates he's a worthy recipient of such faith being shown in him.
</P>
<P>
   He's young _ 31 on opening day _ a clean liver and a hard
worker. He's also pretty darn good. General manager Gerry Hunsicker
is wont to point out that Shane had more ``quality'' starts in 1998
than either Johnson or Clemens. Look it up, Hunsicker says.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off knee surgery in 1997, Reynolds bowed his back and
recovered 100 percent, winding up tied for the league lead in
starts and ranking in the top 10 in five major statistical
categories. Only Cy Young Award winner Tom Glavine won more games
(20).
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson hadn't so thoroughly dominated National League
hitters, never mind local conversation, and then Clemens' name
hadn't taken over the airwaves and sports pages of late, the news
that Shane will be sticking around through at least 2003 would be
enough to make most people sing and dance.
</P>
<P>
   But, no, we want more. Of course we do. We've gotta have the
Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Shane's OK with this, actually. He wants the Rocket, too. That's
another of Reynolds' assets: His ego is completely in check,
unfortunately a rarity for a player of his growing stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for anything that helps us win,'' he said. He called
Clemens ``a friend'' and admitted he would love to locker next to
him. Should the five-time Cy Young Award winner assume the Astros'
``ace'' designation, so what? And so be it. Spahn and Sain had each
other, didn't they?
</P>
<P>
   ```Ace,''' Reynolds said, ``is an iffy term.''
</P>
<P>
   Re-upping Reynolds before he had a chance to seek greener
pastures _ and giving him a ``no-trade'' contract _ removes Shane's
name from speculation he might be part of whatever Astros package
for Clemens may be on the table.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the terms of the extension were hammered out extra
fast, seemingly out of the blue, although player and management say
the conversations had begun well before Toronto agreed to set the
Rocket free for the right price.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding same, the Astros have made it clear what they will and
won't do. Obviously, Shane was an untouchable, as are the other
usual suspects _ Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and Moises Alou. With
Reynolds now locked up, the club doesn't feel _ internally, at
least _ any great pressure to jam a Clemens trade through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very comfortable with the pitching staff we have,''
Hunsicker said. ``Even when you subtract Randy's numbers, ours was
one of the best in the league last year. We don't need to rip the
ballclub apart to improve it.''
</P>
<P>
   As badly as the customers may want Clemens wearing a blue cap
with a gold star, the Astros will proceed cautiously. As they
should, no matter how tantalizing the Rocket's return to his
hometown may be _ or whatever ``mystery'' teams covet Clemens' Hall
of Fame arm.
</P>
<P>
   Too many three-for-one deals, and suddenly you have zero depth.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the payoff on Johnson was, ultimately, negligible. The
Astros advanced no further with him than they had gone the previous
year without him. And, ironically, one of the players they sent to
Seattle, Carlos Guillen, might have helped with their Clemens
quest.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen is expected to start at second for the Mariners in 1999,
and, more than anything, the Blue Jays covet a second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Right, hindsight. Let's not go there.
</P>
<P>
   Having the Big Unit was a gas, just as having Rocket Roger would
be. But Reynolds _ you hardly need a nickname when your real name
is Shane _ remains a comforting presence. He deserves to be
celebrated on his own merit.
</P>
<P>
   Shane's best seasons are surely ahead of him. Who could think
that about the other guys?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
