<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4571 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PRESIDENTSCUP-HNS     12-11 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PRESIDENTSCUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cup
</P>
<P>
   Couples
</P>
<P>
   Internationals &QL; 
ahead 7-3 in &QL; 
Presidents Cup
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MELBOURNE, Australia _ Jack Nicklaus said he didn't want a war.
Good thing, since his American team isn't putting up much of a
fight after the first day of the Presidents Cup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the American team is going to stay undefeated in this event,
it will have to do it in come-from-behind fashion thanks to a Kiwi
invasion on Day 1.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealander Frank Nobilo fired a shot through the Americans'
collective heart with a 40-foot putt on No. 18 at Royal Melbourne
to win a critical foursome match as the International team stormed
to a commanding lead today (Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the International team is getting the hang of this
format. In the first Presidents Cup in 1994, it was hammered 5-0 in
the first morning's matches and the Americans went on to win the
Cup in a breeze. Two years ago, the Americans led 3-2 after the
first morning's matches and that ended up being the margin by which
they kept the Cup, winning 16{-15{.
</P>
<P>
   But the International team got through the morning foursome
matches ahead 3{-1{, and there was no doubt that the International
players sensed they had a breakthrough performance in the
alternate-shot matches. Their play in the morning set the tone for
a grand day at the end of which they led 7-3, putting the U.S. in a
big hole.
</P>
<P>
   There will be 10 more points at stake Saturday (today) in
foursome and fourball matches, with 16{ points needed for victory.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the momentum is with the International team after the
way it dismantled the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our effort is about 100 percent better than it was in the
previous Presidents Cups,'' International captain Peter Thomson
said. ``I'm very pleased with my team.''
</P>
<P>
   And his team should be well-pleased with Thomson. It was his
call to place Nobilo and fellow New Zealander Greg Turner as the
final two members of the International team. They rewarded that
decision by beating Mark O'Meara and David Duval when it appeared
the match was heading for a halve.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. side was one hole down going into the par-4 18th. But
when O'Meara hit a wedge to within three feet and Turner's approach
left Nobilo with a 40-footer from the fringe, the Americans'
chances seemed great.
</P>
<P>
   But Nobilo smoothly sank the long birdie putt, rendering Duval's
tap-in moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hole just sucked it in,'' Nobilo said. ``It was great.
Peter was determined to get off to a good start this time. And it
feels good to be ahead in this thing for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing with Kiwis is we will nip at someone's heels all day
for 18 holes and eventually we will take the leg off.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara said he wasn't crestfallen when Nobilo's putt rattled
in. But it clearly was a jolt to the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit my wedge up there, I told David to just go ahead
and roll it in,'' O'Meara said. ``But in the back of my mind, I
thought Frank might make that 40-footer. In this format, you never
underestimate your opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans weren't already keenly respectful of the
Internationals, they are now.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norman was a question mark coming into the match with
barely a month under his belt since returning from shoulder
surgery. But he held up nicely. He teamed with Steve Elkington for
a solid win over Jim Furyk and John Huston in the morning, then was
with Elkington again in the afternoon against Furyk and O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was doubting Norman's stamina after he and Elkington won
the afternoon battle 3 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever he's available, I need him,'' Thomson said. ``He
doesn't want to be rested.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman credited Nobilo's putt for stoking up the International
team. ``You look at something like that, those are the types of
things that filter all the way down the team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only Fred Couples and Tiger Woods were able to win their morning
match for the U.S., smashing Ernie Els and Vijay Singh 5 and 4. The
Couples-Woods combination proved to be the only highlight as the
teams continued play with five fourball matches in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger was putting so well today, which is very important,''
Couples said. ``I didn't have to putt too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to their match came on No. 8, when they had to take an
unplayable lie after Woods' errant tee shot. But Couples' approach
cozied up to within eight feet and Woods drilled the putt, earning
a half on the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight was huge,'' Woods said. ``It really got us pumped. Then
we made another one on nine. From there, we ham-and-egged it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rest of the American team mostly just egged it.
</P>
<P>
   It took a marvelous approach shot by Justin Leonard on No. 18,
and an eight-foot birdie putt by partner Davis Love III, to get a
split with Stuart Appleby and Nick Price in the morning's final
match. The half-point kept the Americans from falling into a 4-1
hole.
</P>
<P>
   Couples had problems in the afternoon match, however. He and
Love, a strong tandem in Ryder Cup competitions, lost Nos. 6 and 7
when neither could make a par.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day for the Americans. Not much went right.
</P>
<P>
   There were two gripping subplots. Foremost, the wind did a
U-turn and was whipping out of the north at about 20 mph. That
drove temperatures up beyond the 95-degree mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time the wind comes out of that direction, it's like a
furnace,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   More bothersome than the heat, however, was the fact that the
course played completely different than it had in three days of
practice when the wind was coming out of the south and west. The
International players said their experiences in past trips to Royal
Melbourne helped them adjust to the different conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're up against a great team like we are, you need
something to go in your favor,'' Nobilo said. ``The conditions were
really good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the International team members credited Thomson for
giving them their first-day pairings well in advance so they could
practice together. The International players knew two full days
ahead of time what the alternate-shot pairings would be for their
side. The American team requested similar information from Nicklaus
in a team meeting Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, some U.S. players weren't happy about being kept in
the dark about with whom they would be playing in the difficult
format. Nicklaus dismissed any notion that there were problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
