<HEADER>
A4597 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LOFGREN-SFCHR     12-11 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LOFGREN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA REPRESENTATIVE EMBITTERED BY HOUSE HEARINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ When Congress began its impeachment inquiry three
months ago, Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., dug up her copy of the
Federalist Papers and began brushing up on her constitutional
history.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Jose Democrat hoped the House Judiciary Committee's
inquiry would be rooted in constitutional principles and clearly
establish whether President Clinton's behavior met the standards
for ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' set by the Founding Fathers.
Unlike many other Democrats, she refused to attack independent
counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the eve of a historic impeachment vote, Lofgren, the
only Bay Area lawmaker on the panel, has become disgusted with a
process she calls a ``national embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day in our nation's history,'' she said Thursday
night in explaining to the committee why she will vote against
articles of impeachment. ``Unfortunately, it seems to be one more
day in a long, sad season.''
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren's descent into disillusionment illuminates why these
hearings, unlike the Watergate inquiry a quarter-century earlier,
are likely to end with a vote to impeach Clinton along strictly
party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (the Republicans) had come up with a case that the
president engaged in behavior that threatens our constitutional
form of government, he would be in trouble with me,'' she said in
an interview. ``But you can't afford to cause this kind of
disruption over which body parts he touched. I am sorry, that is
not what George Mason had in mind.'' Mason was one of the framers
of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The glamour of media exposure has long been eroded by long hours
away from family, endless discussions of familiar arguments and the
tawdriness of much of the testimony. During a recent hearing, while
her colleagues droned on in front of TV cameras, Lofgren took a
quick break in the cramped two rooms reserved for Democrats next to
the hearing room. In lieu of dinner, she munched on an ice cream
sandwich from a nearly empty vending machine.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms were littered with Coke cans and newspapers, as
lawmakers and staffers milled around or squeezed onto two black
leather couches.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because these hearings have not lasted nearly as long as
the Watergate inquiry 24 years ago, no committee members have
emerged as recognizable stars in the mold of Barbara Jordan, the
late representative from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Lofgren has made her mark as one of the more measured
lawmakers who consistently asks deeper questions about what the
Founding Fathers had in mind when they drafted articles of
impeachment two centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   She was also the first member to talk about the potential
long-term harm of voting to impeach Clinton, which would require a
trial in the Senate that would be presided over by Chief Justice
William Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do this trial, does that mean the Supreme Court does not
get to hear any cases for a period of six months or more?'' she
asked at a hearing this week. ``Is all of government gridlocked?''
</P>
<P>
   She also recounted how several Silicon Valley executives had
expressed concerns that a long trial could have a depressing effect
on the U.S. economy, the first time anyone had raised that
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Katzenbach, a former U.S. attorney general and IBM
chief executive, agreed that that was not a farfetched concept.
``People in business want certainty, and I can think of nothing
much worse than pushing them into an uncertainty that would go on
for some period of time while we rehearsed what has been rehearsed
a dozen times already,'' Katzenbach testified this week as part of
Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren has been able to make her own unfavorable comparisons
with the Watergate hearings. As a first-year law student, she
helped draft articles of impeachment against President Richard
Nixon while serving as an aide to then-Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Watergate, there was a very heavy sense of foreboding and
gravity, which isn't present here,'' she said. ``It was widely
perceived as a committee coming together in the face a national
cataclysmic threat. This time, it is one party going after the
president of another.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, she said, are trying to get back at Democrats
for what they did to Nixon. ``It doesn't seem possible that some
people would be trying to get even, but as astounding as that may
seem, there are people doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   What disturbs Lofgren is that many of her constituents back home
wrongly believed that after the Republican setbacks in the November
elections the impeachment hearings would soon be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to get ready for the holidays, and most people
are not at home watching this stuff,'' she said. ``I'm not critical
of that. But I think a lot of people will be upset, shocked and
surprised when they wake up to find that we have voted to impeach
the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren is also struggling with how to balance her family
responsibilities with those of being in office at one of the most
dramatic moments in U.S. history. Her husband, attorney John
Collins, and her two teenage children are back home in San Jose.
She's relieved she was able to pick out the family Christmas tree
before the impeachment marathon began and put up the trimmings.
</P>
<P>
   But she is way behind on her holiday shopping. During one break
in the hearings, she dashed across the street to the House gift
shop to buy souvenirs for some friends, but she has exhausted her
shopping possibilities there. ``I'm hoping they'll take a mall
break,'' she quipped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
