<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN12-COX     12-11 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once again, tripping the light fantastic
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I am trying hard to get into the Christmas
spirit. The warm weather isn't helping. It's hard to sing along
with Christmas carols while wearing shorts and running the air
conditioner. It's the Yankee in me that wants snow this time of
year, at least for a week or so.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, I did two things: went to church, where the service
concluded with a rousing, five-stanza rendition of ``The Battle
Hymn of the Republic,'' which is one of my favorite hymns, and
strung Christmas lights. It's a good thing I went to church first.
Or maybe I should have gone back afterward. Stringing Christmas
lights can make a man forget his religion in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the crate of lights sent my heart sinking like an
Aggie's spirits after The Game last week. (Sorry, I had to get in a
dig somewhere.) We bought new lights this year. The old lights had
tangled themselves into a wire-and-glass hairball that I refused to
deal with. I gave them to Goodwill. No doubt, workers there have
been hard at it since summer trying to untangle the lights so they
could be resold.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Vacate the premises immediately. (end ital) That
was my first thought upon viewing this massive collection of
lights. Go missing in action. Come back after New Year's. Hanging
these lights, all 16 cartons of them, was going to be the death of
me. I was sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly who invented this tradition of hanging lights? And how
in the world do people who put up those incredible displays have
the patience to do this year in, year out? I looked in dismay at
the many boxes of icicle lights, all the rage these days. They hang
down and allegedly look like icicles. I believe my wife purposely
bought the most complicated set of lights in America. I accused her
of shopping for weeks just to find a set of lights that a NASA
engineer would be hard-put to figure out. She denied it, of course
and left town, leaving me alone to hang the lights while hanging
from the roof. I should mention that she has a large life-insurance
policy on me.
</P>
<P>
   Yeech. I opened the first box and took out a bag containing
about 40 pieces of plastic and two sets of lights. It took about 20
minutes to figure out how to put it together. At this rate, the
lights would be up just in time for Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, things had to get better, particularly my mood. So I
went inside and brought out the jambox. Maybe a little music would
help.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the first song I heard was that horrible version
of ``Jingle Bells'' sung by dogs barking. The cats, who had
wandered out on the second-story porch with me, looked alarmed. I
switched stations.
</P>
<P>
   Click. The next set went together in just 5 minutes. Things were
improving. Now it was time to actually hang a set and see how it
looked.
</P>
<P>
   Here came the tricky part. I had to reach out backwards over the
porch rail and screw a cup hook into the wood to hold the lights.
If I fell, at best I would break something and be out of the
hospital in time to open presents. At worst... well, let's not get
into that.
</P>
<P>
   Englebert Humperdink came on the radio, singing something or
other. In my haste to switch off the dogs and ``Jingle Bells,'' I
had ended up on an easy-listening station. Even worse, I had been
listening for about 15 minutes without noticing. My rock 'n' roll
image was in jeopardy. Quickly I put it on the Oldies Rock station.
</P>
<P>
   Right after I got the first set hung, I went down to check out
my handiwork. By the time I got outside and was looking up, one set
of lights had quit burning. I hurried upstairs and began checking
bulbs, replacing fuses, etc. Nothing worked. The lights would not
come on.
</P>
<P>
   Yuletide spirit was sorely lacking as I took down the second set
of lights and put together yet another set to replace the defective
ones. I was grumbling mightily under my breath.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, things got better. Eventually, I got the hang of
hanging the lights. In a fit of stupidity, I even climbed up on the
roof and hung some from a steep-pitched gable, leaning over the
side and hoping fervently I didn't end up impaled in the azaleas in
the ground below.
</P>
<P>
   By dark all the lights were shining. They don't exactly look
like icicles. More like popsicle sticks with lights on them.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
