<HEADER>
A4749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILNER-COLUMN12-COX     12-11 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Books make long-lasting holiday gifts
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that December is upon us again, although it hasn't been all
that noticeable as far as the weather is concerned, why not think
about giving books for Christmas gifts?
</P>
<P>
   There's very little else you can give that would last as long
and give as much pleasure, unless you're thinking about diamonds or
something in that category, and, if so, you might consider giving a
whole library.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of us a single book would be a lasting and
worthwhile Christmas gift, especially for, well, for just about
anybody you care about.
</P>
<P>
   If you need some suggestions, how about these:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Mountain'' by Charles Frazier (Atlantic Monthly Press).
</P>
<P>
   It's particularly pleasant when a book we love becomes a best
seller without a lot of hype. ``Cold Mountain'' is such a book.
It's Frazier's first novel and publishers more often than not send
first novels out without expensive artificial legs, then nod and
say, ``I knew it wouldn't sell'' when it sinks without creating a
stir on its own.
</P>
<P>
   But now and then, a book will cause an uproar and wind up a best
seller on its own, by word of mouth mostly, although a few sensible
critics may help it along with rave reviews. ``Cold Mountain'' was
raved about by critics and readers alike, and gradually became a
best-seller without the expensive hype. And it's worth it, one of
the best novels I've read in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   It's an absorbing story with characters that are real and
sympathetic. Set during the closing months of the Civil War, it
follows a Confederate deserter's trek back home were his wife is
waiting and living her own adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Patchwork Planet'' by Anne Tyler (Knopf).
</P>
<P>
   I'm one of the many people who greet every new Anne Tyler novel
with a joyful noise. So far I haven't been disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Any lover of good books would be happy to receive this, or any
Anne Tyler book for that matter, as a Christmas gift. (Most of her
others are in paperback.)
</P>
<P>
   Plots aren't the most important aspects of a Tyler book. Oh,
there's always a good story that keeps you interested in the
outcome, but it's the characters and the writing that make Tyler
stand out.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Patchwork Planet'' the main character is Barnaby Gaitlin,
who earns a living in an unusual manner. Here's the way he explains
his job: ``The company I work for is called 'Rent-a-Back.' How I
got into it is a whole other story, but basically we provide a
service for people who are old or disabled. Any load you can't
lift, any chore you don't feel up to, why just call us.''
</P>
<P>
   As Barnaby goes about his work for various elderly and disabled
men and women, he becomes involved in their lives because that's
the kind of guy he is. He even grows attached to the grumpy ones.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times reviewer wrote the following about another
Tyler book, words that could be applied to this new one or any
other Tyler book. ``Tyler does nothing fancy, nothing tricky. But
so rigorous and artful is the style, so measured and delicate is
each observation, so complete is the structure and so astute and
open the language, that the reader can relax, feel secure in the
narrative and experience the work as something real and natural _
even inevitable _ the story that appears to unfold of its own
accord is a fairy tale of sorts, a fairy tale with echoes of both
the tragedy of King Lear and the absurdity of the modern romance
novel.'' She took the words right out of my word processor.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the latest novel by El Paso writer Cormac McCarthy,
``Cities of the Plain'' (Knopf).
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy is called by some ``the Texas Faulkner,'' and there may
be some legitimate cause for this, although I'm not sure I go for
it 100 percent. I will go along part way on that, which means that
in my mind he is something special as far as contemporary writers
in America are concerned. This latest book of McCarthy's is the
third in his ``Border Trilogy.'' The other two are ``All the Pretty
Horses'' and ``The Crossing.'' Any one or all three of these would
be fine Christmas gifts for a serious reader. I emphasize the
``serious'' here because these are not light reading by any means,
but worth the effort by any measure.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of heavy reading ... well, not so heavy you'll have
trouble getting
</P>
<P>
   through it and understanding it. The author here is straight
forward and easy to understand, but the subject is heavy. I'm
talking about David Halberstam's newest best seller, ``The
Children'' (Random House, 783 pp., including the index, $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is the detailed history of eight young black college
students, who in the 1960s, found themselves propelled into the
leadership of the civil rights movement (to quote from the book
jacket) as the movement and America entered a period of dramatic
change. Halberstam, a Pulitzer Prize-winning reporter and author,
was working on the Nashville Banner when this movement
</P>
<P>
   began, a 25-year-old reporter assigned to cover this story.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Halberstam's books, this one has received rave reviews
from coast to coast. It would make a great Christmas gift to people
who would appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   All these books are keepers for now and future generations to
read and enjoy and learn.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there's that brand new book ``Confessions of a
Mad Dog.'' (University of North Texas Press) by that fellow Jay
Dunston Milner. It would make a fine Christmas gift for any friend
or family member who is interested in Texas writers of song and
story, such as Willie Nelson, Bud Shrake, Dan Jenkins, Gary
Cartwright and others of that ilk, who in the 1960s formed a sort
of social and literary club called Mad Dog, Inc., with the motto,
``Doing indefinable services to mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   I've read it and it is indeed funny and informative. We're
trying to cast
</P>
<P>
   the movie version now.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner, who can be reached at jpownall(at)coxnews.com,
writes for Cox Newspapers and unabashedly promotes his own book.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
