<HEADER>
A4750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANTA-SUES12-COX     12-11 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-SUES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Would-be Santa sues company for racial bias
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For years, DeWayne Lofton has been dressing up
as Santa Claus around the holidays to amuse family and friends. So
when a friend suggested he take his Santa suit and apply for a job
at the mall this winter, the 32-year-old state employee thought:
Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Lofton, who is black, said he never thought his race would be an
issue. That is, until he arrived in person to apply for a job with
Santa Plus, a St. Louis-based company that contracts with local
malls to fill Santa positions. He said he was met with surprised
stares and told about a policy against hiring minorities to play
Santa.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Plus representatives say that they have no such policy and
that they hired Lofton, but that he failed to show up for his
training session.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton said he showed up for training only to be told he didn't
have a Santa job.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to a Travis County jury to decide the facts. This
week, Lofton filed a lawsuit in District Court in Austin against
Santa Plus and Barton Creek Square, where he sought employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought that Christmas was for all children in Travis
County,'' said Lofton's attorney, John W. Thomas, who filed the
lawsuit Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Lents, a spokeswoman for Santa Plus, said the company
doesn't discriminate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take our hiring practices very seriously,'' Lents said.
``Santa Plus has great integrity in everything we do.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Santa Plus has minority Santas working at malls across
Texas, including one black and one Hispanic Santa working at Barton
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   A black Santa was hired through a temp service for Barton Creek
Square but was not scheduled to work this week, or any time in
December, according to Ida Funes, a Santa Plus manager at the mall.
Funes said they use Santas from temp services when they do not have
enough Santas to fill their time slots. The Santas directly hired
by Santa Plus have set schedules, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic Santa was working Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In November, according to Lofton's lawsuit, he called Santa
Plus, which has contracts with Barton Creek Square and Lakeline
Mall, and was told they were desperate for Santa applicants. But
after he arrived at Barton Creek Square to meet a Santa Plus
representative, Lofton said a Santa Plus manager told him: ``When I
spoke to you over the phone, I did not realize that you were black.
I'll have to check with the mall to see if it would be OK to hire,
you know.'' The manager was not named in the lawsuit, and Thomas
said she is no longer with the company.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lofton's lawsuit, the Santa Plus manager said the
mall had a policy of not hiring minorities for Santas. The jobs
typically pay between $7 and $7.50 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Hedrick, manager of Barton Creek Square, said the mall has
no such policy and does not request Santas of a particular race.
Further, the mall has no control over hiring policies at Santa
Plus, which it treats like any other vendor at the mall who rents
space, Hedrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Hedrick said she had never heard of any problems with Santa Plus
before Lofton's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that Santa Plus is very well-respected in the
industry as professionals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton's allegations will likely be difficult to prove, an
employment discrimination specialist said. Jack Getman, a law
professor at the University of Texas who has no part in the case,
said there are dozens of reasons a company might not hire a Santa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, you cannot get away today saying that Santa Claus
has to be white,'' he said. ``But employment discrimination is
often hard to prove. While some employer may have had race in the
back of their mind, it's relatively easy to pick out a nonracial
basis for the decision. Maybe you're not affable enough, or you
don't get along well with children, or your laugh doesn't sound
right. This is an acting job, and it depends on who well you act
the role.''
</P>
<P>
   Lents said Santa Plus looks for three things in would-be Santas:
a clear voice, smiling eyes and gentleness. Lofton, she said, met
those requirements and was hired to work as a Santa at Barton Creek
Square, but didn't show up for his training or his first scheduled
shift, which Lents said was Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton agrees that he was promised a job after he complained
about his initial treatment. He said in his lawsuit that a senior
Santa Plus manager said he could work as a cashier at the Santa
exhibit with the understanding that he would be rotated into one of
the four-hour Santa shifts later in the month. But according to his
lawsuit, when Lofton arrived for training on Dec. 3, he was told by
the on-site Santa Plus manager, who also is not named in the
lawsuit, that he did not have a job or an application on file.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton said his lawsuit, which claims breach of contract among
other allegations, is not about money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about obtaining justice,'' he said. ``I will leave the
damages up to the jury to decide after they determine the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
