<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No visions of dancing sugar plums but . . .
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ 'Twas the night before Christmas, and in
Bubbaland,
</P>
<P>
   Folks were so giddy they should hire a band.
</P>
<P>
   The reason South Congress folks were feeling the best?
</P>
<P>
   After years of great struggle, they'd shut Cinema West.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if they'd been freed from a gigantic hex.
</P>
<P>
   No more weirdos in trench coats, no more films rated X.
</P>
<P>
   No more hookers on corners, dressed in hot pants.
</P>
<P>
   No stray lawmakers asking, ``May I have this dance?''
</P>
<P>
   No more drunks at the bus stop sucking down wine.
</P>
<P>
   No more senators asking, ``Your place or mine?''
</P>
<P>
   And how 'bout that road work at I-35 and Ben White?
</P>
<P>
   Until that job's finished, just forget ``Silent Night.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll have a new airport; there'll be lots of jets there.
</P>
<P>
   But with all that construction, you'll play hell to get there.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the new airport, here's my advice:
</P>
<P>
   Just pull down your britches and slide on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, up at the Capitol, state reps were aglow.
</P>
<P>
   From the mayor of Austin they got gift globes of snow.
</P>
<P>
   And not just those cheap globes like you find on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Hey. These snow globes from Saks were the tops in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   And if that wasn't enough to find under their tree,
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said state reps could park _ for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why such a great freebie?'' you're asking yourself.
</P>
<P>
   It's 'cause Mayor Kirk Watson is one crafty elf.
</P>
<P>
   He knows if he brown-noses the state Senate and House,
</P>
<P>
   In the coming session, they won't treat him like a louse.
</P>
<P>
   So next time you're downtown and can't find a space,
</P>
<P>
   Track down Mayor Watson and get in his face.
</P>
<P>
   At the university known far and wide as UT,
</P>
<P>
   Football fans were quite happy; there were whoops of great glee.
</P>
<P>
   What had all those Orange Bloods acting so dopey?
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Williams would soon get his own Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   And not only that _ that was just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The team has a defense and is actually winning.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the season before had been a debacle.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, the players have been taught how to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the Mansion, George W. Bush was in a bind.
</P>
<P>
   'Cause soon he would have to make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Should he hang onto his job as Texas' chief resident?
</P>
<P>
   Or should he throw in his hat and run for president?
</P>
<P>
   Should he go for the big one and face all that scrutiny?
</P>
<P>
   And if he did, would it cause his wife Laura to mutiny?
</P>
<P>
   A decision would have to be made fairly fast.
</P>
<P>
   But if he runs, the media will scour his past.
</P>
<P>
   And Lord knows they'll find stuff, like his remark about Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Hey. The press will report it whenever he sneezes.
</P>
<P>
   In the halls of the Capitol, the people were grieving;
</P>
<P>
   After decades of leadership, Bob Bullock was leaving.
</P>
<P>
   This caused one huge problem for the pols to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   When Bullock walks off, who gets the gavel?
</P>
<P>
   And without him around to tell folks what to do,
</P>
<P>
   Is there anyone left who can tie his own shoe?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that leaves us all quaking in fright, but
</P>
<P>
   Merry Christmas to all, and to all a good night.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears on Sundays, Wednesdays and
Fridays. He can be reached at 445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
