<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KISS-INTERVIEW12-COX     12-11 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KISS-INTERVIEW12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interview with Gene Simmons from the rock group Kiss
 &HT;    By Carol Simmons
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Failure. Doubt. Indecision.
</P>
<P>
   Don't even talk about it. At least not to Gene Simmons, founding
member and bass player for the most theatrical band in rock history
_ Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Negativity has no place. At least not in his worldview. It's
ludicrous, it's preposterous and just down right dumb.
</P>
<P>
   And Simmons, currently on tour with the band that 25 years after
its forming in New York City continues to astound fans and confound
critics, says he'll have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   That's not how you succeed. And Simmons is a winner. With the
kind of focus, drive and confidence that might have found him work
as a motivational speaker if he hadn't gone into the music
business, Simmons preaches a gospel of personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The man who prowls the stage in a costume that's part-dragon,
part-demon, spitting fake blood and real fire and licking the air
with a tongue renowned for its unnatural length has no patience for
whiners. You want something, you work for it. No excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Born Gene Klein 49 years ago in Israel, the musician said his
family moved to the United States when he was 9. Speaking earlier
this week from the Ritz Carlton in Chicago _ in advance of a
concert tonight at Wright State University _ the performer said he
took the name Simmons simply because he liked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no rhyme or reason for it,'' he said. ``When I heard
it in my head, I said that's me. I go through life that way. When I
come across images and things, I just absorb it, and it feels
right.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, the name you're given at birth isn't really yours
anyway. It's not your choice, and it's not based on your own
understanding of yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Naming himself was just one piece in a lifetime of personal
self-invention. But Simmons thinks everybody goes through the same
invention process to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all born to a clean slate, and what we do to it is our
choice,'' he said. ``You are responsible for yourself. Mommy's not
there to wipe your (bottom). Literally. You have to do it yourself.
If you don't, I don't care. You have to live with the
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-pity drives him nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s, this horrific disease came out of Seattle,'' he
said referring to the grunge and alternative-music scene. ``Not the
music itself. There was some very fine music. The disease was of
self-loathing and apathy.''
</P>
<P>
   And from his viewpoint, it looked like the negativity and
depression was coming out of a pretty privileged population. ``It's
always in the white community,'' he noted. ``Some blond, blue-eyed
boy complaining about his life. You never hear a black person
standing on a roof talking about suicide.'' They may be angry, but
they're not whining.
</P>
<P>
   ``How believable is it for you to whine and moan about how hard
life is, especially when you're a rock star.'' You have fame and
fortune, he said. ``The girls all want to have your babies. If you
have any amount of discomfort with the money, send it to Gene
Simmons. I have no problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But while a certain depressed attitude was in vogue for a time,
Simmons said it really was only a ``lunatic fringe,'' and now it's
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Kiss, however, is still going strong. Although the original
lineup of Simmons, guitarist Paul Stanley, guitarist Ace Frehley
and drummer Peter Criss has only been back together for two years _
after Frehly and Criss broke off in the early 1980s _ Kiss never
stopped touring and recording. The latest album, Psycho Circus,
which was released this fall, is the band's 31st or 32nd (Simmons
isn't sure), including European releases, but it's the first album
in 20 years featuring all four original members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss, we're like cockroaches,'' Simmons said ``We've been here
before all of you, and we'll outlive all of you. We don't change.
We have an exoskeleton. It's armor. Nothing gets to us. Cockroaches
are perfect, and we will outlive you all. Whether critics get it,
whether the media get it is beside the point. We're together, and I
have more records to make and miles to go before I sleep. That's
Robert Frost.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Kiss is still storming across the country with an
over-the-top act that critics discounted two decades ago doesn't
surprise Simmons. ``I can be falsely modest,'' he said. ``But any
champion worth his salt must be cocky and brazen.'' It's like being
a tight-rope walker, he said, if you doubt your ability, you fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thrill for me on a personal level is looking out
on stage and seeing Ace and Peter back in the band,'' Simmons said.
The reunion two years ago was something nobody expected after the
acrimonious split-up in large part because of Frehley's and Criss'
drug use at the time. They both have since gone clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like a dysfunctional family,'' Simmons said. ``We
weren't torn apart from within, we were torn apart from without _ I
like that; I'm going to use that in my next interview _ we were
torn asunder from without.''
</P>
<P>
   While Frehley and Criss had a problem with drugs, each of the
band members acted in ways he now regrets, Simmons said. ``Now it
makes me proud the band is as it should have been,'' he said. ``The
pieces all had to be there for the puzzle to be whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Already known for their larger-than-life stage shows, the band
is taking it even further this tour with the additional element of
3-D visuals. Others have pointed out that life is already
three-dimensional, so what more can be done? If you're Kiss,
plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's concert at the Ervin J. Nutter Center ``will decimate
you,'' Simmons said with typical confidence. ``It will drop five
pounds off any fat girl within 20 feet of the stage. The lights
will change your skin tone. And that's besides the 3-D.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the 3-D effects are concerned, ``it's difficult to
explain to somebody what the experience is like,'' he said. ``The
phrase `you won't believe your eyes' is apropos. We believe in
assaulting the senses. No passive sort of experience here. It's
over the top. It's for the eyes and ears together.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a spectacle. And that's the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love magic,'' Simmons said. ``I don't want to know that
Santa Claus is really Uncle Tim with a pillow up his shirt. I like
to look out at a Fourth of July fireworks show and just suspend
belief. I like just looking at stars, not analyzing them, and just
go 'wow.' Magic is good. Don't tell me how it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to analyze Kiss is an equally wasted effort for Simmons.
``Ultimately, we are what we are.'' Kiss has never been about
spreading a message, such as saving the rain forest and the dangers
of acid rain, he said. ``Just shut up and rock. We get paid to
entertain you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
