<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to teach your child to be a self-absorbed slob
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who know me will find it not surprising that I am an
excellent cook of scrambled eggs. In fact, when the goal is
scrambling anything I am darn near a maestro.
</P>
<P>
   Still and all, even in the scrambling of eggs I usually need an
assistant. For some years now, the chief assistant has been my
daughter. She is the Chief Egg Cracker and, as such, she knows no
peer.
</P>
<P>
   Well, she is usually the Chief Egg Cracker.
</P>
<P>
   Because the other night, when I asked her to perform her usual
duties, something funny happened.
</P>
<P>
   A weary look came over her face. She frowned. She sighed. She
rolled her eyes. She said, ``Do I have to do it right now?''
</P>
<P>
   I told her that she could sit where she was. Being the Chief Egg
Cracker requires a commitment to the art. It is not something that
can just be ordered done.
</P>
<P>
   I cracked the eggs myself.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of doing so, I couldn't help but think about what
my daughter had done. It was not such a terrible thing, of course.
In fact, the most remarkable part about it might be that I can
never remember my daughter refusing such a task in her short life.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was something disturbing about it all. I couldn't
help but wonder where my daughter had learned the subtle technique
of brushing someone off. Even more than that, there was something
familiar about that look on her face.
</P>
<P>
   And then it hit me. I knew exactly where she'd learned that
behavior. From me.
</P>
<P>
   And I recognized the look on her face. I knew exactly where I'd
seen it before.
</P>
<P>
   In the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   It all came flooding back to me. Just how many times, sitting at
home in my pink recliner, had she come to me holding a book?
</P>
<P>
   I had read a great many of them, but how many times had a weary
look come over my face? How many times had I frowned, sighed,
rolled my eyes and said ``Do I have to do it right now?''
</P>
<P>
   More times than I can remember or count and they didn't just
have to do with reading, either. I've put her _ and her sister and
brothers _ off on a hundred different subjects a hundred different
times each from reading books to playing catch.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it happened because I was legitimately busy but, as
most of you know (because it is true of yourselves), usually I'm
not too busy, I am just too lazy.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't any wonder, then, that she would do the same to me. It
would only be odd if she did something different. We train our
children to complain, roll their eyes and turn away. If we're
self-absorbed slobs, we can count on our children turning out that
way.
</P>
<P>
   Not that my child is a self-absorbed slob. Not yet. It is my
theory that self-absorbed slobs are made, not born; that if we
weren't such good role models for being self-absorbed, our children
would not learn it so well.
</P>
<P>
   This goes beyond reading books. It is the reason people stay
home in droves on clean-up Marshall day. It is why we have to pay
people (that is, the government) to do some of the good we could be
volunteering to do ourselves. Do it ourselves, that is, if we
weren't busy thinking only of what directly benefits us.
</P>
<P>
   The eggs got cracked, because, after all, that is an easy thing
to do, but in the process something else was broken, something
important and elemental and as fragile as an egg. But unlike
Humpty-Dumpty, you can put caring and sharing your time back
together again. At least I am going to try.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. He can be reached at platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
