<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tree hunting time again
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ We barely had cleared the turkey from the
Thanksgiving table when my wife brought up the dreaded subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to do something about the Christmas tree,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't nag,'' I replied, ``I told you I'm going to take it to
the dump first chance I get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas tree has been behind the shop and out of sight
since we took it down on New Year's Day. All the needles have
dropped off. Only a skeleton remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I should have gotten rid of it,'' I apologized, ``but
with all I have to do now that I don't have a regular job I haven't
had time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about last year's Christmas tree,'' she said.
``It's time to put up this year's tree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be Christmas again!'' I exclaimed. ``If Christmas is
going to come so soon, why didn't we leave the tree up?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping you could get yourself in the spirit of the
season this year,'' she said. ``There's no reason to make an ordeal
of putting up a tree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is when you don't own a crane,'' I replied. ``It wouldn't
be an ordeal if you didn't insist on one the size of a California
redwood. Last year I spent an afternoon and half the night sawing
and hacking so the giant you picked out wouldn't punch a hole in
the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that big when we cut it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I agreed. ``It grew four feet on the way home.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual Christmas tree crisis has been a thorn in our
marriage from the beginning. The 16-foot ceiling in the den of our
house in Fayetteville accommodated a tree approximately the size of
the one Rich's department store hired a crane to hoist atop the
bridge across Forsyth Street.
</P>
<P>
   After several near disasters with size Triple X behemoths, I
persuaded her to move to the farm. The new house created a new
problem. With 16-foot ceilings I could get by with 10 or 12 inches
of air space between the angel and Sheetrock. With our 12-foot
ceilings in the new house, the angel's wings have to brush the
ceiling. Otherwise, the tree is judged too small. Tree selection
has become an exact science. I was surprised when she suggested a
change in the process this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I always pick one that's too tall,'' she said, ``why
don't I stay home and let you pick out the tree.''
</P>
<P>
   I took a broom into the den and measured how much handle I
needed to reach the ceiling. I marked the handle with tape and
headed to my favorite cut-your-own tree farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find one that has a good shape,'' she instructed. ``Sort of
tall, well filled out, but not fat.''
</P>
<P>
   I spent a half-hour wandering through a forest of Leyland
cypress, looking for a tree that would qualify for the Miss America
pageant. I eventually found one with a modest waistline but tall
enough to reach the end of my broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   Sawed down, it looked pitifully small compared to some of our
past specimens. ``You'll never get away with that one,'' observed
my semi-farmer son, who spent the best Decembers of his young life
in harness with his brother, hauling logging-size cedars out of the
forest.
</P>
<P>
   My wife was on one of her not infrequent excursions to the
decadent Phipps-Lenox complex in affluent north Atlanta. ``Get it
inside the house before she gets back,'' the semi-farmer advised.
``If it touches the ceiling you'll have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   I rushed home and began rummaging through the attic in search of
the tree stand. Tree stands tend to vaporize when stored. To my
surprise, I found it where I thought I remembered putting it last
New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The stand slipped easily onto the tree trunk. I didn't have to
saw anything. I eased the tree into the house without removing
doors or shifting furniture. Nothing got knocked on the floor and
broken. I didn't have to say any bad words.
</P>
<P>
   When I wiggled the tree into the usual place in front of the
window and lifted it upright only a inch had to be trimmed off the
top. No wires or ropes were needed to keep it from toppling. I
didn't strain my back or get punched in the eye with a limb. I was
celebrating with a light refreshment when she returned. I was
overwhelmed by her reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the prettiest tree we've ever had!'' she exclaimed.
``It's perfect!''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, miracles really do happen.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
