</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Think sharp when working with 100-year old boards for new floor
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A gentleman in the metro area e-mailed me with a
question that pleased me no end, because it was one I could answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am building a small building in my back yard for my wife to
use as an art studio,'' he wrote. ``I work on the weekends and so
far it has taken me 2 1/2 years. Very early I bought 800 feet of
4x6x16' oak beams from a 100-year-old tobacco warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of it resawn into 5/4 x6x8' boards to use as
flooring. I did not have it tongue and grooved to save money.
Sooner or later I will be laying this flooring. I have looked for
tongue/groove router cutters but none of them will work with 5/4
widths. I have thought of these alternatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Running the boards through a router time after time to
achieve a tongue and groove.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Using a biscuit joiner to join the boards together with
countersunk screws covered by pegs when the boards are laid.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A dado blade on my table saw to achieve the groove and I
guess, with adjustment, the tongue on the other side (again having
to make three passes). Is there a dado blade which can be adjusted
with shims or other spacers to achieve a double cut with the center
left for the tongue?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not have either biscuit joiner or dado blades. Highland
Hardware in their new catalogue has a Dewalt 682k biscuit joiner
for $170. I haven't checked to know if that is a good price and I
don't know if it is good joiner.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as I know the DeWalt is a good biscuit joiner but I
wouldn't use it for this job. Way, way too much work and too many
chances to screw it up.
</P>
<P>
   A router table would be better, but 100-year-old oak out of a
tobacco warehouse is going to be very close in nature to granite.
You would definitely have to make a lot of passes. Again, too much
work.
</P>
<P>
   The natural way to handle this is with dado blades on the table
saw. Once set up, it can be jigged so that it would be very easy to
complete the entire run in two stages without great difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   My friend will have to buy a good dado set. Not the wobbling
kind, but a real multi-blade set, carbide tipped. One can certainly
buy grooving blades, which are wide blades made to cut slots, and
set them up with shims between them to make a double cut. But this
would be quite expensive and not as useful in the long run as the
dado set.
</P>
<P>
   When cutting joints like this I always cut the male section
first; not sure why. I don't think it's very important.
</P>
<P>
   On these 5/4 boards, a 3/8-inch tongue will be just the ticket,
and it doesn't have to be deep. A quarter-inch would suffice.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing we need to do is make a secondary fence with a
piece of 3/4-inch plywood or MDF. Screw it or clamp it to the
fence, and then run the dado cutters up under the outer half of it.
The blades will have to be so close to the fence when we begin
cutting that damage to the actual fence might result.
</P>
<P>
   Once the secondary fence is in place, set up the fence so that
if one pass is made on each side of the board, the result will be a
3/8-inch wide, 1/4-inch deep tongue exactly in the center of the
edge. Mark the face side of each board.
</P>
<P>
   Now set up the cut with some fingerboards or whatever kind of
holders you have so that you can simply feed each board in, first
with the marked side against the fence, second with the unmarked
side against the fence, and with the same edge against the table
(obviously) on each pass. Set up carefully, this should make
accuracy automatic.
</P>
<P>
   Once the tongues are cut, we have to cut the grooves in the
other edge. Once again, take some scrap and set up the fence and
the blades so that a groove that will just accomodate the tongues
will be run down the dead center of the board in one pass. Make it
a tad deeper than the tongue to hold excess glue.
</P>
<P>
   Set up all the fingerboards and other guides, and begin the run,
making certain to keep the face side of each board against the
fence. This will, one hopes, put any unevenness resulting from
varything thickness in the boards on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Make the grooving run, and that should take care of it. But
don't be surprised, depending on how many boards you've got, if you
have to stop at some point and take the dado blades to be
sharpened. Hundred-year-old oak is not something I'm anxious to
encounter. E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
