<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN12-COX     12-11 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Here's one you can knock off my holiday gift list
_ a book called ``Circle Round: Raising Children in Goddess
Traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   This is no doubt a well-meaning, earth-friendly volume. The
co-author is a woman named Starhawk, one of the ``foremost voices
in the women's spirituality movement,'' the dust jacket informs us,
who lives in San Francisco with ``her husband, stepchildren, and
Goddess-children.'' (Apparently the stepchildren didn't make the
Goddess cut, but we won't get into that.)
</P>
<P>
   The book is pegged as ``a one-of-a-kind resource for people of
many faiths and beliefs'' that ``encourages us to gently open
children's awareness to the sacredness of life, our connection to
Mother Earth, and our responsibility to preserve her gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, I'll buy that. Open the first chapter, however, and things
get weird: ``Not long ago I (Starhawk) was part of a circle of
women celebrating the First Blood ritual of my Goddess-daughter
Shannon.''
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, I won't buy that. Why fork over the $25.95,
anyway? My daughter is already firmly convinced she's a goddess. We
have, in fact, invested a considerable amount of energy trying to
convince her otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica is our second child, but we were ill-prepared for her
imperial manner and the thunderstorms of her emotions. Alec was a
docile, eager-to-please toddler.
</P>
<P>
   We always assumed it was because of our superb parenting. That
theory has come under scrutiny since Veronica turned 3. People
always talk about the terrible twos, but in my experience, it's the
threes that are the real terror.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica is loving, she is quiet, she looks like Cindy Lou Who
and she's adorable in pigtails.
</P>
<P>
   And she has a will that rivals Elizabeth I and a temper that
rivals the Queen of Hearts in Alice in Wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   When she's in one of her moods, she won't simply ask for
chocolate milk. ``Mommy, I WANT
chocolatemilkchocolatemilkchocolatemilkCHOCOLATE MILK!'' Her words
run together and her face turns beet red and I'm waiting for her to
shout, ``Off with her head!'' I try hard not to laugh at her 30
pounds of uncontrolled fury because I'm pretty sure that would be
bad parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Veronica is now in the third year, fourth
month of her valiant struggle to remain un-potty-trained. Just ask
John Rosemond: This means we are bad parents and just plain morally
deficient.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rosemond can insult us all he wants if he can just get the
job done. Brag to us all you want about how your kid was
potty-trained at three months, so long as you're ready to take the
Veronica Challenge. We've tried bribes, candy, praise, big-girl
pants, videos. (It's Potty Time, featuring those immortal lyrics,
``She is a super-duper pooper, she can potty with the best.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. Like a tiny Queen Victoria, she insists, ``We will do
things in our own way and in our own time.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked a friend with a teen-age daughter when it starts getting
better. ``You must be kidding?'' she retorted. ``She's a teen-ager.
She thinks she's a goddess every moment of every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there any sanity for the modern parent, any saving grace
between ``goddess traditions'' and John Rosemond? There are oceans
of books and columns out there, telling parents what we're doing
wrong and the five easy steps to perfect children.
</P>
<P>
   Bring 'em on. Let 'em try. I can't wait for the day John
Rosemond knocks on my door.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt he'll achieve instant results with my Goddess-daughter
Veronica.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
