<HEADER>
A4795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-SITES     12-11 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SITES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ROAD TRIPS: CLINTON HEADS TO GAZA, MASADA AND BETHLEHEM
 &HT;    With MIDEAST, MIDEAST-STAKES and MIDEAST-SECURITY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   During his three day visit, President Clinton will spend his
nights in Jerusalem but will be on the road during the day. Here
are destinations on his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   THE GAZA STRIP
</P>
<P>
   The People: Approximately one million Palestinians, two thirds
of them refugees from Israel, as well as 6,000 Israeli settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The Land: A strip along the Mediterranean Sea, about 25 miles
long and three to five miles wide.
</P>
<P>
   The Government: 80 percent controlled by Palestinian National
Authority. The rest is ruled by the Israeli military.
</P>
<P>
   History: A key transit point in the Middle East, Gaza was
settled more than 4000 years ago and has been fought over ever
since. Some believe Samson was buried there. Napoleon camped there.
In 1967, Israel captured it from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The Intifada uprising against Israeli occupation started there
in 1987 and hundreds died over six years of street battles. Israel
began withdrawing its troops under terms of the 1993 Oslo peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Visit: On Monday, Clinton will travel by helicopter to
the first Palestinian airport, opened last month, and watch the
Palestine Liberation Organization reaffirm that it no longer seeks
the destruction of Israel. He will be the first U.S. president to
visit a Palestinian-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, WEST BANK
</P>
<P>
   The People: Approximately 140,000 Palestinians in the city and
suburbs. Adjacent to several large Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The Land: Urban center on rolling hills about 5 miles south of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Government: Almost all Palestinian residents under
Palestinian control. Israeli army controls entrances and site of
Rachel's Tomb, sacred to Jews.
</P>
<P>
   History: Traced back to at least 1400 B.C., this is the
birthplace of King David and Jesus Christ. In 339 A.D., a massive
church was built on the cave believed to be the site of Christ's
birth. Now, the area is mostly Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Visit: On Tuesday, in what aides are calling a
``spiritual visit,'' Clinton will visit the Church of the Nativity
and review preparations for the millennium celebrations. All major
roads are under repair and several buildings are going up. A
cultural center is being built where there used to be a jail used
by the British, then Israelis, then Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   MASADA ARCHAEOLOGICAL SITE:
</P>
<P>
   The Land: Jagged Mount Masada rises dramatically from the barren
desert west of the Dead Sea and a two hour drive south of
Jerusalem. Ruins mark the site of a magnificent cliff-side palace,
water tanks and defense walls.
</P>
<P>
   History: This mountaintop became a Roman fort in 103 B.C. Jewish
rebels eventually took it over and used it to raid neighboring
villages. When the Romans laid siege and broke their defenses in 74
A.D., legend has it, the 960 Jews decided to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   While many historians believe there were just a few suicides and
otherwise a massacre by the Romans, the story is central to Israeli
identity. For years, Israeli troops were taken there for a ceremony
at the end of their training.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Visit: On Tuesday, Clinton will visit the mountaintop.
The stop will give Clinton's day a certain balance to his earlier
stop in Palestinian-dominated Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
