<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SECURITY FOR CLINTON VISIT TAKES DAILY ISRAELI PRECAUTIONS TO
NEW HEIGHTS
 &HT;    For use Saturday with MIDEAST, MIDEAST-STAKES and MIDEAST-SITES
 &HT;    EDS: Originally moved Thursday. Resending for those who missed
it.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM This is the land of high security, but it may never
have been as tight or complex as when President Clinton visits here
beginning Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even on normal days, police stop drivers in the road to ask for
identification and search the trunks of cars entering shopping
malls.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers and settlers routinely walk in restaurants or
stores with M-16s strapped across their backs or revolvers tucked
in their belts. Bomb squad vans constantly patrol the streets,
checking hundreds of suspicious packages each day during times of
suspected terrorist activity.
</P>
<P>
   But never before, according to Israeli police spokeswoman Linda
Menuchin, has there been such a complicated assignment for the
protection of a visiting dignitary.
</P>
<P>
   At times during the three-day visit, as many as 4,450 extra
Israeli police will be assigned to provide security for Clinton _
nearly 20 percent of the police in this small country. There will
be 500 police officers patrolling the area around Clinton's hotel.
</P>
<P>
   This does not include Israeli secret service and army units that
will handle parts of the trip, or the thousands of Palestinian
police on duty when Clinton visits areas they control.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton is coming with what former Israeli secret service
chief Carmi Gillon estimates may be 400 security personnel. If
Clinton's visit is like most other presidential foreign trips, his
security forces will have been in place for weeks examining travel
routes, ``sweeping'' hotel rooms for electronic listening devices,
positioning video cameras to monitor hallways and planting
high-tech equipment around buildings to detect unauthorized
intruders.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, Menuchin pointed out, is that at times Clinton
will be at one site, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will be at
another, daughter Chelsea Clinton will be elsewhere and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright will be in yet another location. All
will need protection. Sixteen members of Congress also will be here
and they will require security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will see efforts of the kind we haven't seen before,'' said
Gillon. ``The issues are much more sharp now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For every terror group, to act against the United States with
all this media around, it is their dream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The issues revolve around the Israeli-Palestinian agreement
negotiated in October at the Wye River Plantation in Maryland. It's
intent was to keep the five-year-old Middle East peace process on
track, but extremists on both sides are dissatisfied with it.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the thousands of police will be near Clinton. Many will
have their hands full trying to patrol areas of East Jerusalem
where Palestinians have been engaged in fierce battles with Israeli
troops in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, police expect right wing Jewish groups to stage
protests. On Thursday, they posted illustrations around Jerusalem
showing Clinton in an Arab head cloth with the caption,
``Palestinian, go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian terrorists have frequently launched attacks in the
days before official U.S. visits. In recent interviews, spokesmen
for Hamas, the militant wing of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, have appeared to try to downplay any threat to
Clinton himself, saying they have never targeted Americans.
</P>
<P>
   However, they said that their organization has small splinter
groups that could act on their own _ statements that maintain the
uncertainty that feeds their image.
</P>
<P>
   In order to help control the environment in
Palestinian-controlled Gaza City, schools and offices will be
closed when Clinton visits on Monday. He will be the first American
president to visit a Palestinian-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli police plan to close major roads used by Clinton for
several hours at a time and will tow away cars parked along the
route, presumably out of fear that they might be rigged with
remotely-triggered bombs.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several days, U.S. security specialists have been
working on phone and radio systems to be used during Clinton's
visit. U.S. military helicopters, including one appearing to be
Clinton's white-topped official chopper, have conducted days of
</P>
<P>
   maneuvers above Jerusalem, Gaza and Bethlehem, the birthplace of
Jesus where Clinton also will visit.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
