<SLUG> BC-COKE-CADBURY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke buys rival brands abroad
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co. is buying Cadbury Schweppes'
beverage brands in 120 countries, in a deal estimated at $1.85
billion, the companies announced today.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement, Coca-Cola warned analysts the
company's fourth-quarter earnings, expected to come in at 30 cents
per share, would be 24 cents to 25 cents per share. The company
blamed volatile sales in many overseas markets that have been
facing economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Trading of Coca-Cola on the New York Stock Exchange was delayed
this morning because of the company's news, which was expected to
impact share prices.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, which does not cover Cadbury Schweppes'
business in the United States, France and South Africa, includes
Schweppes and Canada Dry mixers, Dr. Pepper and Crush, and beverage
plants in Ireland and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is subject to regulatory review in a number of
countries, but is anticipated to be completed in mid-1999,
Coca-Cola said.
</P>
<P>
   M. Douglas Ivester, Coca-Cola's chairman and chief executive,
discussed the deal this morning with analysts in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``These agreements will allow the Coca-Cola Co. to participate
in segments of the beverage business where it currently does not
have meaningful entries,'' he said in a statement. ``The Cadbury
Schweppes brands will be a wonderful addition to the core brands of
the Coca-Cola Company.''
</P>
<P>
   John Sunderland, chief executive of London-based Cadbury
Schweppes, said the deal will create ``substantial value for our
shareowners and simultaneously enhance our ability to develop and
focus on our strong global confectionary and U.S. beverage
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Schweppes is the world's No. 3 soft drink company,
behind No. 1 Coca-Cola and No. 2 Pepsico. The acquisition will give
Coca-Cola, which now has a 50 percent worldwide market share, about
3 additional share points.
</P>
<P>
   It also will give Cadbury Schweppes an influx of cash to become
a larger player in the world's confectionary business and help
bankroll its bottling and distribution system in the United States,
where it relies largely on Pepsico, Coca-Cola Enterprises and
small, independent bottlers to get its soft drinks to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry insiders today expressed confidence in the
Cadbury Schweppes deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes abundant sense if you're Coca-Cola because there's
one goal, and that goal is straightforward: To continue to build
world share. To build world share, you need brands, and you need
systems,'' said Tom Pirko, a New York-based beverage consultant.
</P>
<P>
   John Sicher, editor of trade publication Beverage Digest, said
Cadbury Schweppes' brands will have more opportunity to grow
worldwide through the Coca-Cola system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a deal that works for both parties,'' he said. ``And
it will give them an infusion of a substantial amount of money to
continue to do two things: Build their brands in the U.S. and
perhaps even more importantly, to continue to consolidate the
independent bottling system.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lang, an analyst at Henderson Crosthwaite, said the deal
``sorts out the places where Cadbury's systems weren't strong
enough to compete with Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fighting with PepsiCo for their market share. It was
a murderous battle, and they were getting nowhere with it. This
gives them a war chest for investment and for buying back shares.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal will affect about 450 Cadbury Schweppes employees, who
will have the opportunity to take jobs with Coca-Cola, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news from a strategic point of view,'' said Julia
Bannon, an analyst at Paribas. ``It's another example of how
Cadbury is refocusing. If you look at the share price, the market
is telling us it thinks it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the sale, Cadbury also will sell its bottling
businesses outside the United States. The company is talking to
potential buyers for the businesses, which Cadbury said are worth
about $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Cadbury Schweppes PLC entered a joint venture with
U.S.-based Carlyle Group to acquire two soft-drink bottlers,
Beverage America and Select Beverages, for $724 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was seen as an important step by Cadbury to secure its
distribution system for soft drinks such as 7Up, Dr Pepper, Canada
Dry, Sunkist and A&AMP;W. Cadbury trails Coca-Cola and Pepsi-Cola Co.
in the $55 billion U.S. soft drink industry.
</P>
<P>
   Other news services contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
