<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (Eds: The following column can be held for next week, or can
substitute, as more timely, for the column that moved Thursday, and
Thursday's column can hold for next week.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Schippers' sarcastic rant sums it up
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his summation of the case against President Clinton, David
Schippers, prosecuting attorney for the Republican majority, hit
just the right note to end the Judiciary Committee's impeachment
hearings and cap the six years' pursuit of the president that had
led to them: Sour. Rank.
</P>
<P>
   Not content to lay out the evidence and coach the committee in
the conclusions he believed the evidence would justify, Schippers
was by turns sneering, sarcastic, contemptuous and mocking toward
the president _ in the service, he oddly insisted, of preserving
the dignity of the office.
</P>
<P>
   Even Americans who judge the case properly fatal to the Clinton
presidency should be unnerved by the obvious venom of Schippers'
chosen rhetoric _ carried to the point of, in effect, counseling
other governments never again to trust Clinton's word as president.
(A nice little service to the republic, that.)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, the lawyer salted his performance with expressions of
regret at his unpleasant duty, but his every attitude shouted a
contrary relish for his own studied excesses. This was not the
sober, measured summing up that so solemn a constitutional moment
called for. It was a barroom peroration, with Clinton _ at long
last, for the eager claque of his committed haters _ as scheming,
devious, sexually wanton and endlessly lawless. Clinton as pure
evil.
</P>
<P>
   That is the Clinton hunted from the moment of his first election
by a richly bankrolled and indefatigable array of right-wing
political operatives, fax-driven radio ranters and evangelical
personality assassins. And, of course, crucially, the Clinton
submitted, uniquely among presidents, to a permanent special
prosecution peculiarly licensed to chase every howl sent up by the
hounds.
</P>
<P>
   It should disturb every American _ as it does most, at least
most outside Congress _ that at the end Clinton and the nation have
been brought to constitutional crisis by a trap set for the
president by a politically scheming book agent manipulating an
avaricious tattle and using the (witting? unwitting?) special
prosecutor to service a meritless lawsuit that conservative
activists had provoked Paula Jones to file.
</P>
<P>
   The House will be judging not just Clinton but his pursuers and
their pursuit as well. Impeachment not only would propose the
ultimate sanction for the president's misdeeds but would endorse _
and, endorsing, install as a permanent and devastating feature of
our political life _ the disturbing means by which they were
brought to light.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lies and other misbehaviors in the Lewinsky
matter do count; they warrant the stinging and humiliating rebuke
in the strong censure proposed by Democrats. Schippers' rant to the
contrary notwithstanding, what we have here is not an
out-of-control president, as we had in Richard Nixon, but an errant
husband trying to tiptoe back into the house at 4 in the morning
and tripping over the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Do we take down two elections for that?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
