<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, December 12, 1998 and
Sunday, December 13, 1998 are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: Either of the following columns from Tom Teepen can run
Sunday. The Schippers column was moved Friday as a bonus and would
be more timely. Either way, the column not used Sunday would stand
as the offering that would have moved Monday of next week.)
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The U.S. Supreme Court justices in a recent
ruling seemed shocked, shocked that Iowa police had got it into
their heads they could search any drivers and cars they pulled over
for routine traffic violations. But the court needed only to look
at its own rulings in recent years to see where the idea came from
that privacy claims have little standing against the claims of law
enforcement convenience. MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN-BONUS _ In his summation of the case against
President Clinton, David Schippers, prosecuting attorney for the
Republican majority, hit just the right note to end the Judiciary
Committee's impeachment hearings and cap the six years' pursuit of
the president that had led to them: Sour. Rank. (Teepen, Cox News
Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ We all probably have a gene somewhere
that remembers the ice age and the great glaciers. Weather, like
its big sister Nature, makes us feel smaller and less in control.
There is considerable evidence supporting that view. (Rosenfeld,
Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Last Sunday, I did two
things: went to church, where the service concluded with a rousing,
five-stanza rendition of ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic,'' which
is one of my favorite hymns, and strung Christmas lights. It's a
good thing I went to church first. Or maybe I should have gone back
afterward. Stringing Christmas lights can make a man forget his
religion in a hurry. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED
FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Wrapping up the year's events
with a yuletide rhyme. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ I couldn't help but wonder where my daughter had
learned the subtle technique of brushing someone off. Even more
than that, there was something familiar about that look on her
face. And then it hit me. I knew exactly where she'd learned that
behavior. From me. And I recognized the look on her face. I knew
exactly where I'd seen it before. In the mirror. (Latham, Marshall
(TX) News Messenger) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ The dreaded chore: Picking
out this year's Christmas tree. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Is there any sanity for the modern parent, any
saving grace between ``goddess traditions'' and John Rosemond?
There are oceans of books and columns out there, telling parents
what we're doing wrong and the five easy steps to perfect children.
Bring 'em on. Let 'em try. I can't wait for the day John Rosemond
knocks on my door. No doubt he'll achieve instant results with my
Goddess-daughter Veronica. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg's column FOR SUNDAY will not
be available this week.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVES THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY
</P>
