   NEW NOTICE: Versions of some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   SICKLE-TRANSPLANT _ ATLANTA _ An update on Keone Penn, who
underwent the first-ever cord blood transplant for sickle cell
disease on Friday. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   STRESS-BOOKS _ You said you wouldn't let the holidays get to
you, and you have. Ten stress-relievers from the people who wrote
the book(s) on stress. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX _ American scientists have come up with the first agents
to neutralize bioweapons. University of Michigan researchers this
fall developed a bleach-like substance that safely and effectively
destroys bacteria and viruses. And a second team at Sandia National
Laboratories has produced a new decontaminant foam as non-toxic as
hair conditioner. These two products may revolutionize the way we
think about killing viruses and bacteria, and reduce the terror and
the threat of biological warfare. (Orent, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   AUS-STAR _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Genesis has one version of creation,
astronomy another. Astronomy says we all come from a supernova, a
star whose explosion seeded what became Earth and us with calcium,
carbon, and the 101 other chemical elements in the sun, the planets
and our bodies. Sneden and colleagues, on the trail of our ancestor
supernova, believe they've found a solid clue: a unique star in the
halo around the Milky Way that may have been the first recipient of
the supernova's seeding. (Stanley, Austin American-Statesman) FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ARTS/ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   KISS-INTERVIEW _ DAYTON, Ohio _ An interview with Gene Simmons
of freak band Kiss. (Simmons, Dayton Daily News) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MILNER-COLUMN _ Now that December is upon us again, although it
hasn't been all that noticeable as far as the weather is concerned,
why not think about giving books for Christmas gifts? (Milner, Cox
News Service) MOVED FOR SATURDAY (also moved in the commentary
category)
</P>
<P>
   ART-TRENDS _ What were the trends in the arts this year?
(Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ART-LISTS _This year's hits and misses in the arts - visual,
theater, film, music. (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-HOLIDAY _ Downsizing for the holidays: People are putting
the tenets of the simplicity movement to work during this
most-stressful season of the year. You don't have to send Christmas
cards or buy gifts for everyone. Will include a countdown of simple
things you can do in the days leading to Christmas that the family
with enjoy, without a lot of planning and work. (Sundquist, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-TIPS _ Specific ways to simplify the holidays. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).18. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Options when trying to use
100-year-old boards for new floor. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-PLANTS _ Holiday plants, from poinsettias and Christmas
cacti to Jerusalem cherries and boxwood topiaries, are becoming a
practical and enticing alternative to Christmas trees, especially
for those with small apartments. We'll take a look at what's hot
this year, new varieties, the myths about toxicity, some trivia and
throw in some tips on how to care for holiday plants. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-POSTPONE _ Research of a California sociologist confirms
what doctors and hospice workers have long know, people who are
terminally ill can often postpone _ or hasten _ their death to
coincide with a major event of psychological importance in their
lives. (Powell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Photo is of a hospice worker and a terminally ill girl,
Sholanda Benson, who has metachromatic leukodystrophy, a fatal
genetic disease. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   HANUKKAH _ It's a minor holiday in the overall scheme of things,
but this Jewish festival that celebrates freedom has become a major
happening because it falls around Christmas. Jewish day schools and
pre-schools stay busy this time of year focusing on the real
message of Hannukah and trying to explain that the ancient hero of
the Hanukkah story, Judah Maccabbee, is not some sort of Semitic
Santa Claus. (Feinberg, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA _ We visit Chattanooga's hip neighborhood Bluff
View, with its trendy galleries, shops, restaurants and B&AMP;B, for a
holiday-oriented destination story. Also, includes other holiday
doings in Chattanooga: Enchanted Nights of Lights at Rock City,
Victorian Chrismtas at the Choo-Choo and Dive Into Winter at the
Tennessee Aquarium, last-minute bargains at Warehouse Row.
(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
