<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Dec. 11, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ There aren't many tougher experiences
in life as when you lose your job. It doesn't really make any
difference if you get cut loose because your company filed for
bankruptcy protection or because you were a lousy employee _ it's
still extremely painful. And one of the first worries is how to
find another job. To help ease that transition, many employers
offer severance pay, continue to subsidize the cost of medical
insurance for a time and offer outplacement assistance. By L.M.
SIXEL
</P>
<P>
   POWER-OUTAGE (San Francisco) _ An apologetic PG&AMP;E promised not
to sock customers with the cost of claims stemming from Tuesday's
massive blackout, but said its stockholders will pay up to $10
million in claims. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ For 3D realism and state-of-the-art
game technology, nothing beats Sierra Studio's Half-Life. That is,
so long as you're playing it alone. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-STARTREK (Undated) _ ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' is
even more brain-numbingly stupid than ``Star Trek V: The Final
Frontier,'' which had Kirk and Spock singing ``Row, Row, Row Your
Boat'' around a campfire. This gives Jonathan Frakes the dubious
distinction of having unseated William Shatner as director of the
worst Trek movie in existence. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STARTREK-REVIEW (Undated) _ There are problems in the
``Trek'' universe. But don't blame the cast of ``Star Trek: The
Next Generation,'' now in their third big-screen effort. The
problems with the new movie, ``Star Trek: Insurrection,`` stem from
the screenplay by Michael Piller. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PACKERS-INJURIES (San Francisco) _ Have you seen the Green
Bay Packers lately? In fact, you haven't. Nobody has. This week's
Packers' injured list includes a broken collarbone, a torn
hamstring, a broken ankle, a broken jaw, four knees, three
shoulders and ... well, 17 players are on blocks, 13 questionable,
doubtful or just plain out. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ At one time or another, almost
everybody has neighbor problems. I know I have. I'm recounting this
story because it's a vivid example of the law's shortcomings in
preventing threatening situations from becoming tragedies. By DAN
LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Tuesday morning's major power
outage brought commerce to a halt and cost the city, Pacific Gas &AMP;
Electric and businesses large and small untold millions of dollars.
I'm sorry about that, but I sure enjoyed the way everything in San
Francisco got ratcheted waaaay down. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Oakland, Calif.) _ Two days before ``60 Minutes''
showed Dr. Jack Kevorkian apparently injecting a terminally ill man
with a lethal dose of medicine, my wife and I faced some hard
questions about life and death ourselves. We were in an attorney's
office, signing something called ``Durable Power of Attorney for
Health Care.'' By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
<P>
   PEARL-HARBOR (Danville, Calif.) _ To millions of Americans, the
meaning of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor went far beyond the
end of neutrality and the beginning of war. With a combination of
shock, fear and moral outrage, the 2-hour raid evolved from an
unforgivable act into an inspiration, becoming the defining moment
of an entire generation. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
</TEXT>
