<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-STARTREK-     12-11 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-STARTREK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TREK MOVIE DESERVES TO BE LOST IN SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' the worst Trek movie ever made?
</P>
<P>
   Let us rephrase this. Are Klingons crabby? Do Ferengi cheat? Is
Deanna Troi doomed to intergalactic ridiculousness?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to all of the above questions is: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   In case anyone was wondering, ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' is
even more brain-numbingly stupid than ``Star Trek V: The Final
Frontier,'' which had Kirk and Spock singing ``Row, Row, Row Your
Boat'' around a flickering campfire. This gives Jonathan Frakes the
dubious distinction of having unseated William Shatner as director
of the worst Trek movie in existence. Someone phone Shatner; he'll
be glad to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Frakes directed the previous Trek outing, 1996's ``Star Trek:
First Contact'' (the first that exclusively featured the cast of
``Star Trek: The Next Generation''), with humor and competence, so
there was no cause to expect his second effort to be so
painstakingly bad. Then again, there was no cause to expect a movie
in which Worf's acne, Troi's ``boobs'' and Data's butt are major
punch lines.
</P>
<P>
   There's a giddy, cliff's-edge quality to the whole thing, as
though the actors laughed when they read the script, then murdered
their agents in despair. ``Can anyone remember when we used to be
explorers?'' asks the ever-upright Capt. Jean-Luc Picard (Patrick
Stewart, giddiest of all), to which the weary Trek fan must reply:
I wish I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who never cared about ``Star Trek'' has no reason to
mourn, of course. But for those of us who were weaned on ``Star
Trek,'' who worshiped the old show and gobbled up the new ones and
saw the first few movies multiple times, this deterioration of the
Trek realm is nothing short of tragic. It's Star Dreck.
</P>
<P>
   Things are pretty dippy from the beginning, as the film opens on
an agrarian idyll where white people dressed in earth-tone clothing
are kneading bread and blissfully smiling at each other. Imagine
how surprised they all are when a renegade android, who turns out
to be a malfunctioning Commander Data, crashes into their paradise
and holds them hostage for no compelling reason.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is particularly clear, but it seems that Data was
part of a hush-hush mission to observe the smiling bread-makers.
The mission, we sort of learn, is a joint effort between the
Federation, embodied by an augustly bearded but
not-entirely-trustworthy admiral (Anthony Zerbe), and a group of
shifty aliens called the Son'a. The Son'a, in the grand tradition
of repulsive bad guys (remember the Borg Queen?), look like poster
children for Facelift Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The head Son'a (a vaguely recognizable F. Murray Abraham) makes
his entrance in the middle of cosmetic surgery _ we get to see a
surgeon pull his face back, then clip it to his skull with metal
clasps. Several reels later, he dispatches an opponent with a
deadly eye tuck. Scary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back on the ship, Picard's first officer, Riker
(played by Frakes), is busy cooing at his old flame, ship's
counselor Deanna Troi (Marina Sirtis). They steal kisses, share a
bubble bath and grin stupidly through several scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Even more irritating is the movie's insistent jokiness, which
pushes a horrid, forced hilarity on all of the regulars. Among the
movie's many low points is a sequence in which Picard and the
malfunctioning Data, captaining separate shuttles, engage in a
cat-and-mouse space race while belting out a tune from ``H.M.S.
Pinafore.'' At one point, Data actually pulls up beside Picard and
glares at him through the window, like a dude in a muscle car
looking to drag.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay is credited to Michael Piller, who's been
involved as producer or creative consultant in all of Trek's recent
television incarnations, which probably accounts for its awkwardly
paced dialogue and bloated-episode plotting. Conversations are
stuffed with inside references (the Dominion, Data's emotion chip,
past romances) and the sort of incomprehensible techno-talk that
Trekkers have come to expect (much blabbing about torque sensors
and multiphasic particles and positronic matrixes).
</P>
<P>
   But where previous Trek outings have snared viewers' interest
with engaging characters and philosophic story lines, this one is
content to crack a few bad jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Jean-Luc, you used to be explorers. And, whoops, we used to
care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4989 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     12-11 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSCIENCE AND A VOTE ON IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pro-impeachment crowd is urging members of the House of
Representatives to ``vote their conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could argue with that? All of us hope and expect that
members of Congress will vote their conscience on every issue that
comes before them.
</P>
<P>
   But when people who favor impeachment expound on the
requirements of conscience, they are obviously suggesting that the
only vote a righteous conscience could produce would be ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to intimidate congressional fence-sitters _ mostly
moderate Republicans _ into voting for impeachment by defining a
``yes'' vote as a vote of conscience and a ``no'' vote as something
less than that.
</P>
<P>
   But is it? In this rare business of impeaching the president of
the United States, how can anyone know for sure who is guided by
conscience and who is following some lesser instinct?
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who has followed the House Judiciary Committee's
hearings could attest, the impeachment issue is totally immersed in
partisan gamesmanship. There are probably committee members who are
driven by conscience rather than politics, but how can we know for
sure?
</P>
<P>
   Republicans seem to sincerely believe that President Clinton has
committed high crimes and misdemeanors in connection with the
sex-and-lies scandal that has dogged him for 11 months. Democrats
seem to sincerely believe that Clinton's conduct, though
reprehensible, does not rise to the level of impeachability.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a sense that the Republican majority on the
Judiciary Committee would gladly impeach Clinton for felonious
lip-biting, while the Democratic minority would grimly defend him
if he had robbed an armored car at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Americans with no ax to grind either way might also suspect that
the pro-impeachment and anti-impeachment forces would simply switch
sides if the president facing impeachment happened to be a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Wild-eyed partisanship is nothing new in American politics. But
in times of crisis, this country has often transcended political
concerns because of politicians who truly followed the dictates of
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   One such individual was Sen. Edmund G. Ross, who cast the
deciding vote in the 1868 impeachment trial of President Andrew
Johnson. Ross voted to acquit Johnson of the charges against him,
denying the president's opponents the two-thirds majority that the
Constitution requires for conviction and removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   The vote effectively ended Ross's political career and wrecked
his life, according to ``Profiles in Courage,'' John F. Kennedy's
book about political figures who followed their conscience at great
cost to themselves. The charges against Johnson were mostly
unfounded and politically motivated, Kennedy wrote, but public
sentiment at the time favored removal of the president; Ross's vote
allowing Johnson to remain in office made the Kansas senator a
target of widespread indignation, relentless ridicule and even
``physical attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how Ross explained his vote in subsequent writings, as
quoted by Kennedy:
</P>
<P>
   ``If ... the President must step down ... a disgraced man and a
political outcast ... upon insufficient proofs and from partisan
considerations, the office of President would be degraded, cease to
be a coordinate branch of the government, and ever after
subordinated to the legislative will. It would practically have
revolutionized our splendid political fabric into a partisan
Congressional autocracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross' vote 130 years ago might have nothing to do with the 1998
impeachment debate. Or it might have a lot to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   If most Americans don't want Clinton impeached _ as the opinion
polls suggest _ but the Republican-controlled Congress impeaches
him anyway, is our country facing the prospect of a ``partisan
Congressional autocracy''?
</P>
<P>
   And if it all comes down to one vote, will that vote be cast by
someone whose conscience is ruled by political partisanship _ or by
someone with the courage of Edmund G. Ross?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
