<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4997 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FANTASY-FOOTBALL-AZR &LR;      12-11 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANTASY-FOOTBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF ANGST GRIPPING OWNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - These are nervous times for fantasy owners.
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to spend all year fighting to get to the playoffs,
only to lose because a quarterback sprains his ankle in the first
quarter, or a receiver spends the day nursing a sore leg?
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the guys who started Jacksonville quarterback Mark
Brunell or Minnesota's Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   With that playoff angst in mind, my fearless fantasy predictions
for some of this week's NFL match-ups:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona at Philadelphia: Eagles running back Duce Staley should
leave cleat marks all over the Cardinals, who are decimated on the
defensive line as they wait for Eric Swann to undergo radical
bunion surgery. I don't expect much from the Cardinals running
attack, though Jake Plummer should be good for two or three scores.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago at Green Bay: Look for Bears wide receiver Bobby Engram
to have a nice game against the Packers, whose pass rush has gone
the way of all cheese. This would be a bounce-back for Brett Favre,
but his receiver corps is hurting. Heck, Max McGee was trying out
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati at Indianapolis: Neil O'Donnell fall down and go
boom, so the Bengals will play quarterback roulette. Running back
Corey Dillon should break out against the Colts, whose run defense
consists mainly of yelling ``You come back here right this
minute!''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas at Kansas City: The Chiefs can't tackle Grandmama, so
Emmitt Smith should bounce back. Deion Sanders' toe still hurts, so
Rich Gannon might have fun against the Dallas secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Denver at New York Giants: If you have Broncos, you know what to
do. If anybody scores points for New York, it will be running back
Gary Brown or backfield mate Charles Way. My money is on a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota at Baltimore: They may have to call this one in the
early rounds. Cris Carter is iffy, though he's always played with
minor injuries before. Trouble is, the Vikings don't really need
him.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland at Buffalo: Don't expect Doug Flutie to excel against
the Raiders defense, which is top-rated against the pass. The
Raiders passing game is a mess _ Donald Hollas threw six
interceptions against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh at Tampa Bay: They're dumping beer on Kordell Stewart
in the Steel City, and Jerome Bettis is starting to look like just
another fat guy. I like Bucs receiver Reidel Anthony since
Pittsburgh's Carnell Lake will have to cover Bert Emmanuel.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee at Jacksonville: With Brunell sitting this one out,
Jaguars running back Fred Taylor _ who ran for a team-record 183
yards last week _ will have to carry the load. Jacksonville backup
quarterback Jamie Martin isn't half bad, so receivers Jimmy Smith
and Keenan McCardell are worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   Washington at Carolina: Trent Green has looked OK lately, but
he's lost two of his top receivers _ Michael Westbrook and James
Thrash. Terry Allen was as rusty as a pasture gate last week.
Carolina running back Tshimanga Biakabutuka has taken Fred Lane's
job.
</P>
<P>
   New York Jets at Miami: The Jets dominated the Dolphins in Week
5, so I wouldn't expect much from running back Karim Abdul-Jabbar
or Dan Marino. Look for Jets wide receiver Wayne Chrebet to light
it up from the slot position this week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Waiver wire
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chargers running back Terrell Fletcher would be a nice addition
to any backfield. Seahawks receiver Mike Pritchard is starting to
heat it up. I also like Panthers receiver Muhsin Muhammad. &QL; 
 &QL; 
One-hit wonder
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, it's Saints wide receiver Andre Hastings, who had 122
yards and a touchdown against the Cowboys, who actually used
mannequins in the secondary Sunday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
