<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-11 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SERVE BUT NOT TO PROTECT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The woman lives in an Albany suburb. I'm keeping
her name to myself because she seems to have trouble enough
already. Her problem is the neighbor from Hell.
</P>
<P>
   At one time or another, almost everybody has neighbor problems.
I know I have. I'm recounting this story because it's a vivid
example of the law's shortcomings in preventing threatening
situations from becoming tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This started about three-and-a-half years ago,'' the woman
said. ``My daughter was walking home from school, and she dropped
some flour from a school project in the road. It was a very small
amount, about half the size of a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a neighbor who lives two doors away. He flipped out,
started swearing at her. She ran home. My husband was mowing the
lawn. This guy came up on our property and started swearing at my
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since then, this guy has driven over my lawn, thrown
apples in my pool. We have a lot of police reports on this, to back
this all up. Anyway, we ended up getting an order of protection _ a
temporary one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute I got it, he violated it the next day. My kids were
on their way to school, and he started swearing at them. My one
daughter, she was 11 at the time, and my other daughter was 9. They
were going to the school bus, and this guy starts calling them
whores.''
</P>
<P>
   This neighbor, the woman said, is one strange guy. He's 40ish,
lives alone in a house with heavily draped windows. He doesn't seem
to work. He seems to spend much of his time calling the IRS or the
building inspector or the dog warden to report the woman and her
family for imaginary violations of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls all those places where you don't have to give a
name,'' the woman explained.
</P>
<P>
   The woman finally had the guy arrested after he exposed himself
to her kids during one of his screaming fits. She ended up with
another protection order that required the guy to stay away from
her property and her kids for a year. He then swore out a complaint
against her, alleging that she'd thrown a cup of coffee at him. She
didn't do that, she said, but she had to hire a lawyer and spend
some money before a local court dropped the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Now the order of protection has expired, and this woman is
frightened. She has a guy living two doors away who has engaged in
bizarre, hostile behavior toward her and her family. She has seen
him lurking around the store she manages in another town, well away
from the neighborhood where she and this guy live. A local cop
familiar with this situation backs up the woman's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's a head case,'' the officer said. ``She's a very
nice lady ... He has been arrested for a couple different things.
He has tormented the living daylights out of her ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I would venture to say that he has some type of mental illness
... It's frustrating for us. I want to go up there to give this guy
a blanket party to get him to leave her alone, but I obviously
can't do that ... So far, he has shown no violent tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, hey,'' the officer told me, ``you never know. The scary
part with this guy is that he just persists. He won't let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman is now afraid that something horrible is going to
happen here. And, she realizes, there's nothing the authorities can
do to help until and unless it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they told me,'' she said, ``is that, `We don't take care
of the beginning. We take care of the end.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
