A5032 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IN-VITRO-PREGNANCIES-     12-11 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IN-VITRO-PREGNANCIES-AND-BACK-PAIN-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN-VITRO FERTILIZATION IS A PAIN IN THE BACK  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., DEC. 14, 1998)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By JON COPLEY  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women who become pregnant through in-vitro fertilization suffer
twice as much back pain as those with natural pregnancies,
researchers in Sweden have found.
</P>
<P>
   Per Kristiansson and his colleagues at the University of Uppsala
asked a group of women to keep a record of when they had back pain
during late pregnancy. Those with IVF pregnancies reported pain
twice as often as women with natural pregnancies (``Human
Reproduction,'' vol. 13, p. 3,233), and those with most pain had
the highest concentrations of the hormone relaxin in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxin is produced by the ovaries during pregnancy, and IVF
drugs which stimulate the ovaries to produce eggs increase the
levels. The hormone loosens ligaments that hold the hip bones
together, and Kristiansson believes this causes the pain because
bones can grind together. ``This may be a drawback to high levels
of relaxin,'' Kristiansson says. ``Maybe there are others too.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid such side effects in IVF patients, Kristiansson
suggests stimulating the ovaries and extracting the egg cells as
usual, but then freezing them. If eggs are later inserted in a
normal menstrual cycle rather than one boosted with IVF drugs, the
levels of relaxin in any resulting pregnancy should be normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would seem to be a good way to approach that problem,''
agrees Randall Renegar, an endocrinologist at East Carolina
University in Greenville, N.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
