<HEADER>
A5034 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONG-BULL-NYT &LR;      12-11 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONG-BULL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 497 for Dec. 11  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Dec. 9-10, 1998. This is not the National Football League,
where all referees are infallible, all coin tosses are heads and
the ball doesn't have to make it into the end zone if the ball
carrier's mother lives somewhere in that direction. This is the
Burned-Out Newspapercreatures Guild, where referees are invited to
pull our finger and this is BONG Bull No. 497!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO TELL IF YOU'RE BURNED OUT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You may be a burned-out newspaperman or newspaperwoman if:
</P>
<P>
   _You know at least four newsroom managers who have no clippings
in their clip files.
</P>
<P>
   _You keep forgetting the difference between a staff car and a
trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   _You think the secretarial staff is right, enough cake-and-punch
parties do make us Pulitzer Prize material.
</P>
<P>
   _You personally know at least five felons, and one or more was
on the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   _You always circulate a memo saying, ``I will be out of the
office this afternoon; anyone needing a problem solved, see Wally''
and then one day you forgot and no one noticed, even Wally.
</P>
<P>
   _You don't think it's about sex or perjury either.
</P>
<P>
   _You don't recognize more than half the bylines on Page 1, any
of the isues mentioned on the editorial page, three vegetables on
the food page even by their pictures, or the Diversity Committee's
right to tell you what to put in your coffee.
</P>
<P>
   _You and your bartender have decided it's more convenient to pay
your bar tab weekly.
</P>
<P>
   _You laugh when you think about Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   _You have no idea what the writing coach is talking about but
that's all right because the writing coach refuses to talk to you
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   _You've seen at least two newspaper redesigns in 20 years return
to the original look.
</P>
<P>
   _You're the one all the reporters ask about really historic
stuff, like things that happened in the Carter administration and
when ball parks had grass in them.
</P>
<P>
   _You do at least three things a day that the security guards
have code numbers for.
</P>
<P>
   _Your annual review includes witness statements about what you
said when your supervisor suggested you attend a newspaper seminar
on your vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   _You don't want your mother to know the nickname the newspaper
librarians have for you.
</P>
<P>
   _The last time you smiled was when you got the last staff car.
</P>
<P>
   _You don't own a watch or a suit worth having cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   _You remember what caused five stains on the newsroom floor, and
two of them are from before the carpet was installed.
</P>
<P>
   _You don't know where your copy of the style book is.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT BAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Bunch adds to last week's anecdote about Bat Masterson,
sportswriter, that in fact the famous gunfighter spent more time in
his life as a reporter than he did slinging iron. It seems so
unfair that he should have been portrayed on early TV for his minor
accomplishments, instead of his action-packed years as a boxing
writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did keep a .45 on hand ... in his desk drawer,'' Bunch
said. ``Which he used whenever a fan looked him up in New York.
He'd allow the fan to wine and dine (Delmonico's by preference)
him, then lead the conversation around to `Well, haven't got much
from the old days ... except ol' Betsy here (dragging open the desk
drawer), which I sure don't need in this big city...love to let her
go ... but only to somebody who'd appreciate her...'
</P>
<P>
   ``Which was the cue for the slavering fan to dig out great
stacks of greenbacks, and Masterson would reluctantly pass the
smokepole across. The fan would disappear, and the chuckling
Masterson would head for the nearest pawn shop, buy another .45
for, say, $10 (new ones were going for $15) and bait the trap for
the next sucker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that when Masterson kicked, and all of the guys who
owned `Bat's original Peacemaker' came out of the woodwork, the
screaming was shrill and varied.''
</P>
<P>
   Bat died at his New York Telegraph typewriter on Oct. 25, 1921,
aged 67. In his machine was found the beginning of a column about
luck coming out fairly even for everyone. Rich or poor, for
instance, everyone gets about the same amoung of ice. But the rich
take theirs in summer, and the poor get it in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Bunch: cbunch(at)willapabay.org
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMIX SECTION. &LR;  The Further Adventures of Herman ``Speed''
Graphic, Ace Photographer for the Chagrin Falls Commercial
Scimitar, and his Faithful Companion, Typo the Wonder Pig.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL ONE: &LR;  The Deft Duo sit raptly watching the Judiciary
Committee hearings when Speed, in his trenchcoat, a deathbed gift
from an ancient mystic wire service executive editor on a
fog-shrouded eastern island, remarks, ``I don't know, Typo! I think
I would remember if I ever gave a hatpin to a young woman such as
her!'' Looking up from his Racing Form, Typo starts, ``If you mean
she's zaftig say zaftig, Boss! You don't have to use kindly terms
because I'm sensitive about my (sniff) waistline!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL TWO: &LR;  Speed defends, ``No, Typo! I'm talking about gifts
in general! Does that woman in the gallery behind the committee
counsel look like Absentee Publisher Gimlet Peen in his tango
costume? Would you give her a present without expecting something
in return?'' Typo enquires, ``Something in return? You mean like
signing an affidavit?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL THREE: &LR;  Speed queries, ``And what about the women in the
gallery, Typo? How come at all these Washington hearings, you
always see a mysterious, semi-exotic woman in the seats right
behind the witness, and nobody ever says who she is?'' Typo scoffs,
``That's what I like about you, Boss! Despite all the bruises, down
deep you're still basically a romantic ...!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL FOUR: &LR;  Typo's eyes turn to pinwheels as electricity
passes between him and a mysterious, semi-exotic woman in the seats
right behind the witness.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL FIVE: &LR;  Speed tries to restrain his pal, exhorting,
``Typo! Typo! You can't just convert the copy desk coffee urn to a
low-orbit rocket and take off without the editors' permission!''
Typo asserts, ``Outa my way, Boss! I'm off to the nation's capital
and my date with destiny! And I don't care if it does convert the
coffee to a potent aphrodisiac, against whose effects only copy
editors are immune!''
</P>
<P>
   In the corner of the panel a popout scroll reads: ``UH-OH!''
</P>
<P>
   In matters of romance a heretic to copy desk superstition, BONG
Chief Copyboy Charley Stough, Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St.,
Dayton, Ohio 45401 greets NYTNS rose-droppers worldwide. Phone
(937) 225-2445 after 5 p.m. eastern. Fax 225-2489. E-mail
copyboy(at)dma.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
