A5036 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRANSPLANTS-AND-TIMIN     12-11 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPLANTS-AND-TIMING-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPLANTS GO BETTER WITH THE RIGHT TIMING  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., DEC. 14, 1998)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By RACHEL NOWAK  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Liver transplant patients may be less likely to reject their new
organs if the use of immunosuppressant drugs is delayed for a few
days.
</P>
<P>
   Animals often accept transplanted livers in the absence of the
immunosuppressant drugs that are always given to human transplant
patients to combat rejection of the organ. Even stranger, if a
heart or another organ is transplanted with a liver, it may also be
tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Bishop of the Centenary Institute in Sydney, Australia,
suspected that this tolerance depends on the initial interaction
between the host's immune cells and those that enter the body
inside a transplanted liver.
</P>
<P>
   Previous animal experiments have shown that tolerance is
associated with a surge and then a reduction in the number of
activated T cells _ which normally attack transplanted organs. If
the liver is irradiated to kill its immune cells, this doesn't
occur and the organ is rejected.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that the body's T cells are at first stimulated by
the immune cells that enter with the transplanted liver, but then
die off. To test that idea, Bishop and his colleague Alex Sharland
transplanted livers or kidneys into rats and monitored what
happened to the T cells. Kidneys don't induce immunological
tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, the number of activated T cells that had undergone
apoptosis, or naturally programmed cell death, was far higher in
the transplanted livers than in the kidneys, which were rejected.
But when the rats received the immunosuppressant drug
methylprednisolone along with a new liver, far fewer apoptotic T
cells appeared in the organ.
</P>
<P>
   If immunosupressant drugs similarly disrupt the liver's ability
to induce tolerance in people, problems with rejection may be
reduced by delaying the use of such drugs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
