<HEADLINE>
BLACKOUT BRINGS POWER TO THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tuesday morning's major power outage brought
commerce to a halt and cost the city, the Pacific Gas and Electric
Co. and businesses large and small untold millions of dollars. I'm
sorry about that, but I sure enjoyed the way everything in San
Francisco got ratcheted waaaay down.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic. Noise. Conspicuous consumption. People's blood
pressure. Attitude. Although the comparison was made to 1989, San
Franciscans were not as sweet and docile on Tuesday as we were
after the Loma Prieta earthquake. But we were nicer, slower and
quieter than usual, and that made walking in the city a dream.
</P>
<P>
   Heading up Powell Street towards Union Square, I was stunned. At
Post and Powell, where cars, trucks and cable cars usually form a
horn-honking mess, there was but a handful of vehicles and only the
pleading taxi whistle of the doorman at the Sir Francis Drake
Hotel. The one place on Powell serving hot food was a pizza joint,
and business was brisk.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Saks, a half dozen well-turned out saleswomen stood
behind locked glass doors. Peering out, self-conscious smiles on
their faces, they were the epitome of ``All dressed up and no place
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street on the front door of Borders Books and Music,
an excruciatingly neat hand-lettered sign said: ``Borders Is
Temporarily Closed Due To Power Failure.'' Later on in North Beach,
I would find the emotional (and aesthetic) opposite of that sign,
taped to the front door of the U.S. Post Office: ``No power _
Closed 'til later.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bush and Powell, the first of several stalled cable cars sat
in the intersection. The two-man crew was tucked inside the coach,
one reading a newspaper, the other listening to a portable radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the electricity in the barn that pulls the cable,'' said
the guy with the radio. ``We've been here since 8:15.'' It was
11:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of Nob Hill, I looked down California Street towards
Market. Again, on a normal day, this stretch of city street would
be a long, narrow sea of autos and delivery trucks. Tuesday, I
could count every vehicle in the 14-block expanse: 21 cars, two
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   That was about the time ``Waltzing Matilda,'' the theme from
``On The Beach,'' began playing in my head. The 1959 film (about
the end of the world, thanks to nuclear holocaust) has a famous,
chilling segment of shot after shot of the wind-swept and
thoroughly lifeless streets of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Grace Cathedral seemed like a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   A sign on one of the front doors announced that the 12:10
Eucharist had been moved to the Chapter Room. But the magnificent
Anglican church was open, and inside a handful of folks shuffled
their way in sock feet around the Labyrinth _ a replica of the
design (c. 1220) on the floor of Chartres Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been meaning to do this for ages, but never seemed to find
the time. ``Walking the Labyrinth invites us to experience our
gratitude for life and meets our longing for a change of heart,'' a
sign said. Tuesday, all I had was time, so I laid my shoes next to
Benny Bufano's statue of St. Francis of Assisi and waded in.
</P>
<P>
   It took about 10 minutes to reach the center, or
``Illumination.'' The sign had encouraged me to stay there as long
as I wished, but I spent only about a minute; I wanted to get back
outside before power was restored and the city once again became an
angry, grinding, modern metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   The appetite-tweaking smell of Chinese food wafted up Mason
Street as I walked through Chinatown toward North Beach. Somebody
had electricity. Four more cable cars sat frozen on the Mason line,
one caught in mid-turn at Washington Street.
</P>
<P>
   Lights or no lights, every Chinese produce stand was open, with
proprietors estimating the weight of bok choy and spinach and
making change the old-fashioned way from silent, open cash drawers.
</P>
<P>
   I slid across mighty Broadway as if it were a country lane and
headed down Stockton. I was hungry but had only two bucks on me.
All ATMs were still down, but I figured Ed and Mary Etta Moose
would take a check.
</P>
<P>
   Outside their restaurant, Moose's, a chalkboard offered a
``Blackout Menu'' of seven dishes. Inside, a bunch of society dames
sat at tables in the window and the Mooses huddled in the candle
glow near their long bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about a glass of red wine?'' Ed said. ``And maybe some
split pea soup?''
</P>
<P>
   I had both (and a ham and cheese sandwich) while Mary Etta and I
sat and talked for more than an hour about the genius of artist Sam
Provenzano, Tom Wolfe's new book, religion and how newborn babies
and the recently deceased can actually give you part of their
spirit if you're at all awake.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:28 p.m., the lights in Moose's came on and most of the
patrons applauded. Mary Etta, however, groaned and said, ever so
softly, to a waiter: ``Would you please dim the lights?''
</P>
<P>
   I nearly kissed her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
