<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD SIDE OF THE JACK KEVORKIAN SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Two days before ``60 Minutes'' showed Dr. Jack
Kevorkian apparently injecting a terminally ill man with a lethal
dose of medicine, my wife and I faced some hard questions about
life and death ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   We were in an attorney's office, signing our new wills and
setting up a trust. Among the documents was something called
``Durable Power of Attorney for Health Care.'' On page 3 of this
document was the following passage: ``Health care decisions to be
made by my agent pursuant to this paragraph shall be made
consistent with those of my desires initialed below. If no desires
are initialed below, my agent shall make such decisions in good
faith and its best judgment, consistent with my best interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``1. I desire that my life be prolonged to the greatest extent
possible, without regard to my condition, the chances I have for
recovery or long term survival, or the cost of the procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``2. If I am in a coma which doctors have reasonably concluded
is irreversible, I desire that life-sustaining or prolonging
treatments not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``3. If I have an incurable or terminal condition or illness and
no reasonable hope of long-term recovery or survival, I desire that
life-sustaining or prolonging treatments not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``4. I do not desire treatment to be provided and/or continued
if the burdens of the treatment outweigh the expected benefits. My
agent is to consider the relief of suffering, the preservation or
restoration of functioning, and the quality as well as the extent
of the possible extension of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I separately and privately read those four points.
As I read them over several times, I gulped, realizing the gravity
of what was before me. I won't reveal which, if any, of the four
points my wife or I initialed, but I know I watched the Kevorkian
interview and tape with extra interest.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was because I had attended the funeral of a 92-year-old
woman from Oakland's Chinatown and read about the death of yet
another old Chinatown leader. Maybe it was the memories of the
deaths years ago of both my parents and one of my older sisters.
All three suffered over a long period before passing away. I do not
recall whether any of them expressed a desire to end their lives to
alleviate the sustained pain, and I do not recall whether, within
our family, the subject of euthanasia ever came up.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, Kevorkian surely got my attention _ and that,
apparently, was his point, as was getting arrested so the legal
system can decide whether euthanasia is a criminal act.
</P>
<P>
   The showing of this death by ``60 Minutes'' has been roundly
criticized, but I think it served a worthy public purpose, even
while it obviously served CBS's commercial interests. None of
Kevorkian's numerous other assisted-suicide cases has had quite
this impact. If it triggers a heightened public debate over the
morality and ethics of euthanasia, then all the better.
</P>
<P>
   Having made my choices on the four points cited above, I cannot
say that I am comfortable with what I chose. I am not displeased,
however, with having to think about this most fundamental
life-and-death issue while I am relatively healthy and of
relatively sound mind. I am also comforted by the fact that I can
change my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about terminal illnesses and medically-assisted suicide
and euthanasia isn't usually the kind of thing most of us like to
do, especially if we are not in a personal crisis. But one cannot
predict when the time will come to face these all-important issues.
As obnoxious as Kevorkian may be to many people, he has provided us
invaluable food for thought.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
