<SLUG> BC-PEARL-HARBOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING LESSONS FROM THE PEARL HARBOR SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ Dec. 7 was the 57th anniversary of the
surprise attack on Pearl Harbor. On that day in 1941, at 7:53 a.m.
Hawaiian time, the Imperial Japanese Navy woke up a sleepy American
naval base with a massive preemptive strike, killing 2,400 people
and catapulting this officially-neutral nation into World War II.
</P>
<P>
   To millions of Americans, the meaning of Pearl Harbor went far
beyond the end of neutrality and the beginning of war. With a
combination of shock, fear and moral outrage, the 2-hour raid
evolved from an unforgivable act into an inspiration, becoming the
defining moment of an entire generation.
</P>
<P>
   Defining moments are different _ and much more significant _
than simply a moment that someone remembers. Defining moments are
events that so profoundly influence how a country perceives both
itself and the world that they help change that country's political
life for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it's hard to imagine the Soviet Union lasting as
long as it did after 1945 without its World War II defining moment:
Stalingrad, with all the shared heroism and suffering the word
embodies. Nor is the transformation of Germany into a stable
democracy imaginable without its defining moment, when the Allies
liberated the concentration camps and forced the German people to
come to terms with what had been going on inside.
</P>
<P>
   For the generation of Americans then living through World War
II, Pearl Harbor was such a moment. It taught America that the
price of indolence was destruction, and the cost of vulnerability
was death.
</P>
<P>
   Indolence and vulnerability stalked Pearl Harbor in the days
before the attack. Troubling intelligence reports were routinely
ignored. When they weren't ignored (why was the Japanese consul in
Honolulu burning files?), they were explained away with lightweight
logic (it's nothing _ all consuls burn files). Because an attack
from halfway across the Pacific seemed so unlikely, it was never
conceded that it might be possible; therefore almost no
preparations had been made to protect lives or material.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 7, Pearl Harbor was indeed a pearl, available for the
taking.
</P>
<P>
   To Mitsuo Fuchida, the Japanese naval officer who issued the
famous ``Tora! Tora! Tora!'' message that signaled the attack had
been both a success and a complete surprise, the most surprising
element of all was how completely exposed he found his objective.
The target vessels of Battleship Row, consisting of the doomed
Arizona and her six sister battleships, stood not only undefended
but _ along with 87 other ships _ bottled up, crammed like true
sitting ducks into a three-mile-square cluster. This same lack of
preparedness was even more ironically displayed at the Hickam and
Wheeler airfields: fearing sabotage _ but never imagining an
outright attack _ pilots had lined up their planes wingtip to
wingtip, making them easy to guard but even easier to destroy.
</P>
<P>
   As news of Pearl Harbor spread to the mainland _ which it did
even as the attack was in progress _ the lessons that were to guide
the United States through both World War II and the Cold War began
to take shape: the need for eternal vigilance, the need for serious
intelligence-gathering, the need to stand tall _ and well-armed _
in the face of the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, these lessons continue to function today. But
only partially, for in post-Vietnam America, perhaps in response to
some of our Cold War failures (or our successes), attention has
shifted from Pearl Harbor to Hiroshima. These days, in teaching, in
research, and in popular culture, dropping the A-bomb is often
considered the defining American moment of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we should remember that it was the surprise attack on
Pearl Harbor that led, in time, to the surprise attack on
Hiroshima. Had America been more awake on Pearl Harbor morning, the
road to Hiroshima might have never been taken. If vigilance is the
price we pay to avoid enduring _ or for that matter, inflicting _
surprise attacks, it would seem, as we veer from one undefined
military adventure to the next, well worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Bass is a historical novelist and columnist for the San
Francisco Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
