A5125 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HYDE-BOS &LR;      12-11 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HYDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARINGS AN UNTIDY SHOWCASE FOR HYDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In many ways, the House Judiciary Committee
hearings are winding up exactly as chairman Henry Hyde didn't want.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde vowed to work for bipartisan support, but this week's
expected vote for articles of impeachment is likely to be strictly
partisan. He promised civility _ and he has often tried mightily to
ensure it _ but the panel's food-fight style has proved ready-made
for parody on ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a surprise, the committee will vote within days to
approve articles of impeachment against President Clinton, a move
that Hyde does support and has helped ensure. But Hyde's road to
the impeachment vote has been rocky, and he seems to sense that his
place in history is being rewritten daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process has been a downer,'' Hyde told reporters
late Wednesday night, after yet another long day of partisan
wrangling over whether to impeach President Clinton on grounds that
he lied about his relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's abilities could soon be put to yet another test. If the
House approves articles of impeachment, Hyde has the authority to
act as the manager _ or de facto prosecutor _ of the case before
the Senate. Hyde has not said whether he will take up that
challenge, but there is speculation that he will take a pass,
giving much of the responsibility to another House member or
perhaps to his friend, committee GOP chief investigator David
Schippers.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, few if any of the participants in the impeachment
hearings have come off looking good, which may be inevitable in an
investigation that revolves around allegations of presidential
sexual misconduct with an intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all look bad cause it's a bad issue,'' Representative
Robert Wexler, a Florida Democrat, said on CNN earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   With every member of the panel acting in a partisan manner, Hyde
probably has little chance to emerge as a modern-day equivalent of
former representative Peter Rodino, the New Jersey Democrat who was
widely praised as chairman of the impeachment hearings in the
Watergate case. Rodino, Republicans note, enjoyed a committee in
which some GOP members ultimately voted with the Democratic
majority in passing three articles of impeachment against President
Richard M. Nixon. On the Hyde committee, some Democratic members
have been sharply critical of Clinton and said he lied under oath,
but none are expected to vote for articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde knew he would be under attack from the start. Last
February, in an interview with the Globe, Hyde said he wouldn't be
surprised if Clinton's defenders went after him, ``attacking the
messenger with a fury.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Hyde's difficulties began almost immediately
after the 74-year-old Illinois congressman was billed by
Republicans as the model of a fair-minded chairman. An Internet
magazine, Salon, reported in September that he had an affair with a
woman 30 years ago, even though he was married at the time.
</P>
<P>
   While Hyde decried the report as irrelevant, it inevitably has
made it more difficult for him to question the president's affair
with Lewinsky. More recently, new reports have focused on the fact
that he said during the Iran-contra hearings in 1987 that lying was
understandable in some cases, leaving unexplained why Clinton's
lying is more significant than that by figures such as former
Lieutenant Colonel Oliver North.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters more difficult, Hyde finds himself at the pinch
point of a Republican Party deeply divided between conservatives
and moderates. Hyde's panel is viewed by many as being controlled
by the House's most partisan members, such as committee member Bob
Barr of Georgia. House Whip Thomas DeLay is widely viewed as
running the party's impeachment strategy. The party's moderates,
meanwhile, have no voice on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans seem pleased with Hyde's performance. ``I have
heard respect, affection, and gratitude that he did a job while a
lot of other people went into hiding,'' said Republican strategist
William Kristol, editor of the Weekly Standard magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, of course, see it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will condemn the procedures and the process that Henry
Hyde presided over,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a
Massachusetts Democrat, referring to the way Republicans have
orchestrated witnesses and evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat who sits
on the Judiciary Committee and has worked with Hyde for years, said
the chairman has been ``procedurally fair'' since the hearings
began. But Frank said that is almost irrelevant because the
underlying strategy of the hearings is ``very unfair'' because it
is so partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he doesn't enjoy this because his reputation has
taken a hit,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   While Hyde has made clear he is in favor of impeachment, he has
striven to give Democrats time to present their case against it,
even if he knows that case will fail. At times, Hyde has exhibited
his frustration with a dig at Democrats on the panel. ``The White
House and the Democratic committee members' response to the
allegations to the referral has been Shakespearean: full of sound
and fury signifying nothing,'' Hyde said. The referral is the
report written by the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has, however, won plaudits from Democrats because he plans
to allow a vote on a resolution to censure Clinton instead of
impeaching him. But Hyde knows that vote is likely to fail along
party lines and that impeachment will probably be approved in the
same manner.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Democrats launched another attack on Hyde, arguing
that the committee has not given Clinton's defenders enough time to
present their case against impeachment. Representative Melvin Watt,
Democrat of North Carolina, proposed a motion allowing more
witnesses to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have given lip service throughout this process that no one
person is above the law,'' Watt said. ``The process this committee
has followed throughout this investigation has consistently treated
the president of the United States below any procedural due process
that we would ever think of providing innocent citizens of the
United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hyde tried to explain that witnesses had been called, Watt
interrupted him. This clearly upset Hyde, who cut short his reply,
saying ``If you don't want to be informed . . .'' Hyde then called
a vote on Watt's motion, which was killed along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Such frequent outbursts have visibly upset Hyde, who said
earlier this month that Democrats seemed focused on ``personal
attacks on the chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   In his conversation with reporters on Wednesday night, Hyde was
asked how he would like to be remembered. ``I was a good
congressman. I accomplished some things, and when my time comes,
I'll be missed,'' Hyde responded, without mentioning the
impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
