<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS LIVES IN THE FAITH OF CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, I read that the age at which kids start to
doubt there is a Santa _ about 8 _ hadn't dropped much over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   You can add my 9-year-old to that group of uncertain children.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, everybody knows reindeer can't fly,'' Jamila
argues in measured tones. ``And how in the world can a big fat man
get down a chimney with a bunch of presents? There isn't a Santa
Claus, and when I grow up I'm going to the North Pole to prove
it.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure she has ever believed in Santa Claus, but
personally, I love the thought of a bearded old man making toys and
delivering them to the world's children. I always have, and that's
what I told my little skeptic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do?'' she asked with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, too, Mama,'' her sister, Asha, added before I could
answer. ``He can squeeze through a chimney if he holds in his
stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Asha most certainly believes, as you can tell by a look at her
Christmas list this year. At the very top was this little item:
``my own checking account.'' Who but Santa could grant such a wish
to a 7-year-old as good to herself as Asha?
</P>
<P>
   In any case, I don't know what to make of Jamila's argument,
especially because it was delivered on the same morning she offered
up a Christmas wish list nearly two pages long.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV. VCR. My own phone with caller ID. My own phone line. All
the Spice Girls stuff at the Icing. New covers for my bed. Brandy's
``Never Say Never'' CD. ``Mulan. Dr. Doolittle'' soundtrack ...''
</P>
<P>
   So I ask her, ``If you don't believe Santa exists, what must I
do with such a long list?''
</P>
<P>
   She throws herself on my bed, a big smile across her face and
says, ``Well, I kinda believe, and I kinda don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, she kinda doesn't believe in the Easter Bunny and the
Tooth Fairy, either, but she cries if the bunny isn't bearing just
the right gifts and the dear old fairy forgets to pay.
</P>
<P>
   And so as I write this, I hope it isn't so. I hope Jamila really
does believe in Santa Claus and is just spouting off, as she so
often does. I hope that she's just trying to appear grown-up to her
little sister.
</P>
<P>
   Of course if you believe the experts, this is it for Asha as
well. Come Feb. 19, she'll be 8, perhaps joining the other skeptics
out there.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know; maybe I just need to indulge the magic, to hold
fast to the kind of childlike faith believing in Santa requires.
</P>
<P>
   For it is this kind of childlike faith that I think should
permeate the whole Christmas season. Not because of Santa, but
because of Christ's birth and what that means.
</P>
<P>
   You see, I love the blessing and mystery that are Christmas. I
like that it represents the fulfillment of prophecy, the birth of
the Messiah. And what could be more mysterious than a virgin giving
birth? What could be a more perfect gift to us all? What, indeed,
requires more faith?
</P>
<P>
   I know that for many, the holiday has become more about
business, more about trees and lights, but for me it remains the
most enchanting time of the year, when gift-giving takes on a whole
other meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a religious context, the focus of the Christmas season
often becomes little more than a baby in a manger and wise men who
traveled for more than a year to present their gifts of gold,
frankincense and myrrh. The true essence, though, is ``God with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Claus or not, that's a gift, through faith, worth
celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   And the best part of all is that it costs nothing and means
everything.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
