<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5130 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     12-11 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS A PROBLEM FOR MISS MANNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My gripe is when a friend or relative decides
to jazz up one's computer. After my son and daughter-in-law came
for a few days at Thanksgiving, they left my computer in shambles.
I liked my old screen saver, but now have exotic fish swimming
around. The computer keeps locking up every few minutes, and I
can't find half the icons. Anyway, if you ever have any leftover
space, you might gently tell people to keep their cotton-pickin'
hooks off other people's toys.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grumpy
</P>
<P>
   DEAR GRUMPY: Maybe your kid is finally getting even with you for
making him take down that Ozzy Osbourne poster and get a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   Irritating, isn't it? I'm sure he meant well, but I'm afraid he
suffers from geekomania, the irresistible urge to show how much he
knows about computers by helping bring other, less-enlightened
people out of the Dark Ages so they may worship at his Rockports
(the official shoe of nerds everywhere).
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's painful to watch others around me struggle along
with 6-month-old technology when I know I could upgrade their
software with something newer and totally unnecessary. I fight that
urge. Your kid just needs to learn how to be happy with slapping
his forehead and grinning bemusedly whenever he sees some addled
stick-in-the-mud still using last month's version of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   You can get even, though. Go to his place for Christmas, and
help him out by reprogramming his VCR, rewiring his audio system
and tuning up his Beamer. Oh, and don't forget to ask him why he's
not making more money and living in a better neighborhood. It
should be a yule to remember.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I had a problem in Win95 and had to format the
hard drive and start over. My Win95 is on a CD. When I tried to
reinstall it, it said ``insufficient drive.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Computer Killer
</P>
<P>
   DEAR KILLER: No, ``insufficient drive'' is what my supervisor
noted on my latest performance review. I think you're talking about
``invalid drive.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a nice little gotcha, isn't it? Sometimes, the only way
out of a computer fiasco is to wipe the hard drive and start over.
Unfortunately, when you do that you also wipe out the drivers that
make the CD-ROM drive operate. Gotcha!
</P>
<P>
   In the closing-the-barn-door department, there are two things
you should have done. First, you could have used the master disk
creation utility included with some computers. It lets you churn
out a 29-diskette set of Windows, perfect for your situation. You
generally get that utility only when the Windows CD isn't included
with the computer, though.
</P>
<P>
   Second, you should have made a bootable disk with CD drivers.
You'd think Microsoft would give you an easy way to do that,
wouldn't you? Silly you! You can make a start-up disk (in
Add/Remove Programs), but you still have to add the drivers. Save
yourself the trouble. Get somebody with 95 to format a disk, making
sure to add system files so it's bootable. Get somebody else to
make you a Win98 start-up disk. Copy everything from the Win98 disk
except Command.com, Drvspace.bin, Io.sys and Msdos.sys to the 95
disk. Boot with the sucker, and you'll see the CD.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
