<HEADER>
A5135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV13     12-11 1601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS' PORTFOLIO DUE   FOR DRAMATIC CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 13, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I hope you might provide some guidance with my mother's
investments.
</P>
<P>
   She is in her mid-seventies and relatively healthy. My father,
however, has Alzheimer's disease and is in a nursing home costing
approximately $40,000 a year. Their annual income from Social
Security and my father's pension is $31,000. Their home is paid
for.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the cost of the nursing home, expenses are $15,000 a
year. Their investments consist of $120,020 in Fidelity Growth and
Income fund, $61,780 in Vanguard Windsor II, $33,500 in Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, and a $10,000 CD paying 5.7 percent. In order
to best protect them from the ravages of long-term health care,
what do you suggest be dome with these investments?
</P>
<P>
   B.P., Solana Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My advice would be to make some very dramatic changes in this
portfolio. My guess is that this was put together at a time when
your father was in good health, and at a time when your parents'
Social Security and pension were more than ample to provide for
their living expenses. Thus they viewed this portfolio as emergency
savings, and with any luck most likely to become a major part of
their estate. With that in mind, the preponderance was invested in
stock funds, to provide long-term growth. (I can't give you
portfolio percentages, because you don't specify which of the many
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter funds is represented by that $33,500
position.) At present. there's a $24,000 shortfall between your
parents' expenses and their income.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve such an income stream from an investment portfolio
would require an 11.2 percent return, a level which you are
unlikely to achieve without making extremely risky investments.
What you want instead of risky investments is a conservative
income-oriented portfolio designed to produce a highest income
level and represent prudent risk-avoidance.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to invest the entire $225,480 in a portfolio of
fixed-income holdings which produced an average portfolio return of
6.5 percent, taking withdrawals of $2,000 a month, the pool would
last 14 1/4 years -- not long enough so that you can be confident
that the investment pool will outlast your parents, but still a
good chuck of time. Moreover, if worst came to worst, there's also
that potentially substantial asset represented by your parents'
unmortgaged home. I do not suggest you make any immediate move
there, since your mother has already undergone many unpleasant
changes resulting from your father's illness. But on the other
hand, if the situation hasn't changed in about five years, you
might want to consider the consequences of a sale. Just as an
example, if you were to follow the sequence of withdrawals outlined
above for five years, your principal would fall to a value of
$167,999. If your mother were then to sell her house, netting
$200,000 from the sale and adding that amount to the savings pool,
she would then have $367,999. If you were to then increase the
withdrawal sequence to $3,000 a month, allowing her to add $1,000 a
month in rent to her expenses, the pool would then last a further
16.4 years -- or 21.4 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   As for the investments, I'd suggest 30 percent in CDs, money
markets and short-term bond funds, 50 percent in a good GNMA (or
Ginnie Mae) fund, and the remainder in a high-yield (or junk) bond
fund. You can build such a portfolio with solid no-load funds
available from either Fidelity or Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   If any of your parents' savings are in tax-deferred accounts
such as IRAs or 401(k)s, there would be no tax consequences of
changing the portfolio. If not, you might be well advised to
consult a tax expert to determine the likely tax consequences, and
how you should time the sale of the stock funds. Your father's
deductible health care costs should offset some or all of the
capital gains you realize, and you could probably further reduce
the tax effects by spreading the stock fund sales between this year
and next -- but a tax expert who knows all the details of the
situation would have to determine the specifics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm a 22-year-old in the U.S. Marine Corps and have been
investing for nearly one year, putting $100 a month into
Oppenheimer Main Street Income and Growth fund, Class B. I now have
about $1,100. I know this isn't much time, but I decided to start
investing with what I could afford. I plan to put in my 20 years in
the service, and during that time to continue investing in mutual
funds with what I can afford, with a goal of someday reaching
$500,000. Am I on the right track? Also, I have an additional $50 a
month to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Where do you suggest I put it?
</P>
<P>
   P.B., Oceanside, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. You have made a terrific start, and the main thing you need
at this point is the discipline to keep plugging away at it,
through markets sweet and sour. Resist any temptations to hold back
investments when everything's plunging on Wall Street, and also
keep plugging away when the market seems so high that it seems
impossible that it might go higher and time soon. Remember, you're
in for the long haul, and what seems expensive today should seem
very cheap indeed when viewed ten years from now.
</P>
<P>
   So how realistic is that $500,000 target? Well, let's guess that
your Marine Corps hitch has 19 years to go; if you were to keep up
the $100-a-month discipline for the next 19 years, and if your
portfolio achieved average annual gains of 10 percent during that
period, you would have $70,934. If you were to simply quit saving
at that point and leave the accounts alone for the next 20 years,
the portfolio's internal growth would take it to $477,208 by the
time you are 61. If you continued the $100-a-month contributions
after you leave the Marine Corps and maintained that pace until age
61, the accumulation would then be $549,091. Finally, of you were
to bump the contributions up to $150 a month now and maintain that
pace for 19 years, you would have $103,037 at the time of your
first retirement. That amount, left alone with no contributions,
would grow to $693,181 during the next 20 years; if you continued
making $150 monthly contributions until age 61, you'd have $801,005
at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer Main Street Income and Growth is a fine fund for
beginning your program, and unless something about the fund
radically changes, it should be an excellent fund to treat as your
core holding for the long term. Ultimately you'll want your core
holding to represent about 40 to 60 percent of the total portfolio,
with the balance spread out among various other sectors such as
mid-cap, small-cap, overseas, and health care funds. I suggest you
let the core position grow to a critical mass before you begin
diversifying. After about two years, I'd suggest you begin to build
the four minor portfolio themes. If I were doing it, I'd set an
eventual goal of having 50 percent in Main Street Income and Growth
and 12.5 percent in each of the positions you've chosen for
diversification. As for the choice of funds for the smaller market
positions, that answer is easy; don't worry about it until it's
necessary, in about two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife's mother recently passed away, leaving us with a
$150,000 nest egg. My wife thinks I'm a smart guy and wants me to
invest it for us. It's kind of a big responsibility and I'm really
not as smart as she thinks. My neighbor who is a financial planner
says just stick it in a couple of good mutual funds and forget
about it. But I like your advice to average the investment over a
period of three years. I guess I'm a little confused about what
funds to use and how much to invest at a time. We are reasonably
debt-free, with a few thousand dollars in a money market accounts
and our home will be paid off in four years. I am 73 and my wife is
67. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   D.C., Newport Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I still like dollar cost averaging for buying stock
funds, but I'm not sure that at your age I would be putting a whole
lot of my eggs in that basket. In fact, I suggest that you put no
more than 40 percent of the inheritance, or $60,000 in stock funds,
and I'd take a cowardly course there, both through picking
conservative funds and by adopting three- year dollar cost
averaging. Presuming you put that $60,000 in a money market fund
earning 5 percent, this would entail 36 monthly transfers of $1,850
from the money fund to the stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   What funds? I'd suggest that you use three different funds with
stock-dominated portfolios. I'll cite funds within the Vanguard
family, but you can find similar offerings with most of the major
mutual fund groups. I'd put half of this money, or $30,000, into
Vanguard Index Value. Then I'd target $15,000 each for Vanguard
Balanced Index and Vanguard Specialized Health Care funds.
</P>
<P>
   As for the balance of the inheritance, I'd suggest another
$60,000 go into Vanguard GNMA, and $15,000 each into Vanguard
Short-Term Corporate Bond and Vanguard High-Yield Corporate Bond
funds. With these $90,000 in fixed-income fund investments, I
suggest you go ahead with lump-sum investments. Dollar cost
averaging is fine for the more volatile stock funds, but when
you're in the tamer world of bond investing, I think the practice
is unduly cautious.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
