u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-11 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SYSTEM LED TO A NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was driving a red Dodge Caravan with a pair of child seats
in the back, a typically harried young mother dashing from work to
the supermarket on Thanksgiving eve.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the law reached back seven years into Sonia
Hernandez's past to collect a debt she thought she had long since
paid. She only owed money, a couple of hundred dollars at that.
What authorities took were her dignity and sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   Her tale begins back in 1991, out on Route 24 in Randolph,
Mass., on a ride between a Quincy party and her Brockton home. She
was pulled over by a State Police trooper, registered a 0.14 on the
breath test, and pleaded guilty in court. According to records, she
paid a $250 fine, surrendered her license for 45 days, attended an
alcohol-awareness course, and entered probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drinking,'' she says, sitting in the living room of her
apartment in Boston, recalling that long-ago arrest. ``And it was
my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Flash ahead to 5:10 p.m. on this recent Wednesday. She's the
mother of four now, making her way in life, a medical technician
who dreams of becoming a nurse. For reasons unknown, her minivan
caught the attention of Boston Officer Dave Roberto, a 15-year
veteran. He ran her plate, saw an outstanding warrant in her name,
and pulled her to the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   A second police car arrived, then another. Picture this:
Hernandez, 38, looking nothing if not maternal, ordered out of her
car, hysterical on the street, wondering what will become of her
10-month-old and 12-year-old daughters in day care and her
14-year-old and 5-year-old sons at home. She pleaded with the
officers that she had paid her fine, that she's had a clean record
ever since. The response: Tell it to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   By then, she had descended into a Kafkaesque bureaucratic and
legal hell from which there was, quite literally, no escape. There
wasn't any judge, either, not until Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A bondsman told Hernandez she could not post bail because the
mystery warrant was out of Quincy District Court, a different
jurisdiction. Police led Hernandez from the station and drove her
to the Nashua Street jail. She was searched, told to strip, and
given canvas prison clothes. There were no open cells, so
authorities put her in a communal lockup. She was forced to use a
toilet in partial view of male guards. She slept on a metal bench.
Someone, anyone, could have called an on-duty judge to request
bail, but no one apparently thought it worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   On Thanksgiving Day, the guards put her in the television
lounge, where she spent hours sobbing, unsure why she was there.
Her children sat home asking other relatives where their mother had
gone. ``It was terrible,'' she says. ``My daughter cried for two
days. She thought I was never getting out of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn Friday, someone screamed into her lockup that it was
time to get up. Guards handcuffed her wrists to those of another
woman and drove them to Quincy court. Just when you think things
can't get any worse, they do. Court officers shackled her legs and
made her shuffle before the judge.
</P>
<P>
   So what started as a simple shopping trip to the neighborhood Hi
Lo on Centre Street ends in a tear-streaked appearance before a
judge in Quincy Center. That judge, a decent man named Charles
Black, informed her she owed $230 in monthly probation costs from
1991 that she had never paid. Hernandez's boyfriend, sitting in
court, paid the fee, and she was free at last.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez says she doesn't recall being billed for any monthly
probation costs, and points out that she had been handed back her
license so many years ago by a probation officer who could have
withheld it for the fee. She has also renewed her license since.
But even if she had just ignored the $230 bill, even if she was at
fault, did the punishment fit the crime?
</P>
<P>
   To that question, the system offers only a collective shrug.
Police say it doesn't matter that Hernandez didn't appear criminal
or drunk. The arresting officer could only see from the warrant
that she violated probation, officials said, and in this litigious
day and age, cops can't afford to look the other way.``We're at a
distinct disadvantage. We have to be more than cautious,'' says
Sergeant Margot Hill, a Boston police spokeswoman. ``If we let her
go, would she be drinking? Would she be drunk with kids in the
car?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's easy to believe Hernandez when she says she never
knew about the fee, easy to believe that the bureaucracy never
informed her of the tab. Here's why: The day after Thanksgiving,
Hernandez's license and registration, confiscated at the scene,
were nowhere to be found. At the police station, at the jail, at
the courthouse, everyone told her it wasn't their fault.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory is a columnist with Then Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
