<HEADLINE>
THE BIG COUNTDOWN IS UNDER WAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In preparation for the year's end, the Trends Research Institute
has named the year's ``Trend Losers,'' among them  &UR; Bill &LR; 
 &UR; Gates &LR; , Nike, the National Cattlemen's Beef Association, ``Good
Morning America'' and Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a desperate attempt to stop the crumbling sales of its
SnackWell cookies,'' says the Institute, ``Nabisco pitched them to
women as an ego booster. `At SnackWells,' said one ad, `we like to
think that snacking shouldn't be just about feeding yourself, but,
in some small way, about feeding your self-esteem.' ''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. How do you spot a trend? The year-end Futurist suggests:
``Follow the Yellow Page headings'' (aging demographics, for
example, has resulted in categories for pain management and day
spas); ``Watch for nouns being used as verbs, hinting at increased
activity (such as thrifting, the increasing hunting for bargains at
thrift shops); and ``Think in opposites'' because ``Behind every
trend there is a countertrend.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S.: The New York Daily News says that  &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR; 
won't perform at Madison Square Garden on New Year's Eve 1999
because ``she has a lot of fear'' about the Y2K change.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT GUIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Paul Rauber &LR;  stumbled upon a great stocking stuffer at the Bone
Room in Berkeley: a fully articulated 7-foot-tall skeleton of a
cave bear _ a species that became extinct 40,000 years ago _ for
only $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   This particular bear has a celebrity connection, explained the
store's &UR; Ron Cauble &LR; .  &UR; Steven Seagal &LR;  had ordered it, for his front
room, from a Dutch dealer who procured it in Russia. After the bear
was set up, though, the &UR; Dalai Lama  &LR; came to visit, and _ what would
 &UR; Miss Manners &LR;  say? _ opined that he didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Seagal ordered it removed immediately, so as not to offend his
spiritual leader the next time he came a-calling. The Bone Room is
selling the thing on consignment from the Dutch dealer, who told
Cauble that Seagal never really owned it, because he never paid for
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Jack Greenberg  &LR; points his finger at the culprit for
Tuesday's San Francisco power failure: ``Homer Simpson on loan from
the nuclear power plant.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Carmen Electra  &LR; writes in People magazine that she believes
in marriage, and despite the pending annulment of hers to  &UR; Dennis &LR; 
 &UR; Rodman &LR; , ``there is possibly a future for my relationship. We take
it a step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Asked by Vanity Fair to name his greatest fear, &UR; Paul Newman &LR; 
replies, ``Dinner with  &UR; Rupert Murdoch &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIRST THINGS FIRST, WHATEVER THEY ARE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Having completed the kissing,  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  is now engaged
in the telling, 12 hours a day with co-author  &UR; Andrew Morton &LR; ,
writes  &UR; Jeannette Walls &LR;  of MSNBC. The difficulty is coordinating
the publication of her book with the broadcast of Lewinsky's
interview with  &UR; Barbara Walters.  &LR; St. Martin's Press doesn't ``want
to get scooped by Walters, and ABC doesn't want to get scooped by
the book,'' a source told Walls.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, managers of a traveling Madame Tussaud wax figure
exhibition in Sydney, Australia, have sewn up the zipper on  &UR; Bill &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR; 's pants because ``people have been taking a few liberties
with his clothing,'' said manager  &UR; Vicky Brown &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The Chicago Sun-Times says Watergate investigative hero
 &UR; Carl Bernstein &LR;  is hoping to write a definitive book on  &UR; Hillary &LR; 
 &UR; Rodham Clinton &LR; .
