</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND STADIUM STANDS AS A WARNING TO HARTFORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing is deterring Governor John Rowland and the Connecticut
Legislature from heading into the red-tape district of the National
Football League. Not even a report by the state's Office of Fiscal
Analysis that says the new Hartford stadium for the New England
Patriots could cost taxpayers up to $257 million over 30 years. Nor
an insane clause that would make taxpayers pay up to $17.5 million
a year for unsold luxury boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature has scheduled a special session next Tuesday to
finalize its $375 million, taxpayer-funded colossus. The
politicians are getting ready to walk up the stairs with the
fluttering heartbeat of anticipation of what awaits them in the
skybox. History shows they instead will be walking back down to the
street with the look of suckers who had their lust momentarily
satisfied but realize when they try to hail a cab that they had
been pickpocketed by the prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Rowland says the stadium will ``guarantee the success''
of downtown development in Hartford. He calls it the ``turning
point that will propel this state into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland's lights are clearly out, guaranteeing a mansion and
income for a fabulously wealthy owner and 40 or so incredibly
salaried athletes while many of the state's 73,000 low-income
students go to dilapidated public school buildings that might as
well be homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   If one looks at what happened in Oakland, Calif., Rowland's
claims of success are massive displays of ignorance. In the early
1980s, Oakland lost the Raiders to Los Angeles. Oakland, a city as
tired of being an afterthought to San Francisco as Hartford is to
Boston and New York, has been desperate for some show of civic
testosterone, a show that says, ``We got game.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland got the game and got gamed. In order to lure them back
in the mid 1990s, the city paid the Raiders $70 million up front
just to come to Oakland and promised $100 million in renovations to
the stadium the team had fled.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hartford, Oakland agreed to grandiose schemes of revenue
guarantees for the team. In Oakland's case, it agreed to pick up
any unsold ``personal seat licenses,'' the bizarre fee in which a
Raiders fan would pay between $250 and $4,000 merely for the right
to purchase a season ticket.
</P>
<P>
   When this was all announced, many people fell for the scheme. A
headline for a 1995 San Francisco Chronicle news story said, ``Why
the Raiders are a bargain for Oakland.'' The story said Oakland's
deal with the Raiders, when compared with the deals in other cities
that had thrown massive sums of taxpayer money at NFL teams, ``is
the only one to even attempt to pay for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   In its lust, Oakland never accounted for reality. This city,
laden with a high poverty rate and a team too mediocre on the field
to draw wealthy fans from afar, never came close to selling out. To
maintain its guarantees to Davis, the city now pays the Raiders $16
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sufficiently awakened to the horrors of the deal, a 1997
editorial in the Chronicle called it ``a time-release toxin.'' Mary
King, Alameda County supervisor and head of the stadium authority,
said: ``It was an unfortunate transaction in terms of the
expectations set up publicly. It is a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartford similarly is in no position to guarantee revenues.
Hartford, like Oakland, has a high poverty rate. It is two hours
from Boston and two hours closer to New York, which already has the
Giants and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Boosters of the Hartford deal anticipate luring corporations in
the Connecticut suburbs of New York to the skyboxes. It might
happen when the Patriots are winning, but fat cats will be the
first to stay away during losing cycles. This would seem to be an
important consideration, given that a Hartford Courant story last
month said, ``No one believes there is enough corporate clout in
Greater Hartford to fill all the premium seating.''
</P>
<P>
   No one should believe any of Rowland's promises that the stadium
will not scorch the taxpayers, even if the state gets out of
guaranteeing luxury seat revenues to Kraft. It has not happened in
recent memory. St. Louis taxpayers will end up paying $720 million
for the Rams, three times its annual budget for public schools.
Even though most of its 81 games are sold out or heavily attended,
Baltimore subsidizes the recently built stadium for the Orioles to
the tune of $11 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   No one should believe any promises about jobs. Sports stadiums
are one of the most inefficient ways to produce jobs. Studies show
the new baseball stadium in Cleveland cost the city $230,000 per
new job created. The Orioles stadium cost between $127,000 to
$331,000 per job. It costs Maryland only $6,250 per person to
generate jobs out of its economic development agency.
</P>
<P>
   The lights will shine on the ugliness of Connecticut's deal with
the Patriots sooner or later. The problem for the taxpayers is that
it will almost certainly be too late. Tuesday, the Legislature
walks up the stairs. The politicians will emerge from the doors
smiling as if they made the big score. Just do not ask them
afterwards for taxi fare.
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
