<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-STORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PUERTO RICO, STORM FOLLOWS A STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTAUDO, Puerto Rico _ Along the banks of the Rio Grande de
Arecibo, gigantic sewer pipes lay strewn on the buckled road. Three
dogs _ either lost or abandoned by their owners _ lapped up rice
and beans from a Styrofoam container.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three months after Hurricane Georges ripped through
Puerto Rico, the devastation is still obvious in rural areas like
this mountainside village, where the storm flattened dozens of
pastel-colored concrete houses.
</P>
<P>
   Walking along the ruins this week, Carlos Torres Vera surveyed
his crumbling home, but his anger was not directed at nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government keeps talking about the plebiscite, as if this
never happened,'' said Torres, a middle-aged manleaning on a cane.
``We didn't want this plebiscite. Not now. We're suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, Puerto Ricans will head to the polls to vote on the
status of their homeland, showing whether they prefer to become a
US state or remain a US commonwealth, among other choices. And for
the first time in its 100-year history as a US territory, the
statehood option is expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico Governor Pedro Rossello, an ardent statehood
supporter who pushed for the plebiscite, hopes the results will
spur Congress to authorize a binding plebiscite that would settle
once and for all the political fate of the island and its 3.9
million residents.
</P>
<P>
   The issues of political sovereignty may seem remote from the
destruction in Utuado. But in Puerto Rico, where nationalism and
cultural pride reign, and where people may be more passionate about
politics than even Bostonians, everyone has a strong opinion _
especially hurricane victims who feel betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want us to become a state, that's for sure,'' said Luz
Celeste Negron Rivera, 29, who is living in a shelter with her
husband and seven children.
</P>
<P>
   Negron, like many Puerto Ricans living in the central part of
the island, is pro-commonwealth. Like many hurricane victims who
live in quaint mountainside towns, miles from larger, more
Americanized cities, she believes Rossello pushed for the
plebiscite in the storm's aftermath, hoping that voters like her
won't be able to get to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like what he's doing,'' she said of the governor.
``He's not helping us. It's like he wants to force statehood. He's
putting us up against a wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Negron wants to vote, but she lost everything, including her
identification, when the storm tore her house apart, leaving behind
just parts of the bathroom. Besides, she and her husband, Felix
Oquendo, need to find a home.
</P>
<P>
   For now, home is a former office of the Bernardo Gonzalez Middle
School in Utuado, a squat concrete building. It's been converted
into a shelter for 148 people who say they are lucky the five
bathrooms they share have running water. Negron's children, who
lost all their toys, chased other kids in the asphalt parking lot
under swaying palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in her school uniform _ a plaid skirt and green shirt _
Negron's 5-year-old daughter Diana ran to her mother and began
tugging at her hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy, can we have a party?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, sweetheart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about a house?''
</P>
<P>
   Negron stared stoically into the distance, brushing her long
brown hair from her sweaty face.
</P>
<P>
   When Hurricane Georges hit Puerto Rico on Sept. 20, it turned
the Rio Grande de Arecibo into a freight train that swept along
trees and stones.
</P>
<P>
   All over this lush island, people still suffer from the storm,
which destroyed more than 20,000 homes, severely damaged 36,000
others, and caused untold billions of dollars in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Edmonston, a spokesman for the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, said more than $1 billion has been spent so far on aid and
loans to families whose homes were destroyed. But each day that
figure rises as people file paperwork for loans and assistance.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA's job is to help residents make their homes habitable,
Edmonston said. But downpours in October and nearly three straight
weeks of rain recently have hampered progress.
</P>
<P>
   The rain hasn't stopped the political hype, however. It's hard
to escape the barrage of plebiscite-related commercials on
television and radio. On busy roads, political caravans led by
police on motorcycles snake across the island. In Bayamon, the
pro-statehood New Progressive Party blocked traffic Wednesday night
as a jingle blared from large speakers: ``Vote for your future!
Vote for statehood!''
</P>
<P>
   Along the main streets of Utuado, posters and banners relating
to ``El Plebescito'' hang from telephone poles, stores, and
restaurants. ``Con estadidad puedo ganar,'' reads one sign. (With
statehood I can win). Others say ``Vota por Ninguna,'' or ``none of
the above.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, construction crews work hurriedly for fear of more
rain.
</P>
<P>
   Big-wheel trucks rumbled down the road that snakes past Adelphia
Saloon, a cafe that owner Filiberto LaFontaine named for the city
he once lived in _ Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Like many roadside stores, it offers everything from milk to
candy to freshly killed chickens. Roosters walking freely along the
road crowed as LaFontaine watched the backhoes, bulldozers, and
dump trucks roll by.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're spending millions to publicize the plebiscite,''
LaFontaine said. ``Why is the government spending millions on a
campaign when they can house hundreds of people with that same
money?''
</P>
<P>
   He thanks God that his home was not destroyed, but he and his
wife have not had running water since the storm. Every few days,
they fill plastic drums with water from a spring several miles
away. ``This plebiscite was like the hurricane,'' he said. ``We
were unable to stop it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
