<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-11 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WRITERS WOULD HAVE YOU READ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the years, I have been asking writers: If I could read just
one of your books, which one would you have me read? I view it as
an intellectual economy measure. You can't read everything; why not
read the best?
</P>
<P>
   Some authors bridle at The Question, as did Richard Dooling,
author of several novels, including the brilliant black comedy
``Critical Care.'' My books are like my children, this response
goes. How can I be asked to choose among them?
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK. But books aren't children. Men can't create children,
just for starters, and it is the self-deluding parent who thinks he
or she loves all offspring in the same way. So, anticipating the
Dooling Demurrer, I approached one of my favorite authors, Geoffrey
Wolff, and told him he had to choose a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   One would assume (dangerous to assume!) that Wolff would pick
``The Duke of Deception,'' his memoir of his father that is one of
the great nonfiction works of recent years. Failing that, he'd call
out his delightful Harry Crosby biography ``Black Sun,'' or the
grim ``Providence,'' a novel set in that city.
</P>
<P>
   But no. ``I'd have you read `A Day at the Beach,' a collection
of personal essays that go _ all too literally _ to the heart of my
passions,'' Wolff e-mailed me. ``Because they mark a welcome
farewell to solipsism, I have a perhaps too tender regard for those
circumstances and acts from my life that I have willed into
narrative form, from times in my life when I _ and not my mommy or
daddy _ can be held wholly accountable for those circumstances and
acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Does first book (EQ) first love? Sometimes. Columbia historian
Alan Brinkley has written several books and textbooks since his
first published work, ``Voices of Protest: Huey Long, Father
Coughlin and the Great Depression.'' But it remains his favorite,
``even though I wrote it so long ago (1982) it seems almost as if
it were the work of someone else.'' Likewise George Higgins, now
working on his 30th book, would have you read his first published
novel, ``The Friends of Eddie Coyle'': ``It would have to be that
book, because without `Eddie Coyle,' you wouldn't know me from a
load of goat.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Kaplan, who has written biographies of Walt Whitman and
Lincoln Steffens, also prefers to stick with his first love, Mark
Twain. Of 1967's ``Mr. Clemens and Mark Twain,'' he writes: ``Its
subject, to use a chilling word, was a prodigy and an absolute
original _ dazzling, ferocious, vulnerable, utterly winning,
invariably quotable. Mark Twain may have been a representative
American, but he was more unlike anybody else than anybody else I
can think of. As you see, I'm still pretty fond of the book. . . .
''
</P>
<P>
   There must be a temptation to name one's current (i.e.,
revenue-producing) book as the must-read tome, as novelist Anne
Bernays did when when I popped her The Question a number of years
ago. She referred me to ``Professor Romeo,'' which I liked a lot.
(Her neighbor, Henry Louis Gates Jr., sent me to ``Colored People''
_ excellent.) About the same time, Simon Schama's ``Citizens,'' a
chatty history of the French Revolution, was in the stores. But
Schama said his best book of the three he had then published was
``An Embarrassment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in
the Golden Age.'' I bet it's great; I haven't read it.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, some writers' choices depend on readers' responses.
The prolific poet and prose writer Donald Hall cites his
book-length poem, ``The One Day,'' which won the 1988 National Book
Critics Circle Award. ``It may well be true that I list it as my
favorite because many people whom I admire or trust claim that it
is my best thing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago I bearded John Irving with The Question.
Irving spends five or six years on each of his novels, and takes
enormous pride in his work. I wasn't carrying a notebook, and I
can't remember his precise response. (He mentioned more than one
book, and ``The World According to Garp'' wasn't one of them.) But
I do recall one detail. His mother had said his best book was ``A
Prayer for Owen Meany,'' and, all things being equal, he wasn't
inclined to disagree with her.
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
