<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWTIME IS SHOOTING A BRICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showtime doesn't make any apologies for televising next
weekend's charity game between locked-out NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get into the politics of it all,'' said Showtime vice
president Jay Larkin. ``We are taking a very strong position of
having no position.''
</P>
<P>
   No position is a good position. Showtime is only televising the
event, true enough, but that action sends a signal to NBA players
and their agents that their brand of entertainment can find a home
in the 180-channel television universe.
</P>
<P>
   The product _ even if Michael Jordan plays _ will be akin to a
summer league all-star game, in which defense is absent and
teamwork is truncated to at-best a two-man game. One-on-one is the
rule; competition is between those seeking the most points or
dunks.
</P>
<P>
   Boring.
</P>
<P>
   But not according to Showtime. The cable station is using
superlatives to describe the ``ultimate,'' ``star-studded
basketball event,'' pitting the ``greatest,'' ``world's finest
basketball players'' in the ``ultimate Dream game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a no-brainer for us,'' Larkin said. ``We don't stand
to gain either way with the outcome of the NBA discusions. We view
this as a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the NBA had unresolved problems, Showtime made a
deal to have Hakeem Olajuon play Shaquille O'Neal one-on-one. The
players agreed to play, but Olajuwon injured his back and was
unable to make it.
</P>
<P>
   However, the NBA lockout comes at a different time. Public
perception of the NBA has plummeted to the point where most fans
don't care. In promoting the charity game, union spinmeisters have
tried to paint the participants _ the league's elite players _ as
looking out for the less fortunate 11th and 12th men on NBA teams.
But $1,000 per ticket?
</P>
<P>
   Why don't the highest-paid athletes just donate 1 percent of
their salaries to the fund, and allow fans to watch the event for
free?
</P>
<P>
   Even in their most charitable moments, the top dogs in the NBA
are selfish, forcing the public to pay for exorbitant greed.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime doesn't have anything to do with all of that. The cable
station paid an undisclosed amount to player agent David Falk to
televise the event.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate NBA ``discussions'' are going, the players might
have to start talking about having a league of their own _ and
having their own network televise the mess the NBA has become.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More power to him
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sporting News has named Rupert Murdoch of Fox the most
powerful person in sports for the third time in four years. NBC
Sports chairman Dick Ebersol told the publication that ``it wasn't
even remotely a race. You could make him Nos. 1 through 5.'' Turner
Sports president Harvey Shiller also praised Murdoch. ``I think
there's a frank admission among most people at Turner that on a
worldwide basis, he's certainly the most aggressive and has
accomplished the most in terms of both ownership and regional
distribution of sports television.'' . . . HBO airs the 10-round
rematch between Ivan Robinson (26-2, 10KOs) and Arturo Gatti (29-3,
24KOs) Saturday night at 10. Gatti knocked out Robinson in the
fourth round on Aug. 22. Jim Lampley, Larry Merchant, and analyst
Roy Jones Jr. call the action from ringside. The undercard features
Yory Boy Campas against ``Ferocious'' Fernando Vargas in a 12-round
bout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Calling for reason
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS lead football analyst Phil Simms brings a little reason to
the raging officials debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 8 million opinions out there about what's right and
wrong,'' Simms said. ``No matter how good the officials are, there
are going to be mistakes. The judgments the officials are asked to
make on the field are too hard sometimes. It's impossible for the
naked eye to pick these things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want it to be perfect, then you are going to have to
have instant replay. Even then, they can slow it down to super-slow
motion and still can't quite decipher it. No matter what solution
you come up with, it just becomes more debatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, now every telecast will revolve around announcers
saying, `That was a bad call,' `This was a good call.' Come on, let
me watch some football. I don't want to hear all this other stuff
all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
