<SLUG> BC-BORK-SIDEBAR-SLATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY CONFLICT OF INTEREST 
</HEADLINE>
  By MICHAEL KINSLEY 
 (www.slate.com) 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a Microsoft employee, I have an obvious conflict of interest
in writing this article. Being an employee also makes me a
stockholder, which is another conflict, and a friend of many
Microsoft colleagues, which is a third. And Slate is owned by
Microsoft, making four.
</P>
<P>
   But I write it anyway, simply because the subjects of Robert
Bork and antitrust law have interested me since I reviewed ``The
Antitrust Paradox'' (favorably) for the New Republic 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I have waited for someone else to write this piece, and no
one has done so. Readers are free to discount or dismiss this
article because of its author. But the arguments here are all
heavily documented and can be evaluated, I think, independently of
authorship.
</P>
<P>
   Slate has established its willingness to publish articles highly
critical of Microsoft. This article, in any event, takes no
position on the merits of the Microsoft case. Bork's current
anti-Microsoft position may be correct. The challenge is to
reconcile it with anything he's said before he was hired by
Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Like any hired expert in a legal case, Bork also has an obvious
conflict of interest. Indeed his is worse. My Microsoft paycheck
does not depend on agreeing with my paymasters. Bork's Netscape
paycheck does.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael Kinsley is the editor of Slate.) &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1998 Slate &QL;  Visit Slate on the Web at:
http:www.slate.com &QL;  (Distributed by New York Times Special
Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
