A5171 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARING-LIFEBEAT-NYTS     12-11 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARING-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF A RETIRED AUDIOLOGIST
</HEADLINE>
  By PHILIP A. BELLEFLEUR 
 c.1998 Philip A. Bellefleur 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 30 years as an audiologist for the deaf and
hard-of-hearing, I have aged into one of the very patients whom I
counseled for so long.
</P>
<P>
   I am reminded of this irony daily as I refuse to address my own
diminishing sense of hearing. Each morning, I look in my mirror and
I confront the image of a man, who in my professional judgment
should be wear a hearing aid, but does not.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey taken in 1994 by the National Center for
Health Statistics, I am part of that 44.5 percent of the population
of the United States over the age of 55 having a significant
hearing loss. In most cases, age-related hearing loss is actually a
genetic condition. It's as though we were born with a little clock
inside that switches itself on between 40 and 50 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   It may go unnoticed for several years and be so subtle others
are aware of it long before we are. It may start with annoying
ringing or buzzing in the ear, after which it begins to affect our
ability to hear soft consonant sounds _ ``sh,'' ``th,'' ``ch''_
especially in the presence of environmental noise or when the
speaker's face is no longer visible.
</P>
<P>
   It is often mistaken as a problem of the talker rather than the
listener. I've heard women describe this type of deafness as
``married-man's ear.'' At age 30 for example, I could wander around
the house and with no effort at all hear and understand a story my
wife was relating. At 65, I must see her directly or her speech
sounds garbled.
</P>
<P>
   As the condition worsens more consonants are involved ( ``d,''
``b,'' ``v''), until we feel as though we hear well, but just don't
understand what is being said. This is the essence of the condition
I call ``senior deafness.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, you feel your condition is unique. You feel alone
with your frustration of being able to hear but not understand. You
begin to avoid group events where you must take part in
conversation and your participation in meetings drops to near zero.
Face-to-face conversation in your living room is much the same as
always, but marble halls, tiled floors and city streets become
nearly impossible places to understand conversation. At home, your
grandchildren mumble and your wife constantly complains you play
the television too loud.
</P>
<P>
   After waiting much too long, you may decide to talk to your
physician. Perhaps you visit an ear specialist called an otologist,
or a licensed audiologist, the kind with a Ph.D. Any of these
professionals will conduct diagnostic tests; the suggestion that
you need a hearing aid will figure prominently in most diagnoses.
</P>
<P>
   Other patients will end up in the office of a hearing-aid
``fitter'' with only minimal knowledge of the hearing mechanism and
no training in diagnosing hearing disorders. Still, if your only
problem is age-related deafness, a fitter may be the most
economical solution. Be advised if you avail yourself of any
hearing test advertised as ``free,'' you will certainly be told you
need a hearing aid.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, the smaller the hearing aid the less sound
it will amplify, but the better it will look. But whether you opt
for the $2,500 model which is so small you may have difficulty
handling it, or the larger economy model for around $350-$900,
chances are you will end up dissatisfied. Why? Two simple reasons:
</P>
<P>
   First, most of us simply don't wish to be seen wearing another
prosthetic device on our head. By 65, more than a few of us already
have trifocals, a hair piece and false teeth. Add a hearing aid or
two and we begin seeing ourselves as Robocop with wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   If you have trouble visualizing yourself wearing a hearing aid,
don't buy one no matter who tries to influence you. Half of the
hearing aids purchased in the United States today are in medicine
cabinets or bureau drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the technology allowing audiologists and physicians to
tell you precisely why you cannot hear or understand speech far
exceeds the technology needed to rehabilitate your hearing. It's
hard to believe a country capable of landing a man on the moon
can't make an electronic hearing aid enabling us to hear the sounds
of speech clearly again, but we can't, or at least we can't do it
very well.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to purchase an aid is not like the decision to
purchase eye glasses. With glasses you put them on and see 99
percent of the things you've been missing. You see them clearly and
with a minimum of discomfort. Wearing a hearing aid is more like
the purchase of dentures. They don't look or feel like the
original, and certainly don't work as well, but if you put up with
all the discomfort and disadvantages, and practice using them they
can be very helpful.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 50 years the advances in hearing aid design have
been dramatic, but for the consumer change has been mostly
cosmetic. Hearing aids have indeed become smaller and hence more
appealing, but in terms of being able to clarify speech and improve
speech discrimination damaged in senior deafness the key to success
is still the willingness of the wearer to adapt to the limitations
of the current technology.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Philip A. Bellefleur is a free-lance writer based in St.
Petersburg, Fla.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
