<HEADLINE>
IF COATES IS OUT, PURNELL MUST STEP IN, AND UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ His lifestyle may be another matter, but in
the locker room and on the field, Ben Coates is considered a loyal
teammate and a Hall of Fame player, as indispensable to the
Patriots as are Drew Bledsoe and Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   They may not have him Sunday in St. Louis for a game that
potentially could clinch a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Coates was scheduled to fly Thursday night to Greenwood, S.C.,
to attend services for his mother, Mozzella, 56, who died Wednesday
from a brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   While one of his attorneys initially said Coates would miss the
game, that decision will be made by the tight end Saturday after he
assesses the situation with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ben will have to see how his family is handling things
in South Carolina,'' said his agent, Michael George. ``When I spoke
to him, he sounded devastated. It was expected his mother would
live longer than she did. He's been through a lot this year.''
</P>
<P>
   His aunt and sister both died over the summer. Then Coates was
charged with domestic assault. He was found innocent in Wrentham
District Court Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a strong person like Ben is, mentally and
physically, you learn to handle things like that,'' said Patriots
wide receiver Shawn Jefferson. ``You know that life is going to
present you different challenges and stuff like that, and when it
does, you have to be ready for those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a weak person, stuff like that can really get to
you. But he's a strong guy mentally and physically. Now, maybe some
other guy wouldn't be able to handle all the stuff he's going
through this year. But he's handled it great. His performance
hasn't dropped off any. He's leading the team in receptions and
stuff. And he's a big part of our offense. And I'll tell you right
now, we're behind Ben 100 percent of the way. And our hearts go out
to Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   This would be the second game Coates has missed this season. In
the second game of the season against the Indianapolis Colts, he
was sidelined by two ankle sprains he'd suffered in the first half
of the opener at Denver. It ended a streak of 113 consecutive games
played. Without him, the Patriots beat the Colts, 29-6.
</P>
<P>
   Lovett Purnell, a 6-foot-3-inch, 245-pounder, started in
Coates's spot in Indianapolis and made one catch for 22 yards. Now
he's awaiting word on Coates's status for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing three years now, so it's really no big
deal,'' said Purnell, who has six catches for 47 yards and a
touchdown. ``I just got to go out there and step up and do my job.
I'll probably get a chance to do some things. I don't know if Ben
is going to come back or what. The situation may be up in the air,
but whatever it may be, I'm just gonna go out and help my team
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he's been in this situation before, Purnell said, ``I'm
very comfortable with it. I already had to do it earlier in the
year against the Colts. I think the team is very comfortable. Drew
(Bledsoe) is comfortable with me being in there. And that's very
important. As long as everybody is comfortable with me . . . as
I've said, it's my third year. If it was my first year, maybe I'd
be a little nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Purnell has often been in the game at the same time as Coates.
The coaching staff considers him an excellent pure receiver who is
still lacking in other areas, mainly blocking. Purnell has also had
to learn to play H-back, which essentially is a second fullback.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing I can do better than Ben,'' said
Purnell. ``I can't take his spot because he's an All-Pro player.
He's proved himself. What I got to do is go out there and do some
of the things that I do well _ catching the ball, running long
routes, stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson says the team has faith in Purnell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben is a great player,'' he said. ``You're gonna have
situations arise throughout the season and stuff where guys are
going to have to step in. And when Lovett steps in, we don't expect
any drop-off. Lovett is a good tight end, and Ben has some things
he has to straighten out right now. And our hearts go out to him.
But you don't have to tell a guy like Lovett nothing because he's a
professional and he knows what's at stake. And he knows he has a
job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Purnell has been around Coates for three years. He was drafted
in the seventh round out of West Virginia and anointed Coates's
heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got to go out there every day and work hard, and
hopefully on Sunday, I get a chance to play,'' said Purnell. ``But
yes, it's very difficult sometimes. Especially when you have an
All-Pro player on your team. Like I said, some games I'll play, and
hopefully this will be one of those games that I step up and play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Purnell said his first Patriots camp was tough because ``I was
coming from a school where I was the man. I came here and he was
the man. So it was definitely a challenge to get a friendship with
Ben, and I think now that we have that, hopefully, he can get back
so we can both be in the game together.''
</P>
<P>
   Purnell said he's learned from Coates about ``just being
consistent. If I make one great play, I have to come back the next
time and make another one. Just be ready at any time to make a big
play. I'm not gonna try to be Ben Coates, I'm gonna try to be
Lovett Purnell and play the best way I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
