<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TOO EARLY TO FOLLOW THE BOUNCING BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when college basketball was primarily a winter game
and, for a few glorious days each March, a spring game?
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Oh, we still have the glory and excitement of the
NCAA tournament in March. And we can come up with some conference
gems in midwinter.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to a plethora of so-called ``exempt'' games, which
has pushed the start of the regular season to the point where we'll
have games that count before Halloweeners trick-or-treat, college
basketball has become a sport for all seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Let us be either the first or the latest to offer an opinion.
November basketball stinks. Too much too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island played its first game Nov. 9. Tournaments in
Alaska, Hawaii, and New York are all part of the pre-Thanksgiving
menu. Teams pile up more frequent flier miles than travel agents on
junkets.
</P>
<P>
   Take Kansas. The Jayhawks spent Thanskgiving in Springfield for
the Tip-Off Classic (a total misnomer) against Nevada-Las Vegas the
next night. They then went home to Lawrence, Kan., for a few days,
got on a plane, and headed to Chicago for a Great Eight Classic
game against Kentucky. From there, they got on a plane and flew to
Anaheim for a Wooden Classic appearance against Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   What we have not had in almost every case is classic basketball.
Yet few teams can resist the enticement of guaranteed money and
television exposure from Maui or Fairbanks or San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Classroom time _ or missed classroom time _ is a joke. Let's not
hear any nonsense from school presidents about opposing a football
playoff because it would mean too many missed classes.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball teams abuse that concept regularly, especially in
March, and now they are traipsing all over the country in late
November and early December, when most schools schedule
first-semester final exams.
</P>
<P>
   One of the holdouts is St. Joseph's under coach Phil Martelli.
The Hawks opened their season two days after Thanksgiving against
Tulsa, which was later than anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fitting games in and I don't know why,'' said Martelli.
``We don't know what we're doing. In a couple of years, we're going
to be standing around wondering what went wrong and why the
interest level is down. The quality of play (in November) is not
good. The lack of interest is amazing. The season is too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Martelli wonders where this push for early games developed. And
why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the rush is or where it came from,'' he
said. ``I honestly believe in a couple of years, we're going to be
looking at each other and say, `What happened to the interest?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Martelli blames some of it on a pack mentality. One team
schedules a game early and another team's coach looks at it and
says, ``Geez, we've got to get a game under our belts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me any game in November that has bearing with any RPI or
anything like that in March,'' said Martelli, whose team, plus
Manhattan and Ohio, were the lone holdouts against early play in
Division 1. ``The games are totally forgotten. Basketball is a
winter game.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Martelli is 100 percent right. College basketball is a
great game, but _ perhaps with the exception of selected
longstanding tournaments in Hawaii and Alaska _ not in November.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Things are looking up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does a coach whose team is 1-4 have much to smile about.
But Bruiser Flint of the University of Massachusetts may be the
exception. Sure, the Minutemen were 1-4 following their 59-54 loss
to Connecticut Wednesday night. But Flint felt his team had
bottomed out. ``I like the way we played,'' said Flint, who has
been rewarded by athltic director Bob Marcum with a two-year
contract extension. ``We showed the kind of toughness I like. I
think we'll be all right. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   In their loss to the Huskies, the Minutemen played the tough,
in-your-face, physical basketball that has become a UMass
trademark. Center Lari Ketner, who came up with a team-high 15
points, had his best game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that UConn, which remains the No. 1 team in
the country, was better than the Minutemen. But if UMass can keep
up the intensity level, it should turn things around quickly,
probably beginning wih Saturday night's game against Boston College
at the Worcester Centrum.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jayhawks rocked
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, which is generally a nearly unbeatable team in November
and December, is having its problems. Last week the Jayhawks were
embarrassed in the Great Eight by Kentucky. This week they lost for
the first time since the 1994-95 season at Allen Field House,
falling to Iowa, 85-81, which snapped a 62-game home winning
streak. In case you were wondering, the Jayhawks weren't close to
the NCAA record of 129 straight home wins set by Kentucky from
1943-55. The loss also could put another Jayhawks streak in
jeopardy. They have been ranked in the Top 10 for 75 consecutive
Associated Press polls, dating back to 1994-95 . . . Got to love
Texas Christian coach Billy Tubbs. Seems he was not happy with the
Horned Frogs' concentration during practice, so before this week's
game against Texas Tech, he gave his players a quiz based on the
scouting report on the Red Raiders. He asked his players 110
questions. They answered 55 corrcectly. ``They got an F going into
the game, but I gave them extra credit after,'' said Tubbs
following the Frogs' 105-86 win . . . Washington is in a tailspin,
with losses to UConn, Boise State, and Gonzaga in the last week.
The Huskies' problem may be fatigue. The loss to Gonzaga this week
ended a six-game road trip that began before Thanksgiving and took
them to Hawaii, Chicago, Idaho, and Eastern Washington. Did anyone
say ``student'' athlete? . . . Here's an early candidate for
National Player of the Year: Miami of Ohio's Wally Szcerbiak. Wally
Wonder scored 31 points in Miami's 81-79 win over Marshall earlier
this week and is the prime reason the RedHawks are off to a 5-2
start . . . Speaking of starts, Rutgers is 6-1, its best seven-game
showing since the 1982-83 season . . . Rutgers freshman Rashod Kent
leads the country in field goal percentage . . . What's with all
these upsets and near upsets by have-nots against haves? Florida
Atlantic beat Oklahoma State at home, and earlier this week, 1-8
Pan American nearly beat No. 12 New Mexico at The Pit in
Albuquerque . . . West Virginia is involved in a major rebuilding
plan. The Mountaineers lost their first six players from a year
ago. Through eight games this season, coach Gale Catlett has used
eight players in the starting lineup. Going into the season,
Catlett had only one player on his roster who had started a college
game . . . Say what you will about Indiana coach Bob Knight, but
it's hard to argue with his success, his graduation rate, and the
clean reputation of the Hoosier program. Knight reached the
1,000-game career mark against Kentucky Tuesday. His teams have
compiled a 728-272 record . . . People should start paying more
attention to the Mid-American Conference. Check what has happened
already: Toledo over Xavier; Miami of Ohio over Tennessee; Ohio
University over Syracuse; Ball State and Western Michigan over
Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
