<SLUG> BC-TV-TEMPEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEMPEST' STARTS STRONG, BUT PETERS OUT; FONDA IS WARMLY
EFFECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey isn't the only production megalith trying to bring
``important'' stories to American audiences. The entire TV-movie
division at NBC has committed itself to familiarizing American
audiences with classic stories from literature.
</P>
<P>
   Such noble resolve was easy to muster given the success of
``Gulliver's Travels'' and, more recently, ``The Odyssey'' and
``Merlin.'' But, just as Oprah and ABC discovered with ``David and
Lisa'' last month, NBC learned in October with ``Crime and
Punishment'' that America likes to take its literary medicine with
a little bit of sweetener.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, after ``Crime and Punishment'' attracted an even smaller
audience than NBC expected, the network's cheese trust decided to
pull ``The Tempest'' from its November schedule, fearful of
exposing a literary classic to mass indifference during an
important ratings period. In the obscurity of mid-December, ``The
Tempest'' will now be considered a success if it merely makes a
dent against ``The X-Files'' on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a wise one. Though hardly a disaster, this
``Tempest'' is a morality play that works well for an hour or so,
and then begins to crumble in an allegorical war story that is more
confusing than enlightening. The result: A nice try, but not
completely satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is resting its hopes here on Peter Fonda, who brings to
``The Tempest'' the quiet intensity that got him an Oscar
nomination for his portrayal of a stoic Southern beekeeper in
``Ulee's Gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda remains in the deep South for this earnest ``update'' of
Shakespeare's last play, transitioning smoothly from swarms to
storms. In the telling by ``Attica'' screenwriter Jim Henerson,
Prospero, duke of Milan, becomes Gideon Prosper, Mississippi
plantation owner.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda's Prosper is a kind-hearted man who loses interest in his
plantation after the death of his wife. He prefers to dabble in
magic and sorcery under the tutelage of a slave named Ezeli
(Donzaleigh Abernathy), leaving everyday business to his scoundrel
brother, Anthony (John Glover).
</P>
<P>
   Bad idea. Glover's Anthony is as nasty as the devil (which
Glover plays every Friday on ``Brimstone''). Gideon ends up exiled
to a bayou treehouse with his daughter, Miranda (Katherine Heigl),
and Ezeli's orphaned son, Ariel (Harold Perrineau Jr.). After 12
years, he's gotten pretty good at the magic, better still at
playing the hermit and instilling wholesome values in Miranda and
Ariel.
</P>
<P>
   While marginally faithful to Shakespeare's story, ``The
Tempest'' never achieves the dynamic impact implicit in the title,
even with the Civil War as a backdrop. Fonda is warmly effective as
the loving father who can whip up a storm at will and who wrestles
with questions of loyalty, independence, honor and duty. Heigl is
fresh and appealing as the daughter who's never known anything but
a sheltered life away from civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Special visual effects by the Frame Store, which also handled
``Gulliver,'' ``Odyssey'' and ``Merlin,'' are impressive. But, in
serving us Bard Lite, NBC has only made it obvious that ``less
filling'' doesn't work well in drama.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempest. A retelling of Shakespeare's mystical story of
honor and betrayal. Starring Peter Fonda, John Glover, Katherine
Heigl and Harold Perrineau Jr. Sunday night on NBC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5189 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-EAST-GERMANY-BOS &LR;      12-11 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-EAST-GERMANY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST GERMANS ADMIT DOPING; AMERICANS WANT THEIR MEDALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shirley Babashoff should have been America's golden girl at the
1976 Summer Olympics. Holland's Enith Brigitha would have been the
first black swimming champion. Canada could have won three gold
medals instead of zero.
</P>
<P>
   If only the International Olympic Committee had known then what
everybody knows now _ that East Germany had pumped its teenage
swimmers full of steroids _ it could have rearranged the medal
stand and rewritten the record books.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a decade of admissions by former GDR coaches,
doctors, and swimmers and findings in two recent German criminal
trials, the Americans want what they believe they were cheated out
of 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Appropriate medal recognition,'' says US Olympic Committee
president William Hybl, who has asked the IOC executive committee
to revisit history when it meets this weekend in Lausanne,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Since a German court has found that medley relay swimmer Andrea
Pollack Pinske was doped before the Montreal Games, the USOC wants
the American quartet of Linda Jezek, Lauri Siering, Camille Wright,
and Babashoff, plus alternates Wendy Boglioli and Lelei Fonoimoana,
to be upgraded from silver to gold.
</P>
<P>
   Though director general Francois Carrard has said the IOC would
consider awarding medals on a case-by-case basis if presented with
``conclusive evidence'' that the East Germans were doped, the Lords
of the Rings fear they would be opening themselves up for a global
migraine, with hundreds of athletes from dozens of countries
demanding medals they believe they should have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while, we've looked at the issue
hypothetically,'' says Richard Pound, an IOC vice president who
swam for Canada in the 1960 Games at Rome. ``But it's just a
nightmare when you try to rejigger what you think might have been
history. For the IOC to step in and make these God-like decisions
as to who should have gotten what . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Though the USOC is requesting medals for only one event at one
Olympics, nobody believes it will stop there. Since Petra
Kind-Schneider has admitted that she was doped before the 1980
Games in Moscow, the British are asking that Sharron Davies be
given a gold medal in the 400-meter individual medley.
</P>
<P>
   Even if East Germany had doped only female swimmers before the
1976 Games, the upgrade list for beaten rivals would number more
than three dozen. But signed admissions from former East German
coaches and detailed medical records kept by the Stasi, the GDR's
secret police, show that their elite swimmers were doped for years.
</P>
<P>
   US Swimming, which has been monitoring German trials and media
reports for the better part of two years, has a list of 25 American
women and several men it believes are entitled to Olympic makeup
medals.
</P>
<P>
   And the GDR didn't merely dope swimmers. State Plan 1425
eventually required it for every sport but sailing. Since East
Germany won 409 summer medals and 110 winter medals in 24 sports
between 1968 (its first Olympic year on its own) and 1988 (its last
as a nation), the IOC's potential caseload is staggering. ``It's
just a bottomless swamp,'' muses Pound. ``You wander in and you're
never seen again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A difficult case to prove
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has been quick to redistribute medals when athletes are
caught doping at the Games _ Carl Lewis got a gold after Ben
Johnson was stripped in Seoul a decade ago. And the USOC (which
will honor the swimmers in some way, no matter what the IOC does)
isn't asking that the East Germans' medals be taken away. ``Their
women were victims, too,'' says Hybl. ``They were told they were
being given vitamins.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no East German ever tested positive in any sport at any
Olympics. So while they may not have been innocent, they weren't
found guilty at the time. And IOC vice president Jacques Rogge said
in October that it would need to be proved that the swimmers were
doped on the day they competed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, who can be sure that their beaten rivals weren't doped,
too? ``It may be that we say, `Look, the chapter is closed,' ''
Pound muses. ``It's a quarter-century away, and what we have to do
now is get the genie back in the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that doping began with the GDR. Thomas Hicks, the American
who inherited the 1904 marathon gold medal after teammate Fred Lorz
was disqualified for riding 11 miles in a truck, was drugged
repeatedly during the race with sulfate of strychnine and cognac.
</P>
<P>
   But the East Germans were the first to dope athletes universally
and systematically as a matter of state policy _ to prove that
communism was superior to capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Though the GDR had a population the size of New York State's in
a country the size of Ohio, it leapfrogged past the United States
in the Olympic medal standings in one quadrennium. The American
swimmers, who had their heads handed to them by the East Germans at
the 1973 world meet in Budapest, were the first to sense that
something was odd.
</P>
<P>
   The GDR hadn't won a single women's gold medal at the 1972
Olympics; it won 11 at the worlds. ``It was just too much of a
quantum leap for one country to be making,'' says US Olympic coach
Mark Schubert, who was Babashoff's club coach.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1976 Games, the East Germans held virtually every women's
world record. They blew the rest of the planet out of the water in
Montreal, taking every race but the 200-meter breaststroke and
freestyle relay and winning 18 medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the East Germans were using drugs,'' says Karen
``Moe'' Thornton, who had won the 200-meter butterfly in 1972 but
finished fourth in 1976 despite swimming nearly three seconds
faster. ``But you couldn't really talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans observed that the Kornelias and Petras and
Ulrikes looked more like men than women, they were dismissed as
poor sports. Babashoff, who finished a frustrated and bewildered
second to East Germans in three individual races, was labeled
``Surly Shirley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those accusations hurt her,'' says Schubert. ``Shirley was the
only person who had the guts to speak up about what we all knew was
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The lid comes off
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1989, when the Berlin Wall came down and the two
Germanies subsequently merged, that everyone found out what had
been going on.
</P>
<P>
   The Stasi files, which meticulously detailed which athletes had
been given which drugs how often, were confiscated and made public.
Twenty coaches admitted in writing that they had doped their
swimmers during the '70s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack Pinske, Christiane Knacke-Sommer, and Carola
Nitschke-Beraktschjan all offered to give back their Olympic or
world medals. Knacke-Sommer said Kornelia Ender and Barbara Krause,
both multiple Olympic gold medalists, were drugged. Rica Reinisch,
Daniela Hunger, and Kind-Schneider, who won eight Olympic medals
among them, all said they were doped. Stasi documents showed that
Olympic champions Kristin Otto and Heike Friedrich were also
drugged. And court evidence lists Olympic medalist Manuela
Stellmach and world champions Sylvia Gerasch and Birgit Meineke.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the results from four Olympiads (the GDR boycotted the
1984 Games in Los Angeles) were tarnished. Swimming World magazine
last year ran a two-part series (``The Way Things Should Have
Been'') and began pushing for makeup medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides Babashoff and all the other Americans on down, there
was Brigitha and the Canadians,'' says Phil Whitten, Swimming
World's editor-in-chief. ``Though the Canadians were lambasted by
their press for their poor showing in Montreal, it was actually
their best. But what happened to them affected the enthusiasm and
funding for swimming in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the German government began a series of trials charging
former GDR swimming officials with committing bodily injury on
minors, the compensation push began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   US Swimming asked a German lawyer to monitor the trials and
hired Colorado Springs attorney Rich Young to compile a list of any
former East German swimmers who turned up in court transcripts and
media reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insinuation, rumor, innuendo, hearsay _ that's not the
standard we're looking for,'' says Hybl. ``We want conclusive proof
_ confessions and convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the trials are over (and there may be half a dozen
more), the USOC could be asking for a basketful of medals. Counting
individual events and relays, Kornelia Ender, who won four gold
medals in 1976, affected eight American swimmers. Otto, who won a
record six golds at Seoul, affected a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Odds are that the IOC will turn over the medal issue to its
juridical commission until the trials are over _ whenever that is.
``We don't want to be seen as interfering or anticipatory,'' says
Pound.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the Lords of the Rings are unlikely to wade into the
bottomless swamp, handing out medals to grievants. ``It's a mess,''
concedes Pound. ``I don't know what the right thing to do is.''
</P>
<P>
   The right thing might be a makeup medal. It might be membership
in the Olympic Order, which was the consolation prize US boxer Roy
Jones got last year for being jobbed in Seoul. It might be a formal
letter of acknowledgement. It might be an asterisk in the record
book. And it might simply be a massive commitment to finally put
the drug genie back in the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever it is, Babashoff and her relay mates can't ever get
what they wanted _ their moment atop the medal stand, hearing the
anthem and watching the Stars and Stripes go up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't up there,'' Camille Wright says, 22 years later.
``You can't get that moment back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1351EST &QL; 
