<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-EAST-GERMANY-US-B     12-11 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-EAST-GERMANY-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TOO LATE FOR OLYMPIC LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Camille Wright remembers the first time she saw the East German
swimmers up close. ``It was at a workout before our dual meet with
them in California in 1975,'' she says. ``I was walking behind the
blocks and they were already in the water with their backs to us. I
thought, `Those guys are huge.' And then I saw a strap and I said,
`Oh my God, those are the girls.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The GDR madchen had massive shoulders and deep voices, and they
swam ungodly fast. Not just one or two of them. Eight or nine. ``We
knew in our hearts,'' says Wendy Boglioli. ``Everyone knew that
something was not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the world knows that the East Germans were pumped up on
steroids, that the results from the 1976 and 1980 and 1988 Olympic
Games are tainted. ``I wish they would have been caught 20 years
ago,'' says Wright.
</P>
<P>
   If they had been, Wright would have won a gold medal in the
medley relay and a silver in the 100-meter butterfly. Boglioli
would have had three golds. And Shirley Babashoff, who had also won
three medals in 1972, would have had five golds, the most ever by
an American female at one Games. ``Her life really would have been
different,'' muses Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Babashoff, who was 19 that year, quit swimming the next winter.
She's now a 41-year-old single mother who delivers mail in
Huntington Beach, Calif., not far from where she grew up. She has
an unlisted number, skips reunions with her former teammates, and
rarely talks about what happened _ or didn't happen _ in Montreal.
And she won't be checking her mailbox for makeup medals from
Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going to happen,'' Babashoff told the Orange County
Register last summer. ``To me, this happened a long time ago. It's
like beating a dead horse. People have talked for 22 years.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, Babashoff and her teammates have long since dealt with
losing to ``guys.'' They say they feel sorry for their East German
rivals, who may not have known that the ``vitamins'' they were
force-fed were steroids. Some of them now have health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just kids,'' says Boglioli. ``They didn't know what
they were taking. They did what they were told. But whether they
knew it or not, those aren't the right times. The medals don't
belong to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, after comparing the times from their Olympic
trials with those of the East Germans, were resigned to getting
hammered even before they went to Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no discussion of, well, let's suck it up and beat
them, anyway,'' says Karen ``Moe'' Thornton, who captained the team
with Boglioli. ``A lot of people felt we really couldn't beat them,
that they'd accomplished as much as they could by making the team.
I couldn't do anything to change that. It was an awkward dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   When the GDR medley relay demolished the Americans in the
opening race, breaking the world record by more than five seconds,
the tone for the week was set. Except for the 200-meter
breaststroke, which the Soviet Union swept, the East Germans didn't
lose a race until the finale.
</P>
<P>
   When Babashoff and her mates set a world mark to win the
freestyle relay, they were giddy with disbelief. ``It was something
beyond our wildest dreams,'' says Boglioli, who swam the second
leg. ``Nobody expected anything from us from day one. But we all
went above and beyond what everyone could do.''
</P>
<P>
   That should have been the capper to a golden week for the US
women. Instead, they went home feeling like failures. ``The men's
team (12 of 13 golds and 11 world records) did really great,''
Wright says. ``And it was: `What happened to you guys? You got
killed.' And we did get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at least, the world knows why. That's a source of
satisfaction for the Class of 1976. ``It's something positive for
kids to see,'' says Boglioli. ``That even if it takes this long,
you're going to get caught.''
</P>
<P>
   And though they're not counting on getting makeup medals, they
wouldn't mind something in the record book acknowledging that the
GDR results were chemically enhanced. ``I'd be in favor of an
asterisk,'' says Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no consolation prize can make up for what happened at
Olympus, not just in Montreal but in Moscow in 1980 and Seoul in
1988. ``You can't rewrite history,'' says Thornton. ``You can't
turn back the clock and redo events. It's just the way it was. For
three quadrennials, the best athletes weren't rewarded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
