<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5194 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-STAR-TREK-BOS &LR;      12-11 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STAR-TREK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING COMFORTABLY WHERE STAR TREK HAS GONE BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
STAR TREK: INSURRECTION 
Directed by: Jonathan Frakes 
Screenplay by: Michael Piller 
Starring: Patrick Stewart, Frakes, Brent Spiner, LeVar Burton,
Michael Dorn, Gates McFadden, Marina Sirtis, F. Murray Abraham,
Donna Murphy, Anthony Zerbe, Gregg Henry, Daniel Hugh-Kelly 
Running time: 103 minutes 
Rated: PG (sci-fi action violence, mild language, and sensuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' is the ninth in the series, but
who's counting? What's important to Trekkies in particular and
moviegoers in general is that the successors to the late ``Star
Trek'' founder Gene Roddenberry have got the mix right for the big
screen after a few clunky missteps, and are keeping it on track. On
the one hand, the latest installment goes places Roddenberry never
could in terms of special effects. Beefed up with the latest
computer-generated imagery, the new installment featuring the new
generation is on a new frontier of technology. On the other hand,
``Star Trek: Insurrection'' wisely stays true to the simple
morality tales that have always been the core of the series's
appeal. The planets are always new, at least nominally. But the
stories play out like familiar rituals, and this latest entry
reassuringly provides more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' boasts the last word in
explosions and outer-space fireworks, its charm derives from a
setting that makes no effort to disguise the fact that it happens
to be in the Sierra Nevada of California. It's called the Ba'ku
planet in the film, but it disarmingly suggests a sort of hippie
Shangri-La, much like Ewok country in ``Return of the Jedi,''
populated by peaceful people in homespun garments, using
technology-shunning handmade implements, soon up to their gentle
eyeballs in imported aggression. First, Brent Spiner's
scene-stealing android, Data, runs amok. Then Patrick Stewart's
Captain Picard finds himself double-crossed by the Federation's
moldy, prunelike allies on what he thought was a cultural survey.
</P>
<P>
   But no. The wrinkled Son'a unit, headed by F. Murray Abraham,
with the clothes sense of Darth Vader's boss and never more in need
of a facial, wants to take the planet over for itself. Meanwhile,
Picard learns that the hippies not only are not what they seem, but
are not as young as they seem. They have landed on a
fountain-of-youth planet, and the Son'a want it. What ensues before
the inevitable climactic computer-generated big bang is the usual
endearing agonizing over the morality of disobeying the
Federation's prime directive of never interfering with the lives of
civilizations on other planets. It's spiced by dialogue rich in
pseudoscientific terminology, such as metaphasic radiation _ a key
plot point, you'll be happy to learn. It's hard not to get behind
the moral debates. How many other sci-fi fireworks movies even
bother with morality, as ``Star Trek,'' plain or now fancy, does?
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just about good guys and bad guys; it's also about
values. ``Star Trek'' isn't afraid to be a little square. But
that's all it needs to win anew its audience of hard-core Trekkies,
aging hippies, incipient hippies, and latter-day fans brought on
board by the revitalized ``Next Generation'' TV series. The
direction by Jonathan Frakes, who plays Picard's second in command,
is knowing, if a bit pedestrian. Stewart has never looked better,
or better prepared for Picard's heroics. Possibly it's because
Picard is smitten with one of the planet's inhabitants, Donna
Murphy's Ba'ku grande dame, who's able simultaneously to project
soft allure and timeless wisdom, enough at least to keep Spiner's
Data from walking away with the movie yet again, just as Leonard
Nimoy's Spock used to do. With ``Star Trek: Insurrection,'' the
franchise continues to prosper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
