<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S BEST FOR HAIRLINE CRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 13, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My 30-year-old house had settlement cracks in a ceiling and a
wall recently. I applied joint compound and paper tape, to prevent
them from recurring. Well, they did, cracking right through the
tape. I'd like to retape, but should I dig out the cracks to be a
little wider than the hairlines there now? Is there an alternative?
</P>
<P>
   JOE CRIVELLO, Duxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If cracks appeared within the last few years, they are not
from settlement, because the house has done all the settling within
a few years of its building. The cracks are from expansion and
contraction of the wall and ceiling as they gain and lose moisture.
</P>
<P>
   If you retape, remove the old tape and compund and open the
cracks 1/8 to 1/4 inch wide, and as deep as the plasterboard. Apply
a self-adhesive nylon mesh tape of the type used when Blueboard is
skimcoated. Then fill the crack with joint compound, pressing right
through the tape, and spread it thinly on each side; this will
allow the compound to key into the crack rather than sitting on the
surface. Apply a thin coat over the tape, and after that dries,
apply two more thin layers of compound, letting it dry between
coats. Sand and repaint.
</P>
<P>
   Nylon mesh tape is designed to resist the stress of expanding
and contracting materials.
</P>
<P>
   Or, try this easier method, which might work as well or better.
Remove the tape and old compound. Buy PhenoSeal, a flexible
adhesive caulk in a caulking cartridge. Run a bead of this on the
crack and press it in with your fingers. This flexible caulk is the
only thing that can be forced into a hairline crack; you could
widen it a bit, but that might not be necessary. Scrape off excess
with a putty knife and clean residue with a wet sponge. The caulk
will expand and contract with the movement of the wall/ceiling and
keep the crack from reappearing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I moved into a new house, a condo in September, and noticed a
crack in the basement concrete floor. It is not leaking. The
contractor is willing to come back and fill it with mortar. Will
that solve the problem?
</P>
<P>
   JIM FOGARTY, Chelmsford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no problem to fix, because unreinforced concrete
like your floor is born to crack, sooner or later. Patching would
be cosmetic, unless you are getting water up those cracks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I maintain and clean newly-polyurethaned floors? How
about scuff marks?
</P>
<P>
   FRAN OLFE, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Dry-mopping and vacuuming will keep the floor clean. For
stubborn spots, damp-mop with water, but only damp, not wet. For
scuff marks, put a little oil on the marks, wait 10 minutes, and
wipe clean. For stubborn scuff marks, scrub lightly with Brillo or
SOS pads.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to get rubber roof material to patch a gouge? That is what
Arthur Rosenberg of West Newton wanted to know recently. The
handyman did not know, so he put it up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   One type is called Low Slope, which Charles Radin of Brookline,
Mass. used to fix a leak in a small section of his roof. It is
available through Beacon Sales, 50 Webster Ave., Somerville; Mass.,
phone 617-666-2800.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Montenegro of Randolph, Mass. called to say that her
husband is a roofer, and gave this warning about rubber roofs:
``You should not use any kind of adhesive other than rubber roof
adhesive; others could corrode the rubber. A primer is required; it
is called Hexaprene. You have to use a seam tape to seal the
material. The materials (from Harvey Industries, and R&AMP;R Sales in
Dorchester) are sold only to pros. But you could call my husband,
Patricio Montenegro in Randolph.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Pietraszek of Fall River enclosed a piece of a rubber
material that he used. ``I have a roll of this stuff and will be
glad to share some if it will help,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, kind people, for the information. But the handyman
cannot give out phone numbers of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The new painted shingles on my 1993 addition were covered
with mildew last spring; the painter washed it off with bleach and
water, but in autumn it came back worse than ever. The painted
shingles on the old part of the house are free of mildew. Why is
there such a difference between the old and new?
</P>
<P>
   CYNTHIA CARTER, West Roxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the new shingles were white cedar and then painted, they
were uncured, or full of water; the moisture kept coming, and
mildew thrives on moisture. The shingles on the old part of the
house were dry, having less chance of getting wet; hence little or
no mildew.
</P>
<P>
   Keep going with the solution of one part bleach and three parts
water; you will have to do this wherever and whenever the mildew
appears. You can use an additive for the bleach to be more
effective longer; one is Pittsburgh Pants' Mildew-Proof, sold in
paint stores, and another is Jomax, wich is mixed with bleach and
water. Made by Zehring of Portland, Ore., it may be available in
paint stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
