<HEADLINE>
COACHES STILL OUT THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what's become of the dozens of East German coaches and
doctors who doped their swimmers for nearly two decades? Most of
them are still working in clubs in reunified Germany. And one of
them, Winfried Leopold, headed the German team at this year's world
championships _ until the international federation pulled his
accreditation after he admitted he gave steroids to GDR swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only ones who've been banned have either admitted what
they did or been convicted in a court of law,'' says Swimming World
editor-in-chief Phil Whitten, who has documented the sport's doping
problems for much of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches Rolf Glaeser, Volker Frischke, Dieter Lindemann, and
Dieter Krause and doctors Bernd Pansold and Dieter Binus, who all
worked for the Dynamo Berlin club, were convicted and fined this
year for causing bodily harm to minors.
</P>
<P>
   More coaches and doctors are expected to stand trial next year
as the German government continues its club-by-club investigation
of doping abuses in the former GDR.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
