<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAYS A LA MARTHA: YOUR GOOSE IS ...BOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So I was working on my Martha's Calendar the other day _ you
know, the one in the Martha Stewart Living magazine that we who are
organizationally challenged need so desperately. There are many
entries for outdoor types who just can't get enough Martha.
</P>
<P>
   Martha, you see, is an outdoorswoman extraordinaire, though she
adds these wonderful Martha touches to give her pursuits a kind of
Martha-does-Orvis panache.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there was the famous Halloween canoe ride a couple
of years back, which Martha immortalized on the cover of her
magazine. Martha herself _ dressed, I think, in widewhale corduroys
and a beige cashmere sweater wrapped in a loose, studied way about
her shoulders _ was just pushing off in her canoe for an adventure.
In my mind's eye, here's how the picture remains:
</P>
<P>
   Martha and a golden retriever are just pushing off in the canoe,
perhaps into the Connecticut River somewhere around East Lyme or
Hamburg Cove. Somewhere in the canoe, there must be a wicker picnic
basket _ for all or at least most of Martha's outdoor adventures
involve wicker picnic baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Where the golden retriever is in relation to the wicker picnic
basket, I cannot recall. And that is probably because of the
stunning central focus of this cover shot. On the bow of that
canoe, propped miraculously (and there must be a registered
trademark for the MarthaBracket invented to mount it), is a
candlelit pumpkin with a leering jack o' lantern face carved in it.
</P>
<P>
   It got me thinking back to a few of the canoe trips I have
taken, and I was trying to remember one when I could have paddled 5
yards without the candle in that pumpkin going out. Or perhaps the
pumpkin itself falling off its perch in the bow, and maybe
depositing the candle with that hot wax on the wicker picnic basket
or the golden retriever's paw.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I was then, and remain to this day, spellbound by Martha
in her role as outdoorswoman, which is why I was perusing her
bimonthly calendar in the first place. (But do not climb Mt.
Everest with any of her friends, though that is another story.)
</P>
<P>
   On the Dec. 4 Martha's entry is ``Have dogs groomed.'' One of
those dogs must be the retriever. I'm wondering if he's being
groomed before or after he plods around in the marsh mud retrieving
a bagged seaduck, or perhaps a Canada goose.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, would you actually have your retriever groomed in
December, with waterfowl season open? Or would you wait until Dec.
15, next Tuesday, when the season ends?
</P>
<P>
   But here we find on the 15th Martha is ordering her Christmas
goose from the butcher, a fact I found stunning. Any home ec
overachiever who would grow the corn for her own corn muffins must
surely not accept a butcher's version of the Christmas goose.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Martha has let me down. My heart is hardened to the fact
that on Jan. 5, she is having her gardening equipment serviced, or
that on the 25th, she will refill the wood bin. Because I have a
sneaky idea that in Martha's fireplace is actually one of those
propane jets that keep you from getting all those bark chips in
your house.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the real bottom-line entry in the Martha Stewart
calendar is Jan. 28. That's the day she makes an appointment with
her tax accountant.
</P>
<P>
   And that leaves me out on the marsh with a nice big Canada goose
to bring home for Christmas dinner, but no Martha advice on what to
do next. I mean, goose raises many problems, No. 1 of which is
goose grease. I'm sure somewhere in the Martha lexicon is something
about how to rub goose grease on your deck shoes, but that doesn't
help in the preparation.
</P>
<P>
   From the time you're standing there with your 12-pound goose to
the time it appears on the Christmas table, there is much to do.
Actually, Martha's market goose will have a lot more grease to deal
with than the wild goose, which has much less fat, especially if it
is a newly arrived migrant from the Canadian Maritimes.
</P>
<P>
   You must hang your goose for at least 24 hours and better a
week, and of course, plucking the goose may dampen your desire to
shoot your own Christmas goose again. It is a project. But if you
insist on saving the whole bird, truss it and roast it like a
turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that is, when you shoot your goose, you're not
quite sure of its age, and after a couple of years, a Canada
becomes an unlikely candidate for roasting. Too tough. Roast only
the young birds, which will probably be closer to 6 pounds than 10.
</P>
<P>
   It's a better idea to breast out a big bird, which gets you past
the plucking chores, too. The breast and upper legs should then be
marinated in ginger lime or teriyaki, sliced, then barbecued like
any piece of steak or chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Another preparation is to heat a sauce of butter and onions in a
heavy casserole, drop in browned slices of goose, and simmer with a
little lemon, allspice, and red wine for about half an hour (check
tenderness).
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the Martha Stewart lexicon are there preparations for
this fine form of wild goose, nor is there an entry for going over
the hanging ducks carefully to remove shot with the point of your
knife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     12-11 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT GOES TO CONN...KEEPS THE CON GOING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Connecticut Yahoos will not be discouraged. Fork over $375
million to make a rich guy richer? . . . No problem. Build it on a
toxic waste dump? . . . Pass the shovels. Pay for seats that Bob
Kraft can't sell? . . . Have some more cash, Bob. Ram it through
the legislature before anybody notices what a crummy deal this is?
. . . Pass the pompoms.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut isn't the Nutmeg State. It's the Nutbag State.
Apparently, these folks will do anything to think of themselves as
major league.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime consumer advocate Ralph Nader isn't fooled. He knows
that Bob Kraft's new playpen is the Corvair of stadium deals. A
citizen of (Winsted) Connecticut, Nader refused to attend
Wednesday's sham hearing in Hartford to discuss the prospective
move of the Patriots. ``I don't believe in entering a whorehouse,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his Washington office, Nader was asked what he would
have said to Kraft if he had gone to the public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say, `What quantity of shame do you have in your soul,
Mr. Kraft? Go back to Massachusetts.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a lucky month for him,'' added Nader. ``The
officials gave him a game and (Governor John) Rowland gives him
Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's rigged hearing came on the heels of Tuesday's
nauseating pep rally. Bob took Chad Eaton, Bruce Armstrong, and
Press Corner Tebucky Jones to Hartford's Civic Center Mall for the
lame-o rally. Old Papa Bear Bob once again got all teary-eyed and
said he just felt so welcome. As ever, he talked to the Hartford
Yahoos with total disregard for the loyal fan base back in
Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Like Roger Clemens, Mo Vaughn, and every other free agent of our
era, Kraft can't bring himself to come out and say, ``It's all
about the money.'' No. He has to make himself sound like a
struggling vendor, seeking a new home for his small operation. We
keep hearing about how much money he's losing, about how much he
overpaid for the team, and about a new stadium being the only way
he can bring a championship team to New England.
</P>
<P>
   I love it when Kraft talks about not making money on his team.
He paid $158 million for the franchise, and it's going to be worth
$450 million if/when he gets this deal in Hartford. Yo, Bob. My
house costs me money every month. But I get to live there. And I do
not expect it to be worth three times what I paid for it over the
course of eight years.
</P>
<P>
   This is not even getting into the fact that Kraft sells out
every game and will get $17 million in expansion money this year.
Oh yes, and let's not forget the multibillion-dollar TV deal the
NFL signed last year. Over the course of the eight-year deal, each
NFL team will average $80 million annually from the networks.
</P>
<P>
   And get this, fellow Bostonians. Kraft wants to make sure that
once he leaves Foxborough, no NFL team is permitted to land
anywhere near Boston in the future. He wants to claim the entire
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he's got the suckers in Connecticut buying the whole
thing, ramming home legislation before anybody reads the fine
print. Those were some mighty softballs they tossed his way
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   God bless the ever-vigilant Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to spend $600 million-$700 million, which is
what it's going to come out to, it's better to spend it repairing
the crumbling Hartford school system,'' said Nader. ``The Patriots
should be renamed `The Freeloaders,' and the new stadium should be
`Taxpayer Stadium.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This is corporate welfare at its worst. It's having
middle-class taxpayers subsidize a stadium for the superrich for 10
days a year. It may pass in the legislature. But they won't be able
to put it behind them. This will be a multipronged thorn stuck in
their throat so they can't spit or swallow. It's such a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they'd get away with it, and they might. Why not
have the glitter of an NFL team in Hartford? This is fun and games
for the legislators using other people's money.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote is Tuesday. No later. Rowland wants to make sure this
is handled swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's such a good deal, why was it kept secret from May
until after the election?'' said Nader. ``If it's such a good deal,
why rush it? There isn't anything they didn't give away except the
capitol dome.''
</P>
<P>
   And remember, they're not going to Hartford, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
