<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SIMPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `A SIMPLE PLAN,' DELIGHTFUL COMPLEXITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A SIMPLE PLAN 
Directed by: Sam Raimi 
Screenplay by: Scott B. Smith (from his novel) 
Starring: Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton, Brent Briscoe, Bridget
Fonda, Jack Walsh, Chelcie Ross, Becky Ann Baker, Gary Cole 
Running time: 123 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Simple Plan'' is the holiday movie season's sleeper. It's a
starkly powerful, beautifully controlled, terrifically acted
morality fable, seething with primal forces. It's a ``Treasure of
the Sierra Madre'' transplanted to the snowy Midwest, where
lifelong bonds between brothers _ played by Bill Paxton and Billy
Bob Thornton, with Brent Briscoe as Thornton's sidekick _ are
tested to the breaking point when money unexpectedly comes into
their lives. It also represents a real stretch for director Sam
Raimi, who moves far beyond the genre flair he has displayed on
previous occasions to the shaping of an impressive actors' piece.
</P>
<P>
   As in Raimi's previous films (``Darkman,'' ``The Evil Dead''),
there's plenty of blood, but unlike anything he's ever done, this
is a character-driven piece, with exceptional work by its three
male leads and by Bridget Fonda. Paxton and Thornton tap a mournful
fatefulness as brothers in a Midwestern farm town whose sibling
rivalry is detonated when they and a hunting buddy find a duffel
bag containing $4 million in the fuselage of a crashed plane in a
snowy forest. At first, it seems a windfall. But scarcely have they
finished counting the money than hitherto-latent tensions begin
surfacing.
</P>
<P>
   By local standards, Paxton's Hank is a success. He's educated,
smooth, successful, married. A tidy package, complete with nice
wife (Bridget Fonda), nice house, nice cozy future. Thornton's
Jacob, on the other hand, is retrograde: slightly retarded,
raggedy, living in a shabby apartment in town since the family farm
failed, uneducated, without prospects. Thornton takes a chance,
dancing on the edge of caricature, working with a shaggy wig and a
prosthetic overbite. Jacob, the merest glimpse of him proclaims, is
a loser.
</P>
<P>
   His redneck buddy, Lou (Briscoe), is quicker than Jacob to give
voice to the resentments implicit in the economic and class
differences separating them from Hank. Time and again, your eyes
keep returning to Thornton's Jacob, who is in every way slow, but
soon convinces us that he has lots of soul, and more emotional
intelligence and sensitivity than the other two. Paxton delivers
his subtlest performance ever as a nice guy you want to keep
liking, despite his ever-deepening immersion in corrosive actions.
And Briscoe's redneck sidekick catches all the sourness of
deprivation he feels.
</P>
<P>
   It's a film, in short, that one never knew Raimi had in him.
Given Hank's inclination to simply sit on the money until they can
be sure it's safe to spend, and Jacob's and Lou's impatience to
start spending it to extricate themselves from the economic pits in
which they're mired, rifts develop with what could have been
predictability, but in this case seems inevitability. Raimi uses
the landscape to invoke the primal forces unleashed when the money
triggers greed, deception, and a revelation of how quickly the
fragile bonds linking the three can dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   One thing goes wrong, then another, then there's blood on the
snow, then it's a question of whether the criminals who took the
money in the first place will return looking for it, or whether the
brothers and their neighbor can stick together to somehow bring off
what had seemed a simple plan. It proves anything but as first a
nosy sheriff begins poking around and then a scary stranger comes
to town as the uneasy finders squabble over how to handle the
money.
</P>
<P>
   The film effortlessly nails the texture and flavor of Midwestern
plainness. And Paxton and Thornton plumb and explore the
complicated relationship of the farm-town brothers. At the end,
Thornton's unlikely Jacob rises to something like tragic grandeur.
Although all three deserve Oscar nods, Thornton is the likeliest to
get one. His character is the most vivid and most moving.
Throughout, the characters' concentration never wavers. Nor does
the grave clarity with which Raimi charts the slippage of their
world into chaos. It would be easy to overlook ``A Simple Plan'' in
the glut of holiday movies, but it really is a striking
achievement, partly because Scott B. Smith, who wrote the novel,
wrote the screenplay as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Mike Nichols was the first director mentioned in
connection with ``A Simple Plan.'' Now, Raimi has made what many
would think of as a Mike Nichols movie _ penetrating, focused,
wintry internally as well as externally. And ``A Simple Plan'' is
that rarity in a crowded field of movies that contain violence;
it's one of the few films that make you feel the moral weight of
the consequences of that violence. Indeed, it makes you feel the
violence these men start doing to their souls before any of them
reaches for a gun. We feel the men feeling troubled, we feel the
weight of lives in upheaval in a landscape where nature itself is a
character, impassive and unsparing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
