<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PLACIDO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINGO BEYOND `PAGLIACCI' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty-three years ago the Handel &AMP; Haydn Society's single
performance of Handel's ``Messiah'' presented an unknown young
Mexican tenor soloist who was in town that season to sing in ``La
Boheme'' and Rameau's ``Hippolyte et Aricie'' for Sarah Caldwell
and the Opera Company of Boston. His name was Placido Domingo. The
story is that Caldwell got him for $250 a performance _ plus
baby-sitting fees.
</P>
<P>
   After the tenor's ``Messiah'' performance, Michael Steinberg
reported in the Globe, ``Domingo has a handsome voice and
apparently considerable musicianship and technique. He was,
however, riveted so closely to his score that it seemed as though
he were finding out about `Messiah' one eighth note at a time as it
went along.''
</P>
<P>
   Within three years of that ``Messiah,'' Domingo had begun a
glorious career at the Metropolitan Opera, where this year he
celebrated the 30th anniversary of his debut _ and three decades at
the top of his profession. Domingo has also developed an important
supplementary career as a conductor, and serves as artistic
director of two opera companies, in Washington, D.C., and Los
Angeles. Domingo has not sung often in Boston since ``Hippolyte et
Aricie'' in 1966, but his regular appearances on television have
served as some compensation. A recent Washington performance of
Canio in Leoncavallo's ``Pagliacci'' was taped for television.
</P>
<P>
   To publicize this event, Domingo sat still last week for an
early evening conference-call interview following a rehearsal for a
National Symphony Orchestra concert he was conducting.
</P>
<P>
   The great American tenor Richard Tucker recorded ``Pagliacci''
as a young man, but refused to sing it onstage until he was 50; he
thought the role was too dangerous for a young voice. Domingo, on
the other hand, has sung Leoncavallo's tragic clown throughout his
career _ and he's still going strong at 57.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sang my first `Pagliacci' in 1966,'' Domingo recalls. ``I
was 25 years old. It was a concert performance for the Metropolitan
Opera before my official debut in the house. I had just sung at the
City Opera in Ginastera's `Don Rodrigo,' and the Met asked me to
sing `Pagliacci' at the old Lewisohn Stadium. I sang both
`Cavalleria Rusticana' and `Pagliacci' at that concert. I sang my
first stage performances of `Pagliacci' in Pasadena in 1967 or
1969, as a substitute for somebody else. People said if I did it, I
wouldn't have any voice left, but in my artistic life I have always
taken risks, and the part of Canio has become one of my good-luck
tokens.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger of ``Pagliacci,'' Domingo says, ``is that the drama
is so big. If you are a singer with temperament and feeling you can
lose yourself in the drama; you have to have a good technique
because a verismo opera like this can kill your voice. They say it
takes more technique to sing Verdi and Donizetti, but I'm not sure
I agree. You can start `Vesti la giubba,' but maybe you won't
finish it! The secret is to do it only with your own voice.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981 Domingo appeared in a ``Pagliacci'' production at La
Scala directed by Franco Zeffirelli that resulted in a movie, and
he has also sung in the Met's Zeffirelli production of the opera.
``The 1981 `Pagliacci' was exactly 10 years after my 40th birthday;
16 years later there are naturally many differences. I have done a
whole life singing the role of `Pagliacci.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The production that will be televised is a new Zeffirelli
production, set in in the present day. Domingo has not been
extensively associated with experimental time-travel productions,
but defends this one. `` `Pagliacci' is a believable story that
could happen at any time or in any place, not just Leoncavallo's
time, so there is no problem with updating it. . . . I have seen
updated productions of `Tosca' put into the time of the Gestapo,
but if you're still singing about Napoleon, it doesn't work. You
have to change a lot of things if you want to update `Tosca,' but
this is not the case in `Pagliacci.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Domingo has been a frequent collaborator with Zeffirelli. ``In
the films of `Pagliacci' and `Otello' there was time for him to
work with the singers in a very delicate way. In the opera house it
doesn't matter how much time you have, it isn't enough. . . . There
are always lots of little details in a Zeffirelli production, like
a little girl walking across the stage eating an apple. One of the
really great things is that this aspect works very well for
television _ in the theater it is almost impossible to see
everything that is going on in the theater, but on television you
can be more aware of the different details.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Domingo has amassed what is probably the largest
repertory of any leading tenor in history. A few parts he would
like to sing have eluded him, however. ``There are a very few roles
still that I haven't done that I really want to. Tristan I think I
will only record. I think the part is a little too much; if I were
to try to sing that third act on the stage, I would really
legitimately spoil my voice. Right now I am preparing Tchaikovsky's
`Pique-Dame,' which I have in March at the Met. I will also sing
Beethoven's `Fidelio' on a recording. I have sung Siegmund in the
Wagner's `Ring,' and Loge, but I would also like to try both
Siegfrieds, in `Siegfried' and `Die Goetterdaemmerung,' on the
recording at least. Something I would really like to do on the
recording, which I did already on the stage, is sing Enee in
Berlioz's `Les Troyens.' If I am still singing by 2003 when is
coming the 200th birthday of Berlioz, I would love to do a
recording _ but it is a tremendous achievement to do a recording of
this opera.''
</P>
<P>
   (What a great project this would be for the world's finest
Berlioz orchestra, still the BSO, and its music director, who has
evolved into a major Berlioz conductor.)
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the future of Three Tenors Enterprises is, Domingo
responds, ``We are grateful _ this is a miracle that has been going
on for eight years. In January we will do a concert in Japan and
another one in South Africa in April, and some other ones are being
prepared, maybe three or four, before we arrive in 2002 at the
World Cup football again. Maybe we will just close there. A moment
will come when the public says, `This is enough.' Or perhaps we are
closer to the moment when we are going to say ourselves, `It's
enough.' But we enjoy tremendously doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the phone you can tell that Domingo smiles at the
recollection of his Handel &AMP; Haydn Society ``Messiah'' _ his
speaking voice is expressive and melodious too. ``I had not a clue
that this career was going to come to me. I just really enjoyed
what I was doing. I was very young, but I was also very
professional, and I can tell you I was very dedicated. But you
never really think about what is going to happen _ you just do
something expecting to be good. I never did expect to be one of the
biggest people in opera; that wasn't the reason I did anything. I
went from one place to another, full speed, and I am very happy and
satisfied that I am still singing. I am still dedicated, taking
this career with devotion and dedication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
