<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SOMEWHERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOAP OPERA FOR NEW YORK FRINGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SOMEWHERE IN THE CITY 
Written by: Ramin(cq) Niami and Patrick Dillon 
Directed by: Ramin Niami 
Starring: Sandra Bernhard, Bai Ling, Ornella Muti, Robert John
Burke, Peter Stormare, Paul Anthony Stewart 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani's mad quest to turn Manhattan
into a strip shopping mall, the Lower East Side remains a precious
outpost of seedy fabulousness. It hasn't been Starbucked or
Disney-fied; it isn't jammed with Midwestern tourists with
runny-nosed kids looking for Planet Hollywood T-shirts. It
stubbornly remains the rough among ol' Rudy's cookie-cutter,
franchise diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   More life can happen on the fire escape of a Lower East Side
tenement than in entire neighborhoods, and that's probably why
Ramin Niami has set his film, ``Somewhere in the City'' within one
of those noisy, paint-peeling, vaguely dangerous monuments to New
York's not-so-good life.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``Melrose Place'' for the less-than-beautiful crowd, six
people in an ever-futile search for love, success, and just a
dollop of happiness. Sandra Bernhard's moody, urgent rendition of
Sammy Cahn's ``Until the Real Thing Comes Along'' opens the film,
and the song is accented by screams, arguments, and loud sex _ the
bodacious buzz of the downtown brownstone.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhard's Betty is finishing a rather vocal session with a
one-night stand, Henry (John Fugelsang), who wants nothing more
than to get dressed and go. But Betty, a self-involved therapist
who spends clients' sessions talking about her own problems, wants
more. She wants to talk about what happened, and what this all
means. ``I don't want commitment,'' Henry says, zipping up his
pants, ``I just want my briefcase.'' Betty is wounded but
resilient. ``If you want to apologize,'' she says, handing him a
piece of paper, ``here's my number.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, her encounter is far better than that of Marta (Ornella
Muti), who has yawn-inducing sex with the building's fat, sleazy
super, who slips her $10 and gives her a break on the rent. Marta
hopes for a life with Frankie (Robert John Burke), a would-be crook
who would do well to find another line of work. The gang he
assembles to pull a dream heist at a jewelry store is so inept, the
getaway driver demands a different job because he can't drive a
stick shift.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Graham (Peter Stormare), a struggling actor hoping
to get his big break in a screen adaptation of the old TV sitcom
``I Dream of Jeannie,'' with Madonna as Jeannie and Keanu Reeves as
Major Tony Nelson. In the meantime, he's getting the occasional
commercial and teaching woefully untalented students.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly above the fray _ or below it, depending on your
perspective _ is Che (Paul Anthony Stewart), and what would the
Lower East Side be without some noodge shouting dusty Marxist
slogans into a microphone in Union Square? Che may love talkin'
about revolution, but he's actually a rich kid embarrassed by his
Park Avenue parents. The only innocent in the lot is Lu Lu (Bai
Ling), a Chinese student looking for someone to marry so she can
get a green card.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's driven by character, not plot, the film is a bit
disjointed. And in juggling so many characters, some get dropped
for so long you have to jog your memory to recall who they are and
what their story is. But Niami treats his subjects with respect and
has a genuine affection for them.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is solid, and this is Bernhard's best role since she
shook up the world in her 1983 debut, in Martin Scorsese's ``The
King of Comedy.'' It's appropriate that the role finds her in
familiar cinematic territory _ fringe New York, where the apple may
be bruised but is still juicy and sweet at the core.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
