<HEADER>
A5233 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      12-11 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERS TO CLEO LOOKS BACK TO AN OLDER `SISTER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Letters to Cleo have been a legitimate Boston success story in
the '90s. The band achieved a nationwide hit with the irresistibly
poppy ``Here and Now'' from the ``Melrose Place'' soundtrack. That
was followed by global touring and, more recently, performances on
the Lilith Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Letters to Cleo are presently on a short break, but they've
taken that opportunity to create a special bonus for fans. It's the
remastered CD release of their original cassette of songs written
in 1988 and '89, back when singer Kay Hanley was still in her
teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only sold the cassette at shows _ and we only printed about
2,000 copies,'' Hanley says of ``Sister,'' which just came out on
Wicked Disc, the record label run by Newbury Comics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing any advertising for this. It's a very
grass-roots thing,'' says Hanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a neat way to keep things active between our other
records,'' adds Hanley, reached this week during a vacation in
Hawaii, where her husband, Mike Eisenstein (guitarist for Letters),
is doing studio work for Nina Gordon, formerly with the now-defunct
Veruca Salt.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sister'' CD is surprisingly good _ a heady dose of
incipient alterna-rock, crowned by the girl-pop attitude of Hanley.
Songs such as ``I See,'' ``He's Stayin','' and ``Pete Beat,'' all
recorded at Fort Apache studios, hold up well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what it is,'' Hanley says of the CD. ``The sound of my
voice (then) makes me cringe when I listen today, but I've always
been hard on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Letters opted to release the CD after learning through the
Internet that some fans were planning to make CD copies of the
cassette to sell to other Letters lovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the tapes they'd be copying are from third- and
fourth-generation dubs of the original cassette,'' says Hanley.
``So we decided this would be a good time to remaster it and put it
out ourselves.'' (The CD is available through Newbury Comics and
the band's Web page at www.letterstocleo.com.)
</P>
<P>
   The full-length CD is spiced with a few other tracks from the
archives. The raucous ``You Dirty Rat'' (a Scruffy the Cat tune
featuring onetime Scruffy singer Charlie Chesterman on backup
vocals), was on the ``Safe and Sound'' compilation, and ``Last of
the Secret Agents,'' a B-side that appeared only in Britain, is a
Nancy Sinatra tune given a particularly hard-rocking workout by
Hanley.
</P>
<P>
   For icing, there's also a Letters version of Fleetwood Mac's
``Dreams'' (given a surprisingly faithful reading by Hanley), which
the band originally put on a Rock for Choice compilation album.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Hanley and her cohorts expect to reconvene
early next year to write and record songs for a new album.
``Hopefully, we'll be ready to get back into the studio this
spring,'' says Hanley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1408EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WAKING-BOS &LR;      12-11 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WAKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH LIES, AND SMILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WAKING NED DEVINE 
Written and directed by: Kirk Jones 
Starring: Ian Bannen, David Kelly, Fionnula Flanagan, Susan Lynch,
James Nesbitt, Maura O'Malley, Eileen Dromey, Brendan F. Dempsey 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Rated: PG (nudity, language and thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Waking Ned Devine'' is a charmingly rambunctious village
comedy about a couple of geezers trying to float a lottery scam in
a tiny Irish coastal town. Ian Bannen's Jackie and David Kelly's
Michael, waiting a lifetime for their big score, learn, after much
surreptitious research, that the big winning national lottery
ticket was sold to Ned Devine, a bachelor fisherman. When they pay
him a visit to try to separate him from the ticket, they find him
in bed, dead of natural causes, as it dawns on us that the title
refers to mourning Ned, not bringing him out of a deep sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme escalates. Why not pose as Ned, smiling Jackie asks
nervous Michael, when the national lottery man arrives from Dublin,
and split the huge jackpot? But what's proposed in the quiet of a
dark pub changes in the light of day. Jackie's smile turns ever
more serpentine and rubbery as the complications pile up alongside
the dire predictions of Jackie's wife that they'll all end up in
jail. Given that, and the fact that this is one of those village
comedies where everybody knows everybody else's business, it isn't
long before the whole town is in on the scam _ and the payoff, if
they can bring it off and divert the lottery official with lies and
local color.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film's charm stems from writer-director Kirk Jones's
ability to convince us of everybody's essential innocence. Fionnula
Flanagan, as Jackie's wife, reminds him with a mix of terror and
common sense that Michael, the villager elected to pass himself off
as Ned, has never told a lie in his life. Bannen's Jackie, face
suffused by duplicitous good will, suggests Jack Lemmon's offshore
brother, a nice guy whose head has been turned by the self-deluding
thought that he's a criminal mastermind.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, comically frail, floating through the action like a
breath, suggests a leprechaun who has concluded a long run in a
Samuel Beckett revival. Eyes greedy with excitement and terror,
bulging out of his eggshell skull, he provides just the right note
of precariousness needed to put the brakes on Jackie's tendency to
confuse wishful thinking with reality. They're a disarmingly
orchestrated pair. It's because they're amateurs, and you know they
won't make a habit of swindling the national lottery, that you
can't resist throwing in with Jackie and Michael and hoping they'll
beat the odds _ and their own amateurish ineptness _ and somehow
pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   The locals all are inscribed with total, effortless rightness
that never stumbles into cuteness or quaintness. The setting _ the
Isle of Man in the Irish Sea _ adds a definite magic, too. As if
knowing the very atmosphere is on their side, the actors ride the
communal spirit, from Susan Lynch and James Nesbitt, whose love is
impeded because he can't shake the smell of pig farming, to Eileen
Dromey's contrary old witch, who convinces you she'd take more
pleasure making everybody else miserable than pocketing her share
of the pot. If there's the merest hint of larceny in your heart,
you'll find the delightfully lively and irrepressible ``Waking Ned
Devine'' hot-wired to it. It's one of blarney's greatest hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
