pays what. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-U.N. (United) _ Developments at the international meeting on
the year 2000 computer problem. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The World Briefing column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Japan's government appears ready to come
to the rescue of the financial system again by nationalizing Nippon
Credit Bank, the second nationalization of a major bank in three
months. An announcement appears likely this weekend. Nippon Credit,
the smallest of Japan's three long-term credit banks, is struggling
with trillions of yen in bad loans, ``junk'' credit ratings and a
dwindling business franchise. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:30 p.m., the industrial average was
down 48 points, or 0.6 percent, but the Nasdaq index was up 7
points, or 0.3 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell 2.7 percent in Tokyo
and 3.5 percent in Hong Kong. They were off 2.3 percent in
Frankfurt, 2.1 percent in London and 3.6 percent in Brazil. They
were up 0.3 percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the
long bond was off 7/32 point at midday, with the yield at 4.97
percent.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-SCHWEPPES (Undated) _ Coca-Cola issues another earnings
warning and makes a big international purchase. The company says it
expects to report earnings for the current quarter of 24 cents or
25 cents a share, below the current analyst forecast of 30 cents a
share. It also buys most of Cadbury-Schweppes' soft-drinks
businesses outside the United States for $1.85 billion. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ The recent warm weather across much
of the country has hurt retailers, especially in areas of the
Midwest and the Northeast, as demand has slumped for a host of
winter items ranging from tires and down-filled jackets to snow
boards and skis to sweaters and gloves. Now that temperatures are
falling toward more seasonable levels, retail executives are hoping
the gusts of cold air will send shoppers scrambling to the stores.
By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-EURO (Rotherham, England) _ Even as Britain watches the
launching of European monetary union from the sidelines, the debate
within the country about the wisdom of joining the euro is growing
more ferocious. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
