<HEADLINE>
CHARACTERS TOO SIMPLE IN GRIM `SIMPLE PLAN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED The simplest of plans can turn into the biggest messes
once human imperfection is factored into the equation. That's the
idea behind the crime drama ``A Simple Plan _'' and the reason the
movie isn't as good as it should have been.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in one of those wintry Western towns, where
three guys stumble on a small plane that crashed. Inside that plane
is a bag containing nearly $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The men quickly decide to keep the money. Sounds simple enough.
But for these three ordinary guys, the criminal life is more than
they can manage.
</P>
<P>
   Hank (Bill Paxton) is struggling to make ends meet down at the
feed store as he and his wife (Bridget Fonda) await their first
child.
</P>
<P>
   Hank's brother (Billy Bob Thornton) is a semi-idiot, and their
friend (Brent Briscoe) is even farther down the brain scale but
higher on the danger quotient.
</P>
<P>
   As the men wait to find out if anyone's looking for the money
before they split it, they start to crack under the pressure. Each
small slip leads them deeper into a web of coverup and murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Simple Plan'' shares a premise with the nasty comedy ``Very
Bad Things'': Take ordinary people, throw them into criminal
situations they can't handle, and watch them make messes they can't
clean up.
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Simple Plan'' is a grimly serious film, without ``Very
Bad ``Things' '' dark, demented humor to liven the wait for the
plot to develop. Also without the tense pacing and clever
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Director San Raimi (``The Quick and the Dead'') tells the story
in a straightforward way, which is the movie's strength.
</P>
<P>
   But Raimi doesn't develop the characters into people we either
like or hate. There's no one to cheer for or against in this tale
of how two wrongs don't make a right and neither do 20.
</P>
<P>
   The story itself is believable and the men go through credible
tensions. But the movie doesn't pull you into their plight.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton overdoes the idiot routines with his duct-taped glasses
and writhing face. His performance here only serves to remind you
of how much better he did with a similar character in ``Sling
Blade.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxton (``Twister'') telegraphs every move, so there's no
suspense when he's on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda (``Jackie Brown'') and Briscoe (``Sling Blade'') create
the most interesting characters, but they don't get enough screen
time.
</P>
<P>
   We probably all wonder what we'd do if we stumbled onto that
mythical bag of money. This movie serves as a primer of what not to
do.
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Simple Plan'' might have been more interesting if these
guys weren't such losers and you felt they had a shot at getting
away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Simple Plan'' is rated R for profanity, violence and nudity.
2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
