A5251 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADYOFGUADALUPE-TEX     12-11 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADYOFGUADALUPE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITHFUL MARK FEAST DAY OF OUR LADY OF QUADALUPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Our Lady of Guadalupe's image as a prayerful
Madonna framed by golden rays adorns the interiors of large and
small churches around the world. The famous icon also dangles from
rearview mirrors and is emblazoned on T-shirts of gang members.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a special place in Arturo Loredo's restaurant on
Fort Worth's north side.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is my consoler, my protector _ the protector of all
Mexican people,'' said Loredo, referring to an image of Guadalupe
that hangs prominently in his restaurant. A candle glows beneath
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I light a candle every day for the Virgin,'' said Loredo, who
is among millions of Roman Catholics who will celebrate the Feast
of Our Lady of Guadalupe on Saturday. The feast day of the
patroness of Mexico and the Americas is observed in all dioceses of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The festival recalls Dec. 12, 1531, when the Virgin Mary is said
to have appeared to an Indian peasant, Juan Diego, on Tepeyak hill
outside Mexico City. She ordered him to build a temple in her
honor.
</P>
<P>
   When the local bishop did not believe the apparitions, Juan
Diego was ordered by the Virgin to gather roses, blooming out of
season, on the barren hilltop. He returned to the bishop and when
he opened his cloak, the roses fell to the floor and the colorful
image of the Virgin of Guadalupe had been printed on the garment.
</P>
<P>
   The temple was built. And the faithful believe that the same
image _ which has not faded in more than 450 years _ remains in the
Basilica of Guadalupe outside Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Stafford Poole of Los Angeles, a Catholic priest,
researcher and author of ``Our Lady of Guadalupe: the Origins and
Sources of a Mexican National Symbol, 1531-1797,'' said the church
has taken no official position on the image's origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pope talks about the image, he's not saying people
have to believe the miracle, although many do believe,'' Poole
said. ``Catholics are free to reject the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are legions of believers. More than 1 million people a
month visit the basilica, many crawling to the church on bloody
knees to ask for healing and other favors of the Virgin. Poole said
gang members wear the image on T-shirts for protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``One merchant in east Los Angeles got tired of having graffiti
on his walls,'' said Poole. ``He placed an image of Our Lady of
Guadalupe there, and hasn't had any trouble since.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II will make his own pilgrimage to the Guadalupe
shrine during a visit to Mexico in January and many believe that
may be another step toward canonizing Juan Diego as a saint.
</P>
<P>
   Debates about Mexico's most important icon have been carried on
for centuries by anthropologists, historians, theologians and other
scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Monsignor Guillermo Schulenburg, the abbot of the
Guadalupe basilica, created a furor in Mexico when quotes
attributed to him by a Catholic journal seemed to question the
miraculous origin of the image. Although the 80-year-old priest
said he was misquoted, he stepped down from his basilica position.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no debate among the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is our mother, who comes to us in our hour of need,'' said
Juanita Gonzalez, a member of Our Lady of Guadalupe Catholic Church
in Fort Worth. She admired an impressive painting of the Guadalupe
Virgin that hangs above her church's altar. It was copied from the
original and bought in Mexico three years ago. She knows there are
skeptics, but she is not bothered.
</P>
<P>
   ``My faith is the same,'' said Gonzalez, who keeps an image of
Guadalupe in her home. ``I know there have been a lot of studies
that cast doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Claudio Zudaire, pastor of Our Lady of Guadalupe, said
most of his 1,000 parishioners believe in the miraculous origin of
the image.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the most important thing, though,'' he said. ``The
important point is that after she appeared, the Catholic faith
spread out all over America. During the decade following the
Spanish invasion, very few had converted. After the Virgin
appeared, the conversion was very fast. To me, that is the real
miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   For a minority, the image is negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guadalupe is a symbol of Spanish oppression _ of cultural
rape,'' said Ome Akatl ``Kurly'' Tlapoyahua, the Fort Worth leader
of the Mexica Eagle Society, a national group attempting to reclaim
the pre-conquest language, philosophies and spiritual practices of
Mexico's indigenous Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Juan Diego, he said, is a hoax perpetrated by the
Spanish to negate the indigenous religions of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Tlapoyahua contends that Mexico's Guadalupe was derived from the
Spanish Virgin of Guadalupe in Extremadura, Spain, a mountainous
province where Hernan Cortes and other conquistadors lived before
invading Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He says the Catholic Virgin was a substitute for Tonantzin, an
earth mother figure destroyed by the Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Zudaire, a native of Spain, disputes the view that the Virgin of
Guadalupe is a symbol of oppression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Lady didn't appear to the bishop; she appeared to an
Indian, a poor Indian,'' Zudaire said. ``So this is not something
that comes from Spain. It is something that belongs to the country
of Mexico. It is a triumph of Indian people, not a conquest by
Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
