r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKFROST-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      12-11 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKFROST-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNINSPIRED `FROST' TURNS TO COMIC SLUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Why'd they turn Dad into a snowman in ``Jack Frost''?
So the kid could utter the unforgettable line, ``Dad, you're
melting!''
</P>
<P>
   But one goofy line does not make a comedy, and ``Jack Frost''
does not make it into the small collection of Christmas movies you
would feel happy to put under your tree.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with ``Jack Frost''? No story, not enough humor, a
silly setup, and a guy in the snowman suit who looks like he didn't
make the first cut at the Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Keaton stars as Jack Frost, an aging rock-and-roller who
is almost making it as a golden oldie even though he was never a
star.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Jack has also managed to maintain a normal, middle-class
life with his wife (Kelly Preston) and 11-year-old son Charlie
(Joseph Cross).
</P>
<P>
   Is Jack a bad father? Not compared with every other dad in the
kids-on-the-side world of rock and roll.
</P>
<P>
   He obviously loves his son but, for some reason, hasn't taught
him his secret hockey shot, which would turn Charlie from a loser
into a winner and help him beat the snow bullies in their small
Colorado town.
</P>
<P>
   When Jack dies _ expectedly _ before he can pass along his
hockey wisdom, he magically comes back the next Christmas season as
the snowman in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that probably is a sign that Hollywood has exhausted all of
its ideas for Christmas movies. So if you have a follow-up to
``dead dad becomes a snowman,'' rush it to the movie studio of your
choice right away.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Charlie is the only one who knows that the snowman is
really Dad, which could lead to some fun but doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   A few amusing moments just aren't enough to drag this load into
laughland.
</P>
<P>
   Keaton has come a long way from the comic heights of ``Night
Shift,'' ``Mr. Mom'' and ``Beetlejuice'' _ and it's been downhill,
through ``The Paper'' and ``Speechless'' to ``Jack Frost.'' He can
still deliver the jokes, but the ``Frosty'' scriptwriters leave him
holding an empty bag.
</P>
<P>
   TV director Troy Miller, making his first movie, misses the most
promising moment: What happens when Mom realizes that her
ex-husband has turned from a flake into a snowflake?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Frost'' may work for people with an excess of
sentimentality and for young kids who don't get restless easily.
Everyone else would have more fun making their own snowman and
saying, ``Dad, you're melting.''
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG, ``Jack Frost'' contains a couple of sexual references
and some light profanity. 2 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
