<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5266 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-EXPORTS-TEX     12-11 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS EXPORTS PARED BY ASIAN FIZZLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL BOWEN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas export growth for the first nine months of this year
slowed to one-third of its 1997 rate as the Asian economic crisis
sapped its double-digit power of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Total exports are up 5.1 percent for the first nine months of
1998, to $64.71 billion, a $3.12 billion increase.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with a growth rate of 13.9 percent for all of 1997
and reflects weaknesses in the Asian and South American markets,
according to the Texas Department of Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to question anymore whether the economic
problems in Asia are having an affect on our exports,'' said
Branner Stewart, an analyst for the department.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, however, continued to dominate the state's overall
export picture with solid growth. Exports to Mexico hit $26.65
billion for the first nine months of 1998, up 18.7 percent over the
same period last year and amounting to 41 percent of all Texas
exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``That reflects the stabilization of the Mexican economy and
shows how important that market is for Texas,'' said Bernard
Weinstein, director of the University of North Texas Center for
Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   Exports to Canada, the United States' other North American Free
Trade Agreement partner, were up 9.7 percent over the first three
quarters of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news lies in Asia, where Texas exports had grown 80
percent between 1992 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But so far this year, exports to China and South Korea are off
40 percent. Exports to Japan dropped 18.7 percent, to $1.9 billion,
and Taiwan is down 9.2 percent, to $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   South America, historically another land of export promise, is
showing weakness, too. Exports to Brazil were flat and Venezuela
saw a 5.9 percent drop to $1.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The weakening of export growth has shown up in large and small
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs in the computer and semiconductor industries, and more
recently in the aviation industry, have been blamed on the slack in
Asian orders.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Electronics distribution center in Grapevine has cut
the number of warehouse employees from 170 to 134 in the past six
months.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of sales growth for the company's electrical connectors
have meant that it has had to do the same work with fewer people,
said Ed Kelly, Sterling's warehouse manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is just flat,'' Kelly said. ``We can't help but be
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for telephone systems and computer technology in
developing nations pushed export sales of electronic equipment and
components to $14.74 billion for the first nine months, up 6.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that produce auto parts and other transportation
equipment saw export sales jump 36 percent over last year, to $6.62
billion, much of it bound for Mexico and other parts of Latin
America where automakers have built assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   Petroleum, chemicals and agricultural producers saw declines
because Asian countries have developed their own sources for those
commodities. China, in particular, has developed its own cotton
farms.
</P>
<P>
   The good news lies in early indications that the economies of
Thailand, where the Asian crisis started, and South Korea are
improving, Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
