<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5274 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PACKERS-INJURIES-     12-11 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-INJURIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN BAY'S INJURY LIST IS LONGER THAN 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ever had the itch to shake down a little chaos,
to make people pull their own heads off in madness? To yell,
``Fire!'' in a crowded showing of ``Rugrats,'' or ``Impeachment
hearings!'' to an ordinary citizen?
</P>
<P>
   No, there's nothing quite like good-natured malicious mischief
to speed you on your way into the holiday season. So if you'll
please be in good order, clear your throat and prepare to run like
a rabbit to avoid the ensuing stampede when you say: ``The Green
Bay Packers!''
</P>
<P>
   Have you seen the Packers lately? In fact, you haven't. Nobody
has. Their weekly injury report is like watching Bryant Young of
the San Francisco 49ers break his leg 15 times in succession. And
that's not an exaggeration. This week's Packers' injured list
includes a broken collarbone, a torn hamstring, a broken ankle, a
broken jaw, four knees, three shoulders and ... well, 17 players
are on blocks, 13 questionable, doubtful or just plain out.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the Denver Broncos, who are feuding with the injury
report rule by putting anyone on who looks like he might have been
injured at some time, these are the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, you half expect to see listings like ``Brett Favre:
Couldn't be better, the picture of health, brown as a nut and ready
for love ... but give it time _ questionable'' or ``Mike Holmgren:
Superb reputation, slightly overamped ambition, will probably get
taken out on a sideline tackle against the Bears _ doubtful,
pending.''
</P>
<P>
   All this, when juxtaposed against the fact the Packers still
play Chicago twice, means (a) Green Bay will still make the
playoffs, (b) they will almost certainly end up playing the 49ers
here on the first weekend of the playoffs, and (c) a lot of them
will be only vaguely aware that the 49ers can't beat the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet given the injuries the Packers have endured this season
(they've gone through four tailbacks, and have lost so many wide
receivers they had to pick up Horace Copeland, who couldn't even
make a dent with the Eagles, just to field a full depth chart),
they seem closer these days to the Arizona Cardinals and New
Orleans Saints than to the 49ers or the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   This naturally matters to 49ers fans because, unless the Atlanta
Falcons slip against New Orleans, Detroit or Miami (or draw referee
Phil Luckett's crew for any of those games), the Packers will be
San Francisco's opening-round playoff opponent _ a team barely
limping to the line against a team that could have the best record
of any wild-card team in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, we are left with one of those great philosophical
questions, the kind that rarely get answered to anyone's
satisfaction, namely: Would you rather have history on your side,
or health?
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers could end up the most maligned 13-3 team ever, at
least by those closest to it _ their cornerbacks aren't good, their
interior defense is shot now that Young is gone, Jerry Rice is
slowing up, nobody can find the fullback, they don't win by enough,
they're lousy against the spread, the team's getting old, the front
office is trapped on the space station Mir and
blah-de-blah-de-blah. Some of these things are in fact true.
</P>
<P>
   But they could have those 13 wins going into the postseason
without benefit of the first-round bye and, in that case, it is
nearly a certainty they will host a Green Bay team that has beaten
them five consecutive times in Holmgren-Favre years, the Green Bay
that has dominated both lines of scrimmage, the Green Bay that has
benefited from only one bad officials' call in that time.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Bay that doesn't know who is lining up for it at any
given time, but knows it can beat San Francisco with one ligament
tied behind its back.
</P>
<P>
   Weird, isn't it? And fun, too. A single elimination angst-off
between former Super Bowl winners facing equally uncertain futures.
It beats the rest of the first weekend's playoff schedule, be it
Jets-Bills, Patriots-Dolphins, Patriots-Bills, Jets-Dolphins,
Jets-Patriots, Bills-Dolphins, Cowboys-Saints, Cowboys-Cardinals,
Cowboys-Bucs, Cowboys-Giants or Cowboys-Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Especially Cowboys-Lions, now that we think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, you may now rest a bit easier when you hear those three
dreaded words _ Green, Bay and Packers. There are things far more
worthy of your fear and loathing, like, ``Hey, Barney Frank and Bob
Barr are stripped to the waist and debating impeachment on TV,'' or
even worse, ``Honey, it's Saturday. Let's go to Toys R Us and do
all the kids' shopping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
