<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURN AROUND DILBERT SYNDROME BY TAKING RESPONSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Dilbert dangerous?
</P>
<P>
   The misadventures of Dilbert and his comic strip colleagues have
kept legions of fans chuckling over their morning coffee. But some
believe the joke is on us.
</P>
<P>
   Dilbert doesn't just point out the problems that are endemic in
today's workplace. He is part of the problem, said Paul Bauck, a
Seattle-based author and management consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Bauck, who admits he is nevertheless a Dilbert fan himself, said
there is such a thing as the ``Dilbert Syndrome,'' which leads to
cynicism, lower productivity and the torpedoing of good intentions
at work.
</P>
<P>
   The hallmark of the Dilbert Syndrome is pessimism, he said.
``The first thought about any situation is negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Other characteristics of the Dilbert Syndrome include habitual,
biased thinking, a closed mind, and lack of desire to explore
situations or problems, Bauck said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who suffer from the Dilbert Syndrome don't understand
how their work fits into the overall work of the company, or what
their own value is. They demonstrate an unwillingness to discover
how things work, or figure out what they could do to make the
company better, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Take a general lack of trust, and resistance to growth on the
job, add an unwillingness to volunteer or accept criticism, and you
have someone with full-blown Dilbert Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Bauck, who wrote and self-published ``Stand Out in the Crowd;
Inspire Your Boss to Be Loyal to You'' (Bauck &AMP; Assoc., 1998,
$14.95), said the reason Dilbert is so popular is that it taps
people's cynicism about work and their belief that nothing changes.
</P>
<P>
   While a good laugh may offer short-term relief, it doesn't fix
the underlying problems, and instead reinforces them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the characters in Dilbert refuse to listen to each other
or be open to suggestions and new ideas,'' he said. But survival in
business requires being able to adapt to a rapidly changing
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spirit of inquiry or discovery creates the ability to grow
and learn in a changing business environment,'' he said. ``The
Dilbert characters display a resolution to maintain the status quo,
not learn new things and not inquire about what others think.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people steadfastly believe it's not in their best interest
to ask questions at work, he said. But that's a dangerous
assumption. Asking questions is the only way to find better ways to
get things done.
</P>
<P>
   Bauck draws his observations from working both sides of the
corporate fence. As a career counselor, he's listened to people's
frustrations with their jobs. As a management consultant, he's
listened to the frustrations of employers trying to get the best
out of their employees.
</P>
<P>
   When he asked employers and employees what they wanted from each
other, both sides told him the same things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides wanted the other party to be open-minded, willing
to learn, and to contribute new ideas,''
</P>
<P>
   he said.
</P>
<P>
   The key to combatting the Dilbert Syndrome at work is for both
sides to take responsibility for change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All employees needs to invest time and energy figuring out their
contribution to the corporate bottom line and how what they do
affects the final customer.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals have the responsibility to ask questions, he said.
``It increases your value to the company if you know how the pieces
fit together.''
</P>
<P>
   The person who works in the employee cafeteria is still linked
to the success of the organization, he said. ``No matter how
tangential the link, it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, employers bear the responsibility of
recognizing the ideas and contributions of their workers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies should build in ways to give that feedback, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And both sides should combat negative thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The knee-jerk reaction to any new idea is often to say, ``That
will never work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the response should be: ``How could we make this
work?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short term, Dilbert helps you make it through the
day,'' he said. But humor used to avoid problems only makes them
worse.
</P>
<P>
   All those Dilbert cartoons posted on bulletin boards are a good
thing if they remind people what they could be doing better.
They're destructive if they reinforce the notion that individuals
are powerless to change.
</P>
<P>
   If both sides work at avoiding the Dilbert Syndrome, it will
strengthen the company and advance people's careers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then both sides can laugh all the way to the bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
