<HEADER>
A5289 &Cx1f; tth-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIBE-TREATY-SPI &LR;      12-11 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBE-TREATY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B.C. TRIBE ON VERGE OF HISTORIC TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, B.C. _ More than 111 years have passed since Nisga'a
Indians paddled canoes 650 miles from the remote Nass Valley, just
south of the Alaska Panhandle, to Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   They came to appeal for rights to ancestral lands they were
losing as the white man discovered the fish, forests and minerals
of British Columbia's northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Nisga'a chiefs were spurned by then-premier William Smythe.
They were ignored in 1913 when they sent a petition asking the
British government to intervene and resolve the land question.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the B.C. Legislature and Canada's House of Commons
stand poised to approve a treaty that will give the 5,000-member
Indian tribe about 1,300 square miles of land, cash and powers of
self-government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back,'' said Nisga'a Chief Joe Gosnell earlier this
month as drums pounded and tribal members arrived at a special
session of the B.C. Legislature called to ratify the Nisga'a Final
Agreement Act.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Gosnell stood at the door of the legislative
chamber to appeal for ratification. The accord will return to his
people control of fisheries and forest resources and law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked for justice for more than a century,'' Gosnell
told lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first outsider permitted to speak from the entrance
to the chamber since two Indian chiefs appeared there in 1950 to
thank legislators for being given the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The pending agreement between the Nisga'as and the governments
of Canada and British Columbia has stirred passion both pro and
con.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid we are creating another Yugoslavia here,'' former
B.C. Premier Bill Vander Zalm said in a recent televised debate.
Nisga'a-governed land would be ``communistic in style'' and ``not
unlike a separate country,'' he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, including current Premier Glen Clark, insist that
the treaty is key to redeeming a litany of past injustices toward
natives, who comprise about 4 percent of British Columbia's
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an obligation'' to enact the treaty, Canada's prime
minister, Jean Chretien, said Tuesday in Vancouver. Chretien first
visited the Nisga'as and began land negotiations 30 years ago when
he was Indian affairs minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have subjected aboriginal people to a kind of apartheid,''
Clark told a recent labor convention. He praised the Nisga'as for
their ``integrity, perseverence, dignity and, above all, enormous
patience'' in pressing their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's natives have needed a break. They live an average 10 to
12 years less than non-natives. Tribal infant mortality rates are
twice as high as the rest of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The provincial and federal governments long attemped to suppress
native culture. For example, it was illegal for Indians to stage
potlach ceremonies as recently as the 1950s. Native children were
long confined to residential schools. As a boy, Gosnell was taken
from his family and sent to a school at Alert Bay on Vancouver
Island, where he was forbidden to speak his native language.
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia is the one province in Canada that never
settled claims of natives whose traditional lands were taken during
settlement by whites. The Nisga'as and other tribes have long been
restricted to Indian reserves not large enough for a
self-sustaining economy. One law, passed in 1927, made it illegal
for three or more Indians to even get together for the purpose of
talking about land claims.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 Nisga'as were on hand when the B.C. Legislature
convened to take up the treaty. Members of the group sang, beat
drums and staged a ceremony at which names of ancestors were called
out. One Nisga'a, Harry Moore, shouted the name of Johnny Moore,
his great-great-grandfather and one of the Indians who paddled to
Victoria in 1887.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the Nisga'a agreement will serve as a model for
settling 49 other aboriginal land claims across British Columbia's
vast 360,000 square miles of territory. The cost of settling all
these claims is expected to be as high as $8 billion (Canadian).
</P>
<P>
   The Nisga'a treaty is reminiscent of the 1971 Alaska Native
Claims Settlement Act, which bestowed more than 40 million acres of
land and millions of investment dollars on Alaska's natives.
</P>
<P>
   The Nisga'as are making concessions in the 252-page accord. They
will relinquish their tax-free status, and they will give up much
larger land claims against the government.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, they will get the right to pass laws superseding
federal and provincial law in 14 different areas. They will be
entitled to 26 percent of Nass River salmon for food, social and
ceremonial purposes. They will get extensive wildlife management
rights. And they will get $312 million (Canadian) over 15 years
from the federal and provincial governments. (All B.C. municipal
governments receive revenue from the provincial government.)
</P>
<P>
   While it will cost nearly $500 million (Canadian), the Nisga'a
treaty is seen by some economists as a boon to the British Columbia
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great deal of uncertainty about the future of these lands
will be lifted. It will mean a major infusion of investment
money,'' said Roslyn Kunin, president of the Laurier Institute, a
Vancouver think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien has appealed for British Columbia business to support
the treaty, saying, ``It's much better for everybody to make sure
we settle (who owns land), or there will be a problem over the
business development in B.C. because there will be uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   The treaty will likely win approval by only a five-vote margin
in the 75-member B.C. Legislature. With Chretien promising to whip
lawmakers into line, the Nisga'a agreement should pass Canada's
House of Commons by a larger margin. Both votes are expected early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are naysayers, some sitting here today,''
Gosnell told the B.C. Legislature. He accused some unnamed
opponents of ``fanning the flames of fear and ignorance in this
province and reigniting a poisonous attitude so familiar to
aboriginal people.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, debate over the Nisga'a treaty in British Columbia has
echoed arguments heard in Washington's recent debate over Intiative
200, which centered on affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in equality and that they (Nisga'as) should have
equal opportunities. I don't believe in special rights for a
special group of Canadians,'' wrote David Black, owner of 55 B.C.
newspapers, including most rural papers in the area where Nisga'a
lands are located.
</P>
<P>
   Black stirred controversy when he ordered his editors to write
editorials against the Nisga'a accord and authorized a series of
eight articles by a native land claims opponent denouncing the
treaty. He refused to give equal space to treaty supporters.
</P>
<P>
   In the B.C. Legislature, the opposition Liberal Party has
demanded a province-wide referendum on the accord. The Nisga'as
were permitted to vote on the treaty and ratified it in a recent
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberals' leader, former Vancouver mayor Gordon Campbell,
has raised the specter of treaties producing ``50 to 60 gated
communities that will divide us forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has used phrases borrowed from affirmative action
opponents in the United States. He has denounced the Nisga'a accord
as ``social engineering'' that will create ``special status for one
group based on its ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is folly to entrench in the Constitution a brand new third
order of government that is untried, unproven, unnecessary and
unacceptable to most British Columbians,'' Campbell told the
Legislature this week.
</P>
<P>
   Clark responded: ``The city of Vancouver has its own charter and
its own laws. This is not a third order of government.''
</P>
<P>
   A pro-treaty voice, B.C. Federation of Labor President Ken
Georgetti, has charged that Campbell speaks for ``the kind of
racist, paternalistic attitude the Nisga'a have had to fight for
more than 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberals have challenged the Nisga'a treaty in the B.C.
Supreme Court, arguing that it improperly amends Canada's
constitution by creating a new branch of government.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has hammered at one hard-to-refute argument. Indian
Reserves are, for the most part, a national disgrace. Alcoholism,
unemployment and crime have plagued native communities from remote
Tachie and Fort Ware in northern British Columbia to Mount Currie
near Whistler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year the federal government spends $650 million on
native Indians, keeping them in poverty on native reserves that
don't have land, capital or resources,'' the premier said.
</P>
<P>
   In Victoria, facing the government that so long spurned his
people, Gosnell declared proudly, ``We intend to be free and equal
citizens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
