<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TEMPEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEMPEST' STARTS STRONG, BUT PETERS OUT; FONDA IS WARMLY
EFFECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey isn't the only production megalith trying to bring
``important'' stories to American audiences. The entire TV-movie
division at NBC has committed itself to familiarizing American
audiences with classic stories from literature.
</P>
<P>
   Such noble resolve was easy to muster given the success of
``Gulliver's Travels'' and, more recently, ``The Odyssey'' and
``Merlin.'' But, just as Oprah and ABC discovered with ``David and
Lisa'' last month, NBC learned in October with ``Crime and
Punishment'' that America likes to take its literary medicine with
a little bit of sweetener.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, after ``Crime and Punishment'' attracted an even smaller
audience than NBC expected, the network's cheese trust decided to
pull ``The Tempest'' from its November schedule, fearful of
exposing a literary classic to mass indifference during an
important ratings period. In the obscurity of mid-December, ``The
Tempest'' will now be considered a success if it merely makes a
dent against ``The X-Files'' on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a wise one. Though hardly a disaster, this
``Tempest'' is a morality play that works well for an hour or so,
and then begins to crumble in an allegorical war story that is more
confusing than enlightening. The result: A nice try, but not
completely satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is resting its hopes here on Peter Fonda, who brings to
``The Tempest'' the quiet intensity that got him an Oscar
nomination for his portrayal of a stoic Southern beekeeper in
``Ulee's Gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda remains in the deep South for this earnest ``update'' of
Shakespeare's last play, transitioning smoothly from swarms to
storms. In the telling by ``Attica'' screenwriter Jim Henerson,
Prospero, duke of Milan, becomes Gideon Prosper, Mississippi
plantation owner.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda's Prosper is a kind-hearted man who loses interest in his
plantation after the death of his wife. He prefers to dabble in
magic and sorcery under the tutelage of a slave named Ezeli
(Donzaleigh Abernathy), leaving everyday business to his scoundrel
brother, Anthony (John Glover).
</P>
<P>
   Bad idea. Glover's Anthony is as nasty as the devil (which
Glover plays every Friday on ``Brimstone''). Gideon ends up exiled
to a bayou treehouse with his daughter, Miranda (Katherine Heigl),
and Ezeli's orphaned son, Ariel (Harold Perrineau Jr.). After 12
years, he's gotten pretty good at the magic, better still at
playing the hermit and instilling wholesome values in Miranda and
Ariel.
</P>
<P>
   While marginally faithful to Shakespeare's story, ``The
Tempest'' never achieves the dynamic impact implicit in the title,
even with the Civil War as a backdrop. Fonda is warmly effective as
the loving father who can whip up a storm at will and who wrestles
with questions of loyalty, independence, honor and duty. Heigl is
fresh and appealing as the daughter who's never known anything but
a sheltered life away from civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Special visual effects by the Frame Store, which also handled
``Gulliver,'' ``Odyssey'' and ``Merlin,'' are impressive. But, in
serving us Bard Lite, NBC has only made it obvious that ``less
filling'' doesn't work well in drama.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempest. A retelling of Shakespeare's mystical story of
honor and betrayal. Starring Peter Fonda, John Glover, Katherine
Heigl and Harold Perrineau Jr. Sunday night on NBC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
