A5341 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STARTREK-REVIEW-     12-11 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STARTREK-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTION-PACKED `INSURRECTION' HAS HARD TIME OVERCOMING PLOT, JARGON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If we applied old-style movie hype to ``Star Trek:
Insurrection''_ with a touch of irony _ it easily could sound like
this:
</P>
<P>
   See! Cadaverous, cranky bad guys obsessed with face lifts!
</P>
<P>
   Hear! Dialogue such as ``Reroute its command sequence through
the auxiliary processor!''
</P>
<P>
   Thrill! As good guys fight to preserve the status quo of a small
commune of boring, pacifist vegetarians!
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are problems in the ``Trek'' universe.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't blame the cast of ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation,'' now in their third big-screen effort. The problems
stem from the screenplay by Michael Piller.
</P>
<P>
   Piller is co-creator of Trek's ``Voyager'' and ``Deep Space
Nine'' series, on which he served as executive producer. Here, he's
a first-time film screenwriter _ and it shows.
</P>
<P>
   As enjoyable as their interplay can be, the fine ``Next
Generation'' cast has had to grapple for years with plots laden by
stuffy idealism and tedious technical talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' is filled with both.
</P>
<P>
   Ably directed by Jonathan Frakes, who also plays Commander
William Riker, the film has ample action and enjoyable humor and
humanism. But its plot is driven by confounding jargon and rules
that Piller seems to make up as he goes along.
</P>
<P>
   The only rule he doesn't make up is ``Trek's'' most unmanageable
concept, touted since the '60s series and rarely observed
effectively: the Federation's ``prime directive.'' This means
nonintervention. You leave a planet and its denizens to their own
devices. Of course, the Federation good guys have broken the rule
many times, and in ``Insurrection'' they do so again.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to unexplained involvement by Lt. Commander Data (Brent
Spiner), Capt. Jean-Luc Picard (Patrick Stewart) and his Enterprise
crew uncover a conspiracy between a Federation admiral (Anthony
Zerbe) and overtly hostile space farers called the Son'a.
</P>
<P>
   The Son'a want to extract the regenerative powers of the
Edenlike Ba'ku planet at the expense of its sole inhabitants: 600
inexplicably human colonists who live in what looks like a
California spa for the rich and idle. Via their planet's powers,
these folks are virtually immortal. Most are 300 years old, yet
look 40.
</P>
<P>
   The planet also heals.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Commander Geordi La Forge (LeVar Burton) overcomes his
blindness, and other officers feel young and frisky. But La Forge
realizes he could never enjoy seeing his first sunset if it came at
the expense of the Ba'ku folks, whose own alleged idealism seems to
preclude sharing.
</P>
<P>
   So the Enterprise defies the admiral and the age-obsessed Son'a
leader, Ru'afo (F. Murray Abraham), who spends half the film in
repulsive cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Picard leads the colonists in an armed retreat to mountain
caves, while Riker and the Enterprise race to tattle on the admiral
to the Federation.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, they are boldly running away, much as in
``Battlestar Galactica'' or the ``climb every mountain'' ending to
``The Sound of Music.''
</P>
<P>
   They do finally fight two spiffy space battles, in which the
computer-generated hardware looks nice. But what does it all mean?
</P>
<P>
   The action is driven by jargon-filled lines such as, ``They are
rotating their shield harmonics!'' _ which are difficult to figure
out.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the aging Son'a shouldn't steal this fountain of youth.
But couldn't its powers also help the Federation's ill or dying? As
earlier ``Trek'' films have taught, the needs of the many outweigh
the needs of the few.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is not to think too much and just enjoy precious
moments _ as Picard himself learns to do on Ba'ku.
</P>
<P>
   If you love this series' stars, rest assured you'll have plenty
of endearing moments in which to bask.
</P>
<P>
   Riker and Lt. Commander Deanna Troi (Marina Sirtis) enjoy a
candle-lit bubble bath, rekindling a romance that occurred early in
``Next Generation's'' run and, with TV's typical inertia, never was
pursued.
</P>
<P>
   Data also gets many cute bits, whether singing a song from one
of Spiner's beloved Broadway shows or commenting innocently on
female officers' enhanced endowments.
</P>
<P>
   As for the charismatic Stewart, whose stardom eclipses the
ensemble (he reportedly made $12 million for this), he kicks
bad-guy butt, dances a little mambo and romances Anij, a Ba'ku
woman (Donna Murphy).
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Goldsmith also supplies a solid score, though it often
merely echoes his fine ``Trek'' work of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was uninspired by the script. We can't say that we
blame him. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Star Trek: Insurrection &QL; 
 &UR; Starring &LR; : Patrick Stewart, Jonathan Frakes and Brent Spiner &QL; 
 &UR; Rating &LR; : PG &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
