<HEADLINE>
FIRMS OFFER CLASSES TO SWEETEN LAYOFFS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Losing your job is about as tough as it gets. It
doesn't really make any difference if you get cut loose because
your company filed for bankrupcty or because you were a lousy
employee _ it's still extremely painful.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first worries is how to find another job.
</P>
<P>
   To help ease that transition, many employers offer severance
pay, continue to subsidize the cost of medical insurance for a time
and offer outplacement assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But some employers take it a step further and offer their
severed employees an educational grant to get them started in a new
career or let them beef up their existing skills.
</P>
<P>
   Amoco Corp., for example, is offering the employees it lets go
as part of its merger with British Petroleum a $5,000 educational
grant ($2,500 for part-timers) that can be used for 24 months after
they've left the company. The oil company will reimburse its
employees up to 85 percent of the cost of classes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a difficult time and Amoco wanted to ensure that its
employees got the best available benefits, said spokeswoman Vicki
Kastory from Chicago. The educational assistance will help
employees find new jobs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The grants are a good way for a lawyer to pick up mediation
skills or for someone to start a master's degree, said Robin
Kessler, president of The Interview Coach, a firm that trains
companies how to properly handle the ``exit process.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PEOPLE WANT KNOWLEDGE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Educational assistance programs have been around for some time.
Back in 1988, IBM offered employees taking early retirement $2,500
in educational assistance to help them and their spouses, said Bill
Hollett, vice president of the national project team for Drake Beam
Morin, an outplacement firm.
</P>
<P>
   IBM expected its retiring employees to take golfing and flying
classes but instead, they took computer and business classes to
help them find a new job or start life as a consultant, said
Hollett, speaking from the firm's Stamford, Conn., office.
</P>
<P>
   The educational help was popular with departing employees, and
other companies jumped on the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Educational assistance seems to be more popular now, said
Hollett, who recommends it when he is hired to design a severance
plan.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good corporate citizen move, said Hollett. It's hard to
think badly of a company that helps its departing employees retool.
</P>
<P>
   It's also not very expensive, said Hollett. At one company that
makes photographic supplies, only 25 percent of the eligible
employees participated.
</P>
<P>
   Many senior-level employees don't use the assistance because
they feel they have what they need to get another job and they have
a network of contacts to rely upon, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The money, which typically ranges from $2,500 to $7,500, is used
more by lower- and mid-level employees, who see it as a chance to
go back to get a master's degree or some computer classes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are exceptions, he said, recalling a corporate
lawyer at a chemical company who used the money to get a specialty
in patent law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A GESTURE OF CARING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Chase Bank of Texas, 52 percent of departing employees use
the bank's educational assistance program, said Gretchen Harris,
manager of employee relations. The bank gives its departing full-
and part-time employees $2,500 in educational assistance that can
be used for courses as varied as English literature or computer
repair.
</P>
<P>
   The job market is so good right now that many departing
employees join another company quickly and don't return to school
for classes, Harris said. And many departing employees already
acquired new skills because the bank sent them to courses during
their tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who do want to return to school can do it even after
they've landed another job, said Harris. Lots of workers may take a
job that doesn't fit into their career path or they don't
particularly like but need to pay the bills _ and that shouldn't
eliminate them from using the educational grant, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-employees are also free to return to Chase to take the bank's
own classes such as management training, time management and
computer courses.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, educational assistance and severance benefits
help departing employees. But the assistance also sends a strong
message to current employees that the bank cares, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Severance benefits are an important retention tool because they
let existing employees know that if the bank doesn't need their
services any longer, they won't be out on the street without a
safety net.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
