<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THUMBS UP FOR THE NEW MERCEDES M CLASS SUV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, December 13, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in September, we introduced readers to the new high-powered
version of the Mercedes-Benz M Class
sport/utility/van/whatevermobile, the ML430 with its brand new
268-horsepower V-8 engine. Back then, the columnist had been
favorably impressed by the quickness, agility, and go-anywhere
ability of this new Benz. (Well, go almost anywhere; it won't swim,
it won't fly, and it does not leap tall buildings at a single
bound.) But the proof of a car is living with it over the long
term.
</P>
<P>
   The 4.3-liter V-8 in the 430 will take you from 0 to 60 in a
smidgen more than six seconds _ this is extreme acceleration
potential in a utility package. The price of performance, as we all
know, is fuel appetite. With that performance, there is the
off-road capability of the ML430; it is full-time 4-wheel drive
with a two-speed electronic transfer case for low-range operation
in the muck and mire, sand and snow. As we all know, 4-wheel-drive
off-roaders gobble gas. The ML430 would appear to be twice damned
here _ a plow horse built for speed eats like a lot of horse.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the room and luxury appointments. This is a fairly
large, roomy vehicle _ 4,552 pounds curbside with a 5,000-pound tow
capacity. Not much hope for economy here.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, EPA rated at 15 miles per gallon city, 18
highway, quite respectable for an SUV of any capacity and better by
some than a few high-priced SUVs that don't do nearly as much
nearly as well. Still, you might be willing to sacrifice the
performance and settle for the 215-hp V-6-powered sibling ML320,
EPA rated 17/21 _ and less money in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   But the test is living with it, feeding it, driving it over the
long term. OK, we've tested. It's still a winner. And it would seem
that the EPA has missed something here. If you take the city number
and the highway number, somewhere in between is the real everyday
number, the so-called combined average. Almost never in real life
does one actually get that highway number _ except maybe when the
EPA is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Your columnist kept track for 900.7 miles; the ML430 delivered
18.66 miles per gallon over the measured distance. Part of that
mileage was a section of high-speed highway driving with the
five-speed automatic transmission accidentally locked out of
overdrive (driver error), and part of the time was with a moderate
load. A good part of the driving was the around-town sort, and the
routes covered a variety of terrain, everything from the
ramp-of-the-week in the muddle?? of Boston's Big Dig to dirt road
and a wee bit of snow. The ML430 delivered a measured 18.66 miles
per gallon, more than the estimated highway average.
</P>
<P>
   For laughs, I measured one more tankful: 18.68. The beast is
consistent.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is price. The base ML430 is $43,750 plus $595
delivery _ the 320 is $34,950. The tested ML430 had a few extras
that brought the total delivered price to $48,085, about 2 1/2
times what I once paid for a house. The extras included tubular
chrome side runners and brush guard; the side runners look like
fancy exhaust pipes but really serve as a running board. The brush
guard reminds me of a chrome footboard on a single bed. That
package includes mud flaps for $1,595. Also extra were a Bose
premier audio system with a CD changer ($1,050), and a glass
sunroof ($1,095).
</P>
<P>
   Aren't all sunroofs glass? you ask. Not with the ML430. For a
mere $2,395 extra, you may forgo the glass option and get a
sectional metal roof that slides open and stacks the sections like
venetian blinds to offer a roof hole ranging in size from a
generous slit to a full three-foot by four-foot hole. With that,
however, it would probably be wise to avoid loading anything on the
roof, rack or no.
</P>
<P>
   If you opt for the standard model, you do not come away
ill-equipped; the ML430 offers a lengthy array of standard
equipment, including a few items besides the V-8 that you won't get
standard on the less expensive 320 _ trip computer, rear privacy
glass, heated seats, a lockable storage drawer under the front
passenger seat, and a leather-wrapped steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the standard technology that impresses. In addition to
front and side air bags, the M series offers the Benz Electronic
Stability Program as standard equipment and the new emergency brake
assist system. The ESP senses yaw _ imminent slip _ and corrects
instantly. The emergency brake assist senses panic stops and
immediately applies maximum brake pedal pressure whether the driver
is able to or not. Antilock brakes are standard and the
4-wheel-drive system employed relies on electronically controlled
traction assist rather than locking differentials _ if you can get
traction on one wheel, you can keep the ML moving. The five-speed
tranmission is electronically managed, too, adapts to the
individual's driving style, and resists sudden shift changes as
grades change.
</P>
<P>
   The only real problem with a car so equipped is driver
overconfidence; no electronic system can compensate effectively for
recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   Off road, the 430 is gentler than a standard 4 x 4 truck; on
road it is stiffer than a standard luxury sedan. Handling is very
precise. The ride is very comfortable, more carlike than SUV-ish.
Visibility is quite good, although you are not as high off the
pavement as in traditional SUVs; the step-up height is more akin to
a sedan than a truck, so most people could well afford to skip the
fancy side runners. The bumpers, too, match sedan height, something
neighbors in sedans might appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Interior storage is pretty good _ that drawer, door bins, and
various other bins offer storage room. There are no seat pockets;
the backs are scooped a bit to offer kneeroom, which is ample.
Headroom, too, is abundant.
</P>
<P>
   Benz has succumbed to the cupholder demands of Americans and has
come up with what has to be the most elegant design in the front of
the vehicle. At either end of the dash, one presses, and a polished
cupholder unfolds from its hiding place, folds back up at a touch _
so don't bump it with your knee while there's a beverage in there,
lest you wind up wearing some of it. A couple of cupholders fold
out from the center console for the rear passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The rear seat, by the way, is split three ways, folds down,
folds forward for more cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   The dash in the ML is different from that in other Mercedes
models, especially the radio controls, which are much more
convenient in the ML than in other Mercedeses _ but I wish Benz
would join in the common labeling practices. I prefer separate
selectors for AM, FM, CD, not the single button labeled ``mode.''
There is where multiplicity is simplicity _ you select what you
want rather than going through a whole cycle by strumming the
``mode'' button. Hey, I have to find something to complain about,
otherwise you might not take me seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs up, even if I can't afford one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1527EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
