<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN BEST GAMES HAVE A HALF LIFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been five years since id Software turned the PC gaming
world upside down with Doom, the first-person, 3-D shooter that
made the phrase ``death match'' a household word. Well, at least in
households with computers, fast modems and twitchy young males.
</P>
<P>
   And, in my household. If you read this column regularly, you
know that I am a big fan of good 3-D action titles, largely because
I think they represent the state-of-the-art of game technology.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to more powerful computers, advances in graphics display
and better artificial intelligence, 3-D games have come a long way
since the pixilated monsters that stalked Doom. They are far more
immersive and, most recently, they actually have begun to offer
interesting plot lines that go far beyond ``if it moves, kill it.''
</P>
<P>
   Game designers also have been focusing on the multiplayer aspect
of their games, in which players duke it out with each other,
rather than battling computer-controlled bad guys. The popularity
of the Internet has made this easy _ someone sets up a server in
cyberspace, and players from all over connect to play, often for
free.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never tried this, I urge you to do so _ it is an
astounding experience, and I believe it's the future of
entertainment. A century from now, people will look back on the
makers of these games in the same way that we look at film pioneers
such as Cecil B. DeMille and D.W. Griffith today.
</P>
<P>
   Often game designers make either a great single-player game, or
a great multiplayer game, but not both. Two highly anticipated
titles, out in time for the holiday season, illustrate this
dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   _ Half-Life, $55, Sierra Studios: Usually, when a game receives
as much pre-release hoopla as Half-Life did, there's a serious
letdown once players actually get it on their hard drives. In a
rare case of reality beating expectations, the developers at
Seattle-based Valve have done better than the hype indicated.
</P>
<P>
   It is the best first-person 3-D game ever, dethroning id's Quake
II. Beautiful graphics, intelligent design, a compelling plot line
and superbly timed action take this far beyond the standard shooter
fare. However, to finish the game you do have to kill a lot of
monsters _ and a good number of humans, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the game you are Gordon Freeman, a low-level researcher at
the top-secret Black Mesa research facility. Exactly what the
scientists at Black Mesa are studying is unclear, but in the
stunning introductory sequence you're warned about avoiding
radiation and staying healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Donning a protective suit, you are ordered by your bosses to
enter a chamber to help with a test. But something goes horribly
wrong, and in a visually spectacular scene a hole is ripped between
this world and another dimension. All kinds of creepy, dangerous
things pass through.
</P>
<P>
   When you exit the chamber, you find chaos. Several hideous
creatures are chowing down on your colleagues _ and trying to make
a tasty lunch out of you.
</P>
<P>
   As the game progresses, things get complicated. The military has
been brought in to clean up the mess by killing everything _
including the scientists and workers and, of course, you. You not
only must do battle with monsters, but also your own kind.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, in a 3-D shooter, your job is to obliterate everything
in sight. But not in Half-Life. If you shoot that guard over there
_ or fail to protect him from a monster _ you might not be able to
get through a door that only he can open. If you don't stop and
talk to that scientist in the next room, you may not get the
information you need to move on to another level.
</P>
<P>
   Half-Life is as much an adventure game as a shooter _ it's full
of puzzles and situations you must figure out before you can
advance. However, they are not too hard. Serious adventure gamers
would consider the puzzles here fairly lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence of your enemies is very impressive. Monsters
will duck behind boxes and pillars to avoid your fire, or use sound
to track your movements. The soldiers hunting you will try to
encircle you, executing classic battle strategy. If you begin to
beat them, they will actually retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The single-player part of Half-Life is the closest I've seen a
computer game come to giving you the feeling that you are a
character in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   The multiplayer part, though, is just adequate. While the levels
you play make for interesting death-match scenarios, the weapons
are unbalanced. Players who acquire certain high-powered guns are
going to lay waste quickly to those who haven't. And increasing
your health requires that you plug into a first-aid station and
continuously press a key to power back up, leaving you a sitting
duck in the process.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sin, $50, Activision: In Sin, you play John Blade, a
tough-talking cop out to stop Elexis Sinclair, the chief executive
of a biochemical company who is creating an army of mutants to take
over the world. Sinclair is the latest in a line of female
computer-game characters who are ridiculously top-heavy. But while
Tomb Raider's Lara Kroft is a good guy, Sinclair is pure evil.
</P>
<P>
   Blade is aided by J.C., a young hacker who provides spoken
hints, suggestions and warnings. The banter between these two is
informative, but often irritating. There's no way to turn J.C. off,
unfortunately.
</P>
<P>
   Sin begins spectacularly, with Blade shooting at bank robbers
from a helicopter. But the action soon moves to the ground, where
Sin becomes your basic 3-D shooter that's highly derivative of Duke
Nukem 3D. Blade makes macho comments as he mows down his opponents,
and the environment is highly interactive. Pay phones work, drawers
slide open, money machines dispense badly needed cash.
</P>
<P>
   The artificial intelligence in the Sin baddies is not quite as
good as in Half-Life, but there is one interesting feature here.
When you shoot someone in the leg, it affects only their leg _ the
character grabs a knee, for example. Shoot them in the head, and
they'll go right down.
</P>
<P>
   Sin suffers from some serious technical problems. The version
you install out of the box takes forever to load between levels. A
10-megabyte patch that helps somewhat is available at
www.activision.com. There are other bugs that make single-player
Sin more frustrating than it should be.
</P>
<P>
   But where Sin really shines is in death-match mode. Where
Half-Life is the best single-player 3-D shooter, Sin now wears the
crown for best multiplayer title.
</P>
<P>
   Sin comes with numerous death-match-only levels, including seven
named for the deadly sins. Another one takes place at night on a
faithfully rendered offshore oil rig (Ritual Entertainment, the
game's developer, is based in Dallas), complete with a sniper's
perch atop the derrick.
</P>
<P>
   But the best death-match level, available with the patch, is
like playing in a drawing by surrealist M.C. Escher. Paradox has
multiple stairs and platforms, so that one player's ceiling might
be another's floor, or wall.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons are perfectly balanced in Sin death match. For
example, the most powerful gun requires that you hold the trigger
to build up power. The longer you hold it, the more damaging the
blast, but _ hold it too long and it explodes in your face.
</P>
<P>
   If only you could graft Sin's death-match onto Half-Life's
single-player experience, you'd have 3-D-shooter nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
