<HEADER>
A5433 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTY-SOCIAL-LADN     12-11 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-SOCIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY WHO'S ANYBODY DOES FIRE AND ICE BALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Los Angeles is fast becoming a tent city.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by circuses and European fashion shows, party planners
are finding huge tents to give galas a fashionable edge. Not only
can they transform a parking lot into a ballroom and provide
shelter from the Santa Ana winds, but their plain white walls are a
blank canvas, ready for the artistry of a creative party planner
like Ben Bourgeois.
</P>
<P>
   It was designer-to-the-stars Bourgeois who created all the eye
candy at Revlon/UCLA's Fire &AMP; Ice Ball, held Wednesday night at
Universal Studios. Using Revlon's ``ice'' theme, he turned the tent
into a giant diamond with photo imagery, stage lights and Lucite.
As guests entered the tent, they stepped onto a clear Lucite
platform and down the illuminated stairs onto clear glass pathways
featuring chunks of ice _ or diamonds _ underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 1,300 guests were some of Hollywood's brightest stars
and East Coast celebs, including John F. Kennedy Jr.'s wife,
Carolyn, who attended with her husband's cousins Bobby and Maria
Shriver. Kennedy said New York had wonderful galas, but she and her
husband decided Fire &AMP; Ice was a worthy cause ... and a chance for
her to wear a stunning winter white wool gown by Donatella Versace,
who was the guest of honor at the gala that earned $1.8 million for
the Revlon/UCLA Women's Cancer Research Program.
</P>
<P>
   Others wearing Versace gowns included Revlon supermodel Cindy
Crawford, who chose a silvery-white gown with fur trim on the
shoulder straps; Madonna in basic black, Neve Campbell in lavender
sequins, Fran Drescher in mauve sequins, and Candice Bergen, who,
with teeth chattering, said of her pale gray almost-a-dress with
matching chiffon stole, ``I'm sacrificing my health to wear this
Versace.''
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the ``Friends'' cast were there, too,
including Courteney Cox, who told me both she and her fiance, David
Arquette, were wearing Versace. And, no, they haven't bought a ring
or set a date ... yet.
</P>
<P>
   Honorary gala chairman Jerry Seinfeld, who said he now has
absolutely nothing to do but read the papers, was a fashion rebel
and wore Armani. Ditto with ``Frasier'' co-star David Hyde Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Carey, who came with his sitcom co-star Christa Miller,
made it a point to tell me his tuxedo was by American designer
Hickey-Freeman. ``I'm kinda big, and they fit me well,'' he
commented.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebs in attendance were Jack Nicholson, Dina Merrill,
Kim Delaney, Rupert Everett, Dylan McDermott, Camryn Manheim,
Dennis Hopper, Ted Danson, Sidney Poitier, Goldie Hawn, Jennifer
Tilly, Debbe Dunning, Lisa Kudrow, Lynn Redgrave, Judith Light,
Kelsey Grammer and Charles Bronson, the tough-guy actor who
chuckled over Versace's rhinestone-trimmed menswear and felt bad
for the young models who obviously hadn't had a lot of practice
walking in their stiletto-heeled sandals.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the spring '99 fashion preview was a razzle-dazzle
presentation with plenty of slinky evening gowns and tuxedos,
accented with a vaultful of diamond jewelry loaned by Harry
Winston.
</P>
<P>
   As always, event creator Lilly Tartikoff and her committee
organized a wonderful evening that ended with a pasta and lobster
feast prepared by Wolfgang Puck and served on white Versace china.
Major contributors for the evening were Neiman Marcus, Revlon,
Universal Studios and Versace.
</P>
<P>
   EARLIER IN THE WEEK, the Philharmonic Gala, another awesome tent
party, was held on the plaza of the downtown Music Center.
</P>
<P>
   A retirement tribute to Ernest Fleischmann, executive vice
president and managing director of the Los Angeles Philharmonic
since 1969, the gala began with a concert inside the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion conducted by Zubin Mehta, featuring guest
appearances by opera singer Gundula Janowitz and cellist Mstislav
Rostropovich.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, we followed the red-carpet pathway into the tent that
award-winning event planner David Tutera turned into a lavish
European winter fantasy with huge rose-covered topiary trees,
festive garlands, a sky-high Christmas tree with ornaments the size
of beach balls, and wrought iron candelabras and colorful scarves
suspended from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The tables were covered in numerous layers of velvet and
decorated to the hilt with flowers and fruit, and each table had a
different theme with specially selected china, crystal and antique
silverware. We all had the same menu _ haricot vert salad, roasted
Chilean sea bass and chocolate tartufo _ provided by Andy Nakano of
Jozu restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Between dinner and dancing, I had a chance to chat with Rebecca
De Mornay, who was seated at my table. ``Wasn't the concert moving?
I had no idea I liked classical music so much,'' said the
Austrian-raised actress who became a household name after she
starred with Tom Cruise in ``Risky Business.'' Besides taking a new
interest in the symphony and opera, De Mornay said she's been busy
being mom to her 1-year-old daughter, Sofia, and making three
movies that will be released in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Applause for the wonderful gala goes to chairs Ken McCormick,
Ferne Margulies and Nancy Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN WERE THE STARS and recipients of all funds raised at
H.E.L.P. Group's Teddy Bear Ball at the Beverly Hills Hotel, where
guests didn't dance but stood in line to shake hands with
Gov.-elect Gray Davis, who was honored for his support of better
education programs.
</P>
<P>
   The evening started with an auction of some unusual items,
including a lunch with Dr. Ruth Westheimer, which went for $2,000;
and a real Faberge egg, which sold for $1,800. An international
treasure raising less than a date with a shrink? Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornish game hen dinner was served by candlelight, with many
guests oohing and aahing over the ambience. But Dyan Cannon
diverted everyone's attention, including the H.E.L.P. children
performing on stage, when she joined the kids to sing holiday songs
in a Santa's elf costume that revealed way too much thigh.
</P>
<P>
   In her defense, Dr. Ilene Bell, a psychologist with the Sherman
Oaks-based H.E.L.P. Group, said Cannon and other celebs graciously
give of their time to help emotionally troubled kids gain
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   DIVINE DESIGN '98, a benefit for Project Angel Food and Design
Industries Foundation Fighting AIDS (DIFFA) took place as usual at
the Pacific Design Center, but the venue was the only thing
reminiscent of previous parties.
</P>
<P>
   There was no sit-down dinner, and with too few tables and chairs
to go around, most guests were forced to stand throughout the
entire evening to see L.A. designer Max Azria of BCBG honored as
Women's Designer of the Year. Azria, who attended with his wife,
Lubov, and children Joyce, Michael and Marine, was pleased to see
so many women wearing his label. Among them was ``Will and Grace''
star Debra Messing, who wore a stunning pale-gray gown and stole by
Azria.
</P>
<P>
   Also honored were Nick Graham, the outrageous designer of Joe
Boxer fashions, who wore a novelty print bathrobe; Harry and
Dorothy Lawenda of Kneedler-Fauchere Interior Design; and the
Kohler Co., best-known for bathroom fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Pleshette was the honorary chairwoman who helped get a
number of celebrities to present awards, including David Hyde
Pierce, who told me he is nothing like the character he plays on
``Frasier.'' Said Pierce, ``I don't usually dress up. I have one
fancy suit _ this Gucci one I'm wearing _ and no, my home doesn't
look like the mansion (on `Frasier'). I have dogs, so there's no
way I could have art objects.'' (Later, at the Fire &AMP; Ice Ball, he
pointed out that his Armani ensemble was a tuxedo, not a suit,
fancy or otherwise ...)
</P>
<P>
   Faith Ford, who doesn't usually do the public party scene, was
there, too. The star of the new sitcom ``Maggie Winters'' said
she's been supporting AIDS prevention programs for years and prays
there will be a cure in the coming year. She also talked about
personal style, commenting that her spaghetti-strapped black gown
was by David Cardona. ``As I get older, I get more classic in my
taste ... and besides, I kept the gown simple because I wanted to
wear diamonds,'' she quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
