<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMASCOLLECTIBLES     12-11 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMASCOLLECTIBLES-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VILLAGE PEOPLE: TINY-TOWN COLLECTORS FUEL A BILLION-DOLLAR
BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A middle-aged woman proclaims Kensington
Palace the perfect piece to add to her Christmas village collection
this year, not because it was the home of Princess Di, but because
it reminds her of Fort Worth's Arlington Heights High School, from
which she graduated.
</P>
<P>
   A young child points out a house she says looks just like her
Grandma's house when her family arrives for Christmas each year _
with snow on the roof and lights and wreaths at the windows, and
Mom is hooked. She decides $65 is really not too much to pay for
the little ceramic building, after all.
</P>
<P>
   And, a 12-year-old argues that the New England Village's
Pigeonhead Lighthouse and Old North Church are just the stuff to
start her family's collection because her dad loves lighthouses and
she has just studied Paul Revere and his midnight ride _ plus the
village has its own boat, a porcelain sailing ship which the girl
insists ``is really awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The little houses and figurines that began as coffee-table
decorations, set in nests of cotton and glitter, have taken over
entire rooms in many collectors' homes. Some of the more elaborate
collections now have not only their own boats, but also their own
trucks, trains and motorcycles, ice palaces, Italian-style carved
marble fountains that spout real water and McDonald's hamburger
joints.
</P>
<P>
   This rampant building has snowballed Christmas collectibles into
a billion-dollar-a-year business.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia, family traditions, cultural heritage, emotional and
spiritual values all fuel the desire to acquire Christmas
collectibles, now the fastest-growing segment of the huge Christmas
decorating market.
</P>
<P>
   Individual collectors, estimated to number over 10 million in
the United States, spend more on the little town of Bethlehem and
the North Pole village than is spent on trees, Santas, decorations
and indoor and outdoor lights. In 1996, expenditures for all
Christmas decorations totaled $4.3 billion in consumer sales _ up
13 percent over the previous year, says Pam Danziger, president of
Unity Marketing and author of a new market research study,
``Collecting Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 collectible ornaments, figurines and villages comprised
about one-fourth of the market with $1.1 billion in sales _ an
increase of 21 percent over the 1995 figures.
</P>
<P>
   The billion-dollar business is built on foggy memories of
storybook realities. ``It takes you back to simpler times _ when
life was more gentle and people were happy. It's very
heartwarming,'' explains Carol Taylor, an avid collector.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to come home from work, turn the house lights down
low, turn on all the village lights and sit there looking at it, so
peaceful and calm,'' says Taylor, who works at Lockheed Martin. She
often plays Christmas carols while keeping watch over her village.
</P>
<P>
   The happy little table towns have become a visual Prozac. ``You
don't find very many negative things included in the villages. A
couple of years ago, they introduced a cemetery, and there was a
huge commotion about it over the Internet. People were really
upset. The same thing happened when someone suggested a funeral
procession. It's too down beat,'' Taylor recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy also arose when the minuscule lobsters included in
the ``Lobster Trappers'' accessory turned out to be red. Purists
from all over the country dialed into the Internet to complain that
lobsters turn red only after they are cooked, recalls Taylor with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   She is an eclectic collector who takes liberties with the world
she commands. She once added a tiny aquarium with real live fish to
one of her village scenes. In recent years, she dropped in a
``flasher'' in a yellow raincoat and invited guests to ``find
Waldo.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   One year, Taylor fashioned King Kong climbing up and over the
City Globe newspaper office of her Christmas in the City, with
photographers shooting pictures, and a mother holding her young son
with one hand and pointing with the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes a village come to life are the special things you
do to it, how you set it up and the accessories you put into it. I
have fun talking to other people and giving them ideas for unusual
ways to display their scenes,'' Taylor notes.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Gordon, of Fort Worth, purchased her first houses from the
Original Snow Village collection 10 years ago when a shop in Las
Colinas was going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm hooked,'' she admits. ``I can't even display all of
my collection at one time.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes 156 lighted houses. Her trees alone fill
six or eight packing cases. She says a village can't have too many
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, a retired nuclear engineer, has always been fascinated
by detailed miniatures, partly explaining her enthusiastic response
to Department 56, a gift-ware manufacturer that makes seven of the
most popular collections: the Original Snow Village, Dickens
Village, New England Village, Alpine Village, Christmas in the
City, North Pole and Little Town of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many hobby shops, nurseries, building-supply stores
and department stores _ including Mervyn's, Wal-Mart, Kmart, JoAnn
Fabrics and Crafts, and MJDesigns _ have their own special
villages, as do many mail-order Christmas catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from a couple of dollars for less detailed ceramic
houses to $175 for Department 56's historical reproduction of
Shakespeare's Old Globe Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas Carol Cottage introduced in the Dickens Village in
1997 features curling wisps of ``magic smoke'' drifting from its
stone chimney for $60, and Mrs. Claus' Greenhouse from the popular
North Pole series is filled with red poinsettias ($68).
</P>
<P>
   ``Some collectors know every detail and wouldn't think of mixing
their village pieces, while others mix and match what they like
best from different collections,'' says Lea Anne Seeley, a
collector and co-owner of Tis the Season Christmas stores in Fort
Worth and Arlington, where Christmas village houses and accessories
are hot items.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an adult version of collecting doll-house miniatures
or train sets,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon says a combination of nostalgia and some sort of personal
identification with one or more of the individual shops and houses
keeps a lot of collectors hooked.
</P>
<P>
   For example, lawyers might look for courthouses for their
collections and physicians for doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the fun is in the hunt,'' Gordon says.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of different trees, wreaths, hedges, fences,
walls, bridges, walkways, street lights, mountains and other
``official accessories'' _ including strings of tiny colored lights
to decorate the trees and ``Brite Lite'' decorations to deck out
the yards _ in addition to personal ``finds'' added by individual
collectors and built by entrepreneurs who specialize in mountains,
lakes, waterfalls and other special touches.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, like many other collectors, has constructed some of her
own details, such as a clothesline with tiny dolls' clothes hung by
even tinier clothespins.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband learned how to make special effects at the
weekly meetings of the Cowtown Villagers, a group of about 100
Tarrant County collectors who meet the first Tuesday of each month
at Tis the Season in far west Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The group invites speakers to demonstrate nature building, such
as adding rivers and waterfalls to their layouts, how best to cut
and shape plastic foam and how to achieve natural-looking snow.
</P>
<P>
   The collectors sell and trade houses and accessories, discuss
novel ways to display their villages and sponsor a tour of members'
homes each December to show off. They also participate in the Texas
Roundup, a state-wide convention that attracts about 1,000 village
collectors each year. It is one of more than 20 major
Christmas-village conventions held throughout the country. In
addition, at least three quarterly magazines cater to Christmas
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   A Department 56 spokesman said the company hears from village
collectors all over the world, but so far most are confined to the
United States and Canada. The village rage has not gone global,
yet.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
