<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Dec. 13, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   GUGGENHEIM (New York) _ If anyone could have made sense of the
doings at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum last Thursday, it was
Eve, the top half of Brancusi's wooden sculpture ``Adam and Eve.''
With African features, a Hebrew name and a French-Romanian creator,
she touched more cultural bases than a Benetton advertisement. What
better emblem for the museum's new exhibition, ``Rendezvous:
Masterpieces from the Centre Georges Pompidou and the Guggenheim
Museums,'' and for a fizzy panel discussion dedicated to the
proposition that art, design, fashion, television and everything
else were converging into one huge fabulous cultural goo ball. By
William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-CARDS (Undated) _ As if it's not stressful enough that
people are judged by their looks, their jobs, their addresses and
even where their children go to school, with the holidays
approaching there is one more item to add to the list: Christmas
and Chanukah cards. By Monique P. Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ December and January belong to
evergreens and berried branches, to sprays of laurel and magnolia
leaves where those plants can be grown, and to bowls of colorful
fruit. By Cass Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   HOT-TICKETS (Undated) _ When Ticketmaster offered me the choice
between a good seat in January and a lousy one in early December to
the hottest play in town, I chose the lousy one, just to be ahead
of the curve. And so, with some chagrin, I arrived last Saturday
night for a sold-out preview at the Cort Theater with binoculars in
my coat pocket. Not that having binoculars in a theater was so bad.
But since I was seeing ``The Blue Room,'' I felt sheepish. ``The
Blue Room,'' after all, stars Nicole Kidman and is about sex and
only sex. By Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   CHARITY-AUCTIONS (Undated) _ Whether it means putting on a
Speedo for ``Baywatch'' or lying there like a corpse for ``General
Hospital,'' a cameo television appearance is just one of the
fantasy moments now tempting bidders at charity auctions. By Ellen
Gamerman.
</P>
