<P>
   LADY OF GUADALUPE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Our Lady of Guadalupe's image as a prayerful
Madonna framed by golden rays adorns the interiors of large and
small churches around the world. The famous icon also dangles from
rearview mirrors and is emblazoned on T-shirts of gang members. It
also has a special place in Arturo Loredo's restaurant on Fort
Worth's north side. ``She is my consoler, my protector _ the
protector of all Mexican people,'' said Loredo, referring to an
image of Guadalupe that hangs prominently in his restaurant. A
candle glows beneath it. ``I light a candle every day for the
Virgin,'' said Loredo, who is among millions of Roman Catholics who
will celebrate the Feast of Our Lady of Guadalupe on Saturday. The
feast day of the patroness of Mexico and the Americas is observed
in all dioceses of the United States. By JIM JONES. Story has moved
in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``God Can Heal Your Wounded Heart'' is the holiday
message outside a church in Arlington, Texas. Why display such a
sad message in the holiday season? Curiously, it's a message that
is entirely appropriate. People often feel the greatest emotional
pain during the holiday season, say spiritual leaders and
psychiatrists. By JIM JONES. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ As anyone who has followed the House Judiciary
Committee's hearings could attest, the impeachment issue is totally
immersed in partisan gamesmanship. There are probably committee
members who are driven by conscience rather than politics, but how
can we know for sure? By BILL THOMPSON. Story has moved in ``k''
commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL;
