<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEA-PARTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEA PARTY ISSUES STILL ALIVE TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Officially, it's the 225th anniversary of the Boston
Tea Party _ something of a caper amid the momentous events leading
to the American Revolution _ but there will be a bit of family
history and a burst of 1990s politics in the air at Sunday's
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The historic events _ a protest meeting at the Old South Meeting
House followed by the dumping of chests of tea into Boston Harbor,
took place on the evening of Dec. 16, 1773. They were a protest
against a tax on tea imported from England, even though the tax
lowered the price for which the tea was sold in the colonies.
</P>
<P>
   This year the 1773 unrest will be celebrated Sunday beginning at
5:30 p.m. with a reenactment of the protest meeting, followed by a
march down to the replica Tea Party Ship on the Congress Street
bridge. The events are free, and doors at the meeting house will
open at 4:45 p.m. when Ayriel, a historical-music group, will sing
patriotic and tavern songs of the period.
</P>
<P>
   The bit of family history will be supplied by Charles Chauncey
Wells, a descendent of one of the participants in the Tea Party,
while John Vann, who will portray Samuel Adams in the reenactment,
will supply the burst of 1990s politics.
</P>
<P>
   Wells is a ``four-greats'' grandson of Thomas Wells, a
blacksmith who worked on the harbor's wharves. Handed down in the
Wells family is a wrapper from one of the tea chests, which the
protester took and tucked in his shirt. ``They had been told not to
do that,'' Wells said, ``but they were all pretty lively young
men.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells is a former Chicago newsman, and his interest in his
ancestor prompted him to research and write a guide to Copps Hill
Burying Ground in the North End, where his ancestor and 28 other
Tea Party participants are buried. He will sign copies of his book
at the meeting house Saturday from noon to 2.
</P>
<P>
   Vann, a former Boston radio and television reporter who lives in
Arlington, will portray Adams, who fired up the citizens inside the
meeting house, sending them into the streets with his rallying cry
of ``this meeting can do nothing more to save the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting outside was a crew of young artisans and tradesmen like
Thomas Wells, thinly disguised as ``Indians,'' a group that Adams
had organized to be ready to lead a march to Griffin's Wharf
(located midway between Congress Street and Northern Avenue on
Atlantic Avenue) where the tea ships were docked.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was ``the agitator and the director who made things
happen,'' said Vann. ``He had a good way of getting a crowd flipped
up and excited.'' For himself, said Vann, he will get the audience
at Sunday's reenactment excited ``by the use of my voice and
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   And, to add the note of 1990s politics, ``I'll be bringing up
the matter of taxes. There are certain hot buttons you can push
that work as well today as they did 225 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   However staged the Boston Tea Party may have been as an act of
political protest, it triggered a similar event three days later in
Marshfield. Marshfield was ``a Tory town,'' according to town
historian Cynthia Hagar Krusell, but there were a number of young
men and small farmers who were patriots and were ``emboldened'' by
the events in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight on Dec. 19, they broke into John Bourne's store
(still standing off Route 3A) and seized the boxes of tea they
found. They loaded them on an ox cart and hauled them to the top of
a nearby hill and burned them on a large flat rock. As of Friday,
no commemoration was planned, but the rock is still known as Tea
Rock, sitting atop Tea Rock Hill, across from Town Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
