A5518 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-11 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE PET; BUY YOUR ANIMAL LOVER A BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the animal experts say that buying a pet for someone else
during the holidays is a potential disaster. Choosing a puppy or
kitten is very much like falling in love _ it's something no friend
or family member, no matter how well-meaning, can do for us. And
because the holidays are so chaotic, it's tough to give a new pet
the attention required.
</P>
<P>
   But fear not. You can place something with a spine under the
tree. Animal lovers also tend to be voracious readers, and there
are plenty of new book titles to satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red-Tails in Love: A Wildlife Drama in Central Park''
(Pantheon Books, $24) is one of the most enchanting true nature
stories ever. Wall Street Journal writer Marie Winn falls in with
an eclectic group of New York City birders, the ``regulars,'' as
she follows the saga of a red-tail hawk, Pale Male, through five
years of drama, tragedy, and joy. Fighting against forces of nature
and man, Pale Male struggles to raise a family on an upscale
apartment building in the heart of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Though evocative of classic nature stories, ``Red-Tails in
Love'' is thoroughly modern and gives cameos to Woody Allen, Mary
Tyler Moore, and Glenn Close. The real stars are the dear and
quirky regulars and, of course, the birds themselves. That people
can feel so much a part of the natural world and its rhythms even
in the heart of frantic New York is a wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best animal books lately have come from scientists
who, after years of studying a subject, ask profound questions
about the relationship between humans and other animals. ``Silent
Thunder: In the Presence of Elephants'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25), by
Katy Payne, is the story of two journeys. One is an action-packed
scientific safari, in which acoustic biologist Payne discovers and
explores communication among elephants, which is carried on at
frequencies far below the detection of human ears. And the other is
a spiritual one in which Payne compellingly weaves together her
farmland upbringing, a Quaker sensibility, the philosophy of the
Shona people she works with in Africa, and her own moral leanings
to form a philosophy of wise conservation. The interconnectedness
of life is a matter for the soul and the environment, Payne shows
us through her rich memories of elephants and people.
</P>
<P>
   Not all animal books have to be dramatic to be good. John
Pukite's ``A Field Guide to Cows: How to Identify and Appreciate
America's 52 Breeds'' (Penguin, $11.95) won't give you a lot to
ruminate about, but it is good, clean fun. The cow facts, both
serious and silly, pile up faster than pies in the pasture in this
easy-to-use guide. (Dairy cows are wedge-shaped, beef cows are more
rectangular; the Watusi from Africa has longer horns than the Texas
Longhorn; the Limousin from France may very well be the cow
depicted in the famed Lascaux cave drawings.) And the breed
information is accurate and concise.
</P>
<P>
   It's more Reader's Digest than New Yorker, and the title is
almost longer than the book itself. But Ruth Hanessian's ``Birds on
the Couch: The Bird Shrink's Guide to Keeping Polly from Going
Crackers and You out of the Cuckoo's Nest'' (Crown, $17) is a fun,
breezy read. The book, written with Wendy Bounds, has tiny
subchapters such as ``Why the Caged Bird Balks'' and ``Egging Polly
On'' that reveal the complicated psychology and biology of pet
birds through colorful little anecdotes from a woman who has been
part of the bird world since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Curtis, once a dealer in nature books, now has his own
imprint specializing in field guides. The latest, ``Field Guide to
the Larger Mammals of Africa'' (Ralph Curtis Books, $32.95), by
Chris and Tilde Stuart, is handsome and easy to use. Large color
photos, and a layout that includes range maps, plates, and size
scale with descriptions, make it user-friendly. The Stuarts come
with impressive credentials, and their text is authoritative and
concise. (Other guides under the same imprint bring you birds and
snakes from Australia, Borneo, India, and Africa.) . . . ``The
Mythology of Dogs: Canine Legend and Lore Through the Ages'' (St.
Martin's Press, $12.95), by Gerald and Loretta Hausman, is now in
paperback. From basset hounds in Shakespeare to wolfhounds in
ancient Rome, to the celestial leanings of the dachshund in
Egyptian mythology, this book compiles breed-by-breed information
from religious texts, literature, mythology, and pop culture that
you won't find in other dog books. . . . The design of porcupine
quills allows them to move into the victim's flesh at a rate of
about half an inch a day. That was discovered by a curious (in all
senses of the word) researcher who studied the phenomenon while an
embedded quill traveled from one side of his own calf and out the
other. Sloths do everything slowly _ they only urinate and defecate
every eight days. These facts are part of the collection ``Every
Creeping Thing: True Tales of Faintly Repulsive Wildlife'' (Henry
Holt &AMP; Co., $25), by Richard Conniff. Traveling widely, Conniff
provides the inside story on rats, grizzlies, sharks, cormorants,
and more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
