<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-STAKES     12-11 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-STAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PALESTINIANS HOPEFUL, ISRAELIS ANXIOUS ON VERGE OF CLINTON TRIP
 &HT;    With MIDEAST, MIDEAST-SITES and MIDEAST-SECURITY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank Palestinian Imad Rabah's small factory had
just stamped out 14,000 plastic flags to help welcome President
Clinton, but he still did a double take at the sight of his
three-year-old son waving one in the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, two years ago, I wouldn't have let him show that,'' he
said. ``It would make people angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabah attended the University of Florida, but he knows that you
don't often see Old Glory in a Palestinian street unless it's in
flames.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrives in Israel Saturday night, he will face a
visit hosted by two peoples Palestinian and Israeli with widely
different views of his mission and jealous of his attention.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Palestinians are gleeful at the first visit from the
leader of an America they think has neglected their plight. They
will get to host him in Gaza and Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis, especially their leaders, are nervous that their
stalwart American ally is cozying up to their old enemy.
</P>
<P>
   From his 10th floor hotel penthouse, Clinton will be able to
view the pricey condominiums of Jewish Jerusalem and the walls of
the ancient Old City, populated mostly by Arabs who consider
themselves under Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Out there, the Wye River Plantation peace plan, which Clinton
brokered six weeks ago, is frozen. Even Friday, on the even of
Clinton's trip, two Palestinians died when Israeli troops fired at
hundreds of stone-throwers in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   America has become more involved in the process than ever, and
the question is whether the two sides will get enough from
Clinton's trip to start making concessions needed to get it back on
track.
</P>
<P>
   For the Palestinians it could be easy. Clinton's side trip
Monday to the Gaza Strip looks to them like a step toward their
dream of an independent nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember that President Clinton has a custom of
visiting autonomous areas,''' quipped Ahmed Tibi, aide to
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the poorly-concealed sentiments among Israeli leaders
might best be summed up with an Arabic proverb: You invite your
friend, and he brings his donkey, too. The trip has taken an
unexpected turn.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wye River Plantation in Maryland, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu was eager for Clinton to go to Gaza. He thought it would
force the PLO to meet and reaffirm that it no longer seeks the
destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``But (the Palestinians) reversed it,'' Natan Sharansky, who
helped negotiate Wye for the Israelis, said with some
consternation. ``(Now), it's a reception honoring Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Israelis tend to see Clinton two ways. Left-wing Israelis admire
him perhaps more than any other U.S. president. Many have Hebrew
bumper stickers quoting, ``Peace, friend,'' from the eulogy Clinton
delivered at the 1995 funeral of slain Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Israeli right wing, which currently holds power, sees
Clinton as pressuring Israel to give up land. New posters in
Jerusalem show an illustration of Clinton in an Arab head dress,
telling him ``Go Home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli public is pretty tired and pretty confused,'' said
Joseph Alpher, director of the Middle East office of the American
Jewish Committee.
</P>
<P>
   They will get one day with Clinton to themselves, then he heads
to Gaza for a day. Members of Netanyahu's cabinet even suggested
that Clinton be asked not to come at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left-wing Israelis will applaud it and right wing Israelis
will be appalled,'' Alpher said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has agreed not to fly to Gaza in his Boeing 747 Air
Force One. It was, for the Israelis, too potent a symbol of
official America. He will take his helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   But, beyond all the symbolism, Israelis worry Clinton will try
to revive Wye by letting Arafat slide on promises to fight
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important the president makes it clear that he has no
intention of trying to deliver Israel on issues that go to the
heart of Israel's security,'' Israeli government spokesman Moshe
Fogel said.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate concern is the Gaza meeting. The Palestinians are
sticking to the letter of the Wye agreement, which lets them
vaguely ``reaffirm'' that they have amended their national charter
to no longer call for war against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israel demands a clear, public, vote. Palestinians say they
amended their charter once in 1996 and do not need to vote again.
</P>
<P>
   It will create a tough situation for Netanyahu if Clinton gives
the thumbs up to what he will see in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants the peace process to continue, but members of
Netanyahu's right-wing coalition threaten to dump him if he accepts
anything less than an explicit vote before resuming the land
transfers scheduled in the Wye plan.
</P>
<P>
   As Israeli columnist Hemi(cq) Shalev wrote Friday, ``The
equation is fundamentally simple: Clinton and Netanyahu have
conflicting interests. The victories of the one will come, by
necessity, at the expense of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the forays into Palestinian territories, Netanyahu will
get the last word. On Clinton's final stop Tuesday, Netanyahu will
personally guide him through the mountaintop archaeological site at
Masada, where Jewish rebels 1900 years ago committed suicide rather
than be routed by the Romans.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
