<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S ETHNIC SHIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ All afternoon, mariachi music filled the rotunda,
echoing up the 210-foot dome of the Capitol. After Speaker Antonio
Villaraigosa swore in new members of the Assembly, the fiesta
began.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999-2000 session of the California Legislature, 24
Latinos will help make laws in the nation's largest state. The
seven senators and 17 assembly members add up to a record number,
but this triumph is not bipartisan. Among legislators of Hispanic
descent, Democrats outnumber Republicans, 20-4.
</P>
<P>
   For the GOP, this sour note is minor compared to the ominous
figures hurtling like a meteor toward a dwindling Republican base.
Demographers in the Department of Finance are finishing a survey
that shows the future arriving more suddenly than previously
thought. In 2001, California will have a nonwhite majority, with
blacks and whites declining slightly in their proportions, but
Asian-Americans and Latinos rising dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   By 2040, the Anglo-Hispanic ratio will be almost reversed. In
the 1990 Census, 57 percent of California's population was white
and 26 percent Hispanic. In 2040, demographers expect 60 million
people to inhabit California. By then, whites will have shrunk to
31 percent of the population and Hispanics will have grown to 48
percent.
</P>
<P>
   When Gray Davis, a Democrat, takes the oath as governor next
month, Democrats will dominate the political establishment of
California as rarely before. Only two Republicans, Secretary of
State Bill Jones and Insurance Commissioner Charles Quackenbush,
were reelected. Democrats also picked up more legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor, elected separately, is Cruz Bustamante
of Fresno, a former Assembly speaker, whose presence on the ticket
aided Davis and other statewide candidates by energizing the
Hispanic vote. But the most potent sparkplug was a Republican,
Governor Pete Wilson, now leaving office after two terms. Although
he can count some successes in the economy, education, and the
environment, Wilson's legacy does not include warm relations
between whites and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, his reelection endangered, Wilson adopted Proposition
187, which sought to ban state services for illegal immigrants.
Although Wilson carefully made distinctions between legal and
illegal immigrants, television ads did not, depicting shadowy mass
border crossings in a grainy Willie Horton monochrome with the tag
line, ``They keep coming.''
</P>
<P>
   In elections since, Hispanics have said to Republicans: ``What
do you mean `They,' Gringo?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' has become ``Us'' in California, endangering a party
that often caters to rich white males, thus part of Wilson's
legacy. At a ``roast'' for the outgoing governor last week, the
Sacramento Press Club disproved the notion that California politics
is all mellow bliss. The viejo gringo gave as good as he got, but
even the dinner program mocked his ambitions, reproducing a highway
warning sign, a silhouetted family scampering across the Mexican
border. The captions read: ``Pedro in 2000'' and ``Run, Pete,
Run!''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's friend, longtime Republican strategist Ken Khachigian,
sees bright moments in the future. ``When Latinos become homeowners
and taxpayers, they'll become concerned about taxes, just as they
are already about crime and discipline in the schools,'' he says.
``Basically, we just to have to be patient while demographics
change not just ethnically, but economically. Hispanics will
discover that Democrats believe in higher taxes, less discipline,
and are less interested in family values.''
</P>
<P>
   His patience may not be shared by Hispanic families, only 40
percent of whom now own their own homes, a Census figure trailing
black home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Khachigian's optimism also ignores what a Democratic party icon,
John Maynard Keynes, wrote in ``A Tract on Monetary Reform'' in
1923: ``This long run is a misleading guide to public affairs. In
the long run, we are all dead.''
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
