<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5526 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BIOS-BOS &LR;      12-11 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BIOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BIOGRAPHIES THAT ENTERTAIN AND INFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
INTIMATE PORTRAIT: CHRISTINE LAHTI
<TEXT>
<P>
   Produced by: Valerie Shepherd
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Lee Grant
</P>
<P>
   On: Lifetime, Saturday at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONTGOMERY CLIFT: THE HIDDEN STAR
</P>
<P>
   Produced and written by: John Griffin
</P>
<P>
   On: A&AMP;E, Monday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just because a biography is friendly to its subject, more
approving than probing, doesn't mean it has to be dull or
uninformative. Virtually all of today's stream of made-for-cable
celebrity portraits, like Lifetime's upcoming hour about actress
Christine Lahti and A &AMP; E's biography of legendary movie star
Montgomery Clift, are soft tributes rather than serious studies.
</P>
<P>
   But, like the Clift documentary, they can be moving and
interesting, even if, at 60 minutes, necessarily incomplete. More
about this relatively pleasing production later.
</P>
<P>
   First, let's dispense with ``Christine Lahti,'' one of the
Lifetime channel's so-called Intimate Portraits (debuting Saturday
at 10 p.m.). Don't get me wrong: I admire Lahti's edgy acting style
and mildly eccentric persona; and, for what it's worth, I suspect
she's a perfectly decent human being. But I expect more from even
such a casual, upbeat profile than the statement that Lahti comes
from a ``picture-perfect family.'' Any biography employing those
three words is sure to be a lie and, worse, a bore.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Lahti'' is indeed a bore, primarily an interview with the
49-year-old actress herself, chatting about her idyllic girlhood in
Michigan; her pal Goldie Hawn; her perfect husband, the director
Thomas Schlamme; and the joy she takes in work and motherhood. We
see Lahti as doting working mom on the set of ``Chicago Hope,''
taking a break to amuse her young children: She's cheerful,
unflappable and, frankly, unbelievable. Interspersed throughout the
interview are short on-camera comments from _ surprise _ Hawn,
Schlamme, and other complimentary friends and co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the fact that when she first waitressed and studied
acting in New York, the sheltered Lahti was afraid to go out after
9 p.m. But what remains is totally predictable, and the too-few,
too-short film clips fail to establish what's genuinely intriguing
about this woman _ her singularly stylish acting.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery Clift's was decidedly not a picture-perfect family,
and ``Montgomery Clift: The Hidden Star'' sketches his uneasy
childhood and sometimes tortured adult life in deft strokes. The A
&AMP; E biography airs Monday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Clift, of course, was a major screen figure and a powerful
influence on other actors, notably James Dean and Marlon Brando. In
``Red River'' and, later, ``A Place in the Sun,'' he broke the
Hollywood leading-man mold with his brooding intensity and palpable
vulnerability. Brando considered Clift a better actor, and never
felt he equaled him. Although this last fact isn't included in
``The Hidden Star,'' interesting details abound.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest are tape recordings made by Clift's
brother Brooks including converations with Montgomery and with
their domineering mother. Why Brooks made the recordings of his
brother isn't explained, but they reveal a man whose reedy, needy
voice seems to mirror his fabled anguish. Montgomery had apparently
always abused alcohol and drugs, but after a disfiguring 1956 auto
accident, his drinking and pill-popping worsened, certainly
contributing to his death in 1966 at 45.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was hushed up during his heyday by nervous movie
studios, Clift was gay or, depending on the source, bisexual. When
he was shooting ``A Place in the Sun'' with then 18-year-old
Elizabeth Taylor and was linked with her romantically by the
tabloids, she was getting him dates with other men. Much has been
made of the fact that Clift's sexual identity tortured him, but
Brooks Clift, a chief interview subject in ``The Hidden Star,''
argues otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no denying that the popular actor was a
complicated and troubled man. It didn't help that he was so choosy
about scripts, offered to him in great profusion, that he turned
down starring roles in ``On the Waterfront'' and ``Sunset
Boulevard.''
</P>
<P>
   The A &AMP; E biography evokes a sympathetic picture of this
handsome, gifted, beloved, and sadly bedevilled screen icon.
</P>
<P>
   What it unfortunately fails to do is firmly establish, or even
precisely describe, the unique qualities of his subtly dynamic
acting. As in the Lahti program, too little time is devoted to
clips from the subject's movies. Nor are there any interviews with
film historians or critics that might have enriched our
appreciation of Clift's indelible and influential art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
