<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TRAVELS TO MIDEAST TO REVIVE WYE AGREEMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a trip fraught with political peril, President
Clinton travels Saturday to Israel and Palestinian-controlled
territories as he attempts to revive a faltering 2-month-old peace
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's main mission is to continue to push the Israelis and
Palestinians to adhere to the Wye River Memorandum in which Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu agreed to cede more West Bank territory
in return for security guarantees from Chairman Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew when we left Wye that we would be facing a bumpy road
and some of those bumps have already been jarring, but there can be
no question that Wye has moved us further down the road toward
peace and away from the long and dangerous impasse that proceeded
it,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the visit has become laden with symbolism as Palestinians
view the stops in Gaza and the West Bank as a step toward
recognition of an independent state, an anathema to many Israelis.
Hard-line conservatives in Israel have urged Clinton to postpone
the trip and have threatened to boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Clinton's visit should not be interpreted as
endorsement of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the visit) does not do that. The bottom line here is it is
a part of the Wye agreement. And as we have said many times, the
issue of Palestinian statehood is a permanent status issue. It is
something that needs to be negotiated, and it is part of the next
process,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has marred the region since the leaders signed the Wye
River accord in an elaborate White House ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, his government just weeks away from possible
collapse, has suspended Israeli troop withdrawals in response to
violence in Palestinian areas. The Palestinians are protesting
Israel's refusal to release political prisoners as the Wye accord
required.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, his own health in question, repeatedly has announced his
intention to declare a Palestinian state in May 1999, the deadline
for the completion of the so-called final status talks on delicate
issues such as the status of Jerusalem and Palestine, but those
talks have not yet even begun.
</P>
<P>
   Added to this fractious mix are questions about Clinton's own
status. The president leaves Washington as the House Judiciary
Committee considers four articles of impeachment stemming from
Clinton's lies about an affair with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Also invited to join Clinton's entourage are three moderate
Republicans who have yet to make a decision on their impeachment
vote, which is expected to take place next week in the full House.
</P>
<P>
   The trip may shape up as one of Clinton's most brief overseas
ventures this year, but possibly one of his most critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is making this trip because he is dedicated to
helping both sides overcoming the challenges that still exist to a
productive negotiating process and a durable peace,'' Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clinton will meet privately with Netanyahu, visit the
grave site of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin who was killed by an
Israeli extremist, participate in a Menorah lighting to mark the
first day of Hannukah and speak to young Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can expect the president to make one point very clear:
America has unshakable ties to the state of Israel and enduring
commitment to Israel's security,'' said Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger,
the president's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of our closest allies and shall remain so. I expect
the president to talk in some detail about the Wye River agreement
and why it promotes both the security of Israel and peace of
Israel,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton will fly by helicopter from Jerusalem to the
Gaza Strip where he will address the Palestinian National Council,
which will affirm the Palestinian Liberation Organization's action
earlier this week to strike from the PLO's 1964 charter provisions
calling for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed to address the council when he was helping broker
the Wye River agreement at the Maryland resort. Now, however,
Netanyahu is demanding that the council take a vote to strike the
provisions, not just affirm the PLO's actions. Arafat has refused,
placing in doubt whether Israel will accept the action.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton will meet with Israeli opposition leaders in
the Labor Party and tour the West Bank city of Bethlehem, tour the
Church of the Nativity with Arafat and light a Christmas tree.
Later, Clinton, joined by Netanyahu, also will tour Masada,
symbolic scene of Jewish resistance to Roman enslavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much a part of the Wye agreement for the president
to go and make this trip,'' Albright said. ``I think it will have
an effect of showing that the United States continues to back the
Wye agreement and that the leaders themselves, who made very hard
decisions, will be carrying them out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
