<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-MUNICIPALS-ART     12-11 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MUNICIPALS-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING A WINDOW TO MUNI BOND PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of munis a good buy at year end is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 13)  
 (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, someone bought one or more Los Angeles County
pension bonds due in June 2007. The bonds were of the zero-coupon
variety, and the buyer paid dearly _ $613.23 for every $1,000 in
face amount.
</P>
<P>
   Another buyer, the very same day, paid just $568.23 for the same
bond. As a result, the first investor will get a yield to maturity
of 5.79 percent while the second will get a yield of 6.71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Why the large difference?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the stock market, where investors can scarcely avoid
learning the latest prices, the municipal bond arena has long been
cloaked in such mystery that just to ask about the detailed terms
of an issue can be akin to breaking a fraternal taboo. And some
brokers have used this secrecy to mark up muni bonds by big
amounts.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, retail customers often do not seem eager to
learn more than the yield and issuer's name, said Joe Mysak, editor
of Grant's Municipal Finance, a newsletter. The retail side, he
said, ``does not want information about municipal bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   But even this arcane and traditional business, whose biggest
patrons are individuals in high tax brackets, is succumbing to the
information age. Just before Thanksgiving, the Bond Market
Association, an industry group, started posting daily transactions
on its Web site _ www.investinginbonds.com _ giving potential
buyers and sellers free access to prices, yields, credit ratings
and other information.
</P>
<P>
   And the window is opening just as specialists in munis are
finding the sector a screaming bargain. Yields can now be fully 95
percent of those on Treasury bonds, which, unlike munis, are
subject to federal income tax.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's new effort at transparency may be welcomed by
investors, who sometimes have difficulty learning details of even
their own transactions, a situation that has increasingly rankled
securities regulators. Through the site, investors can learn what
others are paying, like the first hapless buyer of the California
zero-coupon bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this perception that bonds are more risky than
stocks'' because so little specific information about issuers and
the trading markets reaches the investing public, said Alexandra
Lebenthal, president of the municipal bond specialist firm in New
York bearing her family name. She called the Web site ``a good
thing,'' something that would undoubtedly evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Since the new Web postings started on Nov. 23, the site has had
a 28 percent increase in daily visits. Although the site is updated
just once a day, by 8:45 a.m., and is far from comprehensive _
there are, after all, more than 1.4 million outstanding issues of
state, municipal and government-agency bonds _ it supplies useful
data.
</P>
<P>
   The draw is the prices at which the 1,000 or so most active
issues changed hands in the preceding session; the site lists each
issue that had at least four transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the list allows potential buyers to shop for
appropriate securities on their own and to avoid overreliance on a
broker who may have more incentive to sell them less suitable
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The user-friendly features include the ability to sort bonds by
state, credit rating, maturity and yield, as well as to see the
highest and lowest transaction prices.
</P>
<P>
   Investors interested in selling their muni bonds can quickly
determine their approximate value in a secondary market that is
relatively thin, even for more active issues, because most
municipals are put away for keeps.
</P>
<P>
   Without the site, said Peter J. Allegrini, a managing director
at Prudential Investments, ``there are not many ways for people to
verify whether their brokers are giving them the right
information.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Web site prices are not all that current _ on a
Thursday afternoon, say, one might be examining transactions that
took place on Wednesday morning. And it is often difficult to tell
whether a particular high or low price reflects a large block or a
small trade of, say, $10,000 or $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   As in any market, the bigger the transaction in municipals, the
better the price, though some bond industry professionals,
including Ms. Lebenthal, worry about neophytes whose initial
response may point to Web site postings as evidence of a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   Web prices include dealer markups, the typical form of
compensation in the municipal business. Dealers stoutly resisted
listing actual prices that would show the markups separately.
Typically, these are about one-half of 1 percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The prices on the site are based on those reported by dealers to
the Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board, a self-regulatory body
based in Washington that in August began providing this information
to vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The association and J.J. Kenny, the Standard &AMP; Poor's unit,
supplement the prices with data on coupons, yields to maturity,
yields to call date, credit ratings and the company insuring the
bonds, if any.
</P>
<P>
   Mysak of Grant's, who has long lamented the paucity of
information generally supplied to muni investors, is enthusiastic
about the new service. ``I think it's terrific,'' he said, noting
the complicated nature of the bonds and the peddling of low-quality
issues backed by ventures like golf courses and retirement centers.
Such bonds, he said, demand particularly close scrutiny. ``It's a
wonderful tool that any investor can learn to use to their
profit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1701EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
