<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOT-TICKETS-$ADV13-NY     12-11 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-TICKETS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE PLAY'S NOT THE THING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Dec. 13) 
(JT) 
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Ticketmaster offered me the choice between a
good seat in January and a lousy one in early December to the
hottest play in town, I chose the lousy one, just to be ahead of
the curve.
</P>
<P>
   And so, with some chagrin, I arrived last Saturday night for a
sold-out preview at the Cort Theater with binoculars in my coat
pocket. Not that having binoculars in a theater was so bad. But
since I was seeing ``The Blue Room,'' I felt sheepish. ``The Blue
Room,'' after all, stars Nicole Kidman and is about sex and only
sex. As you must know by now, the two-character British import by
David Hare (famously dubbed ``pure theatrical Viagra'' by The
London Telegraph) opens today for a limited run that is getting
almost as much attention as that White House intern did not long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, I needn't have worried about looking too
voyeuristic. As soon as the lights went down, everyone around me
pulled out binoculars. Up there in the rear balcony, far removed
from the big shots in the orchestra, we looked like bird watchers
at a sanctuary during a particularly busy mating season. The play
sparked and shocked, just as sex should. And I'm happy to say that
I found the performances superb. The strange thing is, I would be
just as happy to say they were overrated.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because when you're as interested in seeing something for
its status value as for its artistic value, nothing matters more
than one thing _ seeing it before anyone else you know.
</P>
<P>
   So what if I had to sit in a seat that made me feel as if I were
watching a sports event rather than an intimate play about
intimacy? So what if I was crammed in so tightly up there that I
couldn't move my leg without knocking the binoculars out of the
hands of the well-dressed women on either side of me? And so what
if it took 15 minutes after the play ended to get down the
staircase, where I was jammed between two matrons (one was saying,
``It wasn't romantic _ there wasn't one throb in it for me'') and
three college-age young women shrieking that Tom Cruise, Ms.
Kidman's husband, was definitely in the house? So what, too, if I
was alone on a Saturday night, like a total loser, since pairs of
tickets were impossible to come by? I had just muscled my way
through an experience that would enhance my status for at least a
week, if not longer, and that mattered more than anything.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where hotels and restaurants have ``soft openings''
for insiders before they really open, and where fashion editors go
around declaring as ``over'' a look that has just made it into
stores, because they've already seen the clothes for next season on
the runways, you're nothing if you aren't early.
</P>
<P>
   Museums have private previews for major donors the night before
openings for members. Hollywood hotties have screenings before
premieres, and a handful of power players in New York and
Washington get The New Yorker hand-delivered on Sundays without
asking.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, it wasn't over until the fat lady sang. Now,
it's over before the fat lady opens her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   To get the most out of my prestigiously early ``Blue Room''
experience, I had to flaunt it as quickly as possible. After
threading my way through a mob that had gathered by the stage door
and was spilling into the streets (and was heckling anyone who came
out the stage door who wasn't Ms. Kidman or Cruise), I rushed home
to work the phone. But as it was Saturday night, nobody was around.
I had to wait until morning, when I pulled my first boast on some
friends over coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to see it on opening night,'' replied one of them,
who knows the ``Blue Room'' producer, ``and then I'm going to the
dinner afterwards at the Chelsea Piers.''
</P>
<P>
   With a depressing authority that put me in a blue room of my
own, she proceeded to tell me all kinds of things: That Ms. Kidman
shops like a maniac and wears hair extensions, and that her
director, Sam Mendes, is rumored to be going out with Calista
Flockhart. I found this knowingness very deflating, and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it in London,'' another friend said later, shutting me
down abruptly. ``The theater was tiny, and every time Nicole took
her shirt off the entire audience turned around to look at Tom, who
was unable to hide in the back of the house. In New York, he
watches from the lighting booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Another friend had just gotten back from a Sunday matinee of the
show, where she and her husband had third-row orchestra seats.
``Doesn't Nicole Kidman have the most amazing skin?'' she asked.
From where I'd been sitting, and even with binoculars pressed to my
nose the whole time, I had no idea.
</P>
<P>
   Like social climbing and getting upgraded on airlines, this game
was a lot harder to play than I thought. One friend seemed
genuinely interested in hearing about Ms. Kidman's buttocks (small,
without cellulite), but she was late for Sandra Bernhard's book
party at the Mercer Kitchen. ``Isn't that more prestigious than
seeing Nicole Kidman on stage?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Another had just gotten a longer dose of nudity at an elevating
performance by Ballett Frankfurt at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
``That beats Nicole Kidman's butt any day,'' she snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Even an anthropologist friend in Papua New Guinea, to whom I had
bragged by e-mail, was closer to the heat than I'd ever be. Her ex
used to work in Cruise's office and had regaled her with stories of
his antics.
</P>
<P>
   So then, was there nobody who would allow me to cash in at the
full exchange rate on ``The Blue Room,'' which Newsweek, in a cover
story last week, called the hottest ticket for a nonmusical in
Broadway history?
</P>
<P>
   My parents were at a Ramada Inn in Corpus Christi, Texas, for an
Elderhostel. I called them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never heard of it,'' my mother said. When I explained the
gist, she fell silent. ``Oh, that's terrible,'' she sighed. ``And
this is a big deal right now? What kind of society do we live in
anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   My father was a little less judgmental. ``Sex in every scene,''
he said. ``Is she a Catholic? Do you think she's trying to make
some kind of a statement?''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't what I had in mind at all, but instead of telling
him she's a Scientologist, like her husband, I dropped the subject.
There were more improving things to talk about anyway, like the
weather and their bird-watching seminar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at shore birds and at one of the biggest pelican
hatcheries in the world,'' my father bragged. Of course, they had
their binoculars on hand for the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't suppose you'll be using them,'' I said sourly,
``to look at anything but birds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly not,'' my father replied. ``With no ifs, ands or,
um, buts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
