<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-BJT1212-COX     12-11 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BJT1212-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Saturday, December 12, 1998
and Sunday, December 13, 1998, are moving today to clients of the
New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR _ While America rides an unprecedented economic boom, a
quiet revolution is going on in the factories across America.
Senior workers with their jobs threatened and nearing retirement
often approve two-tier wage systems. The differences in wages are
staggering. Senior assembly line workers earning up to $21 an hour
work with younger workers doing identical jobs earning $7.50 an
hour. It can also take up to two years for a new worker to be
covered by insurance and other benefits. At GM, the company is
going a step further: outsourcing and selling off various divisions
_ at great impact to families in this community. And at Navistar in
Springfield, the viability of an entire community largely depends
on its decision to move its truck production to Mexico, where more
and more companies are taking advantage of cheap labor.
(Hills/Modic/Wagner, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: First of four parts. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   COKE-CADBURY _ ATLANTA _ The Coca-Cola Co. is buying Cadbury
Schweppes' brands in 120 countries in a deal estimated at $1.85
billion, the companies announced today. The deal covers Schweppes
and Canada Dry mixers, Dr Pepper and Crush. The transaction, which
does not apply to the United States, France and South Africa, also
includes acquisition of beverage plants in Ireland and Spain.
(Gramig, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY A.M. FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co., the world's largest
soft-drink company, said fourth-quarter earnings will be below
expectations because of economic problems in many of its
international markets. The Atlanta-based company said it would
report earnings of 24 cents to 25 cents a share, less than the
average estimate of 30 cents among analysts. (Gramig, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BRANDS _ Coca-Cola's deal with Cadbury-Sweppes drastically
increases its brand offerings, including Canada Dry, Crush, Dr
Pepper and Schweppes. (Gramig, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   COKE-IMPACT _ A look at what the deal means for
Cadbury-Schweppes. The company gets cash to improve its U.S.
operations. (Gramig, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   COKE-IVESTER _ The purchase of Cadbury-Schweppes is the biggest
move yet by M. Douglas Ivester since he rose to the helm of
Coca-Cola after the death of Roberto Goizueta. (Gramig, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   COKE-PEPSI _ A look at Pepsi's reaction to the deal. Pepsi
lately has been increasing the competitive pressure on Coke. The
deal turns the tables. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   COKE-STOCK _ Coca-Cola's stock has been under pressure lately,
and the deal adds even more. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   COKE-VOLUME _ A look at what the deal does for Coca-Cola's
volume, which has been under pressure because of Asia's and Latin
America's economic problems. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   CABLE _ LyncStar, a small Colorado cable television company that
wants to expand in Austin, has withdrawn its application for a
franchise from the City of Austin, blamed Time Warner Cable and
promised to try again through the Federal Communications
Commission. (Hight, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS-TRADING _ State securities regulators say about 50 Texas
investors should soon receive $5 million they had invested in
Options Trading Group, a national foreign currency trading
operation with offices in Austin. The receiver found money at a
Bahamas bank account. (Tyson, Austin American-Statesman). FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   AFIT _ Less than a year ago, the Air Force seemed to be digging
the Air Force Institute of Technology's grave. Today AFIT is
digging the next chapter in its history: an $8.9 million laboratory
that will allow its graduate-level engineering students to study
micromachines, high-energy lasers, and other military technology.
The Air Force unlocked construction funds for the project earlier
this year after an independent study showed AFIT's military value,
and ground was broken last week. The lab should be finished by June
of 2000. AFIT is also restructuring itself, slimming down from two
schools with eight departments to one school with six departments.
AFIT commandant Col. John Russell said it matches a downsizing
military. I will try to get some quotes to put AFIT's survival in a
local economic context. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News). 10. FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
