</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT12-COX     12-11 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WILL MICROSOFT SETTLE ITS ANTITRUST CASE?
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT-FELTEN. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Will Microsoft Corp. settle its quarrel with the
antitrust police before U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
gets to rule on the historic civil suit next spring?
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the large ads Microsoft placed recently in several
newspapers, you wouldn't think the battle is near an end. Headlined
``Leave it to the Marketplace,'' the ads quote economists and
editorials opposed to prosecuting the landmark case.
</P>
<P>
   Still, developments in court could induce the battling parties
to strike a deal. The pressure to compromise stems not only from
events in the marketplace, but also the software giant's vision of
how it seeks to evolve its successful monopoly franchise for
personal computer operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said the ads were needed to
counter ``news leaks'' from the government about the trial, due to
enter its ninth week on Monday. But save for a few sealed
documents, the trial has been held entirely in the open. In truth,
what Murray was alluding to was the government's conviction that
the case was going their way.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every day that court convenes, Joel Klein, the
government's chief antitrust enforcer, strolls down Pennsylvania
Avenue from his Justice Department office to the federal
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a phalanx of lawyers, Klein sits on a hard wooden bench
as the testimony unfolds. Klein has shared his upbeat outlook on
the proceedings with a few aides. But his views have seeped out,
creating a strong impact on the defense team.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's billed as the technological legal showdown of the
century, all the key participants remain quite chummy. They trade
jokes during the breaks and even meet for dinner on some evenings.
David Boies, the government's chief litigator, and John Warden, his
Microsoft counterpart, have previously worked together on the
antitrust circuit. Back in Bedford, N.Y., they are friends and
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, while a distant videotaped
visage, is nevertheless fully attuned to the atmosphere in the
courtroom. Twice a day, he is briefed on developments by William
Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel, and by Tod Nielsen,
Microsoft's general manager for outside developer relations.
</P>
<P>
   According to Boies, it was Gates himself who intervened last May
to block a last-minute settlement, against the advice of Neukom,
who has been Microsoft's top lawyer since its founding in 1975, and
that of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell, Microsoft's Wall Street litigators.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Jackson, a decisive figure who has sat on the federal
bench since 1982, has sent mixed signals on how may rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has tipped his hand,'' holds William Kovacic, a visiting
professor of antitrust law at George Washington University Law
School. ``The government is going to win at the trial level. It is
not clear by how much, but I think this judge is going to find a
violation and impose some kind of remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   To buttress Kovacic's view, when Jackson questioned Avadis
Tevanian, an Apple Computer Inc. executive, on Nov. 5 about whether
integrating an Internet browser into the Windows operating system
provided any technical benefits, Jackson's points seemed mapped to
the government's position.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson startled the courtroom last Thursday by suggesting
to James Gosling, Sun Microsystems Inc.'s chief scientist, that Sun
had moved too slowly to counter innovations by an industry leader
in what remains a highly competitive environment. That's precisely
what Microsoft had contended during four days of its
cross-examination, spread over two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping both sides unsure of where he really stands, the
stocky 61-year-old judge raises the chances for an out-of-court
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Recent business pressures point the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's move by America Online Inc. to absorb Netscape
Communications Corp. _ a deal that included new business for Sun _
seemingly weakened the case against Microsoft. ``In an industry
where (this) $4.2 billion merger ...can change the competitive
landscape overnight, why is there any need for government
intervention?'' Microsoft asks in its ad.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft was also caught off guard in September when, with
Jackson's assent, the government amplified its original complaint
from a thrust against the bundling of the Internet Explorer browser
into Windows 98 into a wide-ranging action that alleges a
systematic pattern of misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials privately admit that they once had a
``bulletproof'' bulwark against the government: They have already
sold some 15 million copies of Windows 98. In each of them, the
browser is technologically baked into the cake and cannot be
removed, no matter what the court should decide.
</P>
<P>
   But next spring, Microsoft plans to roll out Office 2000, a
suite of highly useful programs that, judging by the public
``beta'' release, would forever blur all lines among Windows, the
browser and the suite of major applications.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000's premium package bundles new versions of every
major business program that Microsoft now markets, including its
word processor, spreadsheet, database, e-mail client and an image
editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Office 2000 is so deeply intertwined with the (operating
system), test it only if you plan to reformat your hard disk
afterward'' in case software bugs cause a system crash, warns
Edward Mendelson, who previews the huge project for the Jan. 5
issue of PC Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Top Microsoft officials project that most personal computer
users won't require any additional software besides Windows and the
integrated Office suite. Because of this, they say, future software
developers will focus on networks and Internet services, such as
e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   They also know that if an integrated browser raised deep
concerns at the Justice Department, then a fully integrated
``applications system'' could trigger even louder alarm bells, both
there and in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But an early settlement could help clear a legal path for Office
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the judge finds for the government, any remedy could not be
imposed by the court,'' Boies conceded in an interview. ``It would
have to be negotiated, top to bottom, with Microsoft, in order to
protect the interests of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   How such at negotiation might proceed is still anybody's guess.
But imposing a hefty fine on a company with $17 billion in cash
won't make much of an impact, federal antitrust officials
acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   And absent a settlement, Jackson is unlikely to favor creating a
U.S. Department of Microsoft, charged with regulating the company's
behavior to ensure that it competes fairly.
</P>
<P>
   As Stewart Alsop, a Silicon Valley investor, observes:
``Bureaucrats paid on a General Schedule have no incentive to make
quick decisions about a fast-moving technology. This would turn
Windows into an even worse product in the future, which is hard to
contemplate, since it's bad enough as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   By cutting a deal, Microsoft would avoid that nightmare, and
some others as well. Whether a deal will sprout still remains to be
seen. But the necessary seeds appear to have been planted.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
