<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5711 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-KENNEDY-HONORS-$A     12-11 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-KENNEDY-HONORS-$ADV28-AUS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WILLIE NELSON HONORED AT 'WASHINGTON'S OSCARS'
 &HT;    620&AMP;add. For release Monday, Dec. 28.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attire for the Kennedy Center Honors is always
unflinchingly formal, so Willie Nelson arrived in a spiffy black
cowboy hat, shined black boots and black velvet binding the ends of
his braided reddish-gray hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember the last time'' he was so dressed up,
admitted the tuxedoed Texas troubador, who was among this year's
honorees. ``But they sent me a little piece of paper that said,
'You will wear black tie.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Along with Nelson, the Kennedy Center's 21st annual recognition
for lifetime achievement in the performing arts went to Bill Cosby,
Shirley Temple Black, conductor Andre Previn and Broadway composer
John Kander and lyricist Fred Ebb. The star-studded salute to the
honorees was videotaped Dec. 6 and will be broadcast on the CBS
television network on Wednesday (Dec. 30) at 9 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called ``Washington's Oscars,'' the Kennedy Center
Honors have recognized 111 American artists ranging from Bob Hope
and Lucille Ball to Paul Newman and Roy Acuff over the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   After hosting this year's honorees at a White House reception,
President Clinton and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton joined them
in box seats at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts
to watch a stage show recalling the winners' artistic careers.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Academy Awards, the evening begins with fans and TV
crews gathered on both sides of a red-carpeted foyer to see the
honorees and other celebrities walk from their limousines to their
theater seats. This promenade featured familiar faces from Capitol
Hill and Hollywood, including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., Dennis Hopper; Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.; Michelle Lee;
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, and Jack Lemmon. Interesting
couples ranged from Dwight Yoakam and Bridget Fonda to Howard Baker
and Nancy Kassenbaum Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only in Washington _ and certainly only in booming
economic times _ would some of the loudest applause go to Alan
Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board. ``You da man,
Alan,'' shouted one onlooker as Greenspan passed, looking slightly
perplexed as he walked with his wife, NBC-TV correspondent Andrea
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Cronkite anchored the gala, which featured a videotaped
recap of the achievements of each honoree and then salutes from
their performing peers.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his outlaw brand of country music, Nelson has had some
well-publicized run-ins with the law over marijuana and with the
IRS over unpaid taxes. On this night, though, a lyrical Cronkite
called him ``a Texan whose Dust Bowl voice and songs in the neon
night made him a Walt Whitman of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows who he is _ and he knows he's from someplace _ and he
knows where that place is,'' observed Tommy Lee Jones, a fellow
Texan. ``That big bus is always going back to the Hill Country.''
</P>
<P>
   On this night, though, Nelson's tour bus, the Honeysuckle Rose,
was rolled onto the reinforced Kennedy Center stage for the segment
honoring the Red-Haired Stranger. Then Nelson was serenaded with
his own songs.
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam sang ``Blue Eyes Crying in the Rain'' and ``Hello
Walls.'' Lyle Lovett sang ``Night Life.'' Shelby Lynne sang
``Crazy'' and provoked some nervous giggles in the audience when
the TV monitors showed the Clintons in their box listening to the
lyrics ``crazy for trying and crazy for crying and crazy for loving
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Kris Kristofferson strolled out, declaring ``Of all of
Willie's songs, this is probably the best epitaph'' and launching
into ``On the Road Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Nelson earlier told reporters he was taking his bus back
to Texas and might just drape his seven-ribboned Kennedy Center
Honors medal from the rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   For this one evening, record producer Don Was put together ``The
Willie Nelson Tribute Band'' featuring himself on bass, Mickey
Raphael from Willie's ``Family'' on harmonica, G.E. Smith from
``Saturday Night Live'' and Reggie Young on guitar, Clifford Carter
on keyboards and Steve Jordan on guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the show include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Broadway salute to Kander and Ebb featuring songs from two
of their top hits, ``Cabaret'' and ``Chicago.'' Bebe Neuwirth
(familiar as Lillith from ``Cheers'' and ``Frazier'') and Chita
Rivera dance and sing a ``Chicago'' medley and Joel Gray and Liza
Minelli reprise their ``Cabaret'' roles for a nostalgic number.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sinbad's hilarious rag on Cosby. On an evening of effusive
praise, Sinbad's outrageous tales of sharing a foxhole in Vietnam
with Cosby, saving his life and then being treated abominably by
the beloved comedian had Cosby pretending to climb out of his box
seat and later waving a white flag of surrender.
</P>
<P>
   _ A heartfelt tribute to Previn by Mia Farrow, his ex-wife.
``Thanks for the music, Toots, and for the memories,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cronkite recalled Shirley Temple Black from the era of the
Great Depression as ``a little child who lit up the screen, lifted
up the nation and will always be America's princess.'' Later, Jack
Lemmon added his deadpan salute: ``The first drink I ever had was a
Shirley Temple.'' And Henry Kissinger remembered being secretary of
state while the former child star served as U.S. ambassador to
Ghana. Growing up, he had her movies dubbed in German, Kissinger
said, ``so I was surprised when she spoke English _ and without an
accent.''
</P>
<P>
   The show concludes with a bemused Cronkite sharing a stage with
scores of tap-dancing kids as the U.S. Air Force Band plays ``On
the Good Ship Lollipop'' and hundreds of red, white and blue
balloons fall from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
