<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee approves an
article of impeachment against President Clinton and begins debate
on the three other articles. (Carr/Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, expressing
``shame'' and ``profound remorse'' for his extramarital affair,
said Friday for the first time he was ``ready to accept rebuke and
censure'' from Congress. But it appeared that his statement, while
remarkable in the annals of presidential history, did not go far
enough to satisfy many of the Republican moderates undecided about
impeachment. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SONGWRITER-HARGROVE _ AUSTIN_ Local songwriter Larry Hargrove
says his song ``Leave Bill Clinton Alone,'' is getting national
airplay on radio stations all over the country, particularly in
Washington, D.C. NBC Washington doing a story tonight he says.
He'll also appear on Oprah and BET soon. (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) general news category.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ After eight weeks of testimony, what
are the chances of an out-of-court settlement that would curtail
the government's landmark antitrust suit against Microsoft Corp. A
look at the issues. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-FELTEN _ WASHINGTON _ The government releases
testimony Friday of its next expert witness in the Microsoft
antitrust trial, Princeton University computer expert Edward
Felten. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST _ WASHINGTON _ Aides brief reporters Friday on President
Clinton's trip. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-STAKES _ JERUSALEM _ For Palestinians, Clinton's visit
is being billed as another sign of sovereignty. It helps Yasser
Arafat dress up the peace deal signed in Washington last month _ a
deal that is not terribly popular. For Israelis, it looks like
Clinton is getting too cozy with Arafat. They might regret _ and
now some are denying _ that they asked for this visit. (Kaplow, Cox
News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SITES _ Capsules on some of the cities Clinton plans to
visit: Gaza, Bethlehem and a southern Israeli city, Ashkelon or
Ashdod, where he might speak. Suitable to run with a map. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SECURITY _ JERUSALEM _ One of the tightest security
regimes will have to get even tighter when President Clinton
arrives in Israel Saturday. ``We will see efforts of the kind we
haven't seen before because the issues are much more sharp now,''
said Carmi Gillon, Israeli security chief during the last Clinton
visit. The trip includes visits to Palestinian areas that have been
home to terrorists. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: (repeating from Thursday)
</P>
<P>
   MITCH-AFTERMATH _ TECUCIGALPA, Honduras _ This will be a grim
Christmas for residents of this poor Central American country,
devastated by one of the deadliest storms in the history of the
region. It's been over a month since Hurricane Mitch made its
rampage through Central America, leaving 11,000 people dead and
hundreds of thousands homeless. In Honduras alone, a country of 6
million people, more than 1 million have lost all of their worldly
possessions. The storm is gone, but reconstruction may take years.
Many relief organizations, such as Atlanta-based CARE, are working
around-the-clock to bring aid to this shattered country. But it's
an uphill battle. (Emling, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE _ After more than a year of legal wrangling over their
legal fees, the lawyers in Florida's tobacco lawsuit on Friday were
awarded exactly what they wanted in the first place: 25 percent of
the state's $12.7 billion settlement. And state officials also got
what they wanted, because the legal fees, which calculate to about
$3.4 billion on paper, will be paid by the tobacco industry.
Lawyers say they doubt they'll see all the money. As part of the
arbitration system, tobacco has agreed to pay just $500 million a
year toward legal fees. And after reaching a settlement with 46
states last month, that pool of money could be divided into many
slices of pie. (Hiaasen/Date/Waresh, Palm Beach Post). 35.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FEEBOX (Palm Beach Post). 2.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKEBOX _ Background of three arbitrators. (Palm Beach Post). 7
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT _ Five private attorneys are awarded $3.3
billion by a national arbitration committee looking at all the
nation's tobacco settlements to determine what all attorneys will
get. That's more than the 15 percent they signed on for and $1
billion more than both Gov. Bush, Attorney Gen.-elect John Cornyn
and several lawmakers said was reasonable. We examine the decision,
get reaction and explain what happens next. (McCarthy, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   REACT _ State officials said $2.3 billion was too much. So how
are they reacting to $3.3 billion? We get a range of reactions,
some might even be negative, to the lawyer's pay day. We also
explore what $3.3 billion buys these days. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   STATE-SCHOOL-ESCAPE _ Eleven teen-aged offenders, including two
violent crime offenders and some thieves and dopers, flee from the
Hamilton State School in Bryan. Big search is underway. New
questions are being raised about security. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MARS-PROBE _ CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ An unmanned probe blasted
off Friday from Cape Canaveral headed for Mars on a 9 1/2-month,
416-million mile journey to study the planet's thin, frigid
atmosphere and map its barren, rugged landscape. (Kleinberg, Palm
Beach Post). 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPUS-CRIME-SAFETY _ While investigating her children's college
choices, Georgia MacKowiak has asked college administrators about
campus safety. The 1998 Campus Security Act, signed by Clinton in
October, requires colleges and universities to make more i
information available about campus security. The Department of
Education is writing regulations to implement it and parents have
until Dec. 15 to submit comments. Advocates say they expect college
and universities to attempt to water down the law. (Shah, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CRIMEBOX _ very informative box on where to write, call or
e-mail comment on the law, how to get info on campus crime and Web
site for more information and links to copies of the law. (Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-JEWS _ Guacamole gracing the Passover plate, spurs for
making unleavened bread, and peddlers selling bananas are pieces of
Texas history not generally recorded in the annals of the Mexican
territory, the Republic and the state. This is Texas' Jewish
history, which dates back to the first Spanish explorers to step
foot on the land. Now, the stories of past and present-day Jewish
families are in ``Shalom Y'all - The Jewish Experience in Texas,''
a new exhibit at the Institute of Texan Cultures in San Antonio.
The institute is part of the University of Texas. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   JEWSBOX _ if you go box. (Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY _ With two Texas executions put on hold by federal
courts, what about the several that are upcoming _ including one
next Tuesday? Will there be any effect? Has Texas' death machine
been stilled for a time? (Ward, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   DEVELOPMENT-REPORT _ University of Texas report finds growing
substandard development statewide in suburbs. (Haurwitz, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-COTTAGE _ COCONUT GROVE, Fla. _ The cottage's famous
inhabitant departed a half-year ago, passing away after a
remarkable life of 108 years that saw her give a lasting nickname
to one of the world's most unique natural features while spawning
an international movement to rescue it from the predations of human
progress. Long before there was an environmental movement, Marjory
Stoneman Douglas' influential 1947 book, ``The Everglades: River of
Grass,'' led to the creation of Everglades National Park. Now the
Land Trust of Dade County, a private preservation group, is
gathering funds for the home's upkeep and to build a small
educational center nearby as a tribute to Douglas' life.
(MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SANTA-SUES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A man files a lawsuit against
Santas Plus, a contracting company, for what he believes are unfair
hiring policies. (Tanamachi, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
