<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5755 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV13-B     12-11 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ALL ADDS UP TO ANOTHER NEAR-MISS FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 13, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all have front seats for this train wreck.
</P>
<P>
   When impeachment goes to a vote Thursday or Friday, Bill
Clinton's survival in office is weighed on the same political scale
as the the fate of the Republican Party's prospects in the House,
Senate and presidential elections of November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why my sniffer tells me the House of Representatives
will ultimately decide to censure, but not impeach. The
straight-line partisan vote out of the House judiciary Committee
Friday pushes the issue to the next level, consideration by the
full 435-member House.
</P>
<P>
   Riding this runaway locmotive is the Republican leadership in
the House. They are playing Casey Jones, and there's a serious
train wreck in the offing. News reports and congressional leaders
of both parties suggested Friday that the vote of the full House
was still too close to call. Three Democrats from southern or
western states said they'd vote to force Clinton to undergo an
impeachment trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   If the other Democrats stand fast, then Clinton needs more than
a dozen House Republicans to break party ranks and save him from
becoming the second president to undergo an impeachment trial in
the Senate. My hunch is Clinton will get them.
</P>
<P>
   I think wiser GOP heads -- among the presidential candidates,
the senators and most of all the governors, who are best
innoculated against the ideological virus that infects the
congressional Republicans -- may conclude that impeachment is a
trap. The American public has already spoken twice on this
Clinton-Lewinsky mess, first in the rebuke of the GOP in last
November's election results, and then last week in an NBC-Wall
Street Journal poll.
</P>
<P>
   By 68 percent to 28, the sample shouted a loud ''No!'' to
impeachment. That did not deter the Republican phalanx on the House
Judiciary Committee, which voted in lockstep to impeach.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republican senators have to be privately aghast. If the
House sends the impeachment tar baby on to the Senate, there's no
way out: it'll be a full-blown trial, with the senators locked into
their chairs, speechless, pinned down by C-SPAN to a relentless
recital of the sexual peccadiloes that everyone knows about. No
serious nosecounter thinks there are anywhere near 67 votes in the
Senate to impeach. It takes a two-thirds vote, and if Clinton is
going to beat the rap anyway, why put him, the Senate, and the
country through the wringer, when he's out of office anyway in two
years?
</P>
<P>
   In the northeast, particularly, Republican officeholders regard
an impeachment trial with dread. A vote to impeach Clinton for a
northeastern congressman or senator could well be a career-ender.
And if he's not going to be removed from office in the end, who
begin this journey to political nowhere?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Chafee (R-RI) is 75, pondering whether to run for a
fifth term in two years; do you think he wants to confront an
impeachment trial between now and then? For the Sunbelt Solons who
harpoon Clinton with impunity in their states, it's much less of a
problem. But impeachment has the potential to turn the lights out
on Republicans at all levels in New England, New York, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Next time around, there are 19 GOP seats up for grabs, to 15
Democratic ones. A net gain of five, if the Democrats hold the
White House, puts the GOP leadership back in the minority, with
none of the current priviliges of holding hearings, timing votes,
and conducting unlimited investigations of Democratic officials
from the president on down.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's patented smooth talk has not served him well through
Monicagate, but his last-minute speech Friday in the Rose Garden,
timed to take the PR edge off the predictable 21-16 committee vote,
found Clinton at his sorrowfull-est. Bill is the best apologizer in
the business. He's had more experience than any other politician.
And he does it effectively.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Mendacity Capital of the world, there is a
move afoot to make the censure option a bit more palatable to
tenderfooted congressmen by slapping some kind of substantial fine
onto the paperwork. How do you put a price on honor? Is $300,000
appropriate? That's what Newt Gingrich had to pay for whatever it
was he got caught doing. Do Clinton's sins merit a $2 million
penalty? That was the fee former President Reagan got in 1989 for
flying to Japan for a quickie round of speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Is $4.5 million the appropriate amount? That's how much Gingrich
was offered in a two-book contract deal from Rupert Murdoch --
before Newt had to back out of the deal, claiming he absolutely,
positively had no idea that media mogul Murdoch had a keen interest
in telecommunications legislation Newt controlled.
</P>
<P>
   I think the notion of imposing a fine on a president for
Clinton's bad behavior is a nutty idea. The proper rebuke for such
lapses in good conduct is humiliation, which Clinton has had to
swallow in huge doses, and not some arbitrary fine, which Clinton
could pay off with one fund-raising party in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP lost five House seats last month, and goes into 2000
defending the thinnest House majority in 43 years. In this century,
the House changed hands only eight times. But in nine of the last
14 presidential elections, whichever side wins the White House has
picked up at least six House seats -- just what the Democrats need
to make Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.) the Speaker. Two dozen House
Republicans won by less than 10 percent of the vote, five of them
from California, where a Democratic tide is running deep.
</P>
<P>
   Three of those five California seats went Republican with less
than 50 percent of the total vote. Twenty Democrats overall won by
less than 10 percent. But in a presidential year like 2000, turnout
goes up, usually boosting Democrats' chances. So the Democrats can
recruit more robust candidates for contested seats, given their
excellent chance to take back the House. One more reason why I
think Clinton dodges the impeachment bullet? Social Security reform
is on the docket. Nothing happens there without bipartisanship. And
Clinton has this huge club in his closet: his ability to bludgeon
the GOP over Social Security. Summing up? I think Clinton has
another near-miss experience this week when the House votes.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
