</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AN IMPEACHMENT TRIAL, SENATORS ACT AS JURORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 13)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the House votes this week to impeach President
Clinton, the president would stand trial in the Senate with Chief
Justice William Rehnquist presiding and the 100 senators acting as
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   The rare Senate impeachment trial _ convened only once before to
judge a president _ would hear evidence and issue a verdict. If
two-thirds of the senators _ a total of 67 if all 100 were present
_ voted to convict the president, he would automatically be removed
from office.
</P>
<P>
   In a Senate with a 55-45 Republican majority, it's highly
unlikely that Clinton would be convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barring some bombshell, there's no chance at all the president
will be removed,'' said Ross Baker, a political science professor
at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said any Senate trial would stand in stark contrast to the
sharply partisan battle that took place in the House Judiciary
Committee, mainly because of the closer personal relationships in
the clubby Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tone is completely different,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   Senate impeachment trial guidelines envision the Senate chamber
turned into the ultimate federal courtroom, with designated House
members as ``managers'' or prosecutors. The White House would send
its legal team to represent Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rules require that the impeached president be
notified that he must ``appear before the Senate'' to answer the
charges, they allow legal surrogates to go in Clinton's place.
</P>
<P>
   The last _ and only _ president to be tried in the Senate made
no personal appearance. In 1868, President Andrew Johnson escaped
conviction and removal when the Senate fell one vote short of the
two-thirds requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The process begins when the House impeachment managers notify
the Senate that impeachment articles are finalized and the Senate
signifies it is ready to receive them.
</P>
<P>
   When House members bring the impeachment articles over, the
Senate's Sergeant at Arms will proclaim aloud: ``All persons are
commanded to keep silence, on pain of imprisonment, while the House
of Representatives is exhibiting to the Senate of the United States
articles of impeachment against'' Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rehnquist would have the power to delegate the
evidence-gathering role to a committee of senators, it is unlikely
that a presidential impeachment trial would be considered by
anything less than the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The rules specify that at 1 p.m. on the day after receiving the
impeachment articles, the Senate will start the trial and continue
``until final judgment shall be rendered.'' Trial days start
promptly at noon.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate impeachment trial resembles a criminal trial. Witnesses
are called, evidence is introduced and the chief justice rules on
lawyers' objections.
</P>
<P>
   The rules require that the senators _ acting as jurors _ sit
silently during the trial. However, unlike jurors in an ordinary
trial, the senators would be allowed to submit written questions
through the chief justice to witnesses and lawyers. Senators irked
by the chief justice's rulings on evidentiary or procedural matters
can call for votes to overturn them.
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of the trial, senators would vote on each
article of impeachment separately. The chief justice reads each
article and then calls on individual senators by name. Each then
stands and states ``guilty'' or ``not guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   How long such a trial might last has been the subject of much
debate and speculation. One Clinton attorney, Robert Bennett, said
on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' that a Senate trial could take up to
six months.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, however, has said it could
last anywhere from a few days to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, the Rutgers scholar, predicted the trial would last
somewhere in between those two estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be three weeks,'' he said. ``I may be
saying this more out of hope than conviction, but we won't see this
going on when the cherry blossoms come out'' in early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist, 74, has spent 26 years at the Supreme Court, 12 of
them as Chief Justice of the United States. Although he has no
experience presiding over a criminal trial, he has studied
impeachments and written a book about the process, ``Grand
Inquests.''
</P>
<P>
   The book focuses on the 1868 Senate trial of Johnson and the
1805 impeachment of Supreme Court Justice Samuel Chase. Like
Johnson, Chase narrowly averted removal when the Senate fell short
of the two-thirds majority necessary to remove Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist would have to fit his role as Senate trial judge
around his stewardship of the nation's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   Answering high school students' questions last week, Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor said she doubted the court's routine would be
affected by a Senate trial. ``But the chief justice's certainly
would be,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has conducted 14 impeachment trials, mostly of
federal judges. Seven of those resulted in conviction and removal.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent convictions involved judges Walter Nixon of
Mississippi and Alcee Hastings of Florida, both in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier criminal trial, Nixon was convicted of perjury and
sentenced to five years in prison. His impeachment and conviction
by the Senate removed him from a job he had been appointed to for
life.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was impeached and convicted, Hastings had been
acquitted of federal criminal charges that he conspired with a
lawyer friend to soften a racketeers' sentences in exchange for a
$150,000 bribe.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate nevertheless concluded there was enough evidence to
warrant his removal from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings, a Democrat, later was elected to the U.S. House of
Representatives, representing a district in South Florida. He has
been an outspoken defender of Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
