<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARR-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-11 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGTIME CLINTON ENEMY NEARS GOAL OF IMPEACHING CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House Judiciary Committee's approval
Friday of impeachment articles against the president, Republican
committee member Bob Barr passed another milestone in his long
battle to remove Bill Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   His fight began well before the name Monica Lewinsky emerged. In
fact, Barr first called for Clinton's ouster nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997 he wrote Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde
demanding an impeachment inquiry into allegations that the
president had violated campaign finance laws by illegally accepting
money from foreigners and by giving favorable government treatment
in return for campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Barr continues to argue that the president's alleged offenses
that arose from his affair with the former White House intern pale
in comparison with the alleged campaign finance violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we'll ever get him on all the crimes he has
committed, but the key thing is that we get him,'' he said in an
interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the president's most visible critics, Barr has used the
committee's impeachment hearings as a forum to try to convince the
American people that Clinton is guilty of more than lying about
sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be decades before history reveals the vastness of
President Clinton's abuse of power or the extent of the damage it
has wrought,'' he said Friday as the committee debated the
impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, 50, a former Central Intelligence Agency analyst and a
former U.S. attorney, was elected to Congress in 1994, riding a
wave of public sentiment against Clinton and big government.
</P>
<P>
   He became part of the GOP freshman class that helped wrest
control of Congress from the Democrats, who had held power in one
or both houses for four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, who hails from Georgia's conservative 7th Congressional
District outside Atlanta, quickly became a leader in a matter of
symbolic importance to conservatives: He led the drive to rename
Washington National Airport to Reagan National Airport.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 he also wrote the Defense of Marriage Act, which allows
states to refuse to recognize same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   He has opposed increasing the minimum wage, endorsed an
unsuccessful measure to make English the nation's official language
and voted for another unsuccessful bill to repeal the ban on sales
of certain semiautomatic assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most conservative members of Congress, he earned a 96
percent rating from the American Conservative Union for his 1997
voting record.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and its allies on Capitol Hill have eagerly
portrayed Barr as a right-winger out to get Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's part of the radical fringe element of the Republican
Party, and he is obsessed with impeaching the president,'' Rep.
John Lewis, D-Ga., a frequent adversary of Barr, said earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Barr maintains that he doesn't take the attacks personally,
saying they are ``part of the White House's scorched-earth policy
that it employs against anybody it feels is threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   He also argues that the reasons for his attacks against Clinton
are not partisan.``I wouldn't have done one thing differently if
this president had been a Republican,'' he said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that, as a U.S. attorney appointed by President
Ronald Reagan, he prosecuted Republican Rep. Pat Swindall of
Georgia on perjury charges in 1989, angering many conservatives.
Swindall was convicted and sentenced to a year in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he holds every public official, including himself, up
to the same standard of honor that he learned from his father, Bob
Sr., a graduate of the U.S. Military Academy at West Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my father, truth was something sacred, and that without it,
society could not function,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
