<HEADER>
A5778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-AMBITION-465&AMP;     12-11 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-AMBITION-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT CONUNDRUM FACES CONGRESSMEN ASPIRING TO HIGHER OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Del., Md., Del.)  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-DEBATE,
IMPEACH-MOOD, IMPEACH-BOUCHER, IMPEACH-GRAHAM, IMPEACH-WHITEWATER,
IMPEACH-MEDIA) 
 (bl) 
By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As he ponders the complex constitutional,
historical and moral issues at stake in impeaching a president,
Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., says he has tried to clear his mind of
``litter,'' including any thought of politics.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit like raking leaves in a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   For Lazio, who wants to run for the Senate in 2000, next week's
expected impeachment vote by the House is about as politically
charged as it gets. A vote to impeach is likely to please the
conservatives who dominate New York's Republican primaries, but
equally likely to incense Democrats who hold a 3 to 2 advantage in
the state's general electorate. A vote against impeachment might
lose him the primary and keep him from reaching the November
sweepstakes at all.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who will travel with Clinton to Israel on Saturday as a
representative of the House Republican leadership, contends that he
has not been lobbied by either side in the debate and has not
factored electoral calculations into his deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   But he does not deny that political pressures are swirling about
him. ``People advise you on every side of this issue and confuse
you about the political dimensions of the vote,'' he said in an
interview. ``If you allow that to happen, you can be completely
paralyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is far from alone in his conundrum. In states like
Maryland, Delaware and New Jersey, House members who are
contemplating running for statewide offices like the Senate must
suddenly weigh the broader political fallout of their impeachment
votes. For each member, a decision that receives plaudits from the
hometown crowd might prompt catcalls from a statewide audience.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lazio, many are moderate Republicans from Northeastern
states where Clinton remains popular and impeachment is not. They
are people like Rep. Constance Morella of Maryland and Rep. Michael
Castle of Delaware, who are each thinking of running for the Senate
in 2000 in states where Democrats outnumber Republicans. Both have
said they remain undecided on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Rep. Robert Franks, a potential candidate for
governor in New Jersey, where Democrats are closely watching his
every move. ``We would make him sorely regret casting a vote for
impeachment,'' said Rick Thigpen, executive director of the New
Jersey state Democratic committee. Franks has said he is leaning
toward voting for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, where a bevy of prominent politicians from both
parties are considering running for Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan's
seat when he retires in 2000, two potential Republican contenders
have already come out against impeachment: Rep. Peter King of Long
Island and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City. Both said
political considerations played no role in their decisions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lazio, whose Suffolk County district voted overwhelmingly for
Clinton in 1996, has spent much of his three terms weaving a record
that could appeal to New York's raucously diverse electorate, which
tends to be conservative in upstate rural regions and moderate to
liberal in the New York City metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   He often votes with moderates and liberals on abortion and the
environment, but supports the kinds of tax cuts businesses like. He
has fought his own leadership to protect spending for the arts, but
has also become a close ally of the staunchly conservative House
majority leader, Dick Armey of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts say that the importance of impeachment
is likely to dim in voters' minds by the 2000 elections. But many
other analysts say that because Lazio is not well known, his
impeachment vote could become the most vivid thing people remember
about him, particularly if impeachment passes the House and leads
to a trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he has tried to blot out political concerns by
focusing on two broader issues: whether Clinton has lost so much
credibility that he can no longer govern effectively; and whether
the House would be setting the right precedent for future
Congresses if it approves impeachment against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people, and I am one, who are concerned about the
slippery slope of denigrating what the truth is,'' he said. ``One
of the questions in my mind is, `Have we thrown the towel in on
public ethics? Do we have respect for the truth?'''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has twice before faced votes that he thought might
imperil his political future: when he voted for the North American
Free Trade Agreement, which angered labor unions, and when he voted
for a ban on assault weapons, which riled the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anything I've learned from these experience, it is
you just have to clear your head and make the most decent, solid,
right decision that you can make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he still believed the president has not owned up to
his misleading statements about his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
The president would help himself with wavering members of Congress,
Lazio said, if he simply used two words: ``I lied.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is clarity with the word,'' Lazio said, adding that he
would tell the president his feelings on the trip to Israel, if
asked. ``There is in the end some honesty with the word. It's
almost a matter of dignity for the office, the Congress and the
American people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
