<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FACE A ROUGH PATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins have played just 10 games in the past 29
days.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 19 days, they will play 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   And that's something coach Pat Burns welcomes. So does Hal Gill.
And Kyle McLaren makes three.
</P>
<P>
   The season's busiest stretch begins Saturday night at the
FleetCenter, where the Bruins entertain the Buffalo Sabres in a key
Eastern Conference game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after three days off, the Bruins really put the pedal to
the metal. From Wednesday, when they're in Detroit, to Dec. 31,
when they're in Dallas, they play for keeps nine times.
</P>
<P>
   Gone for the rest of the season are those stretches in which the
Bruins would have three or four days off between games. That's
happened six times already this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing with a certain confidence (and the Bruins
are oozing it during their 6-0-2 streak), when you practice a lot,
the message sometimes just doesn't get there,'' said Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking for things you want to work with _ and there's
always things you have to work on _ but I think the players feel
sometimes that things are going well, so why are we doing this
again? There's a little bit of human nauture involved in there,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have started slowly the past two games against
Pittsburgh and Carolina after layoffs of three and four days, and
Burns warns against that happening against Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we start late (Saturday), we're done,'' he said. ``We have
to come out at the drop of the puck. Buffalo is playing so
confident right now. (Dominik) Hasek is, well, what more can you
say? He's one of the top (goalies). This is the two best defensive
teams going at it, and it's going to be inch for inch and very
tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we pack the tents, go home, and give them the 2
points if Buffalo scores a quick goal. But it puts you in a
position where you're going to have to battle back. It's very
important that at the drop of the puck, everybody's ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill is ready for more of the real stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to play back-to-back too often,'' he said,
``but you want to get in a rhythm and get out there. A lot of times
when you're practicing too long, you get, you know, not lazy, but
you're not as sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing every other day, or back-to-back, you get
into a rhythm and you feel good out there. The practices aren't
that bad, either. You just go out there, work up a good sweat, and
you're ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill says the recent unbeaten streak (the Bruins haven't lost
since Nov. 14) has the team playing with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good about what's happening,'' he said. ``(Against
Carolina) we came out with a good win. We had a bad first period,
but we had that confidence and knew we could win. We didn't have
any doubts in our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren, like Gill, prefers the upcoming schedule to what's been
played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, especially when you're on a roll,'' said McLaren. ``You
want to keep playing games. No team wants to be sitting around too
long like we have. The more games, the better, because then you
really have no time to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going mentally. It's good, like I said,
especially when you're on a roll. All you want to do is keep
playing games to keep the ball rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren loves what he sees the Bruins doing lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a patient team and you've seen the last few games that
we're going to stick around right to the end of the third period.
This team is playing with a lot of confidence, and I think a lot of
that comes from our goaltending. It's been brilliant. Both
goaltenders. It starts from the back up. The chemistry is there,
and with that comes the confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   A four-week unbeaten streak helps, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
