<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SULLIVAN OUT, PATRIOTS JUGGLE THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Todd Collins was explaining how it's not all
that strenuous ``to run downfield on the special teams and then go
out on the next play and take your position at linebacker'' when
Marty Moore reached his locker, next to Collins's.
</P>
<P>
   Moore overheard Collins's last words: ``You just have to suck it
up. You're in condition throughout the season and throughout the
year. It's not that big a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   A media member baited Moore, saying his next-door neighbor was
saying that just about any football player could do what Moore was
forced to do last week in Pittsburgh. Moore listened intently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw,'' said Moore, ``you just have to catch your breath. As
long as I catch my breath, I'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' said Collins, backtracking graciously, ``this guy had to
play every (special-teams) play last week and then go out for the
next play. When I had to do it, I was only on one special teams.
Marty's on all four of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The two bantered.
</P>
<P>
   ``So me and Todd are going to rotate (Sunday) and keep each
other fresh,'' said Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Collins. ``I'll have the oxygen tank ready for
Marty.''
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of Ted Johnson for the season last Sunday, the
Patriots are in the midst of a new linebacking plan, one that is
unusual because of the rotation that will be required.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, an outside linebacker, will rotate with Moore at middle
linebacker and also fill in for Tedy Bruschi at left outside
linebacker. Moore, a special-teams stalwart, will continue on all
four special teams (kickoff returns and kickoff coverage, punt
returns and punt coverage) but also will see the bulk of the work
at middle linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Collins played inside linebacker, the Patriots
were in a 3-4 defense and his partner on the inside ``was Vincent
(Brown).'' That long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Moore started a game at middle linebacker was way
back when . . . when? ``I think it was in 1995 . . . in San
Francisco,'' said Moore. ``Then I played the game against Denver
(Oct. 8). It's been a while.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm not going to tell you who's going to start
yet,'' coach Pete Carroll said. ``But right now Marty's a bit ahead
of Todd in making the calls and doing all the things he needs to do
at the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that, we're still going to rotate them because I still
want Marty to be in on all the special teams. It's going to take a
couple of weeks before Marty really feels comfortable there, but
he'll do fine. But right now I think Marty's a notch ahead of Todd
assignmentwise and in his ability to make all the calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, an inside linebacker in college (``We played a 3-4
defense''), played that position for New England in a 3-4 defense,
but Bill Parcells switched him outside in 1995 after Collins took a
year off from football. ``Making the calls (in the huddle) is no
big thing,'' said Collins, ``but your responsibilities are so
different in the middle from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Patriot defense now is a 4-3, with four linemen and
three linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Collins and Moore expect that Collins will be at middle
linebacker on the first play or two after a Patriot punt or
kickoff, allowing Moore time to rest from his special-teams duties,
but then Moore will replace him. Collins also expects that he will
be asked to spell Bruschi at times at the outside spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's how we're going to work it,'' said Moore.
``Right after a kickoff, Todd's going to be in there and then I'm
going to come in after that. It's kind of up to the coaches on how
they want to rotate us and up to Todd and me on how we want to
catch our breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's responsibilities on kickoffs and punts are, as he put
it, ``just get to the ball.'' Which, of course, is precisely the
responsibility of the middle linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   There can be at least 20 special-teams plays a game, and with
the added load of taking most snaps on defense, ``I'm just going to
have to get ready for all the work,'' said Moore. ``But I'm
ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
