<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5790 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-COTTAGE12-     12-11 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-COTTAGE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Famous author's cottage gets facelift
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCONUT GROVE, Fla. _ Sunlight filters through the dense canopy
of Marjory Stoneman Douglas' rain forest of a back yard, dappling
the brown fallen leaves and dense green undergrowth.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing stirs but the hint of a Biscayne Bay breeze, that and
the plop of a few stray drops from fat leaves far overhead, remnant
of a South Florida morning shower.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the tiny English-style cottage, light streams through the
east-facing windows, illuminating the plank floor, the faded couch
and the simple wicker chairs arranged around a comfortably worn
rug.
</P>
<P>
   The cottage's famous inhabitant departed a half-year ago,
passing away after a remarkable life of 108 years that saw her give
a lasting nickname to one of the world's most unique natural
features while spawning an international movement to rescue it from
the predations of human progress.
</P>
<P>
   Long before there was an environmental movement, Douglas'
influential 1947 book, ``The Everglades: River of Grass,'' led to
the creation of Everglades National Park. Her insights into the
inter-connected web of the giant swamp's life predated the most
basic tenets of what has become modern environmental consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas penned the work _ and her other books _ at the sturdy
desk in one corner of the modest cottage she built in 1926. She
lived there, uninterrupted, for 72 years until her death in May.
</P>
<P>
   She had sold the 1,000-square-foot bungalow and the small
surrounding lot to the state in 1990, with the understanding that
she could live there until her death. Now the Land Trust of Dade
County, a private preservation group, is gathering funds for the
home's upkeep and to build a small educational center nearby as a
tribute to Douglas' life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to restore the interior space of the house, which
is very small,'' said Sallye Jude, president of the trust. ``There
will be limited visitation by appointment because the house is so
small.''
</P>
<P>
   The Douglas home is located in the heart of Miami's charming
Coconut Grove section, a half-mile up the slope from Biscayne Bay
in an area where dense vegetation still gives a hint of the
primeval Florida that Douglas loved.
</P>
<P>
   When she built it, Miami was already a boom town thriving with
tourists, but far smaller than the sprawling metropolis of today.
Over the years the tide of development washed over Coconut Grove
and Douglas' cottage and on to the borders of the Everglades, 20
miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas was a character, even somewhat eccentric, say those who
knew her. Daughter of one of the founders of the Miami Herald
newspaper, she divorced in her 20s, when such things were a
scandal. She then carved out a career as a writer, first at the
newspaper, and later on her own, writing novels, plays and
nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Her home is now surrounded by million-dollar mansions in one of
Miami's most prominent neighborhoods. It sits, slightly bedraggled,
far back on a grassy lot, shaded by towering trees roped with thick
green vines. There is no driveway because Douglas didn't drive.
</P>
<P>
   Duck beneath the overhanging bushes, slip past the house to
Douglas' back yard and the vegetation grows in unchecked riot, a
hint of what the area resembled when only Indians called it home.
</P>
<P>
   But only a hint: 20 yards from Douglas' back patio shimmers the
blue water of her back-lot neighbor's swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the house is something of an oasis, a shrine that
breathes with the spirit of its departed master.
</P>
<P>
   Its cedar shingles are tawny with moss, its white stucco walls
decorated with spalted wooden planks. The eaves curve down over the
doors and windows with such exaggeration they give the feel of a
house for little people in some English fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the house is basically one big living room with
head-high bookshelves lining one wall, the desk in one corner and a
heavy table on the opposite wall. On the table is a driftwood
sculpture on which perch two carved flamingos. Stuck on other knobs
are two of Douglas' famous hats, wide-brimmed and tied with white
sashes.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the house consists of two tiny bedrooms, an equally
tiny kitchen with a hot plate _ no stove because Douglas liked to
eat out, not cook _ and a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jefferson's Monticello or Faulkner's Rowan Oak, the house
reflects its master. With Douglas, that means simplicity: she was
known for her straight-forward candor, her imperviousness to the
pretensions of the high and mighty of business or politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marjory was a very private person,'' Jude said. ``The
instruction she gave the architect when she built the house was, `I
want something functional.'''
</P>
<P>
   The house will now be preserved as a monument to her life and
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the education center is expected to take about a year,
with an opening sometime in late 1999. It is doubtful that the home
itself will be open to the general public except by appointment,
although there may be a walkway to allow visitors to peer in
through the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors may appreciate it best if they arrive on a quiet
morning with few others around. Stand in the silence and you can
almost see the tiny figure treading the plank floor, gazing out the
windows into the streaming light, embracing the beauty of the
nature she so loved.
</P>
<P>
   Donations for the education center and the home's upkeep may be
sent to:
</P>
<P>
   Marjory Stoneman Douglas/Everglades House
</P>
<P>
   Land Trust of Dade County
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Box 331811
</P>
<P>
   Coconut Grove, FL 33233-1811
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
