<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE TO WEAR DIFFERENT CAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Drew Bledsoe confirmed Friday that doctors
inserted pins into the top joint of his broken right index finger
Tuesday at Massachusetts General Hospital. The Patriots quarterback
said the procedure was performed because his finger ``wasn't
healing because the bone had displaced.''
</P>
<P>
   He took snaps with his left hand Friday and did not throw the
ball, on doctors' orders. When asked if he knew whether he would be
able to pass effectively Sunday against the Rams, he laughed off
the question, saying, ``I don't . . . but I don't see how it could
be worse. But I feel confident. It's at least as good as last week,
and probably better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he would wear a ``long splint'' in Sunday's game,
one that covers the top of his finger as well as the knuckle area.
He wore a shorter splint in the game against Buffalo and for the
first three quarters in Pittsburgh last Sunday but was forced to go
to a longer splint when he lost feeling in the top of his finger at
the start of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing now is that that last joint is going to heal in
its proper place,'' said Bledsoe. Inserting two pins into the top
of his finger, he said, effectively results ``in an interior
splint. This will hold it in place so that it heals properly and
heals quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said it might have been wiser to have worn a longer
splint from the start, ``but I asked the doctors to cut it down so
I could have more feeling'' at the tip of his finger to aid his
passing touch.
</P>
<P>
   As for the exact procedure, Bledsoe described it this way:
``They went into the top of the finger and stuck a couple of pins
in there to hold the two fragments (of bone) in place. They said it
was going to be a splint, just that the splint is inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
