<P>
   Here are the top Times Express stories planned for Saturday,
Dec. 12. The N.Y. Times News Service Night Supervisor is Henry
Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail: hewarn(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-IMPEACH (Washington) _ After a passionate debate that was at
turns grave, partisan and even sorrowful, the House Judiciary
Committee votes along party lines to impeach President Clinton. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton speaks to
the people before committee takes vote on the four impeachment
articles. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Why, when the people have made
limpidly clear their view that Clinton should not be impeached _
polls, election _ do the Republicans press on. A news analysis by
R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-PINOCHET (London) _ The former Chilean dictator is forced to
appear in a British court for an extradition hearing on the Spanish
charges against him. The general says he recognizes no court
outside of Chile. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-BOMB (Undated) _ German court ruling Friday that high-level
embassy bombing suspect being held there can be extradited to the
U.S. raises tricky questions for prosecutors here. They have said
they want the death penalty for lower-level suspects, but to get
the suspect from Germany, they have to promise no death penalty. By
Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-TOBACCO-LAWYERS (Undated) _ An arbitration panel Friday
handed out the biggest legal fees in this country's history,
awarding $8.1 billion to plaintiffs' lawyers hired by three states
that had sued the tobacco companies over health care costs related
to smoking. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-IMPEACH-CENSURE (Washington) _ What is the Republican
leadership position on censure; where are Livingston and Lott; who
is the White House talking to? By Eric Schmidt and John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-SCI-MARS (Kennedy Space Center, Fla.) _ The Mars climate
orbiter is launched from Cape Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-GERMANY-SCHROEDER (Berlin) _ After assuring its allies that
it represents continuity, the new government of Gerhard Schroeder
is using a bold, often challenging directness that marks a radical
departure from other post-war German administrations. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-EUROPE-SUMMIT (Vienna) _ The European Union summit
conference opens with a squabble over how much expansion will cost
and who pays what. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-PUERTO-POLITICS (San Juan) _ For the first time in decades,
there is a real possibility of Puerto Rico joining the union as a
state. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-NEPAL-GODDESS (Katmandu) _ The little girl became Nepal's
official living goddess the day before she turned 4, a grandly
ceremonial event that made her parents enormously proud, for a
divine spirit was about to enter their daughter and she would be
worshiped by the nation, carried around on a gilded chariot and
bowed down to, even by the King. But now, seven years later, her
parents, Amrit and Namita Shakya, are sorry they allowed their girl
to be plucked from obscurity and turned into the ornately costumed
and fussily pampered goddess, the Royal Kumari. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
