<SLUG> BC-HOT-TIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TICKING OFF TRENDY TIMEKEEPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ever notice how the December issues of fashion
mags are always filled with the faces of time? Some watchmakers
feature their wares next to the faces of supermodels like Cindy
Crawford, others let the wristwatches stand alone as works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, a watch fits all sizes. Another good thing: They're
can be easily exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   On that timely subject, Cartier has reintroduced its now-famous
Santos watch created by Louis Cartier for aviator Alberto
Santos-Dumont in 1904. It was the first wristwatch, still looks
stylish in steel and gold, and is available at Cartier and Saks
Fifth Avenue stores in Beverly Hills for $3,100.
</P>
<P>
   Too pricey? Don't get ticked off.
</P>
<P>
   Miz Hot Tips discovered Anne Klein has several new styles for
the holidays, perhaps inspired by the Santos, for about $150. And
Fossil, known for retro designs packaged in tin boxes, has its own
version of a sporty steel and gold-toned watch (it looks more like
a Rolex) priced under $100. Both brands are available at
fashion-savvy stores like Robinsons-May and Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a trendie, you probably know the G-Shock watch has
cooled down. Now it's the Spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Made by Pulsar, Spoon watches have all kinds of cool novelties,
including monitor-screen-shaped dial openings, and red display
lights; and coming soon will be more insane styles, including a
model that can scroll up to 100 different messages across the dial.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon fans include the cast members of ``Clueless,'' ``Moesha,''
and ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' as well as actors Vivica Fox, Teri Hatcher,
Jack Nicholson and Billy Zane. Spoons are also hot with bands Third
Eye Blind, No Doubt, The Crystal Method, Eve 6 and Pharcyde.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find Spoons for $100 to $175 at American Rag and Fred
Segal in Los Angeles, and Barneys in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't seen a single celeb wearing one, but Miz Hot Tips
thinks the new Scooby-Doo watch by Armitron is doggone cute for
only $20. For the totally clueless, Scooby-Doo is a cartoon that's
been on the tube since 1969 and features a dog who helps his humans
chase ghosts and bad guys. Look for it in adult- and kid-size
versions at most department stores.
</P>
<P>
   PURSE PANACHE: Knowing that lottery winners often have to work
hard at spending their big bucks, Miz Hot Tips shopped around and
found something worthy. It's Vivian Alexander's bejeweled and
enameled evening bags made from real ostrich eggs (they look like
Faberge eggs), so you know it's too small for a cell phone and
compact. But hey, everyone will ooh and ahh over it, which has
gotta be worth the $6,000 you'll pay at the David Orgell store in
Beverly Hills. P.S.: They do have a few priced at $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   WARM AND FUZZY: By now, you've noticed Miz Hot Tips rarely gives
practical tips, but if you really do need a hot-water bottle, read
on. Saks Fifth Avenue has a faux fur model for $75 that looks like
real mink.
</P>
<P>
   THE OFFICE BUZZ: Being in the loop is such a big deal these
days. It requires constant back watching, major suck-up skills, and
fluency in corporate jargon and doublespeak. For the latter,
consider ``The Buzzword Bingo Book'' (Villard; $9.95) as your
textbook.
</P>
<P>
   The new paperback by Lara Stein and Benjamin Yoskovitz is a fun
read with a glossary of terms you'll want to tackle. Among them are
``heritage,'' which means a company's cultural history, otherwise
known as baggage; and ``Hollywired,'' which means the impending
mega-marriage of interactive technology and the entertainment
industry. Miz Hot Tips' personal fave is ``idea hamster,'' a person
who drives others crazy because they're always in hyperdrive with
tons of ideas to share at staff meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
