<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT MAY TAKE OVER SECOND LARGE BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By SHERLY WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The government appears to be on the verge of
nationalizing a second large Japanese bank, Nippon Credit Bank, in
a move that may foreshadow a wider cleanup of the banking system
and a tougher stance by financial authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government has been under pressure to be more
assertive in confronting the country's economic troubles and
banking crisis, and a takeover of Nippon Credit, which has about
$100 billion in assets, would presumably be welcomed by the
financial community as a sign that the authorities will move more
decisively to resolve their banking problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Credit has resisted the move, but the government can
effectively force it to accept nationalization.
</P>
<P>
   If the government chooses to take control of Nippon Credit, it
would be the second bank taken over. The authorities in October
nationalized Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, which is about twice
the size of Nippon Credit. A decision on the Nippon Credit takeover
could come over the weekend, according to a senior government
official who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Both Nippon Credit and the government publicly denied the move
Friday. Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told reporters that he had
heard nothing about the government's leaning toward nationalizing
Nippon Credit.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Credit's financial troubles have been well known for more
than a year, and by some estimates its bad debts are so large that
if accounted for by the rules they would put the bank into
insolvency. Just over a year ago, Nippon Credit was rescued with an
injection of nearly $2.5 billion from the Bank of Japan and a
collection of Japanese financial institutions. Then this March, the
bank received a further $510 million in public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial officials may use the aid as leverage to push for
stiffer standards for banks' financial cushions against loan
losses. Many financial experts argue that the amount of public
funds injected into the banking system in March was too little to
alleviate the banks' capital adequacy problems, and this may
strengthen the hand of officials who want the banks to accept more
public funds under the $510 billion bailout program set up in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Credit has apparently fiercely resisted nationalization,
but it appears that the bank may lose the battle.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent audit of Nippon Credit, the Financial Supervisory
Agency, which inspects banks, discovered that the bank did not have
enough in reserve to cover the possible loan losses already on its
books, according to a report by the Kyodo News Service. The news
service said the audit showed Nippon Credit officials had
exaggerated the value of real estate held as collateral for the
loans. The government said the agency's definition of bad loans was
much stricter than that of the bank.
</P>
<P>
   In its earnings report for the six months ended Sept. 30, Nippon
Credit said bad loans amounted to $15 billion, but other estimates
put the figure at $27 billion, according to Japanese news reports.
Nippon Credit, which has pulled out of international business, said
it easily met government rules for capital adequacy for domestic
banks. It has also said that by the end of the current fiscal year
on March 31, 1999, it will write off bad loans worth $6.3 billion,
a sum that is about equivalent to its capital base.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of nationalization might be crucial in avoiding
marketwide jitters. The benchmark Nikkei average of 225 stocks has
been buoyant in recent weeks, and even as reports about the
possible nationalization arose near the close of the trading
session, Nippon Credit's stock price held its own. It ended Friday
at 158 yen, down 5 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government is unlikely to pay the market price, Nippon
Credit's shares are expected to plunge. But because the bank's
problems were well known, and because it would be the second
government bank takeover, a nationalization of Nippon Credit might
not precipitate a stock market plunge, as happened in the case of
Long-Term Credit.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Credit's stock price tumbled last spring after rumors
arose that it might face challenges in meeting its financing needs.
The jitters spilled over to other Japanese banks, provoking a
crisis of confidence that eventually forced the government to draw
up its plan to stabilize the banking system, including, if needed,
putting banks under temporary state control. Nippon Credit,
however, has faced no major financing shortages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
