<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLOCROSS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEKEND WARRIOR: CYCLOCROSS, FOR PRAISE AND EXHAUSTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(gm) 
 By ANDREA KANNAPELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is something magical about complete ignorance of a sport.
No one has any expectations of your performance, including
yourself. Everything is fresh and new. Even the pain.
</P>
<P>
   I renewed my acquaintance with that magic on a recent sparkling
weekend in the Catskills, with my first ever cyclocross race.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclocross (known simply as ``cross'' to its devotees) is one of
those bizarre sports that blend seemingly unblendable activities,
like the Olympic biathlon combination of cross-country skiing and
target shooting. In this case, it's a merger of cycling and
hurdling. Basically participants ride a largely off-road circuit of
rock, grass and mud. Races consist of loops of the circuit for some
predetermined period of time, usually 45 minutes or an hour. When
the time is up, a bell rings and the racers give all they have left
for one last lap.
</P>
<P>
   Some riders use mountain bikes, but purists ride modified road
bikes equipped with nubbly but still narrow tires. Real cross bikes
are faster than any mountain bike and far more difficult to control
on steep, slippery downhills.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only half of this sport.
</P>
<P>
   The other half is that low barriers like those in a steeplechase
litter the course. Accomplished riders approach the obstacles at
full speed, brake at the last second, dismount running and raise
the bike over their shoulders, leap like gazelles over the
barriers, fluidly put the bike back down and dash along next to it
until still in one smooth, unbroken flow of motion they jump, kick
their heels up behind them, and then bring their legs forward in a
V that lands them in the saddle, feet pedaling instantaneously.
</P>
<P>
   And what do 38-year-old absolute beginners do, I wondered, as my
determination to try cross solidified with the waning of both the
year and my athletic energy.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, I discovered just minutes into my race, was: brake
just in time to avoid hitting the barrier (usually). Heave the bike
any old way, forgetting the clever grip that makes the lift easier.
Raise one exhausted leg over the obstacle. Follow with the other.
Try not to trip. Try not to curse and/or grunt too loudly. Put the
bike down. Fling a leg over and slam the pedal against the shin.
Grunt and/or curse at high volume. Find the pedal and push off.
Repeat. I hadn't thought to be biking this late in the season. All
things considered, the year already ranked as terrific for cycling,
with a week of bike camping in Montana and a personal record of
three centuries. (OK, one was a metric century: 100 kilometers,
only 60 miles. But still.)
</P>
<P>
   And I had finished up or thought I had with a late-season bike
weekend at a sports training center in the Catskills, which added a
certain finesse to my group riding, a little snap to my turns, some
vigor in my accelerations. Then the bike mavens at the place, Mike
Fraysse's Sports Resort in Glen Spey, N.Y., (914-856-3335) started
talking about cyclocross.
</P>
<P>
   Fraysse (rhymes with crazy) is a manic two-time Olympic cycling
coach whose mind is as full of cycling expertise, gossip and trivia
as his Victorian mansion is with historic cycling paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran racer, Fraysse said cyclocross was born in Europe as a
training tool for road racers to maintain strength through the
off-season, when snow, ice and wind-chill kept them off their usual
routes. Straining their bikes over grass and through muddy fields,
and jumping off to carry them over unridable patches, kept riders
warm and toned. And the intensity of the effort required meant that
an hour or so of cyclocross would be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the format was popular enough to attract racers, and in
1950 the first World Championships were held in Paris. In the
1970s, cyclocross racing began taking off in the United States, but
the mountain biking craze of the last decade or so stole some of
its thunder. According to the U.S. Cycling Federation, its
popularity is returning, particularly in the Northeast, the
Northwest and in Northern California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1848EST &QL; 
