<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5814 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-APOLOGY-HNS &LR;      12-11 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-APOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAKES FRESH APOLOGY AS IMPEACHMENT DRIVE PROCEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton expressed fresh regret Friday for
his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair but his last-ditch
remorse failed to stop the House Judiciary Committee from voting
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, standing in the twilight in the Rose Garden of the
White House, said that he was ``profoundly sorry'' for words and
deeds that brought the nation to the brink of the first impeachment
trial in the Senate since the 1860s.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led House Judiciary Committee never broke stride,
voting 21-16 along party lines just minutes after Clinton's address
to approve the first of four articles of impeachment against the
second-term president.
</P>
<P>
   Republican members of the panel said they were unimpressed by
Clinton's remarks, particularly since the president failed to
publicly admit that he had lied in sworn testimony _ the crux of
the GOP case for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, said the president's remarks would
not have ``any effect'' on the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``continues to refuse to take responsibility for actions
that could put him in criminal jeopardy,'' Chabot said. ``What the
president really should do for this country is resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., who called for Clinton's ouster long
before impeachment proceedings began last month, said that Clinton
``basically continues to thumb his nose at the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr added: ``The juxtaposition of sitting here on the verge of
voting on impeachment while the president continued to dance around
the issue was surrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats disagreed. Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., who has
argued that Clinton's infractions are not grounds for impeachment,
said the president made ``a fulsome apology'' that would resonate
well with the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``won't be satisfied with this'' because Clinton has
not admitted lying under oath, Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., said he remained convinced that the
21 Republicans on the Judiciary Committee have been planning to
``vote to impeach since September.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee's action set the stage for House
consideration of impeachment next week. Clinton was scheduled to
leave Washington early Saturday for a four-day trip to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the president and his senior aides would
spend the coming days privately urging moderate Republicans to
reject the Judiciary Committee's recommendation that the House vote
to impeach Clinton and refer the case to the Senate for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stood before the White House colonnade outside the Oval
Office to offer his latest expression of regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want the American people to know, what I want the
Congress to know, is that I am profoundly sorry for all I have done
wrong in words and deeds,'' Clinton said, his eyes rimmed red and
welling with what appeared to be tears. ``I never should have
misled the country, the Congress, my friends or my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I would have given anything to go back and undo
what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was ``ready to accept'' a ``rebuke and censure''
by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention the word ``impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he admit to lying before a federal grand jury in
testimony on Aug. 17 or in a civil deposition in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment case in January.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, Clinton held up his private pain within his
family as a stiffer form of punishment for having carried on an
extramarital affair than anything impending from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painful though the condemnation of the Congress would be, it
would pale in comparison to the consequences of the pain I have
caused my family,'' Clinton said, biting his lip. ``There is no
greater agony.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been refining his apology to the nation ever since
an angry Aug. 17 nationally televised address after more than four
hours of grueling videotaped testimony before the grand jury called
by special prosecutor Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In that first admission, Clinton abandoned eight months of
denials to admit for the first time that he had carried on a
relationship with Lewinsky that was ``not appropriate _ in fact it
was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I misled people, including even my wife. I
deeply regret that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton revised his apology on Aug. 28 during a 12-day vacation
on Martha's Vineyard, Mass., when he told a predominantly
African-American congregation at a local church: ``All of you know
I'm having to become quite an expert in this business of asking for
forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was forced to return to the issue during a joint news
conference with Russian President Boris Yeltsin in Moscow on Sept.
2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have acknowledged that I made a mistake, said that I
regretted it, asked to be forgiven, spent a lot of very valuable
time with my family in the last couple of weeks and said I was
going back to work,'' Clinton replied to a question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, during a photo session with Irish Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern in Dublin, Clinton reacted to a condemnation of his
behavior by a prominent Democratic ally, Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already said that I made a bad mistake, it was
indefensible and I'm sorry about it.'' It was the first time that
Clinton used the word ``sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 9 in Orlando, Fla., Clinton addressed Democratic
donors, saying: ``I ask you for your understanding, for your
forgiveness.'' Clinton added: ``I also let you down and I let my
family down and I let this country down. But I'm trying to make it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton apologized in person to his Cabinet at a private meeting
on Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shared his feelings and apologized to us personally,''
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 11, Clinton offered one of his most dramatic apologies
to religious leaders gathered in the East Room of the White House
for an annual prayer breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a fancy way to say that I have
sinned,'' Clinton said, his eyes welling with tears. ``It is
important to me that everybody who has been hurt know that the
sorrow that I feel is genuine _ first and most important for my
family. Also my friends, my staff, my Cabinet, Monica Lewinsky and
her family and the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks on Sept. 11 were the first time that the president
mentioned Lewinsky by name in his apologies.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Rose Garden appearance Friday, Clinton's most recent
mention of forgiveness came on Tuesday when he joked that Sen. Dale
Bumpers, D-Ark., also a former governor of Arkansas, always
introduced Clinton as only ``the second best'' governor of
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to forgive him _ for one thing I'm in this sort of
forgiveness mode,'' Clinton said. ``And I forgive him because it's
probably true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
