<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WHITEWATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT ARTICLES SCARCELY MENTION WHITEWATER
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-DEBATE,
IMPEACH-MOOD, IMPEACH-BOUCHER, IMPEACH-GRAHAM, IMPEACH-AMBITION,
IMPEACH-NETWORKS, IMPEACH-MEDIA) 
 (bl) 
By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The four articles of impeachment being considered
by the House Judiciary Committee contain only the barest hint of
the long-running investigation into the role of President Clinton
and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, in a complicated Arkansas
real-estate deal.
</P>
<P>
   The only trace of the Whitewater investigation, almost a hidden
reference, is buried in Article III. That article, which involves
obstruction of justice, refers to allegations that Clinton tried
through his ``agents'' to find a job for Monica Lewinsky to help
secure her acquiescence in concealing their sexual relationship.
That issue has nothing itself to do with Whitewater, of course, but
it is a reminder of how the investigation into the land deal led in
fits and starts to the sex-and-lies scandal that is at the heart of
the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to ``agents'' refers most prominently to Vernon
Jordan, a well-connected Washington lawyer and good friend of
Clinton, who worked hard to to find a job for Ms. Lewinsky in New
York City that she would find satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Article III contains the charge that beginning in December 1997
and continuing through January 1998, Clinton ``intensified and
succeeded in an effort to secure job assistance to a witness in a
federal civil rights action against him in order to corruptly
prevent the truthful testimony of that witness.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chief Democratic counsel, Abbe Lowell, argued at
length Friday that Jordan's efforts were not designed to buy Ms.
Lewinsky's silence. Rather, he contended, the job search in which
Jordan aided Ms. Lewinsky began well before she had been subpoenaed
in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr saw Jordan's efforts in a
different light. He used them as the justification for expanding
his Whitewater investigation to include the president's
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, arguing that the job help
paralleled earlier efforts by the president's allies, including
Jordan, to provide help to an important Whitewater witness, Webster
Hubbell. After he was forced to leave the Clinton administration,
Hubbell received several lucrative contracts, some with the
assistance of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has contended in court papers that Hubbell has been
concealing important information about the Clintons' involvement in
Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   If Whitewater figures only indirectly in the impeachment
articles, the other avenues of Starr's investigation are wholly
nonexistent. Starr told the Judiciary committee last month that he
had found no wrongdoing on the part of President or Mrs. Clinton in
dismissing a group of longtime employees in the White House travel
office or in the improper collection by the Clinton White House of
some 900 confidential FBI files, many of them on prominent
Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
