A5817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICALS-COMDEN-NYT &LR;      12-11 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-COMDEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LEAR, MY DEAR'? HOW VERY, VERY QUEER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BETTY COMDEN and ADOLPH GREEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The history of the theater is dotted with musical
shows the sneering multitudes proclaimed would never open.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of the musicalization of Shakespeare's ``King
Lear'' titled ``Lear, My Dear.'' First, five of the principals died
during rehearsal, a definite setback. Then the twelve-tone serial
score a la Schoenberg, struck many potential backers as hopelessly
unwhistlable and they withdrew the $8 million budgeted for the
production. Fortunately a deaf uncle of the lyricist came through
and took up the slack and it was all speed ahead.
</P>
<P>
   As for the scoffers who said it would never open, it not only
opened at the Imperial Theater, but would also have run for three
full performances, were it not for the angry audience uprising that
broke out during the third night near the end of Act II. The fact
that it ran as long as it did can be attributed only to the casting
of Bernadette Peters as the aging monarch.
</P>
<P>
   How is it that a musical about a sharp-shooting female will run
considerably longer, with the very same star, than one based on a
beloved Shakespeare classic? Is it subject matter that determines
success or failure in the musical theater?
</P>
<P>
   There are certain subjects in literature and history positively
guaranteed to be totally unfit for the musical stage. Any
self-respecting theater practitioner would know in a sniff that the
following are ludicrous choices for musical comedy: the signing of
the Declaration of Independence, the bloodthirsty murderous barber
Sweeney Todd and the sinking of the Titanic. Yet they have all been
considerably more successful than the late nonlamented ``Lear, My
Dear.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Let's say the the Three Norns _ the three goddesses of the
past, present and future who play with mortals' destiny _ got
together for lunch at Sardi's and over a dish of cannelloni got a
little tipsy and gave those shows their blessing.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem nonintellectual, nonanalytical and evasive in the
extreme, but there is no other explanation ... except of course for
the skill and imagination and artistry of the creators who
stubbornly refused to listen to reason.
</P>
<P>
   Some years ago we refused to listen to reason, and while looking
desperately for a story about a strong woman in a male-dominated
world, we suddenly saw a flash of lightning spelling out Ibsen's
``Doll's House''!
</P>
<P>
   Our bolt of lightning, ``A Doll's Life,'' flashed for a brief
moment, then hit our house. It was about what happened to Nora
after she slammed that door and walked out into the alien world of
1879. Pawing the floor nervously we took the idea to the
incomparable Hal Prince, having recently had a great experience
with him working on ``On the 20th Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal jumped over the desk in one leap saying it was the greatest
idea he'd ever heard, and guaranteed us a production he would
direct, which he eventually did and superbly. He put us together
with the composer Larry Grossman who wrote some gorgeous music and
was a joy to work with. It closed after five performances.
</P>
<P>
   So what went wrong? Was it the subject matter? Or did we lack
the ``skill and imagination and artistry'' to melt the snows of
Norway into a hot landmark hit? Or did the Three Norns throw up?
Whatever the case, we still feel the basic elements had validity
and life, and find ourselves in the dead of night rewriting in our
heads the key moments and lyrics that would have made it run as
long as ``The Fantasticks.''
</P>
<P>
   This topic of what is valid subject matter for a musical has at
one time or another troubled even the greatest masters. In 1928,
early in their dazzling careers together, Richard Rodgers and
Lorenz Hart faced just such a thorny problem. It was a show to be
based on a novel called ``The Son of the Grand Eunuch.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers expressed his gnawing doubts about how your average
ticket-buying Joe would relate to the leading character and his
desperate attempts to escape the knife, and what kind of lilting
tunes he could come up with to tell his love story.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hart and Herb Fields, the book writer, somehow convinced
him that it was a swell idea. They proceeded to write ``Chee
Chee,'' which had at least one beautiful song, ``Moon of My
Delight,'' but which was cut off after only 37 performances. Maybe
the world wasn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   So what about ``Cats,'' you say? or ``Les Miz''? Uh ... just a
minute ... we have to answer the phone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
