<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBER'S INCOME FORECAST PUZZLING IN LIGHT OF TIGHT LABOR MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ While the Greater Kansas City Chamber of
Commerce economic forecast is fairly predictable, one conclusion
may not compute.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's presentation by Frank Lenk, director of the
Mid-America Regional Council's research services department,
foresaw the same trend toward slower growth for the regional
economy that most economists predict for the national economy.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising prediction in the chamber's outlook for the
local economy, however, was its call for a sharp decrease in the
pace of personal income growth. The call was for a rise of only 1.9
percent from this year's fourth quarter to next year's fourth
quarter. If the prediction proves accurate, this would represent a
40 percent plunge from the real personal income increase recorded
in the previous four quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The cognitive dissonance created by this prognostication derives
from a straw poll conducted in conjunction with the chamber's
formal 1999 forecast. This survey of area business owners and
managers showed just over two-thirds of the respondents identifying
``lack of qualified workers'' as their most significant challenge
to growth.
</P>
<P>
   If growing businesses see hiring and keeping qualified workers
as their biggest obstacle, it would seem to follow that the
resulting competition for effective workers would fuel a bidding
war in the local labor market.
</P>
<P>
   This local labor market, incidentally, is already well beyond
what economists now view as full employment. The area jobless rate
has fallen to just over 3 percent, its lowest since the late '70s
and nearly 30 percent below the national rate. Most economists
consider a 5 percent jobless rate as full employment, which means
anyone hereabouts who wants work already has a job.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, slower growth theoretically causes the available wage
pool to grow more slowly, but extraordinary challenges force
extraordinary solutions. Therefore, it's reasonable to assume that
employers will be compelled in some cases to rearrange operating
budgets to accommodate higher-than-usual labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   The validity of this assumption is reinforced by the chamber
forecast for area employment growth, which is predicted to occur at
only about half the previous year's pace. Though this substantial
decline in new hires may reflect a weakening economy, it's probably
just as reflective of the fact that there aren't that many warm
bodies left to hire. If so, the most prized workers will see their
premiums soar, which perhaps implies considerably better income
growth than the chamber forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more encouraging aspects of the straw poll was that
the local business community has higher expectations for the area
economy than for the country as a whole. While 22 percent expect
stronger growth for the national economy next year, 28 percent
expect improved growth for the Kansas City economy in 1999.
Moreover, only 11 percent expect a slowing of area economic growth,
but nearly 40 percent expect slower national growth.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, both the business community's attitude and the
chamber's outlook are remarkably upbeat for an economic expansion
that will mark its eighth birthday in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1900EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
