<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGLE-FATHERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE MEN ARE RAISING CHILDREN ALONE, CENSUS REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ More Americans are doing what Allen
Russell of Overland Park has been doing for several years: raising
a child as a single father.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. census figures being released today show that since 1995,
the number of single fathers raising children has grown 25 percent,
from 1.7 million to 2.1 million. Fathers now make up one-sixth of
all single parents. The number of single mothers raising children
has remained constant at about 9.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The trend reflects accelerating changes in social attitudes
toward unmarried men raising children, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got more fathers who are petitioning for custody at the
time of divorce and more mothers who are sort of realizing it's OK
for them not to be the custodial parent,'' said James Levine,
director of the Fatherhood Project at the Families and Work
Institute in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Russell was surprised to learn he has so much company. The
38-year-old Sprint employee fought _ against his lawyer's advice _
for joint custody of his daughters when his wife asked for a
divorce five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren, now 10, and Heather, now 7, live with their father and
visit their mother. Russell also is applying to adopt two brothers,
Mike, 13, and Dominick, 9, who are his foster sons. He also works
with other kids through Youth Friends and his church.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assume when there's a divorce that mom gets the kids,''
Russell said Thursday. ``People are shocked when they learn. `You
got the kids?' It's the most frustrating part of being a single
dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Canfield, president and founder of the National Center for
Fathering, which is in Merriam, Kan., said the trend has evolved
from the early 1960s, when single dads were rare and usually
widowers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the rise in divorce and changes in custody laws have
led to more fathers assuming primary residential care for their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more fathers are finding out that they want to do it
and that they can do it,'' agreed John R. Sims Jr., founder of the
Single and Custodial Fathers Network in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau report on household and family characteristics
also suggests social and political discussion about family values
may be slowing the decline of ``family households.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 102.5 million households in the United States, 69 percent
are considered family households _ two or more persons living
together and related by birth, marriage or adoption. That is a 2
percentage-point drop since 1990, compared with a 10
percentage-point drop from 1970-1990.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of one-parent families has slowed. They were 11
percent of family households with children in 1970, 24 percent in
1990 and 27 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A key factor in the leveling off in the number of single mothers
is the drop in teen pregnancies, notes Susan Scribner, director of
the Kids Count project with Citizens for Missouri's Children in St.
Louis. Most pregnant teens are unmarried.
</P>
<P>
   The teen birth rate in Missouri dropped from 63 per 1,000 to 54
per 1,000 between 1992 and 1996. Nationally, teen pregnancy hit a
20-year low in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The census numbers indicate the growth in single fathers raising
children is occurring primarily in white and Hispanic families. The
number of white single fathers raising children grew 36 percent,
and the number of Hispanic fathers doing so increased 18.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The number of black single fathers raising children has declined
15 percent since 1995, said Lynne Casper, a statistician with the
Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   But what does the overall trend mean for the children growing up
in households headed by single dads?
</P>
<P>
   A better financial outlook is one possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The median weekly income for women still is only about
three-quarters that of men. About half of all single-family
households are at or below the poverty line, said Scribner, and
poverty increases other risks for children, such as poor health and
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Scribner said most studies indicate that children are better off
in a two-parent household, but she knew of no studies that
indicated children were better off living with either a single
father or a single mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fathers and mothers bring different things to the parenting
role,'' she said, ``and the child could do exceedingly well with
either one if they are getting the love and support they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren, Mike and Heather seemed content doing their homework
before dinner Thursday evening in the light of a Christmas tree at
the Russell house.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids are well-behaved, and when people find out they come
from a single-parent family, they say, `Really?' '' Russell said.
``That tells me, yes, I'm doing something right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
