<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON12-COX     12-11 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON12-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SAYS HE WILL ACCEPT CENSURE
 &HT;    Eds: subs Franks for Freylinghuysen in grafs 6 and 7.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to stave off impeachment, President Clinton
again apologized Friday for having ``misled'' the nation about the
Monica Lewinsky affair, and for the first time told Congress he is
willing to accept its ``censure and rebuke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want the American people to know, what I want the
Congress to know is that I am profoundly sorry for all I have done
wrong in words and deeds,'' Clinton said. ``I never should have
misled the country, the Congress, my friends or my family. Quite
simply, I gave in to my shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statement, made in a brief White House Rose Garden
appearance, was perhaps the first time in American history that a
president has so frankly admitted his personal failings.
</P>
<P>
   But it seemed to be too little, too late to sway wavering GOP
House members. House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said the
statement was ``an insult to their intelligence and the
intelligence of all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stopped short of admitting that he lied under oath about
his relationship with the former White House intern, and some
moderate Republicans have said that without a full public
confession, they would vote for his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, within minutes of Clinton's appearance, two House
Republicans who had been considered possible votes against
impeachment declared that they would instead vote for it. They were
Rep. Saxby Chambliss of Georgia and Bob Franks of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, saying the House Judiciary Committee ``has laid out a
compelling case that the president has committeed perjury,'' said
that ``unless the president comes forward soon and admits his
guilt, I am prepared to vote for articles of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's hastily arranged statement came even as the Judiciary
Committee was voting to approve the first article seeking his
removal from office. Aides reportedly urged the president, who
leaves early Saturday on a four-day trip to the Mideast, to speak
out before support for impeachment had a chance to solidify.
</P>
<P>
   In his five-minute speech, delivered in a husky voice, Clinton
said he was willing to accept congressional condemnation. He
acknowledged ``the public consequences of my actions are in the
hands of the American people and their representatives in the
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should they determine that my errors of word and deed require
their rebuke and censure, I am ready to accept that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also made it clear that his wife and daughter
continue to suffer through the anguish wrought by his affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painful though the condemnation of the Congress would be, it
would pale in comparison to the consequences of the pain I have
caused my family,'' he said. ``There is no greater agony.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's speech continued a series of increasingly contrite
apologies stretching over several months.
</P>
<P>
   It came three months to the day after Clinton acknowledged, ``I
have sinned,'' before a White House prayer breakfast attended by
clergy members from across the nation. ``It is important to me that
everybody who has been hurt knows that the sorrow that I feel is
genuine _ first and foremost my family, also my friends, my staff,
my cabinet, Monica Lewinsky and her family and the American
people,'' he said then.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide address Aug. 17, Clinton admitted that his
relationship with Lewinsky ``was not appropriate. In fact it was
wrong. It constituted a critical lapse of judgment on my part for
which I am solely and completely responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton still could make an even more forthcoming statement next
week before the House begins debate Thursday on the impeachment
articles approved by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his repeated apologies, Republican critics charge
that Clinton has never fully admitted the extent of his wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's statement appeared to be another tentative step in
that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``These past months have been a torturous process of coming to
terms with what I did,'' he said. ``I understand that
accountability demands consequences, and I'm prepared to accept
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he wished he could take it all back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anyone who honestly faces the shame of wrongful conduct,
I would give anything to go back and undo what I did,'' he said.
``But one of the painful truths I have to live with is the reality
that that is simply not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
