<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE OPRAH GAP
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By FRANK RICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a yearlong standoff between nagging parents and an
adolescent who won't do his homework, the disconnect between the
media gasbags and the public goes on and on. This week, despite the
insistent talking-head lectures about the ``historic'' import of it
all, the audience for impeachment hearings on CNN dwindled to
one-third the size of that for the Clinton grand-jury testimony. It
may take a graphic video of the president and Monica Lewinsky not
having sex while not being alone in the White House to get the
nation's viewers to tune in now.
</P>
<P>
   The same Washington sermonizers who faulted the American people
all year for being too mesmerized by the Dow Jones to care about
Paula Jones are already finding a new cause for the callow, selfish
public's indifference: Christmas shopping. We're just too busy
playing Santa to pay attention to the patriotic show put on for our
civic edification by the House's Kris Kringle wannabe, Henry Hyde,
and his nattering crew of elves.
</P>
<P>
   But the gap between the media and the public isn't and wasn't
about making money or spending it. There's a deeper rebellion afoot
that transcends and may well outlast the specific politics of the
Clinton wars. In 1998 the public didn't merely reject the
prognostications and moral homilies of the Sams and Cokies; it
turned against the media's sermonizing cultural potentates too. The
disconnect that played out in the polls and the November election
was echoed in the mass culture in which Americans also vote, albeit
with clickers at home and dollars at the multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic example was Oprah Winfrey's film ``Beloved.''
In October, according to the tracking of the newsletter NewsTV
Reports, it was the subject of 24 TV news-magazine pieces (second
only to Clinton's 30). Previously this year Oprah was crowned the
most powerful person in show business by Entertainment Weekly and
one of the century's top 20 artists and entertainers (along with
Picasso, Joyce and Stravinsky) by Time. And yet she could not, we
discovered, turn out even a respectably mediocre audience for her
movie _ despite an additional media juggernaut including 11
magazine covers (from Vogue to TV Guide), an overwhelming majority
of favorable reviews (as tabulated by Variety) and a ubiquitous,
costly Disney promotional push.
</P>
<P>
   As with the political disconnect, journalistic post-mortems put
the blame on a frivolous public: we had rejected a long, serious
movie about slavery from a novel by a Nobel laureate. But this same
public was riveted shortly thereafter by the confirmation of
another, real-life slavery drama, that of Thomas Jefferson and
Sally Hemings; it had also taken to the long, often bleak ``Saving
Private Ryan'' in the heat of summer.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem _ and it was true from the day ``Beloved''
opened, before ``word of mouth'' could be the culprit _ was that
the audience feared more sermon than drama from the increasingly
more preachy Oprah. As Tom Shales wrote in The Washington Post,
``Winfrey playing national nanny is getting to be a drag'' _ a
sentence that could also describe TV's Clinton-scandal gasbags.
</P>
<P>
   In a year that has also seen the accelerating collapse of the
broadcast TV networks _ until now the single most constant power in
American cultural life since World War II _ the public is
increasingly ignoring the media establishment. It found ``There's
Something About Mary'' without guidance from cultural authorities;
it boisterously challenged Modern Library's great books list the
moment the luminaries handed it down.
</P>
<P>
   A country that has refused to believe supposed opinion makers
who have been predicting Clinton's imminent demise all year
certainly isn't going to believe them about ``Primary Colors''
(another highly touted flop) or ``Felicity'' (the season's most
heavily hyped new TV series, ranked No. 108 in the Nielsen
ratings).
</P>
<P>
   In this rebellious climate, the newest media juggernaut _
Dreamworks' animated biblical feature, ``The Prince of Egypt,'' now
being hawked by journalists and TV clergymen alike _ is all but
asking for the next national backlash. Should this cartoon fail to
deliver numbers equal to its hype, the public that has revolted
against our media moralists by choosing Clinton over Starr and
Springer over Oprah will end the year on the absolutely perfect
note: voting for animated ants, ``Rugrats'' and ``The Waterboy''
over Moses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
