<HEADLINE>
VIDEO GAMES HOT AS GIFTS, BRING HEAT TO CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports of scuffling in the toy aisles have yet to surface, but
two new Nintendo video games _ Pokemon and the Legend of Zelda _
may be almost as hot as Furby, this year's holiday hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're selling out as fast as we get shipments,'' said Best Buy
spokeswoman Laurie Bauer of Pokemon. ``In some cases, we've had to
give out rainchecks.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BuySafe.com, a Cambridge, Mass. Internet retailer,
issued a statement Friday assuring all hands that it has ``ample
inventory'' of Legend of Zelda games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been shipping out a couple of hundred a day,'' said
BuySafe spokesman Dan Johnson of Zelda.
</P>
<P>
   Zelda is also popular at the Burlington (Mass.) Mall, where the
house Santa has been bombarded with requests for Nintendo 64 games.
</P>
<P>
   At the mall's Electronics Boutique, ``Zelda 64 is all sold
out,'' said mall spokeswoman Sheila Hennessy.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon, which supposedly means ``pocket monsters'' in Japanese,
sells for about $30 and is played on the hand-held Game Boy system,
the new color version of which sells for $79.
</P>
<P>
   Zelda has a suggested price of $60, and it is played on the
Nintendo 64 game console, which lists for about $129.
</P>
<P>
   With a $14 million marketing campaign behind it _ and the KFC
fast-food chain ponying up millions more for its own pocket-monster
promotion _ Pokemon could rack up sales on par with such past Game
Boy hits as Super Mario and Donkey Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the cartoon TV show that has made Pokemon a
phenomenon in Japan for the last few years. With its pulsing bright
lights, the series was blamed for making hundreds of children sick
before the special effects were toned down.
</P>
<P>
   Children's television activist Peggy Charren is nauseated about
Pokemon for a different reason: By her lights, the cartoon is
basically a 30-minute commercial for Pokemon products.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder which came first, the show or the merchandise?''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Given all this hype and hoo-ha, Nintendo expects US sales of 1
million Pokemon games between its fall launch and Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Zelda64 could do even better, selling 2.5 million units between
late November and Dec. 31, Nintendo of America predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Just by way of comparison, Tiger Toys, the Hasbro Inc. division
that markets Furby, is expected to sell between 1 million and 2
million of the jabbering $30 furballs.
</P>
<P>
   In Pokemon, players vie for a black belt in pocket-monster
house-breaking. Simply put, the goal of the game is to locate and
tame the 150 monsters that run rampant through the game
environment. Players must train and nurture one monster to help
capture other monsters and turn them into virtual pets.
</P>
<P>
   From Yarmouth to Yokahoma, there are few more coveted glories
for a 10-year-old boy than being recognized by his pals as a pukka
Pokemon tamer. And in case a kid can't get enough of his Game Boy,
there are also Pokemon comics, videos, and plush toys.
</P>
<P>
   Zelda has the potential to be even bigger. While Pokemon
``skews'' toward boys between 8 and 14, Zelda appeals to a much
broader age range, said Beth Llewelyn, a Nintendo spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers placed orders for 500,000 Zelda games before it even
shipped, triple the number of early orders for any previous video
game, Nintendo claims.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nintendo, Zelda is so intricately layered that
playing the game is like reading a novel, as players journey to a
magic kingdom dense with role-playing plot lines, 3-D graphics, and
an ocarina sound-track. One hype-crazed reviewer was moved to call
Zelda ``The `Gone With the Wind' of video games.''
</P>
<P>
   Because demand exceeds supply, Furby may be the season's
scarcest toy. But in terms of unit and dollar sales, Zelda could
eclipse Furby, and Pokemon could come close to Furby, too.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon and Zelda may be selling better at specialty software
retailers than traditional toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   At KB Toys, spokesman John Reilly said Pokemon hasn't reached
the level of a phenomenon a la Furby.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``That's not to say Pokemon isn't hot.''
</P>
<P>
   At Toys ``R'' Us, spokeswoman Rebecca A. Caruso offered a
similar appraisal of Pokemon: ``It's a big seller. It's the newest
thing in virtual pets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
