<SLUG> BC-NEXAR-WOES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST BAY STATE COMPUTER MAKER NEAR INSOLVENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts' last computer manufacturing company, Nexar
Technologies Inc. of Southborough, is preparing to declare
insolvency after failing to raise capital to pay off creditors and
preferred shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Nexar said it expected its stock to be delisted by Nasdaq for
failure to meet minimum financial requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Shares Friday were trading at 1/16, where they have been since
November, when an announcement of possible bankruptcy set off a
flurry of trading. Nexar hasn't traded above 1 since July; it
closed Friday at 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Conrad, a Nexar spokesman, said he did not know whether
the company would seek protection from creditors under Chapter 11
of the bankruptcy law, or file for a Chapter 7 liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   Nexar reported in November that it was facing $5.5 million in
lawsuits by creditors and a $3.3 million claim by holders of
preferred shares who want to redeem those holdings. Conrad said
Nexar doesn't have the money.
</P>
<P>
   The company closed its Hayward, Calif., factory in November and
has reduced its payroll to 23 employees from 80 in June.
</P>
<P>
   Several attempts to find a buyer earlier this year failed,
Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   Nexar's modular design for personal computers, with features
that let owners buy and install upgrade parts in minutes, was
widely hailed when it was introduced in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But apart from a contract to supply some federal agencies, sales
never took off and plunged this year as the company's future became
uncertain and prices for competitive personal computers fell below
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nexar reported $33.6 million in sales in 1997, losing $13.6
million for the year. Revenues for the first nine months of this
year were just under $10 million, with losses for the period,
including preferred stock dividends, posted at $14.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Originally capitalized with $12 million from Palomar Medical
Technologies Inc. of Beverly, Mass., Nexar raised $19.7 million in
April 1997 through an initial public stock offering. Most of that
went to repay Palomar, Conrad said. Palomar continues to be Nexar's
largest shareholder and dominates the company's board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
