<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-JUDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET DEFIANT AT LONDON COURT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Twenty-five years after he led a bloody coup in Chile,
former dictator Augusto Pinochet appeared Friday in a court of law
_ an appointment with justice decried by his supporters as
outrageous but cheered by those he brutalized as long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a wheelchair, Pinochet 83, was defiant during a
brief, initial hearing on his extradition from England to Spain,
where authorities want to try him for murder and torture committed
during and after the 1973 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Spanish, Pinochet read from an index card, telling
Magistrate Graham Parkinson, ``With respect to your honor, I don't
recognize the jurisdiction of any other court but in my country to
try me against all the lies of Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   With a dismissive wave of his hand, Pinochet concluded, ``That
is all I want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkinson continued the case until Jan. 18, adding that Pinochet
does not have to attend that hearing. Parkinson said Pinochet can
remain at the mansion he is renting 20 miles southwest of London
during the extradition proceedings, which could last for months. He
said too that Pinochet could use the grounds of the mansion, as
long as he did so under armed guard.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's lawyers plan an all-out offensive to have the
extradition charges dropped. Pinochet's enfeebled appearance
clutching a walking stick and asking to be excused from standing
while the charges were read struck some legal observers as the
beginning of a campaign to gain his release for health reasons. Yet
last week, he was told to leave the London hospital where he had
undergone back surgery because doctors there said he did not
require further care.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, British Home Secretary Jack Straw cleared the way
for the extradition proceedings to begin by saying that the former
dictator is not entitled to any form of immunity and does not
deserve to avoid prosecution on compassionate grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Straw upheld the Nov. 25 decision by five Law Lords in the House
of Lords who ruled 3-2 that Pinochet could not claim sovereign
immunity for human rights violations committed while he ruled Chile
between 1973 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Chilean government report, at least 3,197 people
were killed or disappeared during Pinochet's tenure. Human rights
organizations maintain that the figure is much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, lawyers for Pinochet will begin a rare appeal of the
Law Lords' decision on the grounds that one of the three judges who
voted against Pinochet, Lord Leonard Hoffmann, serves on the board
of an Amnesty International charity. Lawyers for Amnesty
International were among those who argued in the House of Lords
that the lower court ruling that Pinochet could not be extradited
was legally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International says that attempts to paint Lord Hoffmann
as biased are specious and that the charity on which he serves as
an unpaid director was also supported by the chief justice of the
High Court, whose decision to grant immunity to Pinochet was
overturned by the Law Lords.
</P>
<P>
   Held back by security cordons and separated by police at the
Belmarsh Magistrate's Court, Pinochet's supporters and detractors
Friday assembled on opposite sides of the road leading into the
court complex and traded insults. Supporters waved Chilean flags
while his enemies danced and sang songs recalling the 1,000
``disappeared'' who were abducted by Pinochet's security forces and
are presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Pinochet is convicted in Spain, he will not be sent to
prison there because under Spanish law no one over the age of 75
can be incarcerated. But he could spend years defending himself
against other countries that have formally lodged warrants for his
arrest. France and Switzerland have asked that he be extradited to
face charges for the murder of their nationals, and Italy is
considering making a similar request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
