<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gingrich Gets A New Platform &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich grabbed headlines back in 1995 for complaining
about his seat on the Air Force One flight to Israel for Yitzhak
Rabin's funeral. Soon, the outgoing House Speaker will have another
forum for opining about flying in style.
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann Little &AMP; Co., a private investment firm whose holdings
include Gulfstream Aerospace, said this week that Gingrich would be
joining its advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich will be in familiar company. Theodore J. Forstmann, a
general partner, is fond of inviting brand-name Washingtonians onto
the boards. Gulfstream, which is publicly traded, counts Colin L.
Powell, Henry A. Kissinger and George P. Shultz as directors. They
also are on Forstmann Little's advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strategy that allows Forstmann and Gulfstream to fly with
a tail wind. These directors are on the phone all day with people
who might need a $35 million Gulfstream jet. It has certainly been
lucrative for the directors, many of whom pocketed profits of
around $1 million this year from stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Such sums may tempt Gingrich to lobby for a seat on Gulfstream's
board. Chances are that he will nab a seat more to his liking than
the one he had on Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Bryant &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leveling the Trading Field &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Mark Cuban, president of Broadcast.com, a soaring initial
public offering on NASDAQ in July was more than just an opportunity
to market his shares. He turned it into a chance to market his
services _ namely, the broadcasting of audio and video on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NASDAQ said that beginning early next year,
Broadcast.com would carry the quarterly earnings conferences that
the 100 largest NASDAQ companies conduct for analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban says individual investors will have the same access as
Wall Street insiders to information that often moves stocks. ``A
conference call usually maxes out at four or five hundred,'' he
said. ``Yet for us to have four, five, six thousand users on line,
listening in, is no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Napoli &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They Came, Saw and Conquered &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Swanson, a co-founder of Genentech, was the impetus
behind the biotechnology revolution and by virtue of that role is
the most important business leader alive today. So, at least, says
a new book, ``1,000 Years, 1,000 People'' (Kodansha International
Press), which ranks the movers and shakers of the millennium. (This
writer is the co-author, with Barbara Bowers, and Henry Gottlieb
and Agnes Hooper Gottlieb.)
</P>
<P>
   Other business and economics leaders who made the list include
Karl Marx, No. 14; Adam Smith, No. 21, and Henry Ford, No. 51. As
the founder of modern communism, which came to rule half the world,
Marx had even greater influence than Smith, though Smith's
doctrines are now ascendant while Marx's are fading.
</P>
<P>
   Among the living are Swanson (No. 612); Robert N. Noyce, creator
of the first silicon chip (No. 730); Milton Friedman, the
inflation-fighting monetarist (No. 731), and the financier Warren
E. Buffett, ``the embodiment of the human itch to get rich'' (No.
889).
</P>
<P>
   Such rankings, admittedly, are idiosyncratic. Time magazine's
list of the greatest business titans of the 20th century, published
earlier this month, included Ford, but none of the book's living
legends. Time made room for Bill Gates; the compilers of the
millennial list left Gates off, judging him more a mogul than an
innovator.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Bowers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tempting the Inner Child &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Mary Theresa Weil, the executive-floor receptionist at T.
Rowe Price, the mutual fund company, the hardened leaders of
corporate America are boys at heart. They prove it by shyly asking
to play with the ball of rubber bands on her desk.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is because the sphere, made of 26,000 rubber bands, is
nearing the size of a soccer ball, but visitors just can't seem to
resist. That includes Alexander Trotman, Ford Motor's chief, who
bounced it off the marble tiles when visiting to push Ford stock,
Ms. Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   She gets the raw material from the mail she opens for 14 T. Rowe
Price executives, including George Roche, the chairman, and James
Kennedy, director of the equity and research departments.
</P>
<P>
   The buttoned-down Roche, Ms. Weil said, has never even looked at
the ball, but she once caught the more sportive Kennedy eyeing it.
``I have a lot of daily lookers,'' she said. ``They want to bounce
it, but they don't in front of me. I wonder what happens when I go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Furchgott &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
