<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS &LR;      12-11 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL SPECIALISTS DIVIDED OVER CHARGES ISSUE, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A basic legal principle lay at the center of the
House Judiciary Committee's debate Friday about the articles of
impeachment against President Clinton: Every defendant has a right
to know the charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   But legal scholars fell into the same disagreement as the
committee members over whether lawmakers were legally obliged to
spell out precisely the charges against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Democrats on the House panel, some scholars said any
charge of perjury should include the exact words that the president
used that are alleged to be untrue. And like the Republicans, some
said that the committee could approve general charges of perjury,
referring the president for details to lengthy reports on the
matter written by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and by the
committee's chief Republican counsel, David Schippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a 350-page referral by the independent counsel and a
three hour presentation by David Schippers, in which they go
through the elements of each one of the charges,'' said Stephen
Presser, professor of legal history at the Northwestern University
School of Law. ``It's mind-bogglingly astonishing to think that
there's a specificity problem here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Low Bloch, a professor at the Georgetown University
School of Law, said those documents were too broad and general to
constitute a fair notice to President Clinton of the exact nature
of his perjury. ``Before he faces trial, he has to know what he's
alleged to have said, which of his statements are perjurious,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to be a little bit of shadow-boxing,'' said John O.
McGinnis of the Cardozo School of Law at Yeshiva University in New
York. ``I don't think anyone is in deep doubt about the issues that
president is being charged with.''
</P>
<P>
   Perjury is the basis for first two of the four charges against
the president before the committee. Both perjury articles passed
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In most criminal prosecutions for perjury, prosecutors would
seek an indictment that included fairly specific details of the
alleged lying. For example, Starr's indictment of Webster Hubbell
on perjury and other charges last month includes the exact
questions put to Hubbell by a congressional committee, as well as
Hubbell's allegedly false answer.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's indictment even underlines the 10 words in Hubbell's
answer that prosecutors say constituted perjury.
</P>
<P>
   But legal scholars said there was no analogy between a criminal
case and impeachment, which is a political act as well as legal
process. The lawmakers themselves have the power to decide what
goes into the articles of impeachment. No judge or appeals court
will review their decision, as long as they do not violate the
broad guidelines set out in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Washington lawyer Charles Cooper said that Clinton, unlike a
traditional criminal defendant, would draw his understanding of the
charges against him from more than the indictment. In addition to
the Starr and Schippers reports, the impeachment process has
already produced hours of debate in which lawmakers and their
staffs state the case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not like a defendant who knows what is being alleged
against him,'' said Cooper, of the firm Cooper, Carvin &AMP; Rosenthal,
who handled constitutional cases for the government as an assistant
attorney general. ``Everyone on earth has notice of what the
charges are here.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous articles of impeachment have charged presidents with
making false statements, but they varied in the amount of detail
they included.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee charged President Nixon with
``making false or misleading public statements'' regarding the 1972
break-in at Democratic Party offices at the Watergate complex. The
impeachment articles charged that Nixon misled the public by saying
the administration had investigated the break-in and had cleared
members of Nixon's staff and of his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the articles did not lay out the exact misleading statements
that Nixon made.
</P>
<P>
   The 1868 articles of impeachment against President Andrew
Johnson contained great detail about his allegedly misleading
statements. One article charged that Johnson on Feb. 22, 1868 tried
to induce William H. Emory, a major-general in the Army, to violate
a law recently passed by Congress by telling him that the law was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Another article claimed that Johnson tried ``to excite odium and
resentment of all the good people of the United States against
Congress'' by making ``certain intemperate, inflammatory and
scandalous harangues . . . and bitter menaces.'' Not only were the
dates and locations of the statements listed, but so were excerpts
of Johnson's speeches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
