<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUAL-TRANSPLANT-BOS &LR;      12-11 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUAL-TRANSPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGAN SHORTAGE LEADS TO DUAL LIVE LIVER TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Faced with a chronic shortage of donor organs, a
husband from Vermont and a sister from Massachusetts chose to give
pieces of their own livers to their desperately ill loved-ones in
dramatic, pioneering operations over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In a first for New England, surgeons at Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center removed large portions of the healthy donors' livers
and transplanted them successfully into their wife and brother,
respectively, to save them from terminal liver disease, officials
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital spokeswoman said late Friday that three of the
patients were in stable condition and the fourth _ the Boston
recipient _ had required longer surgery but was on his way to the
recovery room.
</P>
<P>
   None of the patients was identified.
</P>
<P>
   The operations, each lasting at least eight hours and requiring
four surgeons and two operating rooms, took place Thursday and
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Because the liver alone among human organs can regenerate, the
two pieces of one original liver will support both donor and
recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun thing is that the donor and recipient (livers) sort of
race toward regeneration'' and grow to almost their normal size in
a matter of weeks, said Dr. Roger L. Jenkins, chief of the division
of transplantation at BIDMC.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fantastic news, because there's a severe shortage, and
this means that more lives will be saved,'' commented Alan
Brownstein, president of the American Liver Foundation in a
telephone interview, when informed of the Boston successes.
</P>
<P>
   He said 4,000 liver transplants are performed annually but there
are 11,000 patients waiting for livers, and 1,000 die while on the
wwaiting list. And, he said, the need for liver transplants is
expected to triple in the next 10 or 20 years because of the
epidemic of liver-destroying hepatitis C. Both of the Beth Israel
Deaconess patients were hepatitis C victims.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said that transplant surgeon Dr. Elizabeth Pomfret at
BIDMC led the development of the new procedure over the past year.
Pomfret had spent time in Germany observing the work of Dr.
Christoph Broelsch, who performed the first successful living-donor
liver transplant. Broelsch was on hand for the initial Boston
transplants and was ``extremely helpful,'' said Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the transplant team were Dr. David Lewis, director of
liver transplantation at BIDMC, and two transplant fellows, Drs.
James Pomposelli and Douglas Hale.
</P>
<P>
   The adult living transplants are desperate measures being taken
at a time when the need for donor livers is rising and the supply
of livers from brain-dead donors hasn't grown. The chances of
finding a compatible donor within a family or close friends is
excellent because the only genetic matching required of donor and
recipient is that they have the same blood type.
</P>
<P>
   Instances of parents donating a small piece of liver to a child
have become relatively common. But only a handful of the riskier
adult-to-adult transplants, involving the entire right lobe of the
liver, have been done in the United States: between 50 and 100 are
thought to have been performed in the world. It's a more difficult
procedure because as much as 60 percent of the donor's liver has to
be removed, in painstaking surgery to prevent severe bleeding, to
provide enough organ for the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   However, a number of adult-to-adult transplants have been done
this year in Denver, at the Medical College of Virginia and the
Johns Hopkins Medical Institutions in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said that each of the operations here began with about
three hours of surgery to divide the donor's liver and tie off
blood vessels. Then surgery in an adjacent operating room began to
remove the diseased liver of the recipient. After the donor liver
was removed, it was flushed in preservative solutions and then
implanted into the sick patient.
</P>
<P>
   Done this way, the liver is outside the donor's or recipient's
body for only a short time, which leaves it in better condition
than cadaver livers which may take many hours to transport before
being implanted.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said both donors in the new transplants had come forward
of their own accord. ``If it's a positive approach on their side,
it makes us more comfortable,'' he said, adding that the two donors
``are two of the most incredible people I've ever met...they are
real heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday surgeons at the Medical College of Virginia in Richmond,
Va., performed their 11th adult-to-adult liver transplant, said Dr.
Marc Posner, head of the division of transplant surgery there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience has been remarkably good, better than we
expected,'' said Posner. He said there have been no serious
complications in the recovery of the donors, all of whom have left
the hospital in six to 10 days. ``And they have felt very good
about it psychologically,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Liver transplants ordinarily cost about $500,000 for the surgery
and the first year of post-surgery treatment. Jenkins said the new
approach may actually be cheaper because it avoids the considerable
costs of procuring cadaver livers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
