<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-BOSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS GET HARD FACTS OF BOSTON'S CONVENTION BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pssssst. The Democratic National Committee's visit to
frontrunner Los Angeles was a disaster this week and could endanger
their widely perceived lock on the year 2000 Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   That was the buzz putting smiles on the faces of Boston
officials Friday as an endless line of number crunchers and
logistical whizzes trotted out details for the DNC's visiting panel
of seven.
</P>
<P>
   Granted the Boston operatives don't know if the rumor was fact
or spin to get the city to give up more loot for the giant bash _
even more than the $32 million already pledged, but they were
bouyed by word that earlier this week Los Angeles officials were
fuzzy on the details of their offer to hold the convention in LA.
</P>
<P>
   Verbal agreements to provide cash and goods in Los Angeles
contrasted sharply with Boston's documented numbers and signatures,
insiders said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston proudly offered pledges in black and white from Fidelity
Investments, John Hancock Financial Services, BankBoston, and Fleet
Bank for $250,000 each. The Chamber of Commerce has promised
$100,000 and Bell Atlantic, $2 million in services and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of morning presentations on everything from
shuttle bus service to transit passes and crime statistics, Joe
Andrew, chairman of the DNC site advisory committee, insisted at a
noon press conference that there is no front runner among the three
finalists. And if the Big Dig was a problem, Andrew said, ``We
wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor A. Paul Cellucci told the committee the state would
give full support besides the $8 million it has pledged. And
Senator Ted Kennedy had an afternoon cameo appearance to show
support.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC staffers did have a series of detailed queries for
Boston on how it might incorporate more technology in the
convention, said Boston's intergovernmental affairs director Howard
Leibowitz. The questions were heartening, he said, because they
signaled that Boston was still in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew played down the importance of geography for where the
convention will be held, saying it has become more of a television
and Internet operation.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the money the convention host offers, Andrew said it
is still a good deal for the host, if history is a guide. Chicago,
host of the last Democratic convention, offered $27 million to $30
million and reaped direct economic benefits of $175 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great bargain,'' Andrew said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1939EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
