</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-JUVENILES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUVENILES ESCAPE FROM TEXAS YOUTH FACILITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
and PATTY REINERT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ Just two weeks after a murderer escaped Texas'
death row, 11 teen-age inmates, including three violent offenders,
escaped from the state's largest youth correctional facility,
authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, five had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates, ranging in age from 14 to 17, obtained a key to the
fire door in their dormitory at the J.W. Hamilton Jr. State School
and escaped about 7:30 p.m., CST, Thursday. They then used
wirecutters to cut through a fence about 15 yards away, said Judy
Briscoe, director of juvenile corrections for the Texas Youth
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the youths had been incarcerated for assault and
firearms offenses; the other eight are nonviolent offenders,
Briscoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Byran is about 90 miles northwest of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan police arrested five of the youths who had been hiding in
a trailer near the school, said TYC spokeswoman Pamela Ward. All
will face additional charges for escape, which could add nine
months to a year to their sentences. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Escapee Donald R. Flint, a 17-year-old from Houston, telephoned
his parents and advised them he would be home for Christmas,
authorities said, but as of late Friday, he had not been sighted.
Flint was serving time for robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Bain, a 17-year-old from San Antonio, who was charged with
theft, reached his parents' home Friday, along with a few other
escapees. The group fled again when Bain's parents called police.
</P>
<P>
   They apparently stole a staff member's car, which later was
recovered on the campus of Texas A&AMP;M University in College Station,
about 10 miles away. Authorities believe the youths then stole
another vehicle from the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities normally do not reveal the identities of juvenile
offenders, but are allowed to release their names and descriptions
if they escape.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 inmates made their break Thursday evening as a fight
broke out between two other boys in the activity room of Dorm 5,
said Jean Tomlinson, program administrator for the school. They
fled as staff members, who are unarmed, were trying to quell the
fight. Others in the 32-bed dorm apparently were about to bolt as
well, but staff managed to close the door and lock it, Tomlinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the escape had apparently been planned for
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened real fast,'' Briscoe said. ``Staffers picked up on
the fact that the door was open and they saw the kids running
across the field. They saw the kids get through the fence and then
they separated in three directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain hit the Bryan area just minutes after the youths
escaped, and temperatures were in the 40s Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are in T-shirts and jeans and it is raining, so
they're probably getting pretty cold by now,'' Briscoe said. ``We
hope they are.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Tomlinson said the inmates had been issued winter
clothing Wednesday and Thursday, and some were believed to be
wearing orange sweatshirts and gray pants with the school's name
printed on the legs. They also had access to gloves and knit caps.
All the inmates have short haircuts.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson said it was unknown how the youths got the key to the
fire door, but they would have known it existed because they would
have seen it used during fire drills. Authorities also were
investigating how the youths obtained the wirecutters they used to
cut a 4-foot-long slash in the chain-link fence.
</P>
<P>
   The school, a former adult prison northwest of Bryan, was
renovated for juvenile offenders and opened about 1 1/2 years ago.
More than 500 male juvenile offenders are housed in open
dormitories at the school.
</P>
<P>
   The escape took place just one week after authorities found the
body of escaped death row inmate Martin Gurule floating in a creek
near Huntsville. Hundreds of officers had searched for Gurule for
seven days after a dramatic escape late Thanksgiving night. Six
other death row inmates also tried to escape but surrendered before
reaching the fences.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
