<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SOLZHENITSYN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLZHENITSYN REJECTS AWARD, CASTIGATES RUSSIAN LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It was supposed to be the crowning moment in the career
of Russia's most celebrated writer, an overdue gesture of
recognition by the Kremlin for a man whose uncompromising stance
against Communist repression helped hasten the demise of the Soviet
police state.
</P>
<P>
   But as Russia celebrated his 80th birthday Friday, Alexander
Solzhenitsyn, ever the angry dissident, tore up that feel-good
script by refusing Russia's highest cultural award.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Kremlin announced that President Boris Yeltsin had
awarded Solzhenitsyn the Order of the Apostle St Andrew for
``outstanding services to the Fatherland and for his great
contribution to world literature.''
</P>
<P>
   But Solzhenitsyn, who today attacks Russia's current leaders
with the same messianic zeal he once directed at the Communist
Party, refused in a rare public appearance to accept the award from
``the high authorities who drove Russia to its moribund state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are on hunger strikes for their salaries and
striking, I cannot accept such an award,'' Solzhenitsyn said from
the stage at the Taganka Theater, where his friend and fellow
former Soviet dissident Yury Lyubimov put on a stage version of his
1968 novel, ``The First Circle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, maybe some time from now, when Russia climbs out of its
quagmire of catastrophies, my sons will accept it for me,'' he
added, as the theater burst into applause.
</P>
<P>
   Solzhenitsyn's daring and frank accounts of the Gulag labor
camps made him a leading voice of the Soviet underground, where
unofficial samizdat copies of his works were eagerly read and
passed around. Smuggled out and published in the West, works like
``The Gulag Archipelago'' and ``The Cancer Ward,'' opened the eyes
of the world to the brutality of the Soviet system and earned
Solzhenitsyn a Nobel prize. They also earned him the wrath of
Communist authorities, who finally sent him into exile in 1974 and
stripped him of his Soviet citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in Germany, Solzhenitsyn moved to New England,
where he worked in seclusion in a well-guarded compound near
Cavendish, Vermont. Always irrascible, Solzhenitsyn mercilessly
criticized the US that gave him refuge as an immoral society
weakened by prosperity and predicted he would one day return to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s, this seemed like a wild dream. But as the
Communist Party released its grip in the late years of the Soviet
Union, Solzhenitsyn's early works, banned for most of the Communist
era, suddenly became available. They found a willing audience.
Their main theme _ that labor camps were not the exception of
Soviet socialist society, but the very essence of it _ was a
powerful message for people learning for the first time the full
truth about their past. Between 1989 and 1992, millions of copies
of Solzhenitsyn's books and essays were sold in the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   So great was the moral authority of Solzhenitsyn's writing that
upon his return to Russia in 1994, some here thought that he would
assume a leading position in Russian society.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the only person who is capable of uniting the divided,
dispersed unfortunate people under the banner of national rebirth,
and give it back hope and confidence in its strengths,'' wrote the
literary journal Strannik in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It did not work out that way. Solzhenitsyn has spent the past
few years lamenting Russia's crime-ridden, poverty-stricken state
and railing at the country's current leaders for allowing the the
country to become that way.
</P>
<P>
   This is not so daring in today's Russia, and Solzhenitsyn
gradually has become irrelevent, a dissident writer in a society
that has lost interest in both its dissidents and its writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solzhenitsyn was important when his writings said things no
one else dared say,'' said Masha Lipman, deputy editor of Itogi
magazine. ``Russians today don't need anybody to tell them that
they are poor and the authorities are corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, he defied the regime,'' Lipman said. Now, he defies
the people's indifference.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Solzhenitsyn has continued to write
prolifically, but he has faced a number of setbacks. He was kicked
off prime time television show for being boring and irrelevant. He
was ignored during a speech in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   And worst of all for an writer whose works once gripped millions
of readers in Russia and throughout the world, almost no one buys
his books.
</P>
<P>
   His latest work, ``Russia in Collapse'' had an original print
run of only 5,000 when it was released in June, although a second
5,000 copies were later ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The book, a seething denunciation Yeltsin's Russia which
predicted the economic collapse of Aug. 17, much like Solzhenitsyn
once predicted the end of Communism.
</P>
<P>
   His birthday has brought a temporary surge of public attention
for the reclusive writer. Three major television networks have run
documentaries on the writer _ a fourth was taken off the air by the
Solzhenitsyn family's request, in a bit of unintentional irony from
a man who used to have to smuggle his works out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the only writer in Russia to whom the title `great' can
be attached without any hesitation,'' said the liberal business
daily Kommersant this week. ``Of course the rotten Soviet system
would have fallen sooner or later, but it was Solzhenitsyn who
drove the stake through its heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
