<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MORELLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERAL REPUBLICAN MORELLA WOMAN OF THE HOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrat Geraldine Ferraro hasn't had any luck
getting a call through to her, and the local Republican committee
is resorting to faxing her a letter. That's because Representative
Constance Morella of Maryland is keeping her own counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The six-term lawmaker, considered the House's most liberal
Republican, is in uncommon demand these days as she weighs whether
she will vote to impeach President Clinton. Her decision is
critical since it, along with those of a small group of wavering
GOP moderates, could seal Clinton's fate when articles of
impeachment come to the House floor next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton doesn't get Connie Morella, the ballgame for him is
over,'' said Mark Plotkin, a political analyst for WAMU, the
Washington area's public radio station. ``She is every Democrat's
favorite Republican. If she votes against the president, there is
no real hope for anybody else supporting him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morella is keeping her constituents _ she represents a
suburban Washington district that is 60 percent Democratic _ in
suspense. She ducks reporters' questions and isn't taking calls.
</P>
<P>
   Friday she stayed home from her Capitol Hill office and watched
the House Judiciary Committee impeachment debate and votes on
television. She listened to Clinton's late-afternoon remarks on the
car radio as she drove to a GOP dinner in Annapolis, the state
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Anne Leary, her press secretary, said Morella is keeping an
open mind while she spends the weekend studying the Judiciary
Committee proceedings and reviewing her mail, e-mail, and phone
messages. Morella has not spoken with either the White House or GOP
leadership, Leary said, and she does not intend to make her
deliberating public.
</P>
<P>
   The silence irks former vice presidential candidate Geraldine
Ferraro, a longtime friend of Morella's. She said that like Maine
Senator Margaret Chase Smith, who in her 1950 Declaration of
Conscience speech condemned the witchhunts of Senator Joseph
McCarthy, women lawmakers need to come forward and say
``impeachment is wrong for the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching a lot of television, and I haven't seen any
women speak up and say `this is what I believe,''' said Ferraro,
explaining why she was trying to reach and lobby Morella Friday.
``Women need to exercise leadership, do what is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro said she is not coordinating her efforts with the White
House, but rather is acting as an ``American and as a woman.'' In
addition to Morella, who did not call back, Ferraro made
impeachment-related calls to Republican Representatives Marge
Roukema of New Jersey, Tillie Fowler of Florida, Nancy Johnson of
Connecticut, and Sue Kelly of New York.
</P>
<P>
   None of those women, however, has quite the same experience as
Morella _ who has raised nine children, including six of her late
sister's _ and no one has a district quite as Democratic. A native
of Somerville, Mass. and a former school teacher, Morella has kept
her seat by voting against GOP initiatives more often than any
Republican in Congress. She opposed seven of the 10 items in House
Speaker Newt Gingrich's Contract with America, supports abortion
rights, voted against the war in Iraq, and has such a strong
environmental record that she was endorsed in the last election by
the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton carried Morella's affluent Montogomery County district
with 57 percent of the vote in 1996 and 53 percent of the vote in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Morella, 67, a quiet, likeable lawmaker who tries not to
antagonize the GOP leadership with her votes, was reelected with 60
percent of the vote in November. The margin would have been higher,
polls showed, if her opponent, civil rights activist Ralph Neas,
had not run television and radio ads criticizing Morella's vote in
October to allow the House to move forward with an impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt it was absolutely necessary, in fairness to the
country and the president, that all sides be aired,'' said Leary,
explaining Morella's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Haller, president of Potomac Survey Research, a Bethesda,
Md., polling firm, said more than 70 percent of the voters in
Montgomery County are against impeachment. Voting to impeach the
president could be risky for Morella, Haller said, both in her own
district and particularly as she weighs a run for the Senate in the
heavily Democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's likely to be an albatross that will be difficult for her
to shake,'' Haller said. ``But this must be an excruciating dilemma
for a moderate Republican and certainly the hardest vote of
Morella's 12 years in office. With her indecision, it strikes me
that she is teetering.''
</P>
<P>
   Morella is getting pressure from her party. Members of the
Montgomery County Republican Central Committee were meeting Friday
night to draft a letter they will fax to Morella, reminding her she
is a Republican and urging her to vote to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we are the minority party in her district, and we
rarely do this, but we feel strongly that Connie Morella should
vote to impeach and remove the president for committing perjury,''
said Robert Miller, the committee's chairman. ``We will be very
disappointed if she doesn't support this view.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, aides to Morella indicated the congresswoman
might entertain a censure resolution instead of impeachment if the
president came forward with more contrition. But appearing this
week at a series of events _ a meeting on the president's race
initiative, a visit to a hospice, a breakfast with business and
civic leaders in the district _ Morella wouldn't tip her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, her offices are being flooded with constituent calls
that are close to evenly split, pro and con, on impeachment, Leary
said. She is also fielding ``99,000 requests'' from journalists who
suddenly want to interview with the usually low-profile Morella.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know know what she is going to do,'' Leary said,
``but that's not what most reporters want to hear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 1956EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
