u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDEX-HIKE-BOS &LR;      12-11 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDEX-HIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE CROSS SEEKS 9.9% MEDEX GOLD RATE HIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes monthly rates text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts proposed
Friday to raise 1999 premiums for its Medex Gold supplemental
insurance for seniors by 9.9 percent to $283.97 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past Medex increases, which met with sharp opposition
from senior advocates, the proposal was greeted Friday with
relatively mild disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry to see the rate increases, but we are glad that
Medex remains a viable option for seniors who can afford it,'' said
Geoff Wilkinson, executive director of the Massachusetts Senior
Action Council, an advocate group.
</P>
<P>
   Medex Gold, like other so-called medigap supplemental insurance,
helps pay medical bills not covered by Medicare, the federal health
insurance program for seniors and disabled citizens. The plan has
more than 53,700 members.
</P>
<P>
   Medex Gold remains one of a handful of options for seniors who
want unlimited prescription drug coverage. Earlier this year,
Medicare health maintenance organizations in Massachusetts said
they will no longer offer unlimited drug benefits starting Jan. 1.
The change leaves Medex, United HealthCare Insurance Co., and
Hartford Life Insurance Co. as the only plans open to the general
public with unlimited prescription coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Medex rates require approval by the state's
insurance commissioner, Linda Ruthardt, who has 30 days to act.
Once approved, the rates will become effective March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Because the increases are just under 10 percent, Ruthardt does
not have to call a public hearing on the rates, though she has the
authority to do so. Rate increases at or over 10 percent
automatically trigger a requirement for hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross also proposed to increase premiums for its other
medigap insurance products, including a 4.3 percent hike for Medex
Bronze, 3.9 percent for Medex Core, 9.9 percent for Medex Silver,
8.9 percent for Medex Standard, and 9.9 percent for Medex Basic.
Only Gold, Bronze and Core are accepting new members during open
enrollment period between Feb. 1 and March 31. Of the three plans,
only Gold offers drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed rates, premiums for Medex Bronze would rise
to $110.54 a month, while Medex Core would be $58.99.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Massachusetts Blue Cross plan said its executives
are in discussion with Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Rhode Island
about a range of possible deals, including affiliation or merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some discussions with them, and we hope to continue
those discussions,'' said Peter Meade, executive vice president of
Blue Cross in Massachusetts. ``There are a whole list of
possibilities, from joint marketing to affiliation to the plans
coming together in some form.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Rhode Island Blue Cross confirmed the
preliminary talks with Massachusetts Blue Cross, but added that the
plan had also talked with numerous other potential suitors,
including Wellpoint Health Networks, a former Blue Cross plan in
Southern California that converted into a for-profit insurance
company, and Anthem Inc., a company based in Indianapolis that
operates Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans in several states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field is still wide open,'' said Scott Fraser, the Blue
Cross spokesman in Rhode Island. The plan, which has a commanding
50 percent market share in Rhode Island, this week announced its
third consecutive year of red ink, a projected $22 million loss for
1998. Blue Cross said it would raise premiums 12 percent to 17
percent next year and begin looking for a business partner to cope
with the financial decline.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONTHLY RATES FOR MEDEX MEDICARE &QL; 
(! used a column separator) &QL; 
 &QL; 
