<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-VOTE-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SUBURBAN REPS UNDECIDED ON WHETHER TO IMPEACH, PHILLY DEMS
WON'T
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 11 -- Moderate Republicans who represent
Philly's nearby suburbs, are still on the fence about whether to
impeach Clinton, while the city's three U.S. House Democrats are
standing firm behind the President.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County's Jon Fox, Delaware County's Curt Weldon, and
Bucks County's Jim Greenwood, are among a group of roughly 40
lawmakers in the House whose ``swing'' vote could help determine
the fate of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Niko Yen, a spokeswoman for Greenwood, said the congressman's
office has been flooded with calls from residents who want to voice
their opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty equal the number of calls we've gotten from
each side,'' Yen said. ``But if it leaned one way it would be that
more people who called were for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment process gathered steam in Washington Friday, as
the House Judiciary Committee voted on which impeachment charges to
offer up. Clinton addressed the nation in a short speech and
apologized for putting members of congress and the nation through
this process.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, that didn't matter to Philly's three
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Chaka Fattah, Robert Borski, and Bob Brady said they will
not vote to impeach Clinton no matter which impeachment articles
are approved by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Peck, a spokeswoman for Borski, said he thinks none of the
impeachment articles amount to high crimes and misdemeanors on
which to throw the president out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Fattah's spokeswoman, Rebecca Kersor said the congressman is
leaning toward censure, while the other two Philly Reps. are
undecided on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Kersor said the city's Representatives were close allies and
were eager to move on with the nation's business.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fattah) is pretty confident the president will not be
impeached,'' Kersor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
