A5914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EARNINGS12-COX     12-11 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tighter quarter leads to lower profit estimates
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_ Coca-Cola's stock dropped 4.8 percent Friday and
analysts started cutting their earnings estimates again after the
company warned its fourth-quarter profit will be below
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's third-quarter earnings were below original
projections, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing different than what is going on with Gillette
and Procter &AMP; Gamble,'' said Dana H. Halberg, president of the
Arden Group, an Atlanta money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings disappointments reflect lower demand because of
economic problems around the world and are affecting all companies
with global sales, not just Coca-Cola, Halberg added.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which produces three-fourths of its profit overseas,
said it expects to report fourth-quarter earnings of 24 to 25 cents
a share. Wall Street analysts had predicted a profit of 30 cents a
share, against 32 cents earned a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to the news, five of the 11 analysts who follow the
company trimmed their profit projections. The analysts cut their
full-year 1998 forecast to $1.40 a share from $1.46, according to
First Call, which tracks estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Those same analysts reduced their 1999 forecasts to a range of
$1.40 to $1.55 a share, said Chuck Hill, director of research at
First Call. The average forecast for 1999 had been as high as $1.79
a share.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola blamed ``continued economic and political
uncertainty'' in announcing worldwide unit case volume would be
down ``slightly'' in the fourth quarter. Case volume was up 10
percent in the 1997 quarter, a period that included more shipping
days, the company noted.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola specifically cited economic uncertainty in Brazil,
Germany, Japan, Russia, Southeast Asia, Venezuela and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said the changing value of other currencies vs.
the dollar is still hurting earnings, to the tune of 10 percent in
both the fourth quarter and all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Those problems may make the next couple of years ``rough'' for
Coca-Cola, said analyst John C. Maxwell of Davenport &AMP; Co. in
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell cut his 1999 earnings estimate to $1.40 a share, making
him the most pessimistic of the analysts who made changes Friday.
He now expects Coca-Cola's first-half earnings in 1999 to be below
those of the comparable 1998 period, when the company earned 82
cents per share including one-time items.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell also looks for the third-quarter results to be about the
same as Coca-Cola reported for this year's July-September quarter,
or 35 cents a share, excluding a gain.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Maxwell said he likes Cola-Cola long-term, echoing the
sentiments of other analysts.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Jennifer F. Solomon of Salomon Smith Barney,
upgraded her rating on Coca-Cola stock to ``buy'' from ``neutral,''
according to Dow Jones News Service. She suggested in a research
note that the stock price currently reflects expectations for
slower earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   While Friday's warning was a surprise, Halberg does not expect
Coca-Cola shares to decline sharply, unless the overall market
takes a tumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stock will probably go sideways for a while,'' Solomon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which is a major holding in many of the portfolios
managed by the Arden Group, has a built-in cushion against
declines, Halberg suggested, partly because of the loyalty of
investors like Warren E. Buffett of Berkshire Hathaway, and
SunTrust Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people who aren't going to sell. And for those who
sell, you have a company that is going to buy back some stock,
probably,'' Halberg noted.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors who have kept Coca-Cola over the years have
become millionaires, even though the stock hasn't risen every year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Coca-Cola has traded as high as $87.93 3/4. But
Friday's decline of $3.18 3/4 to $66.06 1/4 means the stock is now
down 5.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock finishes with a loss for the year, it would be the
first time that has happened since 1980, when the shares fell 3.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
