<HEADER>
A5916 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-PEPSI12-COX     12-11 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-PEPSI12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pepsi stoic, but industry observers say it hurts
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the never-ending cola wars, Coca-Cola Co. has
dropped what amounts to an atomic bomb on archrival Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Pepsico _ at least publicly _ said little Friday
about the deal in which Coca-Cola will purchase Cadbury Schweppes'
brands outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we're going to have to take a close look at every
aspect of this deal,'' said Pepsico spokesman Brad Shaw. ``Beyond
that, there's really nothing else we can say.''
</P>
<P>
   But others weren't as tight-lipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes things substantially,'' said Tom Pirko, a New
York-based beverage consultant. ``Remember those adventure stories
you used to watch on TV or in the movies, where a person is
standing in a room and the walls start closing in and that person
is holding out his arms to keep that from happening? Well, for
Pepsi, the walls are getting uncomfortably closer.''
</P>
<P>
   For some industry experts, a more likely pairing in fact would
have been Cadbury Schweppes and Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a constant set of rumors,'' Pirko said. ``Even though
everyone talked about Cadbury and Pepsi, there was an essential
unwillingness there. There's more of an affinity there between the
companies (Pepsico and Cadbury) because they're No. 2 and No. 3 and
the fact that they've already done some business together. Everyone
always wants to team up against No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, it will become harder for Pepsico to ``defend itself
against a company with that much punching power.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico declined to comment on any possible talks with Cadbury.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico has become increasingly aggressive this year in trying
to take market share from No. 1 Coca-Cola. It has sued the
Atlanta-based company in New York federal court, alleging antitrust
violations in the way Coke structures its contracts with
independent food service distributors. Coca-Cola denies the claims.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico also is fighting Coke's efforts to purchase and expand
its reach in India and France. And the launch of Pepsi One, a
one-calorie diet soft drink, is designed to undercut the popularity
of Diet Coke. The company is expected to spend $100 million
promoting Pepsi One over the next 12 months, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pepsi is going to look very carefully at this deal,''
said John Sicher, publisher of Beverage Digest. ``Pepsi has been,
in the last couple of months, performing very strong in the U.S.
... Basically, as with any deal in the soft drink industry, how it
plays out and how it affects competitive dynamics simply won't be
known for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are certainly good and strong brands Coke is buying, so
in certain markets Coke is in an even more stronger competitive
situation,'' Sicher said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, just days ago Cadbury Schweppes' Plano, Texas-based
U.S. unit announced it had renewed a distribution contract with
Pepsico's Pepsi Bottling Group for the company's Dr Pepper and 7UP
brands. Under the agreement, Pepsi Bottling, which is scheduled to
be spun off from Pepsico in 1999, bottles and distributes 32
percent of Cadbury's soft drinks sold in the United States. By
contrast, Coca-Cola handles 24 percent of Cadbury's domestic
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico's Shaw said the Coca-Cola-Cadbury Schweppes deal would
have no impact on its existing U.S. agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bellas, chairman and chief executive officer of Beverage
Marketing Corp., said the deal puts another arrow in Coke's quiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep chipping away, adding one (market) share, then two
shares, then when you wake up 10 years from now, it's really piled
up,'' he said. ``In Atlanta, they are long-term players.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
