<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-TESTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US AGENCY RECOMMENDS IDENTIFYING AIDS-POSITIVE PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After repeated delays and months of contentious
debate within the Clinton administration, the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention has for the first time recommended that
health-care providers report the names of individuals testing
positive for the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC guidelines, which are open for a public comment for 30
days, would allow states to adopt whatever system they choose to
track the epidemic as long as it provides high-quality data. But
the center ``advises'' states to adopt names-based reporting rather
than a system that uses codes to hide the identify of infected
indivduals.
</P>
<P>
   While AIDS activists and health-care providers welcomed improved
``surveillance'' or tracking of the epidemic, they said mandatory
reporting of names is self-defeating and warned that it will only
increase _ rather than diminish _ the public health risk of more
infection and death.
</P>
<P>
   The stigma of AIDS and the human immunodeficiency virus, they
say, is still powerful enough to steer people away from testing if
they have to identify themselves by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't produce the names that such a system depends upon for
success,'' said Steven Fisher, communications director for the
Washington-based AIDS Action group. ``Individuals at risk should be
tested often, voluntarily and confidentiality.''
</P>
<P>
   The CDC plans to implement its new guidelines after 30 days.
Though the agency says it will give states wide leeway, states as
well as public and private health-care providers fear the agency
will channel funding toward systems that require names reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines are a compromise after what one high-ranking
administration official described as ``hearty debates on all
levels.'' Privacy concerns, in fact, prompted the CDC to allow
states to implement alternative ``unique identifier'' systems _
even though it had a strong preference for names only _ and to
strongly urge states to maintain anonymous HIV testing sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CDC recognizes that confidentiality concerns are valid and
that's why the CDC is not closing the door to other systems,'' said
Laurie Boeder, spokeswoman for the Human Health and Services
Department. ``The CDC will provide technical assistance and funding
to all states _ but they must meet certain performance standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Names-reporting, Boeder pointed out, has always been
successfully used to track epidemics such as syphyllis and
tuberculosis -- with very few breaches of confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly understand concerns about confidentiality,'' said
Kevin M. De Cock, director of CDC's HIV/AIDS prevention division,
in an interview this summer. ``Terrible things could happen
someplace, somewhere, but experience says this hasn't happened so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   The push to expand HIV surveillance _ tracking how and where the
virus strikes so prevention and treatment is better focused _ began
in 1996 when the number of AIDS cases began to drop for the first
time, while HIV infections increased.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 30 states now require names reporting, while half a
dozen, including Massachusetts, are developing or have implemented
code-based systems. But many states with the highest HIV-infected
populations, including California, are now debating what kind of
tracking system to adopt.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC has said it favors names because special codes that
contain personal information without revealing identity are not
necessarily reliable or efficient. States using codes have battled
problems with reliability and completeness of information, the CDC
said.
</P>
<P>
   State administrators who run these programs reject the CDC's
analysis as flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even within the administration there remains a deep
unease about ``the possible impact of names-based systems on the
willingess of certain populations to seek HIV testing,'' said the
official, who asked for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Communities increasingly hard-hit by HIV are not white and
homosexual, as they once were, but poor, black, Hispanic and
immigrant communities, according to the CDC. But these communities,
providers say, already are marginalized and fearful of government
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it would only send further people underground because
the fear and stigma of being HIV-positive is still so great,'' said
Barbara Gomes-Beach, executive director of the Multicultural AIDS
Coalition in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   A CDC-funded survey published in October by the Journal of the
American Medical Association found that anonymous testing increases
the chances that individuals test themselves early and seek care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
