A5924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-TOBACCO-HNS &LR;      12-11 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TOBACCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL AWARDS TEXAS LAWYERS $3.3 BILLION IN TOBACCO CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A yearlong controversy over tobacco legal fees
came to a head with a $3.3 billion payday for five private law
firms that helped Attorney General Dan Morales win Texas' $17.3
billion settlement from cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   The award by a national arbitration panel is larger than the
$2.6 billion award approved for the lawyers earlier this year by a
federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   But Morales said the decision, reached Thursday night in
Washington, should guarantee that the state won't have to pay the
main team of outside lawyers because the tobacco industry has
agreed to pay the fees set by the arbitrators.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't immediately known, however, how the arbitrators'
action would affect another outside lawyer, a friend of Morales who
had a separate arrangement with the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   That attorney, Marc Murr of Houston, was paid $1 million by the
national arbitrators. But he has a $260 million fee award set by a
separate state arbitration panel _ not payable by the tobacco
industry _ that he could ask a federal court to enforce and order
the state to pay.
</P>
<P>
   That would surely prompt Gov. George W. Bush to attempt to
intervene. He has been an outspoken critic of the attorneys' fees
in the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has called Murr's role in the tobacco suit ``critical''
and said he does not think he was adequately paid. But other
lawyers in the case said he did little, if any, work. Murr did not
return phone calls from the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Morales called the $3.3 billion award ``fair and reasonable''
for the five law firms headed by Walter Umphrey and Wayne Reaud of
Beaumont, John O'Quinn and John Eddie Williams of Houston, and
Harold Nix of Daingerfield. O'Quinn is currently the center of a
disbarment trial accusing him of unethical solicitation of clients
after a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who led a fight against Morales over the tobacco legal
fees earlier this year, said he ``will never understand &UR; '' &LR;  why
private law firms should collect $3.3 billion ``for working less
than two years on a case that was settled before it went to
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fee seems totally out of proportion for the work
performed,'' he said, and vowed to fight any attempt by lawyers in
the tobacco case to get any part of their fees from Texas
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General-elect John Cornyn, who also has fought the
legal fees and will succeed Morales on Jan. 1, said he will
investigate the contingency contract with the five law firms and
look into Murr's involvement in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the main five lawyers said the
arbitrators' award ``will not reduce the payments the state will
receive under the settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   They noted that when the Texas lawsuit over smoking-related
health care costs and tobacco marketing practices was filed in
March 1996 ``no one predicted the state would recover a dime from
the (tobacco) industry. This industry had never paid anything in
its 40-year history of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco industry was finally held responsible,'' they
said. ``The citizens of Texas can stand tall in their victory over
the tobacco industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said the three national arbitrators, who included
Texas Tech Law School Dean Frank Newton, set a base fee of 10
percent of the state's $17.3 billion settlement. Then the panel
increased that by a so-called ``difficulty'' factor to take into
account Texas' ``contributions as pioneers in tobacco litigation
and the tremendous results we obtained.''
</P>
<P>
   That put the award at about 19 percent of the Texas settlement.
A contingency agreement the five lawyers signed with Morales when
the anti-tobacco suit was filed guaranteed them only 15 percent of
whatever damages the state won or negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette companies will limit their payments to lawyers
representing Texas and other states involved in anti-tobacco
litigation to $500 million a year. Since most states have now
reached settlements with the industry, it will be an undetermined
number of years before the lawyers are paid in full.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco company Brown &AMP; Williamson said the awards are obscene
and shouldn't be viewed as a precedent for awards to the rest of
the states.
</P>
<P>
   If five lawyers alone were to share the $3.3 billion award, it
would compute to about $120,000 to $150,000 an hour, based on
fulltime work during the nearly two years that elapsed between the
time the anti-tobacco suit was filed and the settlement was
announced last January.
</P>
<P>
   But as many as 120 lawyers may share in the award, including
other members of the five firms, a spokesman for the lawyers said.
And part of the award _ an amount not disclosed _ will go to Ron
Motley, an anti-tobacco specialist from South Carolina who
participated in the Texas case.
</P>
<P>
   Civil justice reform groups immediately fired broadsides at the
award.
</P>
<P>
   John Butler, chairman of Texans for Reasonable Legal Fees, a
Houston-based group, said the size of the award ``shocks common
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrators also set fees for attorneys in Mississippi and
Florida, the only two states to settle anti-tobacco suits before
Texas. The private lawyers in Florida, which settled with cigarette
makers for $13.2 billion, were awarded $3.4 billion, or a 26
percent contingency fee, and lawyers in Mississippi, which settled
for $4.1 billion, got $1.4 billion or 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The contingency percentages for the lawyers in those states were
higher than those for the Texas team because of a greater
``difficulty'' factor.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Williamson was not pleased. ``When we reached a
settlement with each of these three states, we agreed to pay
`reasonable compensation' to the lawyers representing the states.
The award of $8.1 billion defies anyone's definition of
`reasonable,''' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
