<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE LIKELY TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Barring a last-minute change of plans,
captain Rob Blake will return to the Los Angeles Kings' lineup
tonight, ending a disastrous 15-game absence during which the team
posted a 3-12 record.
</P>
<P>
   With Blake's return at 7 p.m. against Vancouver at the Forum,
the Kings will be as close to being whole as they have been all
season. Only three players remain injured, which qualifies as a
health boom for the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It solidifies our defense,'' Coach Larry Robinson said of
Blake's return from a broken foot. ``And it gives a bunch of
players who haven't had much confidence a little psychological
boost.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake is one of a number of significant Kings to be sidelined
for lengthy stretches this season. But with the returns of goalies
Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr, No. 1 center Jozef Stumpel,
defenseman Doug Bodger and now Blake, Robinson will get his best
look this season at something resembling his entire team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard to judge our team,'' Blake said of the Kings
(7-17-3). ``We haven't had our full lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake is expected to receive full duty tonight, playing on
special teams as well as at even strength.
</P>
<P>
   Bure update (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled Vancouver star Pavel Bure, the subject of trade
rumors involving the Kings (among other teams), may be traded soon
by the Canucks, but it's uncertain where he'll be going.
</P>
<P>
   Canucks general manager Brian Burke was in Vancouver on Friday,
not in Los Angeles with his team. The New York Rangers, New York
Islanders and Kings are believed to be three of the leading
contenders to acquire Bure.
</P>
<P>
   Kings general manager Dave Taylor has declined comment on Bure.
But the Canucks are believed to desire a front-line center in any
deal for Bure, which would mean the Kings would have to give up
either Jozef Stumpel or Olli Jokinen, players they would be
reluctant to part with.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible deals involving Bure would be one that would
bring the Canucks a package of players from the Rangers, including
center Nicklas Sundstrom, or a deal with the Islanders for unsigned
winger Zigmund Palffy. The Canucks might then include Palffy in a
second trade for a center.
</P>
<P>
   __ Loose pucks: Mark Visheau, usually a defenseman, played right
wing during practice Friday on a line with Josh Green and Nathan
LaFayette. Robinson was uncertain whether he would use the
combination in tonight's game. He said it might hinge on the
availability of center Yanic Perreault, whose fiancee was in labor
Friday. ...Winger Steve McKenna (strained abdomen) was placed on
the injured-reserve list. ... Prospect Pavel Rosa, sidelined the
past month with symptoms of post-concussion syndrome, may start
skating soon. Rosa is assigned to the IHL's Long Beach Ice Dogs.
... Unsigned defenseman Aki Berg, who is playing in his native
Finland, has been chosen to play for his country in the Baltica
Cup, a tournament later this month in Moscow. Berg has six goals
and nine points in 22 games for his Finnish team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
