u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-LEE-IMPEACH-H     12-11 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-LEE-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON DEMOCRAT APPEALS FOR CENSURE, NOT IMPEACHMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As one of President Clinton's most ardent
defenders, Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas has emerged as a
vociferous combatant on the Constitution, arguing that to impeach
the nation's chief executive for lying about sex would trample that
``sacred document.''
</P>
<P>
   In a last-minute appeal Friday to her Republican colleagues on
the House Judiciary Committee, Jackson Lee called it
``preposterous'' to consider his impeachment. She instead urged the
panel to adopt a resolution of censure, as the ``right, punitive
and just'' punishment for the president's conduct in the Monica
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did our founding fathers have in mind individual personal
behavior when they described an impeachable offense? A re-reading
of the Constitution will suggest that they had no such triviality
in mind, but rather, major offenses against the state,'' the
congresswoman told her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What major ... offenses have been committed? How has the
unacceptable behavior of this chief executive brought severe damage
and harm to the nation? What actions have posed a threat to the
security of the nation and its position in world politics?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee, one of 16 Democrats on the judiciary panel, has
taken the lead among her colleagues in pushing censure as an
alternative to impeachment. In remarks several weeks ago as the
committee was just beginning its impeachment inquiry, she first
raised the possibility of censure, not only as a way out of ``this
mess,'' as she put it then, but as possibly a worse punishment for
Clinton than an impeachment trial where he might be acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine a situation where the president of the United
States would have to endure a public reprimand in the House of
Representatives?'' she asked at the time, shaking her head. ``I
can't understand why that would not be an acceptable resolution of
this to my Republican colleagues ... rather than dragging the
country through a long impeachment process.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's 21 Republicans instead voted through articles of
impeachment Friday. The House will meet in special session next
week for a vote as early as Thursday on the committee's final
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the committee is not likely to approve a resolution of
censure as a ``fallback position,'' as one committee aide put it,
that alternative could still be raised during the floor debate if
the Republican leadership allows it. If they do, it will likely be
the resolution authored by Jackson Lee and three of her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   It acknowledges that Clinton made false statements about his
``reprehensible conduct'' with Lewinsky, took steps to delay the
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation of the affair,
and should remain subject to criminal and civil penalties after he
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Committee member William Delahunt, D-Mass., called Jackson Lee
``a critical player in drafting'' a resolution that the Democrats
hope will appeal to enough moderate Republicans to head off a vote
by the full House on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all sat down and hammered out what we thought would be
language that was necessary and most acceptable,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In her appeal Friday, Jackson Lee said that censure would at
least allow ``the healing of the nation'' to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us promote censure, not impeachment. For impeachment would
not be grounded in the Constitution and has not been proven beyond
a reasonable doubt,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the vote on the House floor next week, she
added: ``To those ... House members who are searching their souls
today, with censure you stamp this president's legacy forever, but
you maintain the stability of the institution of the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee, who represents the 18th congressional district , is
following in the footsteps of another black congresswoman from
Houston _ Barbara Jordan, who 24 years ago gained national
prominence as a member of the committee that drew up articles of
impeachment against President Nixon for his conduct in the
Watergate scandal. She is all too aware that her performance in the
present impeachment drama is likely to be compared to Jordan's.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't mind the comparison, especially when it comes to
defending the integrity of the Constitution as Jordan did so
eloquently during the Watergate proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson Lee has delivered statements reminiscent of the
high oratory of Jordan, her remarks have often been closer to
street fighting. When Starr testified before the committee last
month, she seemed to delight in mixing it up with him. She once
referred to him as ``a ticking time bomb,'' determined to destroy
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deny that I am, and I will continue to be, persistent
in my ... insistence that this proceeding be fair to the president
and to the people of this country,'' she told a reporter recently
when asked if Clinton would be able to get an objective hearing
before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Her battle against impeachment has not been easy for Republican
committee members to deal with, especially committee chairman Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., who has engaged in a number of parliamentary
wrestling matches with her.
</P>
<P>
   Although irritated by some of her interruptions in the committee
hearings, Hyde commended her persistence in a recent comment to a
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish she were on my side,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
