<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-NIEDERHOFFER-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAPPINGS OF FADED RICHES: SOLD! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 13)  
 (af)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A five-foot horn of plenty made of silver and podolian ox horn,
which once belonged to King Charles XV of Sweden, is Victor
Niederhoffer's favorite in his collection of silver trophy pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But Niederhoffer can no longer afford his horn of plenty. He
desperately needs money, so Sotheby's will auction his extensive
collection on Tuesday. Indeed, he has already borrowed against the
$3 million that Sotheby's hopes to fetch.
</P>
<P>
   The money manager lost all his capital in October 1997, when the
Global Systems funds he managed for himself, his family and
investors were hurt first by his leveraged and unhedged
speculations in the Thai stock market, and then by his bet that the
United States market would not decline drastically. It plunged 7
percent on Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The two catastrophes wiped out the funds, once valued at $130
million, leaving them with margin calls that those in the industry
estimated at $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at age 55, Victor Niederhoffer is struggling to pay his
debts, support the four of his six children who are still at home,
maintain continuity of the family's life style and tiptoe back into
the only business he knows: trading.
</P>
<P>
   The family still lives in the 20,000-square-foot home that he
built 12 years ago in Weston, Conn. (Since the debacle, he has
taken a mortgage against the sprawling house, complete with its own
squash court.)
</P>
<P>
   He has also raised cash by selling a small investment banking
business for about $1 million. Those moves have helped pay down
debts and provide the $1 million in pretax income he needs to
support his family and his tiny home-based trading operation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by the standards of the rich, the severity of
Niederhoffer's crisis is evident in his need to part with the
silver collection, assembled in the halcyon days when he was making
millions.
</P>
<P>
   A comeback from the devastation _ both financially and
psychologically _ has been far harder than even Niederhoffer had
imagined. ``It is hard to be resilient when you are 55,'' he said
during an interview last week in the double-height library of his
home.
</P>
<P>
   Niederhoffer, dressed typically in jeans, sport shirt and socks
_ he is not a fan of shoes _ seemed surprised at how difficult it
had become to trade. ``When you have bad fortune, your suppliers
and customers are afraid,'' he said. ``I am on a very short
leash.''
</P>
<P>
   How is he doing? ``The jury is still out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is looking to past recoveries as a blueprint for his future.
``I stopped playing squash for two years, when I was 23,'' he said.
``Then I had a match with a 50-year-old schoolteacher. I lost, and
I heard voices reverberating, saying I would never come back. But I
went on to win the national championship four more times.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, in his years as a trader, he had at least an
intellectual concept of the dangers. In a letter Niederhoffer wrote
for the Sotheby's catalogue, he said, ``The proximate reason I
collected was that my business of speculation in commodities was
highly volatile.'' He added that collecting gave him ``the ability
to store value in pieces I could enjoy, use and invest in.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver proved a prescient investment. In addition to putting his
own capital into the funds over the years, he said, ``I borrowed
money personally to put in.'' Even as the Thai debacle slashed the
value, he borrowed further. ``In retrospect, it was the worst
speculation of my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the funds imploded, ``I read an article that listed the 10
characteristics of depression,'' Niederhoffer said. ``I had all of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But he never considered giving up. ``I have six children,'' he
said. ``I have a lot of obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Always an eccentric _ he still says the only paper he reads is
The National Enquirer _ Niederhoffer said he had been lonely of
late. After 20 years of success, many investors had become friends.
Today, some remain loyal. Albert Hallac, whose company, Weston
Capital Management, marketed the funds and was himself an investor,
said Niederhoffer had handled the debacle with integrity.
</P>
<P>
   But many of his friendships unraveled. ``My phone stopped
ringing a lot,'' he said. ``When you stop making money for people,
you lose your utility.''
</P>
<P>
   He feels that it is important that he suffered with his
investors. ``A captain should never let the ship sink without going
down with it,'' he said. As for his own psychology, ``I don't
believe I had a death wish,'' Niederhoffer said. ``Where I was,
good things happened. Of the people who worked for me, six or seven
became billionaires.''
</P>
<P>
   Today he waivers between contrition about the losses and a
stubborn conviction that what he did was rational. ``I am saddened
and chastened,'' he said. ``My wisdom is quite suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added: ``My modus operandi is very analytical and
hopefully scientific. But I ran into some unexpected
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years from now, if things went well, would he make such
bets again? ``I would do it,'' he said. ``I don't think my strategy
was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He compares his downfall with the bailout of Long Term Capital
Management, the much bigger hedge fund recently rescued by Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have used Long Term's breathing time,'' Niederhoffer
said. Instead, he is selling his silver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
