<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-SCHEME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY SCAM SUSPECTS FREED ON BAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A 24-year-old BankBoston employee was released on
$100,000 bail in federal court Friday following her indictment
earlier in the week in connection with a $2.7 million money
laundering scheme that turned out to be an FBI sting operation.
</P>
<P>
   Two other defendants, whose accounts at the bank's West Newton
branch were among those used in the money laundering operation,
continued to be held after they were unable to satisfy bail
requirements set by US Magistrate Judge Lawrence P. Cohen. They
likely will be released next week, their lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The three, Oksana Galchanskaya of Needham, Roman Luban, 44, and
Samuil Lyubomirsky, 41, both of Newton, will be arraigned Thursday
with six New York-area men who were charged in the 43-count
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's bail hearing at the US District Court in Boston
produced few details about how the two-year sting operation began
or how the three Boston defendants were connected to the New York
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   FBI special agent John L. Riggi testified that the two
BankBoston accounts were used to accept wire transfers and issue
cashiers and regular checks to undercover FBI agents who posed as
narcotics dealers looking to launder their profits.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the undercover agents gave $2.7
million in small bills to the New York individuals, who held
themselves out as being able to exchange the cash for checks and
wire transfers. In all, 64 accounts were used, including the two at
BankBoston, to launder the money, the indictment stated.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by defense lawyers, Conrad J. Bletzer, Jr. and
Patrick J. Loftus, Riggi acknowledged that neither Luban or
Lyubomirsky were ever observed meeting with the New York principals
in the alleged scheme or with the FBI undercover agents who posed
as the drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a bit player,'' Bletzer said of Lyubomirsky, his client.
``At best he is a dupe who may have been used by someone else.''
Although he is not a citizen of the United States, Bletzer said
that Lyubomirsky was not a flight risk because he had been recently
been told that he needed surgery to remove a lump in his chest and
he may have to undergo cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Following the hearing, Galchanskaya's lawyer, Jonathan Shapiro
said he believes she met Luban and Lyubomirsky either from her work
as a customer sales representative at the bank or through the
Russian emigre community in the Boston area. Galchanskaya is a
native of Uzbekistan and has been a US citizen since August 1991.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the $100,000 bail, Galchanskaya pledged the equity in
her Needham condominium and her ownership in two taxi medallions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
