<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeing Social Benefits In Corporate Disclosure &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to socially conscious investing, sorting good
companies from bad can be tricky. Now, a group of socially
conscious funds and institutional investors have joined
environmental organizations and unions to ask securities regulators
to require companies to disclose more about pollution they have
caused, worker benefits they have cut and neighborhoods they have
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition, the Corporate Sunshine Working Group, includes
more than 60 organizations, from Kinder Lydenberg &AMP; Domini, a money
management firm, to Greenpeace to the United Steelworkers of
America.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to deliver a letter Monday to Arthur Levitt Jr.,
chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, requesting
stricter reporting rules. The group contends that better disclosure
by companies will help protect shareholders _ and prompt companies
to do good.
</P>
<P>
   Among the group's priorities is tightening the rules so that
companies responsible for polluting toxic sites are required to
tell their shareholders how much they must pay for a cleanup.
Current rules allow companies to escape disclosure of those
obligations by arguing that cleanup costs are not significant, even
if they add up to tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The group is also asking regulators to crack down on companies
that they say are violating even the current rules by giving
shareholders false and misleading information.
</P>
<P>
   Melody Petersen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Rising Chorus of `No' Votes On Executive Stock Plans &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In growing numbers, shareholders are registering their
complaints about executive stock compensation plans. That is one
finding of a recent study conducted by Strategic Compensation
Research Associates, based in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The firm looked at shareholder votes on 2,250 plans submitted by
companies between July 1997 and June 1998 for new stock
compensation plans and additions to existing plans.
</P>
<P>
   Such management proposals have typically received ``no'' votes
of 5 percent to 10 percent, on average, in recent years. In the
last year, however, the average vote against management reached
13.8 percent. At 270 companies, it was higher than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The negative votes would be even higher but for the fact that
many companies changed their proposals after floating trial
balloons with their biggest shareholders before putting their plans
to a vote, said Richard H. Wagner, president of Strategic
Compensation Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story that is not told in those statistics,'' he said,
``is the many concessions that boards are having to make to
institutional shareholders to secure their vote even before the
annual meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Bryant &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   25 Ways to Slice a Universe &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a few thinly veiled jabs at its rivals in the mutual fund
rankings business, a new logo and even a new name, Lipper Inc.,
formerly Lipper Analytical Services, disclosed its revamped fund
classifications last week.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher, changed the way it classifies funds to incorporate a
fund's investment style and what actually ends up in a fund's
portfolio, rather than simply relying on the investment objective
laid out in its prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar replaced old categories like growth and income,
equity income and aggressive growth with a ninefold array, divided
among large-, medium- and small-capitalization stocks and value,
blend and growth styles.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Lipper, which recently was acquired by Reuters and has
been working on its new classifications for at least a year. Lipper
has constructed a 25-place matrix that classifies equity funds in
one of five capitalization categories _ large, flexible, middle,
small or micro _ and in one of five objectives _ income, value,
general, growth or aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Steven M. Lipper, a senior vice president, said the
classifications were based on more than analysis of investment
style. ``Style-based structures don't address the question of
risk,'' he said, adding that Lipper's objectives incorporated a
measure of how far out on a limb a manager might be going.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies' classifications do not always agree with each
other. The Baron Asset fund, for example, is judged to be a
small-cap growth fund by Morningstar but is classified a mid-cap
growth equity fund by Lipper.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone prefers one classification system to another, it might
be fund managers, who with Lipper have more than twice as many
opportunities to find a grouping in which they can beat the
average.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Wyatt &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
