<HEADER>
A5974 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-FRENCH-OIL-ART-$A     12-11 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FRENCH-OIL-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRENCH OIL COMPANY THAT DOESN'T ACT THE PART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 13)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Total SA's fan club sent up a groan Dec. 1 when the news broke
that the company had agreed to buy Petrofina SA of Belgium for
$11.6 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blanched at the rich 37 percent premium that Total, the
well-regarded No. 2 oil company in France, had agreed to pay. They
complained that Total was betraying a proven strategy _ a
concentration on exploration and production, the more profitable
upstream parts of the oil business _ by buying the downstream-heavy
Belgian company with its refineries, chemical plants and gas
stations.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, Jeremy Hudson of Salomon Smith Barney, went as far
as slashing his rating of Total from ``outperform'' all the way to
``underperform,'' saying the Petrofina deal ``raises questions
about Total's future.'' And investors in general voted with their
feet, driving the stock price down 11 percent in a day.
</P>
<P>
   But Total chairman Thierry Desmarest says they groaned too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarest (pronounced day-muh-RAY), a reserved man with an
aristocratic air who turns 53 on Friday, is not easily fazed. When
markets reacted sourly to the Petrofina deal, he flew to London and
New York to make his case to money managers face to face. Within a
week, Total had doubled its estimates of the cost savings it will
wring from the merged company, and Desmarest was projecting that
adding Petrofina would accelerate the growth in Total's earnings
per share to 16 or 17 percent a year, from 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors may not believe it yet _ Total's stock finished the
week 21 percent below its last close before the merger announcement
_ but the company's track record suggests that those promising cost
and profit figures aren't just wishful thinking. In Desmarest's
five years as chairman, Total has shown how a European oil company
can excel, increasing production, sales and profits in an era of
slumping oil prices. Even in the painful first half of 1998, when
the industry was watching a quarter of its earnings evaporate,
Total managed to hold its own damage to less than 6 percent of net
income.
</P>
<P>
   Achievements like that have made Total popular with British and
American fund managers, who hold 42 percent of its shares. Total
stands out in a country noted for cosseted state-owned industries
that hemorrhage cash; large, well-run investor-owned companies like
it are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast with Elf Aquitaine, France's largest oil company,
is stark. Despite broad strides toward competitiveness since its
privatization in 1991, Elf retains an ``air of French
administration,'' said Aymeric de Gillaret, oil analyst at Societe
Generale de Paris in London. ``Total is free enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, it is largely because of Desmarest's thick-skinned
managerial talent for getting productivity up while keeping costs
down, coupled with an entrepreneurial audacity that does not shy
from tough decisions. Last year, in the face of a firestorm of
criticism and threats from the United States, he signed a $2
billion agreement to develop the immense South Pars gas fields in
Iran; he won his wager when Washington, after bitter debate, backed
down and waived sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, much has changed at Elf under Philippe Jaffre, who
became chairman around the time Desmarest took the helm at Total
and has since made his own considerable headway in cutting costs.
</P>
<P>
   But productivity at Elf continues to lag far behind Total. Last
year Total produced $584,000 of revenue for each employee, while
Elf managed only $505,000. And Total far outshone Elf in
profitability, with an operating margin of 6.1 percent of revenue,
compared with Elf's 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming chairman, Desmarest oversaw Total's worldwide
exploration and production, winning concessions in places like West
Africa, where drilling has revealed immense oil deposits. Since
1993, he has secured promising exploration rights in Nigeria,
Indonesia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Such aggressive exploration pushed up Total's crude-oil
production to 780 million barrels last year, 44 percent more than
in 1990, without increasing production staff. The acquisition of
Petrofina will mean an additional 240 million barrels a year.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Petrofina acquisition undoes a streamlining
move that Total made last year, when it sold its refineries and gas
stations in North America to Ultramar Diamond Shamrock. Total said
last Thursday that it would seek a buyer or partner for some of
Petrofina's U.S. refineries and gas stations as well.
</P>
<P>
   But Desmarest makes no apologies for the overall thrust back
into refining and retailing. ``Over the next five years, our
concern was to have our downstream pole strong enough,'' he said.
``It's important to keep sufficient balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts share that view. De Gillaret of Societe Generale
said the acquisition was ``wise, given the market developments,''
referring to planned combinations like Exxon-Mobil and British
Petroleum-Amoco that threaten to marginalize Total.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rebalancing the business is not the main point of the
merger. Steven Pfeifer, an oil analyst at Prudential Securities,
said the key was the chance for both companies to cut costs. Total
has said it would probably eliminate 1,000 of a combined 90,000
jobs, mostly by attrition; streamlined refinery management and
combined purchasing would yield further savings.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Pfeifer argued, Desmarest's cost-savings
projections are too modest. Pfeifer noted that British Petroleum
and Amoco expect their merger to yield savings equal to about 5.1
percent of their combined market capitalization by 2001, while
Total and Petrofina are forecasting just 3.7 percent by 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
