<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      12-11 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS TO ACCEPT CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, making a dramatic and
unambiguous appeal to moderate Republicans, Friday expressed
``profound remorse'' for putting the country through the
impeachment ordeal and said he was ready to accept ``rebuke and
censure.''
</P>
<P>
   But initial indications were that Clinton's speech did not help.
As many as six previously undecided Republicans announced Friday
they would back impeachment or were now leaning strongly for it.
</P>
<P>
   Just just minutes before the House Judiciary Committee approved
the first article of impeachment, Clinton walked somberly from the
Oval Office to the Rose Garden, and for the first time expressed
his willingness to accept censure, the preferred alternative to
impeachment among Democrats and some moderate Republicans,
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing, not piety, nor tears, nor wit, nor torment can alter
what I have done,'' Clinton said. ``I must make my peace with that.
I must also be at peace with the fact that the public consequences
of my actions are in the hands of the American people and their
representatives in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should they determine that my errors of word and deed require
their rebuke and censure, I am ready to accept that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for sanctioning his censure, Clinton failed to move much
beyond his earlier apologies for lying about an affair with a
former White House intern. It was not clear Friday night what he
meant by saying he would accept a rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   Though some undecided Republicans have been demanding that
Clinton acknowledge having lied or perjured himself during the
investigation of his relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky, his
statement stopped well short of such an admission.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bob Franks of New Jersey was perhaps the most
closely watched Republican because he had written a letter to
Clinton last week urging the president to admit he committed
perjury. If Clinton made such an admission, Franks would probably
vote against impeachment. But after watching Clinton's speech
Friday, Franks all but declared for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was needed from the president today was an admission, not
contrition,'' Franks said. ``He needed to come to terms with the
fact that he has broken the law by lying under oath to the grand
jury and committing perjury.'' Unless Clinton makes such a
statement, Franks said, he is prepared to vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Saxby Chambliss of Georgia declared for
impeachment and said: ``Having viewed the president's defense
before the Judiciary Committee, I believe he has failed to refute
these charges or overcome the evidence presented.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, Representative Rodney P. Frelinghuysen of
New Jersey, announced immediately after Clinton's speech that he
would support impeachment. The Clinton speech ``confirmed it for
him,'' a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who announced before Clinton's speech Friday that
they would support impeachment included Representatives Lincoln
Diaz-Balart and Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, both of Florida, according to
the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came on the eve of a four-day trip to the
Middle East that begins Saturday, and amid a cacophony of advice
from White House aides and Democratic leaders over how to try to
sway two dozen House Republicans who are undecided on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his aides and Democratic leaders had suggested that
Clinton wait until after the Judiciary Committee acts because
anything he said would be drowned out by the committee's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Others had argued that he should make a statement before the
committee votes and before leaving for the Middle East. White House
aides left open the possibility that Clinton might make another
statement before the full House votes next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's former labor secretary, Robert Reich, said that even
Clinton's embrace of censure could cut both ways. ``It may make it
marginally easier for a few wavering members to vote in favor of
censure knowing that he will accept it,'' said the Brandeis
University economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other, it's entirely possible that a few wavering
members may be persuaded to vote for impeachment because he seems
so eager to accept censure,'' he said. ``They may figure it's not
enough of a punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking pained and remoseful, and with the wind ruffling the
paper containing his statement, Clinton said he had been
``grappling with how best to reconcile myself to the American
people, to acknowledge my own wrongdoing and still maintain my
focus on the work of the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had left his defense to his lawyers and had nothing
to add to what they have argued. ``What I want the American people
to know, what I want the Congress to know is that I am profoundly
sorry for all I have done wrong in words and deeds. I never should
have misled the country, the Congress, my friends or my family.
Quite simply, I gave in to my shame,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the past few months had been a ``tortuous process'' of
coming to terms with what he had done. ``I understand that
accountability demands consequences, and I'm prepared to accept
them. Painful though the condemnation of Congress would be, it
would pale in comparison to the consequences of the pain I have
caused my family. There is no greater agony,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other undecided Republicans said through aides that
they either had not watched Clinton's remarks and saw them and were
still undecided. But one House aide familiar with the vote-counting
said Clinton's comments ``didn't move the process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Steve Chabot, an Ohio Republican on the Judiciary
Committee who voted for the articles of impeachment, said he
believed Clinton's remarks would have no impact on GOP members.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statement was ``not nearly enough,'' Chabot said. ``He
still has not admitted he lied under oath.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Democrats expressed concern that Clinton's comments did not
go far enough. Representative Martin Meehan of Massachusetts had
called for Clinton to admit he lied, in order to gain support from
moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hasn't won over any moderate Republicans, I'm very
disappointed,'' Meehan said. ``This is going to be a very close
vote.'' Meehan said that, contrary to the fears of the White House,
a presidential admission of lying would not result in criminal
prosecution after Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Charles Schumer of New York, one of the most
outspoken critics of impeachment, said he felt Clinton's comment
would be well-received by the public, but probably wouldn't
persuade most Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fearful his statement will have no effect on them,''
Schumer said of the GOP members. ``If the vote were held now,
impeachment would pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said his best hope was that Americans would become
outraged this weekend at the Judiciary Committee's action and
convey that view to their congressmen. If that happens, Schumer
said, ``the counter reaction will build. It may sway some votes
against impeachment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
