u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SORRY-HNS &LR;      12-11 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SORRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE WOULD ACCEPT CENSURE IN OFFERING APOLOGY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to sway moderate House Republicans,
President Clinton said Friday that he was ``profoundly sorry,'' for
misleading the country and would accept congressional censure as a
consequence of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Standing alone in the Rose Garden, the somber president
delivered his latest apology about the Monica Lewinsky affair just
minutes before the House Judiciary Committee approved the first
article of impeachment against him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message, however, was not intended for the highly
polarized panel, but rather for a handful of undecided Republicans
who will be crucial when the full House takes up the impeachment
debate next week. Some of those moderates have been clamoring for
the president to admit that he lied about his involvement with
Lewinsky in both civil and criminal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The president did not go nearly that far, and there was no
immediate evidence that his remarks were persuading lawmakers
sitting on the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the Clinton's statement, two New Jersey
Republicans who had been undecided, Rodney Frelinghuysen and Robert
Franks, announced they would vote for at least one of the articles
of impeachment. Both said that the president did not go far enough
in his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was needed from the president today was an admission, not
contrition,'' said Franks. ``Unfortunately, through his remarks
this evening the president continues to put his own self interest
ahead of the nation by refusing to take personal responsibility for
his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   While the president was remorseful in his brief comments he did
not specifically acknowledge that he had committed perjury as some
lawmakers had urged him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never should have misled the country, the Congress, my
friends or my family,'' Clinton said. Quite simply, I gave into my
shame.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's apology was not substantively different from a
number of other professions of remorse he made earlier this year
after admitting to an affair with Lewinsky in nationwide address in
August.
</P>
<P>
   However, for the first time the president publicly stated what
his advisers have already said: that he would accept either censure
or rebuke from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must also be at peace with the fact that public consequences
of my actions are in the hands of the American public and their
representatives in Congress,'' he said.`` Should they determine
that my errors of word and deeds require their rebuke and censure,
I am ready to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee are expected to offer
a censure resolution Saturday after the panel concludes work on all
four impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also repeated his contention that lawmakers must return
to the business of governing the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must all return to the work, the vital work of
strengthening our nation for the new century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president is scheduled Saturday to embark for the Middle
East where he will attempt to patch up a tattered accord between
Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A number of White House advisers, Democrats and some Republicans
have been urging the president for some time to make a personal
appeal, arguing that it was not adequate to leave his defense to
his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   One political analyst, Thomas Mann of the Brookings Institution,
said the president was in bind because if he had admitted perjury
he would have bolstered Republicans' argument that he should be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that an admission of guilt on the perjury
charges would make easier for independent counsel Kenneth Starr to
indict him once he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said that he doubted that ``there is anything (Clinton) can
say that will alter the course of what is happening,'' in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst said the only thing that might move moderates as the
House impeachment vote draws nearer is the realization that they
are ``pulling up to the precipice,'' of a constitutional crisis
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton's adversaries, his latest comments only reinforced
their determination to proceed with impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip, Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, a longtime Clinton
critic who has been leading the impeachment drive in the House,
condemned the president's latest apology saying ``this last-ditch
effort to influence undecided members of Congress is an insult to
their intelligence, and the intelligence of all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said the president ``should end this process by resigning
his office for the good of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of undecided Republicans, including Michael Forbes,
Rick Lazio and Jack Quinn of New York and Jon Fox of Pennsylvania
remain undecided Friday, according to their spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Another undecided lawmaker Rep. Bob Ney, R-Ohio, was not swayed
one way or the other by the president's comments, according to his
spokesman Neil Volz. Nevertheless Volz said the congressman ``hoped
(Clinton) would have admitted he lied under oath.''
</P>
<P>
   However, several other Republicans, who had previously been
undecided or undeclared, announced they would vote for impeachment.
They included Rep. Richard Baker, R-La., Saxby Chambliss, R-Ga.,
and Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to be retaining support among Democrats, as 112
indicated they would vote against impeachment, according to a
survey by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Only three House Democrats have said they will vote for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
