<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ADDISON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN ADDISON, COMPOSER OF TV, MOVIE, THEATER MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Vt.)  (rl) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Addison, an English composer whose score for the 1963 film
``Tom Jones'' won an Oscar and whose theme music for ``Murder She
Wrote'' won an Emmy, died on Monday at a hospital in Bennington,
Vt. He was 78 and lived in Bennington.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was a stroke, said James Goldstone, a
director for whom Addison supplied music and a friend of the
family.
</P>
<P>
   Addison was born in Chobham, England, in 1920 and studied at
Wellington College and the Royal College of Music in London. Early
in his career he composed symphonic and chamber works, including a
ballet, ``Carte Blanche,'' and a Concerto for Trumpet, Strings and
Percussion.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in concert music was rekindled in recent years
after he moved to Vermont from California, where he had lived since
1976. His Bassoon Concertina was given its world premiere last
summer by the Halle Orchestra in Manchester, England.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the 1950s, though, Addison was drawn most strongly
to theater and film, and later to television and to the idea of
writing music that helped create atmosphere and character.
</P>
<P>
   He was known for an approach to scoring that favored small
ensembles, often with single instruments being associated with
specific characters.
</P>
<P>
   His works for the London stage included incidental scores for
Laurence Olivier's staging of ``Hamlet'' at the National Theater,
and new songs for Brecht's ``St. Joan in the Stockyards.'' Several
of the plays for which he wrote music were staged in New York after
their first successes in London. These included John Osborne's
``Luther'' and ``The Entertainer'' and a John Cranko revue,
``Cranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Addison wrote scores for more than 70 British and American
films, among them ``Torn Curtain,'' ``Seven Days to Noon,'' ``The
Charge of the Light Brigade,'' ``Sleuth,'' ``Swashbuckler,'' ``A
Bridge Too Far,'' ``Start the Revolution Without Me'' and ``A Taste
of Honey.''
</P>
<P>
   When the British film industry went through a dry spell in the
mid-1970s, Addison and his family moved to California, where he
began adding television scores to his works list.
</P>
<P>
   Among his best-known television scores are themes for ``Murder
She Wrote'' and ``Nero Wolfe,'' and music for ``Pearl,''
``Centennial'' and ``Charles and Diana: A Royal Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Pamela; two sons, Jonathan, of
Hastings, England, and Daniel, of London; a stepson, Rex
Birchenough of Peterborough, England; a daughter, Lucinda Sanderson
of Paris; a stepdaughter, Sandra Stapleton of Leamington Spa,
England, and a sister, Jill Lucas of London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0342 </DOCNO>
