<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE CREW INSTALLS GEAR, PREPARES SPACE STATION FOR FUTURE
CREWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The U.S. and Russian crew of the shuttle Endeavour
retreated from the new international space station Friday after
installing communications gear and readying the two modules for
future crews.
</P>
<P>
   Four construction and supply missions are scheduled for next
year with shuttles, and the first live-in residents will arrive in
early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure wish we had more time to spend here to get more work
done,'' said Bob Cabana, Endeavour's commander.
</P>
<P>
   The retreat took more than two hours. And much as compulsive
vacationers might prepare their home for a long absence, the
astronauts checked carefully to make sure nothing was out of place
and that lights were switched on or off as required.
</P>
<P>
   Six airtight hatches had to be secured, each requiring a long
wait while pressure levels in the empty compartments were adjusted.
Nancy Currie, Jim Newman, Sergei Krikalev, Jerry Ross and Rick
Sturckow lazily twisted and somersaulted in the weightless of the
station's roomy new chambers, clicking away with cameras as they
waited until it was time to close the final door.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the planned objectives have been accomplished,'' declared
NASA flight director Mark Kirasich, who monitored the procedure
from mission control.
</P>
<P>
   The first shuttle crew logged a total of 28 hours, 32 minutes
aboard the fledgling outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Though now off limits to the shuttle crew, the compartments of
the new station will remain docked to Endeavour until Sunday.
Joined together by the shuttle astronauts six days ago, the U.S.
``Unity'' and Russian ``Zarya'' modules tower eight stories above
the docking assembly and airlock in the shuttle's cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
   While inside, Cabana and Ross installed three electronics boxes
in the U.S. module, completing the installation of a satellite
communications link with NASA's Mission Control Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The link enables U.S. ground control teams to monitor equipment
aboard the station while it is unoccupied and to send a range of
commands. The station also is monitored by Russian and U.S.
controllers in suburban Moscow, but their contact with the modules
is limited to when it flies over Asian ground stations.
</P>
<P>
   Krikalev and Currie teamed to replace a power controller on one
of six storage batteries aboard Zarya. The original controller,
which was to automatically regulate the flow of electricity
generated by the module's solar panels, faltered soon after Zarya's
Nov. 20 launch from Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   Krikalev solved a puzzling airflow deficiency in the Russian
module when he discovered and removed a blockage in some of the
permanent ducting.
</P>
<P>
   During their brief stay, the shuttle crew also removed 774 bolts
installed before Zarya's launching to secure equipment bays and
electronic equipment. They stowed clothing and a laptop computer
for the first resident crew of astronauts and cosmonauts.
</P>
<P>
   As they departed, the astronauts disassembled portable air
ducts, and removed fans and other equipment that delivered and
recirculated air fed by the shuttle. The Russian service module,
with the station's first independent life support equipment, is not
expected before late July. Its development has been stalled by
Russian economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   After a night's rest, Ross and Newman plan the third of the
mission's three spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, the two men will emerge from Endeavour's airlock and
ride on the shuttle's 50-foot robot arm to stow a bag of tools on
the exterior of the outer reaches of the new station. They also
will inspect the docking mechanism that will accept the service
module, checking for potential obstructions, and photograph the
exterior of the two modules for ground-based engineers. They also
will work on an external guidance antenna on the Russian module
that failed to unfurl fully.
</P>
<P>
   During two previous excursions, the two spacewalking astronauts
connected power and computer data cables, installed a pair of
external communications antennas and freed another obstructed
external Russian antenna.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
