<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-IMPACT12-COX     12-11 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-IMPACT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Acquisition of Cadbury Schweppes a bold move
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. showed it isn't letting worldwide
economic jitters, sluggish sales and threats from No. 2 rival
Pepsico hinder its push for growth.
</P>
<P>
   In a bold power play, the Atlanta-based beverage giant is
betting $1.85 billion that buying Cadbury Schweppes' beverage
brands in 120 countries will beef up its already aggressive
worldwide expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, which does not cover Cadbury Schweppes'
business in the United States, France and South Africa, includes an
array of brands, including best-sellers Schweppes, Canada Dry, Dr
Pepper and Crush, plus beverage plants in Ireland and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The move will take Coca-Cola's global soft drink share to 52
percent from 50 percent, further cementing the company's No. 1
position in the worldwide beverage market. London-based Cadbury
Schweppes is No. 3, behind Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   M. Douglas Ivester, Coca-Cola's chairman and chief executive,
called the acquisition a win-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These agreements will allow the Coca-Cola Co. to participate
in segments of the beverage business where it currently does not
have meaningful entries,'' Ivester said. ``The Cadbury Schweppes
brands will be a wonderful addition to the core brands of the
Coca-Cola Co.''
</P>
<P>
   New York-based beverage consultant Tom Pirko said the deal is
another step toward achieving the dream often spoken of by former
Chairman and Chief Executive Roberto C. Goizueta. The Cuban
refugee, who led the company through a phenomenal 16 years of
growth before his death in October 1997, only half-jokingly
envisioned a day when the ``C'' on household faucets would stand
for ``Coca-Cola'' rather than ``cold water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very rational decision for Coke because it gives them
more opportunity to pursue the dream. It was Roberto's dream, and
now it's Doug's dream,'' Pirko said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes abundant sense if you're Coca-Cola because there's
one goal: to continue to build world share,'' he said. ``To build
world share, you need brands and you need systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides helping the Coca-Cola Co. grow, the deal will give
Cadbury Schweppes an influx of cash to solidify its position in the
worldwide confectionery market, where it ranks No. 4. After the
deal, half of the company's profits will still come from beverages,
but confectionery will make up two-thirds of the group's $5.74
billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also will help bankroll the expansion of Cadbury
Schweppes' Dr Pepper business in the United States, where it
derives two-thirds of its soft drink sales and has a 15 percent
market share. Cadbury Schweppes acquired Dr Pepper/Seven Up Inc. in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Selling off the bulk of the company's soft drink operations will
create ``substantial value for our shareowners and simultaneously
enhance our ability to develop and focus on our strong global
confectionery and U.S. beverage business,'' said John Sunderland,
chief executive of Cadbury Schweppes.
</P>
<P>
   The deal _ made up of $175 billion in cash and $100 million in
notes _ is subject to regulatory review in a number of countries.
It is anticipated to be completed in mid-1999, Coca-Cola said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Coca-Cola's stock price dipped as much as 6.2 percent
Friday, analysts and industry insiders expressed confidence in the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schweppes has been around longer than Coke. Everyone knows the
brand name. They have the creme de la creme of mixers,'' said
Emanuel Goldman, a beverage analyst for Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the new brands will round out Coca-Cola's portfolio,
Goldman said, adding that Dr Pepper in particular could prove to be
a major asset. The brand, now sold in just five countries outside
the United States, could take off worldwide through Coca-Cola's
massive distribution network, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an acceptance of that taste within overseas
markets, then there is an awful lot of potential because of the
guzzle-ability of pepper-flavored products,'' Goldman said. ``Both
colas and pepper-flavored soft drinks are guzzle-able. They go down
easily, and you don't tire of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dr Pepper's sales in the United States have grown on
average 1.5 times the market rate over the last 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   John Sicher, editor of trade publication Beverage Digest, said
Coca-Cola's powerful worldwide bottling system is better equipped
to grow the Cadbury Schweppes brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cadbury had a small international business. Critical mass is
essential in the bottling business,'' he said. ``Coca-Cola has the
system to help them grow.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Ivester said he's confident the company
won't face regulatory roadblocks, and that despite global economic
uncertainty, he's maintaining the company's stated goal of growing
annual volume by 7 percent to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester said the Cadbury Schweppes brands will add volume to
Coca-Cola's system on a one-time basis, ``but then after that we
would expect our business to be in line with the long-time (growth
projections) we've talked about before.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some analysts and investors might be bothered by the
company's short-term outlook, Ivester said the fundamentals have
not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long-term business. We have low per-capitas, on the
whole, around the world. The company has demonstrated the ability
to build per-capita consumption of its products over 113 years,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe when you look out 10 years from now that you're
going to be very, very pleased that you made an investment in the
Coca-Cola Co. in 1998 _ in the fourth quarter of 1998, even,''
Ivester said.
</P>
<P>
   As a side note, Ivester added that the situation was similar to
1982. That's when the company's stock dropped 10 percent, on a
relative basis, from $2 to $1.80.
</P>
<P>
   ``And everyone that I know that bought that stock at $1.80 feels
really good today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
