<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SHOW BELIEF IN KISELAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Just before a Cowboys team meeting several days
ago, team owner Jerry Jones stood outside a classroom at Valley
Ranch and pulled center Mike Kiselak aside for a brief word.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was concerned about the performance of the offensive line
in New Orleans, which struggled mightily as the Cowboys were held
to a franchise-low eight yards rushing. Kiselak, making just his
second start at center, had been a flashpoint of the breakdown. The
Saints had crashed the middle of the line for six tackles behind
the line of scrimmage and two sacks.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones was coming with a word of encouragement, not
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jones told me he watched the film and he said, `You took
some heat, but we still have confidence in you,' '' Kiselak said.
``It feels good to know I'm still backed by the coaches and the
owner. It was exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clay Shiver, whom Kiselak replaced as the starter, took
some reps with the first team this week. Cowboys coaches, no doubt,
want him ready in case Kiselak or rookie Flozell Adams struggles
again in Kansas City tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Kiselak said some of his problems against the Saints stemmed
from miscommunication.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the fourth quarter, the Cowboys faced third
down, deep in their own territory. Quarterback Troy Aikman called a
pass. The play called for Adams to yell out the blocking assignment
for the right side of the line. The Superdome was very noisy and
Kiselak thought he heard Adams tell him to slide to the left.
Kiselak, indeed, was supposed to slide to the right. Saints
defensive tackle La'Roi Glover sped in through the hole nearly
untouched for the first of two sacks on Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little flustered with things,'' Kiselak said. ``I'd
never dealt with what they were throwing out there. I think that
led to the bad snap I had, too. I was thinking about my assignment
instead of just going on my instincts and I didn't snap the ball
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week was a learning experience,'' he said. ``This week, I
invite people to watch how I play. They'll see for themselves if
they should start worrying if I'm going to have problems, or if the
real Mike Kiselak shows up.'' Briefly Deion Sanders practiced in
the rain at Valley Ranch yesterday, but coach Chan Gailey still
said it would be a game-time decision on Sanders' availability.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Kevin Smith (back) and running back Chris Warren
(groin) probably won't play tomorrow, Gailey said. It appeared that
Smith and Warren had progressed after practice Thursday, but
neither was able to practice yesterday. ``Chris and Kevin are a
little farther away from playing than Deion,'' Gailey said.
 &LR; tagtop:Kevin Lyons (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:lyonsnfl &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
