<HEADER>
A6051 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-2NDTA     12-11 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: to call. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican leaders have so far been adamant that the full House
would vote next week only on articles of impeachment, not on
censure. Rep. Tom DeLay, the Republican whip, fears that permitting
a censure option would siphon votes away from impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy is designed to pressure as many as three dozen
undecided Republicans to vote to impeach the president on at least
one count, and send the charges for a trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It's conceivable that if impeachment fails, Livingston could
relent and permit a vote on some kind of censure. But at that
point, with the president out of peril, many Democrats who wanted
censure as an alternative might balk, and many Republicans who
believe a censure is unconstitutional or a bad precedent would also
oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   The precise dimensions of a censure are still shifting. Several
Democrats and a handful of Republicans have discussed including a
strong condemnation of the president's actions, to be signed by
Clinton, and a fine.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the White House presses for a censure vote, presidential
aides have contacted 45 Republicans in the past few days to help
explain the president's defense or urge them to vote against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win over some of these Republicans, Clinton
publicly acknowledged for the first time Friday that he would
accept a censure from the House, just moments before the House
Judiciary Committee voted along party lines to impeach and remove
him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public consequences of my actions are in the hands of the
American people and their representatives in the Congress,''
Clinton said. ``Should they determine that my errors of word and
deed require their rebuke and censure, I am ready to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart refused to parry with reporters over what censure
language the president would accept. ``I'm not going to get into a
negotiating position from here at this podium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unmoved by the White House's defense of the president this week
and Clinton's statement, six of the undeclared Republicans _ Jack
Metcalf of Washington, Saxby Chambliss of Georgia, Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen and Lincoln Diaz-Balart, both of Florida, and Bob
Franks and Rodney Frelinghuysen, both of New Jersey _ announced
Friday they would vote to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now clear that the president violated both his oath of
office and the oath he took to tell the truth,'' Frelinghuysen said
in a letter to constituents. ``In doing so, Bill Clinton not only
committed perjury, he violated the public trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz-Balart, who an aide said turned down a White House offer on
Thursday to speak to the White House general counsel, Charles F.C.
Ruff, said in a statement: ``Failure to impeach President Clinton
would do grave harm to the integrity of the judicial system in the
United States.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
