<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ART-3RDTAKE-N     12-11 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: his inquiry.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I don't want this to be an endless process,'' he said. ``I
think it's in the interest of the country to finish it and we have
tried to do our level best. And I have tried to grant every request
the Democrats have made. Maybe I haven't succeeded, but I have
certainly tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, as he called for impeachment, praised a few of the
committee's Democrats. He said he admired Schumer greatly. He spoke
kindly of Rep. Thomas M. Barrett, a Wisconsin Democrat. ``He has
tried to say to this committee, `Let's bring the country
together,''' Graham said. ``What a noble cause. Don't worry, Mr.
Barrett, if we don't come together. This country is strong. We
shall survive.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the long day went on the partisanship became ever more
pronounced. Democrats fought to the end against every charge
against Clinton and they plunged the committee Republicans into
some noticeable confusion when they demanded to know precisely
which of the president's statements were perjurious.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said that in a presentation Thursday, David P. Schippers,
the Republicans' investigative counsel had ``set out in detail''
the lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you should be able to tell me what they are,'' shot back
Rep. Jerrold Nadler, a New York Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde had to summon Schippers and his other chief aide, Thomas E.
Mooney to his side. It was finally Rep. James Sensenbrenner, who
began giving the answers, plowing grimly through the sexual details
needed to make the perjury charges.
</P>
<P>
   He cited Clinton's grand jury testimony that he did not think
his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky fit the definition of sexual
relations used by Ms. Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned Clinton's denial when he was asked whether ``oral
sex performed on you was within the definition as you understood
it.'' He noted that Clinton conceded that ``kissing or touching of
the breast or genitalia of another person'' would be covered by the
definition of sex in the Jones case, and yet Clinton had still
denied lying when he said he had not had sexual relations with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The testimony is false and misleading,'' Sensenbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat, charged that the
Republicans were guilty of ``deliberate vagueness and obfuscation''
because they were prepared to impeach Clinton over definitions of
sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't tell us what he touched, therefore it was perjury,''
Frank said, mocking the Republicans case.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the Watergate scandal of 24 years ago, Republicans
countered that the articles of impeachment against Nixon had also
lacked a detailed bill of particulars. And Rep. Charles Canady, a
Florida Republican, noted that it was the Republican defenders of
Nixon who had made the same demand for specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner said the Democrats were really engaged in a
``clever ruse'' designed to limit the evidence that the Senate
could consider in any trial.
</P>
<P>
   But at other moments the debate reached a higher tone conscious
of history, as lawmakers quoted the nation's founders, and John
Kennedy and recalled wrenching chapters in the nation's history,
from civil war to assassinations.
</P>
</TEXT>
