<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GATTI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATTI GIVES HIS ALL, BUT DOES HE HAVE ANY LEFT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY _ Arturo Gatti comes to fight . . . which these
days may be part of his problem.
</P>
<P>
   The former International Boxing Federation junior lightweight
champion has always been a face-first fistic warrior, a guy who
understands what business he is in. He's in the hurt business and
he's hurt plenty of opponents while building a 29-3 record with 24
knockouts. But to do it, he's hurt himself as well, which is why he
comes into Saturday night's bout on HBO against Ivan Robinson
riding a two-fight losing streak and grave doubts that he is the
same crowd-pleaser he was when the year began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatti is the kind of guy who gives TV people and fans a lot of
pleasure but doesn't give himself a long career,'' veteran trainer
Teddy Atlas said. ``He's very appealing for TV, but if you're not
attached to the situation, you know it can't last. Every time you
win in a war like that, you lose something, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatti is a game guy. He has the things it takes to be a
champion. He understands what he has to suffer to do what he does
best and he gets accolades for being exciting, but there are
physical laws you just can't beat. It's a matter of time before the
things that allowed you to be exciting keep you from having a long
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not dumb. Gatti knows the way he fights can do damage,
but it's human nature to think of the immediate rewards first. HBO
pays him a lot of money because he makes good fights. You got that,
you don't think long-term. But if you fight that way, you usually
don't have to worry about long-term because you don't have a long
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Former light heavyweight champion Matthew Saad Muhammad wrote
the same story. One day he was the gamest fighter in boxing. Next
day he was finished, a pummeled punching bag whose reflexes _ and
world title _ were gone, and nobody wanted to watch him anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gatti faces the same crossroads, insisting he will change
while others wonder if such a man can remake himself at 26 against
an opponent who won a split decision from him Aug. 27 by taking all
he could give and giving back more hurt than Gatti handed out.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti understands this has become the prevailing opinion about
him among boxing's cognoscenti but he does not share it.
Considering that his ability to come back in the face of apparent
defeat is what made him one of the most popular fighters in boxing,
his contrarian's viewpoint is no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't 100 percent last time and I still hurt him,'' Gatti
said of Robinson. ``He showed me a lot of heart that night. I hurt
him a couple times, but he wouldn't quit. If he doesn't this time,
I'll make him quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but many experts who have watched Gatti take brutal
punishment in victories over Gabe Ruelas, Wilson Rodriguez, and
Tracy Harris Patterson and in a January loss to Angel Manfredy
wonder if it is he who will be forced to quit this time.
</P>
<P>
   If so, they say, he will have been as much a victim of his own
hard-won celebrity as of any opponent, including Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to him than just punching power, but there's also
a fine line to what he's doing. When you cross it, you can't go
back,'' Atlas said.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti claims to understand that and insists he has retreated
from that line before crossing it. A product of the tough side of
Jersey City, he has retained an actor's good looks and a warrior's
heart while paying an incredible price in pain and blood for his
unique place on the business side of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only guy I know could lose two fights in a row and
get a pay raise,'' an associate of Gatti's said this week. ``Every
punch he takes, he's worth more money.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true until he takes one too many and no longer can fight
back enough to win. Then warriors like Gatti are transformed into
sad steppingstones, game guys who get beaten up for money rather
than to win. Gatti has seen enough of boxing to know that is a
story that has been written many times, but he sustains himself
believing it is not his story.
</P>
<P>
   At least not this night, against this guy, it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of being Rocky,'' Gatti said. ``I want to fight for
a while. I know there are people who think my style caught up with
me already, but if I want to box, I can box. When I put myself in
desperate situations, then's when I do what I do best _ declare
war. But I don't want to put myself in desperate situations no
more. I've made a lot of money because people know I'll show up to
the show, but sometimes I show up too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is counting on that. A better boxer but a far lighter
hitter than Gatti, Robinson sees a road to victory that seems clear
to him and his handlers, who have come up with a unique battle
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's manager, Eddie Woods, has offered to take $5,000 off
his managerial end and give it to Robinson's two children if his
fighter throws at least 1,200 punches Saturday night. His belief is
that Robinson (26-2, 10 KOs) can wear Gatti down and eventually
overwhelm him with so many bee stings that the former champion's
oft-closed eyes will begin to resemble the slits of a piggy bank,
as they did the night Gatti got off the deck to knock out Rodriguez
while half-blind.
</P>
<P>
   If they're right, Woods knows, his fighter can win. Of course,
to do that, Robinson must get close enough to Gatti to be hit, and
therein, Gatti believes, lies his opponent's problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure he'll box me like he did last fight,'' Gatti said of
Robinson's surprisingly aggressive style that night. ``He opened up
a couple of times and I hurt him. This time I'll finish him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first fight wasn't me. I had a lot of problems. I was
coming off a long (eight-month) layoff (after the Manfredy defeat)
and I had weight problems. This time I was 139 two days before the
fight. I feel better physically. I'll go in the ring this time with
a clear mind. If you're not 100 percent, your mind starts spinning
when you get in that place. This time I feel perfect. I don't feel
like being a great loser.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
