<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN AUTHORITY ACCUSED OF NOT FULFILLING PEACE PACT
COMMITMENTS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While Israel has frozen its compliance with recent
peace accords, the Palestinian Authority is not fully complying
with its own commitments, senior U.S. and Israeli officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems they cite are incendiary Palestinian
statements about prisoner releases, lagging efforts to confiscate
illegal firearms, and to cut the security forces, all of which are
required under the accords that were reached in Wye, Md., in
October.
</P>
<P>
   These deficiencies made it harder for Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to keep selling the accord to the Israeli Cabinet, the
officials said. And U.S. officials in Washington and the Middle
East have scrambled to cool tempers and get Palestinians to meet
their obligations. As President Clinton prepared to fly to the
Middle East early Saturday, the Americans have pressed Palestinian
officials to stop any statements that would qualify as incitement
to violence and to call off hunger strikes by Palestinians being
held in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, has denied Israel charges
that the Palestinians are violating the Wye accords.
</P>
<P>
   While each side has raised contentious issues during ongoing
security talks, chaired by the CIA, security professionals have
nonetheless continued to engage each other seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday U.S. diplomats worked out procedures with the
Palestinians for a critical meeting on Monday in Gaza with Clinton
in attendance. At that time, a quorum of the Palestinian National
Council and other Palestinians are to ``reaffirm'' that clauses in
the Palestinian charter calling for Israel's destruction have been
nullified. But the Americans have not yet received Israeli backing
for those procedures.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House Friday morning, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger refused at a
news conference to say whether there would be a formal vote at the
meeting, which the Israelis have demanded. The reaffirmation ``will
be done through a set of procedures that have been agreed upon,''
Albright said, but she did not specify them.
</P>
<P>
   Albright urged Israelis and Palestinians to carry out all their
obligations under the Wye accord, under which Israel will withdraw
in phases from a further 13 percent of the West Bank in return for
Palestinian steps against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   As White House domestic aides continued to raise the difficulty
of the trip's timing _ with Clinton in the Middle East until late
Tuesday night when the House discusses his impeachment _ Clinton's
aides on the foreign side insisted that the trip had to go ahead
for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Berger asserted: ``I don't think the president had second
thoughts for a second about going on this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   But senior U.S. officials conceded that with Netanyahu in
political trouble with his right wing and Yasser Arafat trying to
placate radicals on his left, Clinton will need all his political
skills to navigate what was supposed to be a celebratory visit.
</P>
<P>
   The president's special Middle East envoy, Dennis Ross, was
called back to Washington to help senior officials prepare for the
morning briefing and then to travel back with the president on
Saturday. It will be Clinton's fourth visit to Israel as president.
</P>
<P>
   Albright spoke optimistically Friday morning about the Wye
accords. ``I believe we can and will overcome the challenges we
face,'' she said. ``The first phase of the Wye implementation
process has now been completed, and it has produced real results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no denying that the second phase of implementation
has proven more difficult than the first,'' Albright said.
``Provocative rhetoric, violence and disputes over key issues such
as prisoner exchanges have created real difficulties. And it's
unrealistic to expect that after an 18-month crisis of confidence,
Israelis and Palestinians would build strong working relationships
easily or quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about problems of compliance, Albright said: ``From our
perspective, there is more that can be done on security. And we
would hope to see that happen. And we also believe that it's
important for disputes that have come up over the prisoner issue to
be resolved at the negotiating table.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically about the Palestinian effort to collect guns,
Albright said carefully: ``Well, that process has begun, and it
needs to continue. And I'm not going to characterize our level of
contentment at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But other officials said that U.S. diplomats in Israel were
spending much of their time using the leverage of Clinton's visit
to get Arafat to cool the rhetoric on prisoners and to stop street
demonstrations that have led to violence.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., wrote Clinton a
letter praising the Wye accords but noting: ``Israel has complied
with her obligations under Wye thus far, but continued
implementation is in jeopardy because the Palestinians have not
followed through on their commitments.'' He urged Clinton ``to
press the Palestinians to implement aggressively their new laws
outlawing possession of weapons and preventing incitement'' and to
ensure that the Palestinian National Council ``makes unmistakeably,
unambiguously clear'' that offending clauses of the charter are
repealed.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg said in an interview that his concerns arose from
information provided him as a member of ``a confidential committee
I sit on,'' a reference to the Senate Select Committee on
Intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
