<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6076 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI &LR;      12-11 0209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Saturday, Dec. 12, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Bob Schenet at 206-448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBE-TREATY (Victoria, B.C.) _ More than 111 years have passed
since Nisga'a Indians paddled canoes 650 miles from the remote Nass
Valley, just south of the Alaska Panhandle, to Victoria. They came
to make a futile appeal for rights to ancestral lands they were
losing as the white man discovered the fish, forests and minerals
of British Columbia's northwest coast. But now, the B.C.
Legislature and Canada's House of Commons stand poised to approve a
treaty that will give the 5,000-member Indian tribe about 1,300
square miles of land, cash and powers of self-government. ``We're
back,'' said Nisga'a Chief Joe Gosnell.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story has moved in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-PRODUCTION (Seattle) _ Boeing has reversed itself and
decided not to open a new 737 assembly line in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ On Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
