<SLUG> BC-FBC-GSOUTHERN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eagles' offense faces big challenge
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ The two teams playing at Paulson Stadium at 1
p.m. today took different roads to the Division I-AA semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Georgia Southern (13-0), in the semifinals for the
sixth time, has ridden a high-powered option offense to within two
victories of a fifth I-AA national title.
</P>
<P>
   For the Western Illinois Leathernecks (11-2), the key has been
defense, even though they feature their own All-American running
back.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Greg Hill and fullback Adrian Peterson have been
driving the Eagles' offense behind a veteran front that includes
first- and second-team All-Southern Conference linemen Mark
Williams at guard, Matt Winslette at center and Rich McGrath and
Grant Chesnut at tackles. Georgia Southern is averaging 43.7 points
a game and 379 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we execute, nobody is going to stop us from scoring,'' said
Hill, who has rushed for 1,292 yards and 21 touchdowns, although
his numbers pale in comparison with Peterson's totals of 2,342
yards and 32 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   The Leathernecks, from the Gateway Conference, feature consensus
All-American Aaron Stecker, the rushing rage of I-AA in '97 when he
gained 2,293 yards and scored 28 times. But their defense held
playoff opponents Montana and Florida A&AMP;M to an average of 10.2
points and 136 rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play in a tough conference, and though you get beat up
physically ... that has prepared us for games like this,''
Leathernecks coach Randy Ball said. ``We've relied on our defense
all year. It's definitely been our strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The Leathernecks start seven players on defense who transferred
from I-A programs, including end David Bowens. A 6-4, 245-pound
junior, Bowens started at Michigan, where he ranks ninth in career
sacks with 15, and was selected to the All-Big Ten second team in
'96.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern is worried about its defense, which has given
up an average of 29 points and 439 yards total offense in playoff
wins over Colgate and Connecticut. The Eagles will be without
linebackers Daryl Morrell (neck injury) and Larry Rogers (knee).
Another linebacker, Dante Harrow, is slowed by a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll play hard on that side of the ball,'' Eagles
coach Paul Johnson said. ``(Coach Ball) has confidence in his team,
and I've got confidence our guys. I'm anxious to see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
