A6082 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-JORDAN-SPI &LR;      12-11 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-JORDAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVING, ILLUMINATING BIO OF BARBARA JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An adoring biography can still be revealing and capture a sense
of the time and place in which its hero made history.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Beth Rogers' ``Barbara Jordan: American Hero'' is a fine
read even for those who never heard of the ``gentlelady from
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was the first African American woman to serve in Congress
from the old Confederacy. She was a booming orator, but also
somehow managed to operate with old boys in the back rooms of
Austin and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan served only six years in the House before multiple
sclerosis forced her back to Texas. But at the 1974 Watergate
hearings, she captivated a nation with a clarity of mind and depth
of expression in explaining her vote to impeach President Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My faith in the Constitution is whole, it is complete, it is
total,'' she declared. ``I am not going to sit here and be an idle
spectator to the diminution, the subversion, the destruction of the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was chief of staff to Gov. Ann Richards, another heroine
of Texas populism. She has a clear understanding of Jordan's
upbringing in a segregated Houston, her chafing at rules set down
by a strict preacher-father (and later revulsion upon learning of
his secret infidelity) and the deals she had to make to rise in
Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly with the spectacle currently unfolding in the House
Judiciary Committee, however, the book's most valuable chapters
center on the 1974 Nixon impeachment decision. It focuses not only
on Jordan's role, but on the work of another American hero:
committee chairman Peter Rodino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairman Rodino determined privately, and then announced
publicly, that he would not play politics with something as serious
as the possibility of removing a sitting president from office by a
means other than a national election,'' writes Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodino was determined that his committee would rise to the
occasion and not let the impeachment proceedings degenerate into
the kind of sordid, partisan mess that had for 100 years clouded
the House of Representatives' only other impeachment against a
president of the United States _ Andrew Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the sordid, partisan mess going on today in Washington,
D.C., Rodino made sure that grand jury materials remained secret.
He allowed President Nixon's attorney, James St. Clair, to sit in
on all closed meetings. Majority and minority committee counsels
worked in close harmony.
</P>
<P>
   The result was not an American tragedy, but an affirmation of
the rule of law most ringingly expressed by a freshman lawmaker
from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was made an instant celebrity, and wore it well. She used
her clout to help renew the Voting Rights Act that had enfranchised
the minorities who put her in office. She keynoted the 1976
Democratic National Convention with a ringing call for national
reconciliation, and a confession of her own party's past mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   But illness began to slow her down. Jordan told no one of the
reasons and would keep the extent of her health problems concealed
until the day she died early in 1996. The reader can feel her
increased difficulty in getting around, the health complications
and the denial. Jordan was still planning the next term's lectures
at the University of Texas as leukemia was killing her.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers respects a zone of privacy around Jordan. Blessedly, not
a word is devoted to her subject's sex life. The author does put a
few things in soft focus, like the deals Jordan made with
conservative Texas Democrats that propelled her upward. But the
book is contrarian on some counts. Jordan appears as a character
witness at the bribery trial of former Texas Gov. John Connelly.
Jordan later learns, months after Connelly's acquittal, that she
was cynically used.
</P>
<P>
   One more character stands out in a different light: Lyndon
Johnson. The famous arm-twister and wheeler-dealer took a deep
liking to Jordan. He promoted her career at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson died, Jordan reflected: ``Other people are always
talking about what they had done for me. But Lyndon Johnson wasn't
like that. He just did it and he didn't take credit for it.''
</P>
<P>
   A fine book about a tough lady, ``Barbara Jordan'' is about a
hero whose star shone far beyond the Lone Star state. America is
hero-deficient in public life at the moment. It's timely to
celebrate those of recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Jordan:
</P>
<P>
   American Hero
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Beth Rogers. Bantam, 414 pages, $27.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 2142EST &QL; 
