<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFTS COME UP WITH POOR EXCUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Patriots have consistently paved their way toward a new
stadium, be it in the Boston area or Hartford, with the same theme:
``We are one of the lowest-grossing teams in the NFL, and unless we
get a new stadium _ and with it more money _ we will not be able to
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   We have heard this over and over, ad nauseam, for the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the truth is, the Patriots are nowhere near one of the
lowest-grossing teams in the NFL. They are one of the
highest-grossing teams in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this writer has been told by two sources that the most
recent league-wide audit shows that the Patriots rank second only
to the Dallas Cowboys among the 30 teams in Excluded Defined Gross
Revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the NFL has an audit for both the teams and the
owners. The 1997 season review was recently completed.
</P>
<P>
   There are two major areas of cash flow in the league _ Defined
Gross Revenues and Excluded Defined Gross Revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The DGR includes all money from network television, local
television, radio, and tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The EDGR encompasses the rest _ mostly money taken in by the
owners of the stadium: parking, concessions, advertising, signage,
et al.
</P>
<P>
   Under the collective bargaining agreement, the players are
entitled to 64 percent of the DGR. They are entitled to a smaller
share of the EDGR, as determined by a complicated formula.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are one of the few teams in the league to own the
stadium in which they play, and this has been a bonanza for them.
Some governmental body owns most stadiums and takes the majority of
the money from concessions, parking, etc.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, the Kraft family has done a brilliant job
marketing its stadium. When they came into the league, the Krafts
studied the best in the business, Jerry Jones and the Cowboys, who
take in some $40 million a year from their stadium, putting them
some $15 million ahead of their nearest competitors . . . your own
New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, while they might get away with pleading poverty on
one end, the Patriots more than make up for it when their revenue
from Foxboro Stadium is factored in.
</P>
<P>
   One source, who knows the numbers, says that in terms of DGR and
EDGR combined, the Patriots are definitely in the top 10 and most
likely in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, for the Patriots to say they have to move out of
Foxborough and get a new stadium because they do not make enough
money here to compete is a farce.
</P>
<P>
   The move to Hartford in 2001 will make the Patriots the
top-grossing team in the NFL, assuming the deal goes through and
they sell all the stadium seats, as they do in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   And to say that the Kraft family fortune would be at risk if
they stay in Foxborough, or that the team would have to be sold out
of New England because it does not make money, is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Factoring in all team and stadium revenues, the Patriots make
money. And when they get to Connecticut, they will make a lot more
moneey.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Bob Kraft, it must be said that he did his best
to stay here. He was willing to take the risk of building a new
stadium, and for short money, compared to what is being spent by
other states and cities, he should have gotten help from
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president of business operations Andy Wasynczuk
offers this:
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything we could to keep the team here. Foxboro
Stadium will not stay competitive (financially) in the future. New
stadiums are being built each day. And more stadiums will be built
in the near future. All of these teams will pass, or have passed,
what we have been able to do (financially) in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (moving to Connecticut) is not about the present. Going
to Connecticut is about the future _ staying competitive with the
other NFL teams and putting a great team on the field 10, 15, or 20
years from now. We think this will be a great deal for our team and
a great deal for Connecticut. This is the only way we could have
kept our team in New England and kept it competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   This deal will pass in Connecticut _ and in the NFL, when the
owners vote on it. But when those in favor raise their hand, they
should use it to hold their nose, and here is why.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has said consistently for years _ including in court
under oath, when then commissioner Pete Rozelle testified in the
unsuccessful case to stop the Raiders from moving from Oakland to
Los Angeles _ that no team should be allowed to relocate if it is
being supported by its fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have not played to an empty seat in five years.
Patriots fans, and businesses in the community, has spent more
money in their stadium than those in all but one other city,
Dallas. If that isn't supporting a team, what is?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carl Yastrzemski on Dennis Eckersley: ``I'm glad he retired this
week. The timing was right. He's a Hall of Fame pitcher, and you
don't want to see a pitcher with his credentials get beat up at the
end of his career by staying around too long. When he first came
up, he had a mid-90s fastball, a good slider, and good control.
When he was with the Sox as a starter, he was fun to play with. He
had courage. I thought he had a little too much in those days. He
didn't care who the hitter was, he wasn't going to pitch around
him. He just about said, `Here it comes; let's see what you can do
with it.' Because of that, he gave up some tremendous home runs. I
used to love to needle him about some of those shots, and he didn't
like it. He was such a great competitor, but I knew the next time,
he would do everything to strike that guy out. His guts helped him
as a relief pitcher, and he had fantastic control at the end of his
career. I'm happy for him. He's a good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaz on Joe DiMaggio: ``I grew up on Long Island as a Yankee fan.
My father used to take me into the city to see those games. I
didn't get to see Joe in his prime. I got to see him a couple of
times toward the end of his career when he was limping with the bad
heel and all. What I remember most about him was the great series
he had in Boston after his operation, where he just about won the
games himself. I remember listening on the radio, and the people
talking about it. Those were great days for baseball in New York.
After Joe, we had Mickey Mantle in center field for the Yankees,
Duke Snider in center for the Dodgers, and Willie Mays in center
for the Giants. All Hall of Famers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the great Joe Cronin was near death, I was privileged to do
the last interview with him, at his home in Osterville on Cape Cod.
During the conversation, I asked him to pick the greatest player he
had ever seen. Keep in mind, Cronin played against Babe Ruth, Ty
Cobb, and the giants of that era, played into the '40s with Joe D
and Ted Williams, and managed until after World War II before
becoming American League president. He was a Hall of Famer in his
own right, so who better to judge the best of all time?
</P>
<P>
   His response: ``Joe DiMaggio. Joe could do it all _ hit, throw,
run, play great defense. And he always made the plays to win the
big games. All those years (with the Red Sox), we had great teams,
and if he wasn't playing for the Yankees, we would have been the
dominanat team. But he was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who never saw him play, here is a stat that perhaps
best sums up DiMaggio. In his career, he hit 361 home runs and
struck out only 369 times _ virtually a 1-1 ratio _ because he
hated to strike out and was embarrassed when he did. Take a look at
the other great New York center fielders (mentioned by Yaz) of the
mid-century and you can measure how great DiMaggio's ability to put
the bat on the ball was. Mantle had 536 career home runs and 1,710
strikeouts, Mays 660 homers and 1,526 strikeouts, and Snider 407
homers and 1,237 strikeouts _ all at least a 2-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' Ray Bourque on going one-on-one against some of the
best in the NHL during his marvelous career:
</P>
<P>
   Jaromir Jagr ``has the unusual combination of size _ he must be
6-3, 220 _ speed, skill, hands, and reach. He is hard to knock off
the puck because he is so strong. You better have position on him,
try to get him to move where you want to go, or he'll get the best
of you. It's a positioning thing with some of the best (scorers).
</P>
<P>
   ``(Peter) Forsberg in Colorado is the same type of player. He's
not as big as Jagr, maybe 6-1, 6-2, but very strong on his skates.
If he gets position on you, you don't have a chance. You either
have to take a penalty or he's going to get a good (scoring)
chance. When you play against these kinds of players, you have to
be very focused. Before the game, you have to think about what you
are going to do in certain situations, and how you are going to
react.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mario Lemieux (6 feet 4 inches) was bigger. He didn't look
like he was going that fast, but when he turned it on, he was
scary. He had the longest reach, and a stick that seemed 6 feet
long. He held you off and wouldn't let you at the puck. What made
him so difficult (to defend) was that he could reach right over the
top of you, still play the puck, and get a shot off.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wayne) Gretzy is different than all of those guys. He really
is not a one-on-one type of player. He is always looking to make a
play. He is great at finding one of his teammates coming late (in
transition) and putting the puck right on the tape. You can't give
Gretzky a lot of open ice. You have to get on him right away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Josephine Cashman, the goalie for the Colby women's hockey team,
has a job this year none of us would want. Colby has yet to win a
game. In the last four games, it has been outscored, 45-0, and
outshot, 303-30. Against Providence, Coleman faced 39 shots in the
first period and 83 in the game. Against Princeton, her teammates
had one shot on net. Harvard scored 15 goals and had 60 shots in
two periods before backing off . . . Matt Groh, son of former
Patriots defensive coordinator Al Groh, quarterbacked his team to
the Catholic high school championship in New York City this year
and is being heavily recruited by the Ivy League. He carries a 92
grade average at Chaminade on Long Island . . . The University of
Connecticut has received almost 200 applications for its head
football coaching job. Reportedly, former San Diego Chargers head
coach Kevin Gilbride is one of them. The major irony in this year
of complaints in the NFL is that Gilbride cast the biggest vote
against bringing back instant replay at the annual league meetings
in March. ``We had the votes we needed from the coaches to bring it
back,'' says Colts general manager Bill Polian, ``but then Kevin
switched and went against it. Then he was the first coach fired in
the league this year.'' . . . Rumor has it that CBS college
football analyst Terry Donahue is the leading candidate to become
Charger coach. June Jones, who became the interim coach after
Gilbride was fired, will leave to become coach at the University of
Hawaii, where former Patriots offensive coordinator Larry Kennan
reportedly was the other finalist.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
