<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6086 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADIAN-EXECUTION-TE     12-11 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIAN-EXECUTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS' CLEMENCY PROCEDURE IS SUBJECT OF CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By John Moritz 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When lawyers for condemned killer Karla Faye
Tucker pleaded with a federal judge early this year to spare her
life, the judge said no.
</P>
<P>
   This week, when lawyers for two other Death Row inmates
presented the same arguments to the same judge, asking that their
clients be spared, the judge said yes.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's reversal came as other courts have increasingly
questioned the process by which Texas decides whether to grant a
condemned inmate clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tucker went to her death Feb. 3, U.S. District Judge Sam
Sparks of Austin found no fault with the fact that the Texas Board
of Pardons and Paroles rejected her appeal for a reduced sentence
without a formal hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But the next month, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in an Ohio case
that inmates facing execution are entitled to at least a modicum of
due process when they appeal to the state to spare their lives.
Sparks cited the Ohio ruling when he stopped the executions this
week of Danny Barber and Joseph Stanley Faulder.
</P>
<P>
   Because the parole board holds no public hearings and its
members state no reasons for their decisions, Sparks said, it is
impossible to determine whether the inmates' rights were
safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas attorney general's office is seeking to overturn the
stays issued Wednesday by Sparks, but death penalty opponents said
the judge sent a clear signal that the state's clemency procedures
are seriously flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the board arrives at its decisions when it decides
clemency applications does not give me much faith in its
fairness,'' said Cynthia Orr, a member of the Texas Criminal
Defense Lawyers Association. ``You have members sending in the
votes by phone or fax. They don't have to hear from witnesses.
There's really no telling what goes into the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   But defenders of the process argue that condemned inmates, who
on average spend about nine years on Death Row, have ample
opportunities in the court system to escape execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these folks have been in the system for years and
years, yet they wait until the absolute last moment'' to appeal for
clemency, said Victor Rodriguez, chairman of the 18-member Board of
Pardons and Paroles. ``It's a tactic to stall the execution.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is a stalling tactic, it has been an unsuccessful one.
During the past two years, while Texas has been carrying out
executions in record numbers, only one condemned inmate, Henry Lee
Lucas, has been spared by the board.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas once confessed to more than 600 killings, only to recant
in all but the 1961 stabbing death of his mother in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   But as his June 30 execution date neared, Lucas' lawyers
presented volumes of documents _ including one for a 1985-86
investigation by the Texas attorney general's office casting
serious doubt on the man's guilt in the slaying that earned him the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the Lucas case shows that the state can be
trusted to intervene in cases where strong doubts about guilt
arise. Critics counter that doubts about Lucas' guilt simmered on
the back burner for more than a decade while he lingered on Death
Row.
</P>
<P>
   Two state district judges have skewered the state's clemency
procedures in recent death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sparks acted in the cases of Barber and Faulder, state
District Judge Paul Davis of Austin ordered the parole board to
meet in public to consider their clemency applications.
</P>
<P>
   But plans for an emergency board meeting were scuttled when the
Texas Supreme Court overturned Davis' ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In April, state District Judge Mary Pearl Williams of Austin
made a similar ruling on behalf of condemned killer Lesley Lee
Gosch that was also overturned after the state appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Austin lawyer Maurie Levin, who has handled appeals for numerous
condemned inmates, has filed a class-action lawsuit on behalf of
all Texas Death Row inmates seeking to force the parole board to
hold open meetings. The suit is pending.
</P>
<P>
   She said the judges' actions demonstrate the need to reform the
clemency process.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many judges are hammering Texas on this issue,'' Levin
said. ``I can't help but believe it's going to start sinking in
that there's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But the head of a victims rights group disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is open enough as it is,'' said Dianne Clements of
Justice For All. ``I doubt that putting everyone in the same room
would change the outcomes of their decisions at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
