<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6087 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-PRODUCTION-SPI     12-11 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-PRODUCTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING DECIDES NOT TO OPEN 737 ASSEMBLY PLANT IN LONG BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. said Friday it will keep all final
assembly of its 737 passenger jets in Renton, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The decision reverses one made last summer, but never
implemented, to set up a 737 assembly line in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for Boeing's Seattle workforce, which is facing
layoffs and needs all the work it can get. Bill Johnson, president
of Aerospace Machinists Lodge 751, called it ``a positive thing''
and said his members in the Puget Sound area ``can meet any
challenge'' in aircraft production.
</P>
<P>
   Kedrick Legg, president of United Auto Workers Local 148, which
represents about 7,700 employees in Long Beach, had the opposite
reaction. ``It's like getting punched in the gut right before
Christmas,'' he said. ``The work force is pretty devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Craig Martin said the latest Long Beach
decision _ like the one last summer _ had gone to Boeing's
president and chief operating officer, Harry Stonecipher. The
former McDonnell Douglas boss had first decided to cut his old
division in on the 737 work, and now has cut that division out.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has changed. The focus then was on getting planes
out the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Renton factory was in significant disarray,'' Martin said
of the time when the company considered sending work to California.
``We were missing our customer commitments. We could not look
toward the future with any sense of confidence that we would be
able to make the rate increases we had planned.'' Boeing planned to
go from 14 of the new generation 737s per month last September to
24 per month in March 1999 _ and management was none too sure it
could do that.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, demand for the 737 was so strong that it was
conceivable that Renton would eventually have to produce more than
24 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Production is now under better control. Production rates have
been increased from 14 to 21 on the new-generation 737s, and the
parts shops are all the way to 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renton is humming along,'' said Martin. ``We're not seeing the
high shortages, and we're beginning to bring down some of the high
overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's also bad news on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The company has made its gloomy production forecast for 2000.
Though the 737 remains its best seller, production is forecast to
drop from 24 to 21 per month in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Management's focus is now shifting to costs. Stonecipher has
said the company is using at least 20 percent too much labor time
to assemble the 737. And that's not a problem that calls for a
second production line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some incremental costs of going to Long Beach,''
Martin said. ``In today's environment, we could not justify those
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Long Beach will offer its services to airlines as a
repair shop to modify 737 lap joints, the company said. Lap joints,
the areas in which skin panels overlap, are subject to fatigue
cracking. Martin said that about 250 airplanes would need lap-joint
work in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pearson, vice president and general manager of the Long
Beach Division, said in a prepared statement that his division
could get a good piece of that work, ``if we are competitive. But
we will have to be extremely cost-conscious because we'll be
competing against other organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Long Beach could be competitive within its existing
labor contracts, Martin said `yes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could acheive a rate of five airplanes a month in Long
Beach that would mean about 400 jobs there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Having a 737 line would have saved up to 600 of the 6,000 jobs
Boeing plans to eliminate in Long Beach as it phases out production
of three planes inherited in its takeover last year of McDonnell
Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two weeks, workers at the former Douglas
Aircraft plant have ridden an emotional roller coaster waiting for
Boeing's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel disappointed. I feel like the union finally got its way
up there to keep the work in their house,'' said James Haynes, 44,
a 13-year McDonnell Douglas mechanic at the Long Beach plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't help anyone's job security down here. If we don't
get additional work, layoffs will be hitting real quick, and most
of us will looking for jobs at half our wages,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Kutler, president of Quarterdeck Investment Partners, an
investment bank specializing in defense and aerospace, called the
Boeing announcement a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern California is destined to be a subcontractor and is
no longer a player in the big leagues,'' he said. ``Long Beach was
the last shot at that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
