u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-POSTPONE11-COX     12-11 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-POSTPONE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Evidence mounts that big events influence survival
 &HT;    By Kay Powell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even at the very end of life, we can postpone _ or
hasten _ the moment of our death.
</P>
<P>
   Hospice workers and doctors have long understood how patients
can hang on for an anniversary or the birth of a grandchild, or how
husbands often die within six months of losing their wives. But now
the research of a California sociologist documents these phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   David P. Phillips, a sociology professor at the University of
California at San Diego in La Jolla, Calif., says he's not sure
what the ``biochemistry'' of this bargaining with God is, but he
has compiled statistical evidence proving that deaths from natural
causes _ most commonly cancer, heart disease and strokes _ dip
before a date significant to the person and peak following it.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' most noted research looked at the death rate of
Chinese women for 24 weeks around the Harvest Moon Festival _ when
the oldest woman is in charge _ and at the death rate of Jewish men
around Passover, in which they play the central ceremonial role.
The dip-peak pattern convinced him that people can postpone their
own deaths if they are trying to reach a psychologically
significant occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common example is a 50th wedding anniversary,''
Phillips said. But he found the same dip-peak pattern around
birthdays and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Aylor of Atlanta, a case manager for Children's Hospice _
part of Hospice Atlanta, administered by the Visiting Nurse System
_ says children are most likely to hang on for a birthday, a
graduation or Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``February is a real busy time for us as far as kids dying,''
Aylor said, adding that 18 children in hospice care locally died
between the Tuesday after last Christmas and the end of March this
year.
</P>
<P>
   From the findings of various studies, a pattern of death
emerges. Mortality in general is highest in the winter months.
There are slightly more suicides in the spring. People are more
likely to die of a heart attack on a Monday than on any other day.
Men face a greater risk of dying within six months of the death of
their wife.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Kriseman of Atlanta, who teaches courses on death, dying
and aging at Kennesaw State University(Ga.) and has a private
therapy practice specializing in gerontology, or the care of the
aged, considers the mind's power over the body to be nothing short
of amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Older people ``have a pretty good idea how they want to die,''
Kriseman said. ``They are focused that the end of life is
approaching, and they do end their lives that way.''
</P>
<P>
   One client, she noted, was a horse trainer who insisted he would
die in the saddle _ despite his family's objections _ and he did.
Another client in her late 80s, when told that she needed full-time
residential care, told her daughter that she would never die in a
nursing home. Within 24 hours, she was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, people can hang on for the sake of loved ones.
``They linger in order to take care of the family,'' said Cecil
Fike, founder of Good Grief support groups and director of pastoral
care for WellStar Health System. ``Patients still tend to take care
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman who had suffered a massive stroke was on a ventilator
and was not expected to live through the night, Fike recalled. Six
days later, she was still clinging to life. Fike advised her
children to tell her they would be OK and would take care of their
father. Hearing that, Fike said, the woman died within five
minutes. A slightly different logic applies when the one near death
is a child, Aylor said. Especially a young one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents have to be able to tell them it's OK to die. Kids
suffer longer when the parents won't let them go.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child's not going to die until they're good and ready,''
Aylor said. ``It's between the child and God. When things are the
way the child wants them to be, they will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay Powell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
