<HEADER>
A6093 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-TRENDS13-COX     12-11 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-TRENDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An odd year, with bad taste up to no good
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If 1998 needs a totem to tell future scholars what
really mattered in American culture this year, it may take a coin
toss to decide what goes in the time capsule.
</P>
<P>
   Blue dress from the Gap or a videotape of uncensored excerpts
from ``Jerry Springer''? A dab of that mystery hair gel from
``There's Something About Mary'' or a stack of autographed
transcripts from Kenneth Starr? From the reel to the surreal, bad
taste was a consistent theme in popular life and media. An ongoing
explosion of Internet technology made everyone a potential porn
star, every dream home the set of a do-it-yourself ``Truman Show.''
Even the Oval Office was not immune. Especially the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you had heroes like Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire slugging
for history's horizon, and 77-year-old John Glenn making a return
rendezvous with the heavens, but, mostly, it felt like a year
secretly scripted by Beavis and Butt-head. And, as that
pseudo-hermaphroditic free speech advocate Marilyn Manson reminded
us, ``We're all stars in the Dope Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the white-trashing of America is necessarily a Very Bad
Thing. There's something kind of kicky about a national
bottom-feeding frenzy. For one, it's democratic. People have more
to say to each other. And it's funny. Weird funny. Ha-ha funny.
Gross-out funny. Glad-it's-not-me funny.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, rising to the occasion, reflected the trend most
vividly. Bust-out hits ``There's Something About Mary'' and ``The
Waterboy'' somehow made scatalogical humor oddly sweet and
sentimental. Meanwhile, the terminally dysfunctional family in
indie filmmaker Todd Solondz's ``Happiness'' simply made you
relieved to be on the other side of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the republic seemed to be sinking like James Cameron's
``Titanic,'' the economy kept spirits afloat. An abiding theme
could have been written by Puff Daddy: It's all about the
Benjamins, stupid. And the hip-hop impresario, crisp as one of
those $100 bills he sang about, ought to know. As rock music
continued its slow fade _ except as background music for car
commercials _ rap increasingly dominated the pop charts, confirming
a major cultural shift. Fugees vocalist Lauryn Hill took the high
ground on her righteous solo debut, ``The Miseducation of Lauryn
Hill,'' sharing a spiritual vibe with such non-rapping soul sisters
as Alanis Morissette, Jewel and Madonna (whose techno-pulsed ``Ray
of Light'' appropriated two trends at once: electronica and Hindu
chic). New star Jay-Z borrowed a sample from Broadway's ``Annie''
to offer a graphic depiction of a ``Hard Knock Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Down in New Orleans, rapper-mogul Master P turned his No Limit
Records into a production powerhouse, groaning and grunting over
heavy beats. Can you say ``Uhhhhhhhh?'' While he became rap's new
``ghetto hero,'' Atlanta-based artists Outkast and Goodie Mob
offered listeners inventive relief from Puff'n'Fluff radio
redundancy.
</P>
<P>
   Such vibrant output wasn't the only lightning rod drawing
attention to Atlanta, of course, as the city became part of the
year's major publishing event: Tom Wolfe's mega-hyped ``A Man in
Full.'' The former journalist's broad social satire tweaked
Atlanta's provincial nerves with its epic tale of a big-time real
estate developer on the ropes and sold Danielle Steel-like numbers.
Meanwhile, much-admired Atlanta playwright, essayist and novelist
Pearl Cleage joined the ranks of authors invited to Oprah Winfrey's
Book Club.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Wolfe could donate some of his profits to the Arts
Festival of Atlanta, which shut down after 44 years when it
couldn't rebound from massive debts incurred by the event's bold
relocation downtown in 1997. Accusatory fingers pointed in all
directions, but one of the disturbing upshots seems to be that
Atlanta isn't ready to get behind a world-class arts festival. We'd
really rather watch sports on big-screen TV. While second-guessers
said, ``I told you so,'' there were encouraging signs of life: New
art spaces began to pop up downtown, and two concert halls _ the
Rialto Center for the Performing Arts and the Tabernacle _ thrived.
Transitions continued elsewhere, as well, as the Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra searched for a new conductor, the High Museum of Art and
the Carlos Museum welcomed new curators, and the Nexus Contemporary
Art Center looked for a new director.
</P>
<P>
   The city's biggest pop event, a production of Disney's
``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida,'' didn't have much to do
with the theater that happened to host it _ the Alliance. But it
didn't matter one way or another, in terms of the Alliance's
artistic stature, because Kenny Leon had already alloyed pop
culture glamour and home-grown excellence with his stunning
production of Phylicia Rashad's ``Medea.'' And if high culture
wasn't your cup of meat, by golly, there was the Dad's Garage
production of ``Cannibal! The Musical,'' an adaptation of a film by
``South Park'' creator Trey Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Bad taste? Pass the salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
