<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-PLANTS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seasonal greenery mixes with small shrubs and houseplants to
make the indoors festive
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Too rushed to deck the halls? Too cramped to put up a
tree?
</P>
<P>
   Relax. You can still bring the holidays indoors with a seasonal
plant, such as a poinsettia, Christmas cactus or potted spruce. But
why not think outside the decorating box and combine those plants
with less traditional ones to create eye-catching displays?
Creamy-white poinsettias with deep red amaryllis and frilly
maidenhair fern. Bright red poinsettias with delicate white orchids
and trailing English ivy. Pastel-pink amaryllis with sweet-scented
paperwhite narcissus and pink-and-green variegated calathea.
</P>
<P>
   Or to keep things really simple, try a potted or burlapped
landscape plant _ a boxwood, cedar or cryptomeria, or a shrubby
herb such as rosemary or lavender _ clip it in a conical shape to
resemble a Christmas tree and tie a ribbon around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's nice is that after the holidays most of these plants
can be put in the garden. So you end up with something for indoors
or out,'' said Dan Belman of Boxwoods Gardens and Gifts in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Think of these live arrangements, or ``compositions,'' as a pot
of soup. Each plant, like each ingredient, is fine by itself. But
when you combine them with others, the results can be delectable.
</P>
<P>
   The key, said Randy Korando, Boxwoods' co-owner, is to think
big. ``If you aren't doing a tree, do masses of plants with a lot
of the same color to create impact,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you know which plants make good mates?
</P>
<P>
   Consider the plants' color, scale and texture. You already know
the Christmas colors. For scale, aim for a plant that will provide
height (orchids, amaryllis, paperwhites), something that will spill
over the container (ferns, ivy, creeping fig) and a medium-size
plant for filling in the center (poinsettia, kalanchoe, cyclamen).
Or, as best-selling gardening author Felder Rushing puts it,
``something roundy, something spiky and something frilly.''
</P>
<P>
   Think outside the clay pot as well. Look around the house before
rushing out to buy something new, Korando said. Consider Grandma's
silver epergne, the garden's rustic urn, the deck's concrete
trough.
</P>
<P>
   The cost for a composition, whether you create it yourself or
pay a florist, varies widely, depending on its size and the plant
selection. ``But for the cost of an arrangement of cut flowers that
will last only three days, you can have something that lasts for
three months,'' Belman said.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the case of potted landscape plants, even longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't do anything but buy a little boxwood and tie a
big red bow around it,'' said Judy Perry of Forrester's, an Atlanta
florist, ``the point is to bring something indoors for Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   TRY THESE COMBINATIONS
</P>
<P>
   6 combo recipes
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A trough of red amaryllis underplanted with white poinsettias
and ivy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A white orchid, silver lace fern and variegated ivy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paperwhites, small red poinsettias and maidenhair fern.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pink amaryllis, calathea and ivy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A white or red azalea topiary underplanted with wheat grass.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Three white amaryllis, silver lace fern and variegated ivy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An Alberta spruce, primrose and maidenhair fern.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
