<HEADER>
A6097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRESS-BOOKS12-COX     12-11 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRESS-BOOKS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Books offer ideas for handling hectic holidays
 &HT;    By Amanda Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More evidence 13 is an unlucky number: Count the days
until Christmas. And you're already at wits' end.
</P>
<P>
   The holidays ratchet up everyday stresses and worries.
</P>
<P>
   A little concerned about the family budget? Well, you still have
to buy gifts for your sister's four kids. That's if you can find a
parking space at the store.
</P>
<P>
   How to cope? Books and books and more books have plenty of
advice on stress relief. At a Barnes &AMP; Noble store in Atlanta,
countless volumes offer hope for ``Instant Stress Relief'' or
``Mastery of Stress.''
</P>
<P>
   What stress books all stress are the three basics _ good diet,
regular exercise and restful sleep. But there's also some advice
you might not expect _ deep breathing, for instance, or saying
``no'' without guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Ten pieces of advice from dozens of people who know enough about
stress relief to write a book:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Thorsons Principles of Stress Management'' (Thorsons
publishers, $11):Pay attention to the warning signs of stress:
Increased smoking or drinking, overeating, eating very little,
neglecting appearance, shutting yourself off from others, driving
aggressively, starting lots of projects and never finishing them,
nervous activities such as nail biting or hair pulling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Idiot's Guide to Managing Stress'' (Alpha Books, $16.95):
Check your stress level by mapping out your average work week, and
activities outside of work, particularly during the holidays. Start
with your start time _ whether it's heading to the office or
dropping the kids at school _ and note lunch and break times, and
get a daily total. Is it too much to handle comfortably? Ask for
help from co-workers or family; cut back on activities that aren't
essential.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Instant Stress Relief'' (Ballantine Books, $5.99):Eat
well-balanced meals, including breakfast, and drink plenty of
water. Take a vitamin-mineral supplement, eat more fiber and limit
saturated fats. Monitor caffeine consumption, and if you drink, do
so in moderation. Learn which foods relax you. If it's a cup of
herbal tea, drink it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Working Woman's Guide to Managing Stress'' (Prentice
Hall, $14.95):Without exercise you become more fatigued and tense,
not less. If you can't take an exercise class or schedule time for
some other organized activity, put on some music and dance around
the house for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Life Puzzle, Putting the Pieces Together'' (Good for You
publishing, $24.95), ``Thorsons Principles of Stress Management,''
``Idiot's Guide to Managing Stress'' and many other books:Breathe.
Deep breathing as a relaxation technique can be done anytime,
anywhere. It slows down a racing heart and mind, gives you time to
reflect.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Guide to Stress Reduction'' (Celestial Arts, $12.95) and
many other books:Meditate. That doesn't necessarily mean a mantra
and lotus position. It could just mean sitting quietly for five
minutes in a comfortable chair, closing your eyes and letting your
mind drift. If you fall asleep, back to the basics _ maybe you're
not getting that good night's rest.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Working Woman's Guide to Managing Stress,'' ``Beat
Stress With Strength, A Survival Guide to for Work and Life'' (Park
Avenue Productions, $12.95), and others:Just say ``no,'' say it
without guilt, say it politely and mean it. Taking on too much
because others ``need'' you is a quick route to burnout.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``When 9 to 5 Isn't Enough'' (Hay House Inc., $12):Take breaks
during the work day. Even five minutes outside the office can do
wonders for concentration and recharging, and fresh air is
refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Working Woman's Guide to Managing Stress,'' ``Idiot's
Guide to Managing Stress'' and others:Practice visualization
techniques, visualize the future. People who use visualization as a
stress-reducer think about pastoral scenes; clear, cool streams;
places they visited once and loved. Those who visualize the future
begin to plan ways to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Idiot's Guide to Managing Stress'' and others:Use
aromatherapy. Remember the welcoming smell of mom's fresh-baked
bread? Pleasing scents have the ability to soothe the most troubled
mind. All the better if it's scented bath oil and the end of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, try counting backward from 13, one day at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
