</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANUKKAH12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For many American Jews with small children, focusing on their
own religious beliefs this time of year becomes the challenge of
Hanukkah
 &HT;    By Ron Feinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While the religious holidays of Christmas and Hanukkah
fall at about the same time each year, they share little in common.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the beauty of Christmas _ twinkling lights, festive
music, decorated wreaths and trees _ is a distraction and constant
challenge for Jewish educators and parents wanting to teach their
kids about the Jewish holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Hanukkah, the Festival of Lights, begins at sundown Sunday and
continues for eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's difficult to keep our focus on our holiday,''
says Raye Lynn Banks, director of the Sunshine School, a Jewish
preschool in east Cobb County(GA.) operated by the Atlanta Jewish
Community Center. ``Kids see all the lights and can't help but
think about all the gifts'' their Christian friends are getting for
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Hanukkah, which means dedication in Hebrew, recalls the
rededication of the Second Temple in Jerusalem after the military
victory of the Maccabees over the Seleucid Greeks in 165 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday is celebrated by lighting one candle the first night
of the festival, two on the second, and so on, until eight candles
are burning in a special candleholder, a menorah, on the eighth and
final night.
</P>
<P>
   The story includes a spiritual twist, based on a Talmudic
legend, that details a miracle. When the Maccabees rededicated the
Temple, they found only one small jar of sacred oil to be used to
rekindle the holy menorah. The jar contained oil for only one
night, but miraculously burned for eight, until fresh oil could be
produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the messages of Hanukkah is that those who are devoted
and committed can overcome great odds,'' says Rabbi Shalom Lewis of
Congregation Etz Chaim in east Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge,'' says Lewis, 49, ``is never to be intimidated
by overwhelming odds.''
</P>
<P>
   But practicing Judaism and observing Hanukkah in America,
particularly in the Bible Belt of the South, can be intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of purpose and sense of humor can help.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my daughter Jill was small we were at the mall and she
saw Santa,'' Lewis says. ``She wanted to sit on Santa's lap, like
all the other kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told her the line was way too long and perhaps we could
just walk by him and wave. She was OK with that. She waved and
Santa waved back. It worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so easily handled, however, is the issue of gifts.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, Hanukkah was a minor holiday on the Jewish
calendar, a time to recall the might of the Maccabees and the
miracle of the oil.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1920s in America, some Jewish parents started doing
for their children what their Christian neighbors already were
doing each Christmas. That link _ the giving of gifts _ continues
to this day.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Sunshine School and other preschools and synagogues,
efforts are made each year to focus on the religious significance
of the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to let the kids know all about the holiday,'' said
Ellen Michelson, assistant director of the Sunshine School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids know about the gifts; but we try to teach them why we
celebrate the holiday, about the customs and history,'' Michelson
added. ``The kids are very receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day at the Sunshine School, the ``Superstars'' (a
classroom of 18 4-year-olds) are making dreidels, a top with Hebrew
letters on its four sides that is used in a holiday game.
</P>
<P>
   Their little fingers juggle the plum-sized pieces of wood as
they attempt to paste the multicolored Hebrew letters onto the
smooth sides.
</P>
<P>
   Class discussion, led by Linda Geiger, a nine-year teacher at
the school, focuses on the Maccabees and doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can all be Maccabees,'' Geiger tells her students.
</P>
<P>
   And many agree, offering suggestions on what they can do right
in their lives, like listening to their parents, talking nice and
not making fun of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting along'' is good and right, says Geiger, 59.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a thought Lewis thinks many of us need to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first message of Hanukkah is religious freedom,''
Lewis says. ``There are elements in our society today that think
their religious system is the answer for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the case,'' he says. ``Such thinking is spiritual
tyranny and has no place in God's world.''
</P>
<P>
   But the other side of the puzzle, he says, is believing in
nothing, forgetting the transcendent messages of both holidays,
trying to somehow ``squash the two beliefs'' into one.
</P>
<P>
   Banks remembers facing the issue squarely, telling her own
children years ago why Santa never made it to their house each
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanukkah,'' she remembers saying, ``isn't a Jewish
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Fienberg is the religion editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
