u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-TIPS12-COX     12-11 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-TIPS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here are some ideas to reduce stress of December days
 &HT;    By Eric Sundquist
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adopting a simple lifestyle can be a complicated undertaking. At
least it would be if you tried to read all the books on the
subject, or thoroughly downsize by selling your sport-utility
vehicle and five-bedroom house.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not necessary to get a degree in simplicity to take
advantage of some of its ideas, and the holidays offer many
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just taking one step _ maybe having a potluck instead of a
formal Christmas dinner _ will go a long way toward minimizing the
stress people feel at the holidays,'' says Elaine St. James, author
of ``Simplify Your Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   A starting point for simplifying the holidays: ``Sit down and
take some time and think. What do we like? And what causes the
stress? For some it might be the shopping, or it might be Christmas
cards,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ideas to consider, from St. James and others.
Before you call us Scrooge, remember that the Cratchit family had a
truly merry Christmas without ever visiting a mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about bah, humbug,'' says St. James. ``It's about
making choices. We can't do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ignore the how-to holiday articles that fill many magazines
all autumn. Martha Stewart has some great ideas, but she also has a
large staff and electronic airbrushing programs to make them look
truly picture-perfect. In the real world, a simple holiday dinner _
even pizza _ might be more pleasant for the family than one that
requires hours of preparation and cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't confuse organizing with simplifying. Being organized
might actually complicate things. Shopping and decorating early may
just spread stress through more of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Consider the environment. Eco-sound practices often have a
side benefit of saving money. Wrapping presents and mailing
Christmas cards, for example, are costly to the wallet and the
Earth's resources. Another Earth-friendly idea: Instead of killing
a tree to have in the house for a few weeks, decorate one in the
yard with popcorn or birdseed, and watch the birds flock to feed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cut back on gift giving and receiving. Have everyone in your
extended family draw one name; each person can give and get one
thoughtful gift instead of 20 landfill-bound electric tie racks or
Chia Pets. Cut back at home, too. The kids might just get the
message that the holidays aren't only about getting presents. Take
the idea one step further and give the gift of your family's time
in a homeless shelter or other charity.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Above all, do what's meaningful, not what you think is
expected. The holidays can become a keeping-up-with-the-Joneses
treadmill. Getting off means you might not win the subdivision
award for best holiday decor. But the simple creche or menorah you
put up in place of a Las Vegas-like light show might be the only
symbol you really need to tap into the seasonal spirit. ``When I
started to simplify, some people said `What?' '' says St. James, a
former real estate businesswoman. ``But I said I'm not interested
in impressing people who want to live like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Sundquist writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
