<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgians help to restore Jesus' hometown
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four Georgians are helping to restore and re-create
the hometown of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Carter and his wife, Rosalynn; former Atlanta
Mayor Andrew Young; and Linda C. Fuller, president of Habitat for
Humanity International, are all key players in the Miracle of
Nazareth International Foundation Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation recently began work restoring first-century
terrace walls and clearing brush on a Nazareth hillside
archaeologists say once may have been cultivated by Jesus and his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers hope to have a significant part of the work complete
in time for the influx of millions of pilgrims to Israel in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This will be no Six Flags Over the Holy Land, Fuller promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to develop a theme park,'' she said. ``It
will be more on the idea of historic Williamsburg. Much research
has to go into it to make it as authentic as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   People will be dressed in period costume doing work that may
have been done in Jesus' time, she said. There also will be a
museum where visitors can learn the New Testament version of Jesus'
life, death and resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   On her first visit to Israel, Fuller said, she was disappointed
so many sites believed to have been significant in Jesus' time are
now covered by churches and shrines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to get a sense of the way it would have
been when Jesus was there,'' she said. ``Our purpose is to
re-create a setting that would have been very similar to the way it
would have been.''
</P>
<P>
   About 400 volunteers from the Nazareth area joined the mayor of
Nazareth and project organizers in late November to clear brush
from the land and rebuild terrace walls. The work is supervised by
conservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Workers hope to reclaim archaeological finds, such as a wine
press, watchtowers and farmland terraces that date to early Roman
and Hellenistic periods, and to reconstruct houses and other
buildings to resemble as nearly as possible those of the first
century.
</P>
<P>
   When work is complete, visitors should get a better
understanding of Jesus' life and of some of the parables and
lessons of his ministry, said Dr. Nakhle Bishara, an Arab Christian
physician in Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where people once saw dusty stones and open meadows, we hope
they'll now see the mustard plants, vineyards and olive trees of
Jesus' childhood that he used to illustrate spiritual truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
