<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texans react to tobacco settlement lawsuit
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans for Reasonable Legal Fees blasted it as
an unreasonable legal fee.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Metroplex Citizens Against Lawsuit Abuse said
it's the reason they are against lawsuit abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush called it ``exorbitant,'' and the chairman
of the House Appropriations Committee blasted it as ``excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is some debate about exactly how much money five
Texas law firms will share for representing the state in the
tobacco lawsuit, there is no doubt that the answer will include a
word _ ``billion'' _ that produces unfiltered disgust among some.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Friday he just doesn't get it and doesn't think he
ever will. The fees, valued at $3.3 billion by the lawyers who will
get them over several years, are ``exorbitant,'' said the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never understand and never agree that five private law
firms should collect more than $3.3 billion for working less than
two years on a case that was settled before it went to trial,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fee seems totally out of proportion for the work
performed,'' said Bush, former managing general partner of a
baseball team that paid players millions of dollars to use a wooden
club-like device to attempt to strike a horsehide-covered sphere.
</P>
<P>
   The suddenly-even-richer lawyers were cool under pressure Friday
as the criticism piled up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a true honor to represent the state of Texas in its
historic lawsuit against the tobacco industry,'' they said Friday
in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   The fee was set by an arbitration panel including members
appointed by the attorneys and the tobacco industry. In their
Friday statement, the lawyers said the panel came up with a base
fee of 10 percent of the $17.3-billion settlement, but didn't stop
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognizing the staggering risks in taking up the tobacco
fight, Texas' contributions as pioneers in tobacco litigation and
the tremendous results we obtained, the panel determined to apply a
`difficulty' factor of 1.9 percent,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was pleased that his intervention in the court
battle helped make sure the lawyers' fees will come from the
tobacco companies, not taxpayers' pockets.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, blasted
the fees, but said he could do little more than gripe from the
sidelines as long as the money does not come from state coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the amount of money is excessive,'' said Junell, an
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Ratliff, executive director of the Metroplex Citizens
Against Lawsuit Abuse, called the arbitrators' award ``the epitome
of legal fee abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
