</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-SCHOOL-ESCAPE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Offenders break out of youth lockup
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Five of 11 teen-age offenders who cut their way
to freedom through a fence at a Bryan prison for juveniles were
recaptured Friday as a statewide manhunt continued for the others,
including one who called his mother and promised to be home for
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The youths, ages 14 to 17, were being held at the Hamilton State
School on charges ranging from burglary to arson to robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had this many kids escape before from any of our
facilities,'' said Judy Briscoe, a spokeswoman for the Texas Youth
Commission, which operates the 520-bed Hamilton lockup. ``We feel
it was a planned escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Dale Price said the escapees apparently used a
key to unlock a fire-escape door, then cut a hole in a 12-foot-high
security fence with wire-cutters. An investigation was under way to
determine how the delinquents got access to both items.
</P>
<P>
   Recaptured without incident about 3 p.m. Friday were Michael
Barker, 16, of Athens; Mark Gamez, 17, of Arlington; Kenneth
McLarty, 16, of Stephenville; Steve Lair, 14, of Glen Rose; and
Billy Sanford, 14, of Port Arthur. Police said they were found
hiding inside an abandoned trailer about two miles south of the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Barker and Gamez were serving time at Hamilton
on drug charges, McLarty was in for indecency with a child, and
Lair and Sanford were in for burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Still at large were James Remmer, 17, of Dallas, held for
assault with a weapon; Joseph Trahan, 15, of Hardin County, held
for escape; Tim Bain, 16, of San Antonio, for theft; Donald Flint,
17, of Houston, for armed robbery; Chris Victorino, 16, of San
Antonio, for arson; and Brian Frazer, 16, of Abilene, for burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Flint was being sought in Houston, where he reportedly paid his
grandmother a brief visit and phoned his mother to announce he
would be home for Christmas, Briscoe said. Another escapee was
spotted in San Antonio, and others were believed headed for the
Dallas area. Police searches were under way in those cities late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the escape occurred about 7:30 p.m. Thursday,
as a steady rain and fog blanketed the area.
</P>
<P>
   A security panel signaled that a locked fire escape in one of
the center's dorms had been opened. Guards who checked it spotted a
third of the dorm's residents squeezing through a hole in a
perimeter fence about 15 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the fence was clipped open at a point where the
chain-link panels are attached to a metal pole. Once through the
fence, the escapees split up as they sprinted across an open field
toward Bryan's business district. ``Five ran one direction; three
went another; three went off in another,'' Briscoe said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time police and sheriff's deputies could cordon off the
area, some escapees had stolen a car from an employee's parking lot
and others had fled on foot. The car was recovered near the Texas
A&AMP;M University campus in College Station, several miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they probably stole another car there, but we have no
reports yet of one being missing,'' Briscoe said. Bloodhound teams
from the Texas Department of Criminal Justice were brought in late
Thursday to assist the more than 100 law enforcement officers who
searched throughout the night in the immediate area. But their
efforts were hampered by the bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the escape the youths were wearing assorted
orange jumpsuits and khaki and blue pants with T-shirts _ ``their
normal apparel,'' Briscoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Youth commission officials immediately ordered a full
investigation of the escape, including a review of security
procedures at the year-old lockup, which in recent months has been
plagued by behavioral problems among offenders. Officials said it
was the first escape at Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe said no key had been re- ported missing by staff
members, and investigators were attempting to determine how the
youths got a key to unlock the fire door.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Texas' adult prisons, the youth commission's lockups have
only a single perimeter fence. Guards at the youth lockups are not
armed as they are in prisons, although doors are kept locked and
offenders' whereabouts are closely monitored and controlled.
</P>
<P>
   While youth commission officials would not say Friday whether
any of the escapees had been involved in the earlier problems,
Briscoe said several of them were within a month of being released.
In the past, Briscoe said, escapes from youth commission lockups
have involved only up to four offenders at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-12-11-98 2138E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
