u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT12-     12-11 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyers win fees in Texas tobaaco settlement
 &HT;    WITH REACT-COX
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Five Texas lawyers hired to sue U.S. cigarette
makers have won legal fees that could amount to almost $3.3 billion
over 25 years, a divided three-person team of arbitrators has
decided.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas lawyers said Friday that the tobacco industry _ and
not the state _ is obligated to pay the entire amount, but one of
the arbitrators said the attorneys will likely see no more than $1
billion. A a second arbitrator called the fees excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and others called the fees excessive for a
case that never went to court. The tobacco industry settled with
Texas for $17.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the arbitrators affects only what lawyers from
Texas, Florida and Mississippi will receive. Two of the same
arbitrators must also determine next year what lawyers from other
states will be paid as part of a $206 billion national agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the national agreement, the industry is only
obligated to pay $500 million a year in legal fees. All attorneys
from all states must draw from that pot of cash.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrators also decided that a sixth attorney, Marc Murr of
Houston, should be paid $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Murr surprised and angered many attorneys when he laid claim to
part of the legal fees despite criticism that he did little
apparent work in the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement with Murr and his claims to the fees drew sharp
protest from Arthur Golden, one of the attorneys representing the
tobacco industry and may result in investigations by lawmakers and
Attorney General-elect John Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Murr clearly is not entitled, as he claims, to one-sixth
of the aggregate attorneys' fee that the panel determines is
reasonable for this litigation,'' Golden wrote in a letter to the
arbitrators obtained by the Austin American-Statesman. ``All
reasonably probative evidence makes clear that any contributions by
Murr was at most paltry _ both relatively and in absolute terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Murr's attorney, Roy Minton of Austin, said Golden's objections
were refuted at the arbitration hearing last weekend in New York.
``It was clear that he did not have knowledge of anything,'' Minton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrators' award to the Texas plaintiffs' lawyers _
calculated at 19 percent of what Texas recovered from the tobacco
companies _ surpasses the federal court order setting their fees at
15 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement the Texas lawyers issued Friday, they recalled
their contributions in winning the $17 billion state settlement,
but it did not mention whether they would seek money from the
state's recovery _ which they are entitled to do under the terms of
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that lawyers for 46 other states that settled with
tobacco companies last month would share in the $500 million-a-year
legal fees in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until all of these 46 states' fees are determined, it is
impossible to know how much in fees the Texas attorneys will
actually receive or what it is worth in today's dollars,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who sued to protest the legal fees awarded by the judge in
January because he believed the state was obligated to pay them,
called the arbitrators' award exorbitant. ``The fee seems totally
out of proportion for the work performed,'' Bush said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Tort-reform groups also complained.
</P>
<P>
   Even the arbitration panel was split over the size of the legal
fees.
</P>
<P>
   One of the members, former federal judge Charles Renfrew, of San
Francisco, said the huge fees only help to undermine the the legal
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work of counsel in each of the states has truly been
remarkable and brought about unparalleled recoveries,'' he wrote in
a dissenting opinion. ``They should be fairly and fully
compensated. However, we need to be mindful that these excessive
fees will undermine public confidence in this arbitration, in our
profession and in our civil justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the arbitration panel, Texas Tech Law School
Dean Frank Newton, said the $3.3 billion calculation for the Texas
legal fees was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Even if no other lawyers for other states shared in the legal
fees, Newton said, a Yale professor's financial analysis showed the
tobacco industry would never pay more than $7 billion when the $500
million-a-year payment was reduced to what it would be worth today
in a lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   At best, the private lawyers would get only $1.1 billion if they
cashed in the tobacco companies' obligation the way mortgage
lenders resell home loans reduced to present values.
</P>
<P>
   The Murr award by the so-called national arbitration panel, in
stark contrast to what a state panel said his work deserved,
represented a broader consideration by the national panel, Newton
said. Murr's own panel considered only his contract and support by
Morales and Murr, the attorney general's friend and onetime
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Murr's attorney, Minton, said he did not know whether Murr would
seek a court order based on his special panel's finding that he
deserved 1.5 percent of the state's $17 billion recovery, or more
than $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Morales supported Murr's claim before the national arbitrators
last Saturday. He has said Murr was invaluable in helping him with
strategy _ including the decision to sue the tobacco companies for
racketeering _ and assisted in choosing the state's tobacco team.
</P>
<P>
   But Murr's contract was dated in October 1996, months after
Morales hired the trial lawyers and after the state filed its
lawsuit with the racketeering claim in it.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys involved in various stages of the Texas tobacco
litigation said they never dealt with him. And two legislators who
negotiated an agreement for county hospitals to share in the
tobacco recovery _ an issue that stalled completion of the
settlement last summer _ said Murr tried to attend a final
negotiating session but they threw him out of the room at a
Texarkana courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard of the guy, much less saw him,'' said state Sen.
Bill Ratliff, who with state Rep. Rob Junell helped seal the deal
with hospital districts and counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junell said to him, 'Who are you?' Then he kicked him out,''
Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said he and Junell had discussed a legislative
investigation of Murr's contract and claims when news broke this
week about his arbitration award.
</P>
<P>
   With his letter to the national arbitrators, Golden attached an
affidavit by another tobacco attorney, Stephen Patton of Chicago,
to support his claim that ``Mr. Murr's connection to the State's
case has been at best limited and indirect; at worst, it is a
post-hoc fabrication to exploit these proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales and his spokesman, Ron Dusek, could not be reached for
comment late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
