<HEADLINE>
STADIUM SITE CAN BE CLEANED UP, REGIONAL EPA CHIEF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY AND GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Mass. _ Federal officials who once warned that the
site of the proposed new stadium for the New England Patriots
reeked of contamination, declared Friday the area could be cleaned
and made a model of environmental efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was a dramatic turnabout from weeks ago when
environmental concerns at the site along the Connecticut River
threatened to undo the state's controversial plan to move the
football team to a $350 million publicly-financed stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But after touring the site Friday, John DeVillars, regional head
of the Environmental Protection Agency, enthusiastically embraced
the stadium proposal, saying the contamination cleanup would be
less costly than originally thought and that the stadium would be a
showcase for new environmentally sound construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great opportunity here to bring in environmental
design principles _ through building materials and water
conservation,'' said DeVillars, who was joined on his tour by U.S.
Senator Joseph Lieberman, Hartford Mayor Michael Peters and project
visionary Richard Fiondella, chairman of Phoenix Home Life Mutual
Insurance Co. ``If we work together we can make this a model for
environmental design and efficiency. That's one of the things we
very much want to work on with project developer,'' DeVillars said.
</P>
<P>
   The US Department of Housing and Urban Development has already
committed $9 million _ a $2 million grant and a $7 million loan for
cleaning up the extensive contamination that could run seven-feet
deep, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   A coal gasification plant that operated on the site from the
late 1800s until 1951 left behind coal, tar, and other hazardous
wastes such as benzine, cyanides, and heavy metals, officials have
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeVillars said the 2001 target date for opening the
stadium is ``aggressive,'' he said it was not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary estimates for the cleanup have ranged between $80
million and $100 million. A full study on the environmental
problems at the site could begin within the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the contamination is significant, it is by no means
unresolvable and we're fully committed to working with the
developers to remediate the site expeditiously,'' DeVillars said.
</P>
<P>
   As he was touring the site Friday, Patriots owner Robert Kraft
and his son Jonathan met with Governor John Rowland's chief stadium
negotiators for most of the day, hammering out the details of a
development agreement before next Tuesday's scheduled vote by the
Connecticut General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who was in New London christening the USS Connecticut,
canceled plans to attend a reception at Foxwoods Resort &AMP; Casino
for the submarine launch and drove back to the Capitol to meet with
the Krafts around 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   While it has been widely speculated that the discussions would
mostly center on Rowland's desire to rewrite a controversial luxury
seat guarantee that could cost the state $175 million, officials
said more mundane aspects of the complex agreement took up most of
the negotiations. The first item on the agenda, according to people
close the negotiations, concerned guarantees that roads, ramps and
parking lots could be built in such a way to allow cars to be out
of stadium traffic in less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   However, Patriots business manager Andy Wasynczuk, who was also
in the meetings Friday night, said lawmakers' desire to reduce the
state's risk on luxury seat guarantees would be discussed at some
point. Those guarantees would require the state to pay the team a
subsidy if it is unable to sell all of the expensive club seats and
luxury boxes. Skeptical legislators, of which there are a few, have
criticized those guarantees as a needless giveaway and have
threatened to vote against the proposal unless they are whittled
down.
</P>
<P>
   While the Krafts reportedly want to keep the guarantees intact,
there appeared to be some ``wiggle room,'' on the provisions,
sources said Friday. And officials said they weren't a major factor
in Friday's talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been a lot about the development agreement, which
is going to be a highly technical and detailed document,''
Wasynczuk said. ``It's gotten to the point where communication
pretty much needs to be continuous til Tuesday. So whether it's by
meeting or phone communication or what have you, we'll be working
until Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rowland's budget director, Marc Ryan, released yet
another financial analysis of the project that contends the state
will reap between $20 million and $650 million over the 30-year
leasae period, depending on stadium attendance, the health of the
state economy and how big a draw the University of Connecticut's
upgraded football team becomes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
