<SLUG> BC-BOMB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING AWAITED ON EXTRADITION OF SUSPECTED BIN LADEN AIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (rl) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A German official said Friday that his government has received
indications from U.S. officials that they will not seek the death
penalty for a suspected aide to Osama bin Laden, which could clear
a major hurdle to win the man's extradition from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   German law prohibits extradition of suspects to countries where
they could face charges carrying the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Germany's highest court dismissed an appeal by
the suspected aide, Mamdouh Mahmud Salim, who has been fighting
extradition since his arrest three months ago in Munich on charges
of conspiring to murder Americans abroad and use weapons of mass
destruction. Salim, 40, has denied the charges or that he is a
member of any terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   American officials would not confirm the German account Friday
night, but the German official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that Salim could be turned over to face charges in
New York within a week or two. German officials must still receive
formal word from the United States, he said, and also review
Friday's court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The extradition process involving Salim may force American
prosecutors to take a public position on the death penalty earlier
than they had wanted and to rule it out in at least one
high-profile prosecution where they may have felt it was
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   It also sets up the possibility that some defendants accused of
being high-ranking associates of bin Laden would escape capital
prosecution, while other more junior operatives would face
execution if they are convicted. Bin Laden is suspected of
masterminding the bombings of the American embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania last August and other acts of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Manhattan told a federal judge on Oct. 8 that
``the death penalty will seriously be considered'' in the case of
two other defendants who were arrested after the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-'Owhali and Mohammed Saddiq
Odeh, have each been charged with separate counts of murder in the
deaths of more than 200 people in the attacks. Each man has pleaded
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   But neither man has been portrayed by prosecutors in the kind of
senior position which the government contends Salim had in the
organization run by bin Laden. Salim has been described in
government documents as a close associate of bin Laden who managed
the group's finances, tried to buy material for nuclear weapons,
and worked with officials of Sudan in a joint-weapons production
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers for other suspects charged in the case refused
comment Friday, and Salim's lawyer in Germany could not be reached
by phone for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But experts in the federal death penalty law said that if the
government rules out a capital prosecution for Salim, and for a
second suspect awaiting extradition from Britain, it may make it
easier for the lawyers for Odeh and al-'Owhali to argue that it
should be ruled out in the case of their clients as well.
</P>
<P>
   One of the mitigating factors which the Justice Department is
required to consider in deciding whether to seek capital
punishment, the experts said, is whether other equally culpable
defendants in a crime will not be punished by death.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision on whether to seek the death penalty, in any
case, is made by Attorney General Janet Reno, after receiving a
recommendation from the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, Mary Jo White.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
