<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6114 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-CADBURY12-COX     12-11 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-CADBURY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal frees up company to narrow focus
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just over a month ago, one of Cadbury Schweppes' top
executives told industry colleagues of the difficulty his company
faced getting its soft drinks to market.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining its No. 1 position in the non-cola arena, where its
brands outsell Coca-Cola and Pepsico products, was an uphill battle
given the ``predatory'' competitive environment, John F. Brock,
Cadbury Schweppes' managing director and chief executive of global
beverages, told executives at InterBev, the soft drink industry's
largest trade show.
</P>
<P>
   That battle will be over _ except in the United States, France
and South Africa _ now that the London-based company is selling its
beverage brands in 120 countries. It's also seeking buyers for most
of its bottling network, which is estimated to be worth about $800
million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will make Cadbury Schweppes stonger, said Chief
Executive John Sunderland, who explained that proceeds from the
$1.85 billion deal with Coca-Cola Co. will help the company grow
its chocolate and confectionery business while expanding operations
where its beverage sales are strongest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have substantial financial flexibility and this, in
turn, will give us freedom to develop our brands and markets around
the world,'' he said in a release.
</P>
<P>
   Sunderland, who took over the company in 1996, approached
Coca-Cola more than a year ago with his offer to sell the brands.
Though rivals, the two companies have a history of working together
through bottling agreements in both the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about 24 percent of the company's U.S. volume flows
through Coca-Cola's vast bottling system. In addition, M. Douglas
Ivester, Coca-Cola's chairman and chief executive, helped shepherd
a deal with Cadbury in the 1980s that created a jointly operated
bottler in England. That operation was sold to Atlanta-based
Coca-Cola Enterprises in June 1996 for $1.85 billion.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Coca-Cola agreed to shell out that same amount after
months of top-secret discussions and lawyering every angle of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry insiders hailed Cadbury Schweppes' action,
which pushed up the company's stock 8 percent Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a significant player in a few markets, but overall,
outside the United States, they were a distant third in the soft
drink battle,'' said Gary Hemphill, a consultant with New
York-based Beverage Marketing Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ``sorts out the places where Cadbury's systems weren't
strong enough to compete with Coca-Cola,'' David Lang, an analyst
at Henderson Crosthwaite in London, told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fighting with Pepsico for their market share. It was
a murderous battle, and they were getting nowhere with it. This
gives them a war chest for investment and for buying back shares.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal will affect about 450 Cadbury Schweppes employees, who
will have the opportunity to take jobs with Coca-Cola, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news from a strategic point of view,'' Julia Bannon,
an analyst at Paribas in London, also told Bloomberg. ``It's
another example of how Cadbury is refocusing. If you look at the
share price, the market is telling us it thinks it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Schweppes' brands will have more opportunity to grow
worldwide through the Coca-Cola system, said Beverage Digest Editor
John Sicher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a deal that works for both parties,'' he said. ``And
it will give them an infusion of a substantial amount of money to
continue to do two things: Build their brands in the U.S. and
perhaps even more importantly, to continue to consolidate the
independent bottling system.''
</P>
<P>
   That independent ``third-tier'' bottling system now handles 44
percent of Cadbury Schweppes' U.S. distribution, while Pepsico
bottlers distribute 32 percent, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be acquisitions in the future to strengthen that
distribution system. We never talk about potential business
transactions until we're ready to announce them,'' said Michael A.
Martin, a spokesman for Cadbury Schweppes' Plano, Texas-based U.S.
division.
</P>
<P>
   The company has made recent moves to strengthen its U.S.
distribution pipeline, to become a stronger player in the country's
$55 billion soft drink market.
</P>
<P>
   In February, it entered a joint venture with U.S.-based Carlyle
Group to acquire two soft drink bottlers, Beverage America and
Select Beverages, for $724 million. And just last month, the joint
venture group bought a Cleveland bottler for an undisclosed price.
</P>
<P>
   Hemphill, of Beverage Marketing Group, said the U.S. operation
will likely stick to acquiring bottlers, rather than soft drink
brands, given that its portfolio is so large.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got brands that compete within categories,'' he said,
citing as examples the company's Sunkist and Crush orange drinks
and Hires, IBC and A&AMP;W root beers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got their hands full with trying to keep their
existing brands on store shelves,'' Hemphill said. ``They've done a
good job with that, given that they don't own the distribution
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
