<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, DECEMBER 12
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-IRAN-NIGHTLIFE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 8,
about celebrations of a Shiite Muslim holiday in Tabriz, Iran,
referred incorrectly to 12 descendants of the Prophet Mohammed.
They are called Imams, or religious leaders, not prophets.
</P>
<P>
   BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Dec. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Dec. 9,
about testimony to the House Judiciary Committee by legal experts
and former prosecutors on the possibility of impeaching President
Clinton misstated a former position of Ronald Noble, associate
professor at New York University Law School. He was Under Secretary
of the Treasury for Enforcement, not Deputy United States Attorney
for the Northern District of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-HAMPTON-NYT (moved on Monday, Nov. 23)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of the documentary-film maker Henry Hampton sent by
the New York Times News Service on Nov. 24, misidentified the
leader of the ``Bloody Sunday'' civil rights march in Selma, Ala.,
in 1965, the event that inspired Mr. Hampton's Emmy-winning survey
of the civil rights movement, ``Eyes on the Prize.'' The march was
led by John Lewis of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee;
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. led a second march two days
later.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SHOE-FASHION-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Dec. 7,
about the growing market for women's shoes misspelled the name of a
street in Beverly Hills, Calif., where a Jimmy Choo boutique opened
last week. It is North Canon Drive, not Cannon.
</P>
</TEXT>
