</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCOMING HOUSE SPEAKER LIVINGSTON REMAINS SILENT ON VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-MOOD,
IMPEACH-BOUCHER, IMPEACH-GRAHAM, IMPEACH-AMBITION,
IMPEACH-WHITEWATER, IMPEACH-NETWORKS, IMPEACH-MEDIA, EDIT-IMPEACH) 
(js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ As the House Judiciary Committee voted Friday
night to impeach President Clinton, Rep. Robert Livingston, the
incoming speaker of the House, continued to avoid specifics on the
whole topic.
</P>
<P>
   He said in a brief interview here Friday that he had been
deliberately vague with democrats and the press about whether he
would allow a censure vote by the full House and would likely not
address the matter publicly until the Judiciary Committee issued a
report, expected Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he had told Rep. Dick Gephardt, the Democratic
leader, that he would not allow a vote on censure, Livingston said,
``Actually I haven't been very clear. I haven't been any more clear
with him than I have with you _ deliberately so. I haven't given
him anything definitive.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke Friday night after a reception honoring his
``becoming'' speaker, but in the interview referred to Newt
Gingrich as the speaker, which he technically is until Livingston
takes over January 6.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would talk with Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the
Judiciary Committee, ``to get an idea what's going to be in the
report. Then I'll set the agenda and I'm working with the speaker.
Remember, anything I do is contingent on agreement with the
speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gephardt, in an interview in Washington,
voiced his strongest criticism of Livingston to date for, in his
view, failing to take the reigns of the speakership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good start,'' Gephardt said. ``I guess he can say
he's not in charge and it is speaker Gingrich's call. But the truth
is, once a speaker leaves, a new speaker takes over. He's not just
there for the majority _ he's there for the whole house.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has been urging Livingston to allow a vote of censure
on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was being honored here at a reception hosted by The
National Association of Realtors and other business leaders. As
guests snacked on hors d'oevres of quiche and shrimp, Livingston
told them only: ``We have a few things to take care of in
Washington, and that's enough said about that.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed blissfully unaware of the proceedings in Washington,
asking a reporter after the reception whether the Judiciary
Committee had finished voting.
</P>
<P>
   Told it had not, he said he would talk to Hyde ``after the dust
settles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
