<HEADER>
A6121 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-11 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
  
 DiMAGGIO ONE OF THE ONLY TRUES HEROES OF SPORTS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For one game in 1951, when Casey Stengel was manager
of the Yankees and Joe DiMaggio's well-worn legs made chasing down
fly balls in Yankee Stadium too tough on the 36-year-old center
fielder, Stengel moved DiMaggio to first base.
</P>
<P>
   It happens all the time. Aging outfielders get brought in to
first, to keep their bat in the lineup, to keep them part of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Only DiMaggio would have nothing to do with diminishing skills,
a slow decline.
</P>
<P>
   That one game told DiMaggio what he needed to know about his
baseball career. As he stood on first, perhaps worried sick he
would flub a routine grounder, the story goes that DiMaggio sweated
straight through his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   At age 36, he knew what he would do.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1951 World Series, which the Yankees won for the ninth
time in DiMaggio's 13 seasons, the Yankees tried to get DiMaggio to
play one more season. But on Dec. 12, 1951 _ exactly 47 years ago
today _ DiMaggio read his retirement statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been unusually privileged to play all my major league
baseball for the New York Yankees,'' he said. ``It has been a
greater privilege to play baseball at all.'
</P>
<P>
   Such class. Always.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since October and the 1998 World Series, when Joe DiMaggio
was too sick to make it to Yankee Stadium to throw out the first
pitch, too sick to grace us with his dignified, classy,
well-dressed-as-ever presence, the news of DiMaggio's decline in a
Florida hospital has kept the world on notice.
</P>
<P>
   How is the Yankee Clipper doing?
</P>
<P>
   Every day since October, his 84th birthday on Nov. 25th among
them, the world was watching.
</P>
<P>
   You did not have to be a Yankee fan to feel that the dying light
of Joe DiMaggio reduces the earthly shine around us all. That's why
news of DiMaggio rallying from a deep coma yesterday and squeezing
the hand of his doctor was just more affirmation of the strength
and determination of this man.
</P>
<P>
   You did not have to be a Yankee fan to root for DiMaggio _ one
of the only true heroes of sports _ because he understood what it
meant to be proud, to never let anyone down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be a kid in the stands who has never seen me play,
or would never see me play again. I burned to be the best for them,
to leave them with a good memory of me,'' DiMaggio once told a
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving a good memory . . . no question DiMaggio long ago
accomplished that with his image so noble, so immaculate, it makes
you wonder how only half a century separates DiMaggio from the
arrogant, ego-driven, pay-to-play ``stars'' of today.
</P>
<P>
   Light years are a better way to calculate the distance between
DiMaggio and Albert Belle or J.D. Drew or even the gentle Bernie
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The newest Yankee center fielder, Williams finally agreed to
take $12 million to play ball out there near the monuments and the
ghosts of Yankee Stadium. Once upon a time, it was a boy's biggest
dream to get to play center field for the Yankees, just like
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the last few years, DiMaggio was asked how he would
handle George Steinbrenner if ever DiMaggio had the occasion to
negotiate a deal with the Yankee boss. DiMaggio reportedly said he
would walk into Steinbrenner's office and begin with, ``Hello,
partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a civil, novel idea. Maybe this tactic is something
today's agent-shackled players could try, in honor of Joltin' Joe
DiMaggio, who stayed around the game, handsome, royal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the New York organization like I was for 15 years, I
had a chance to get to know Joe,'' Mariner manager Lou Piniella
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, it was always a thrill. And, yes, Joe liked
his privacy, but he liked to talk baseball, especially with other
players. He shared a lot of insights. He didn't like to talk about
his career, but out of all the Yankee greats, he had the most aura
about him. He carried himself with class. Quiet class.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the things DiMaggio did not want to talk about was, of
course, The Streak. Despite the frenzy that surrounded Mark
McGwire, Sammy Sosa and the pursuit of the home run record this
season, it is DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak that most baseball
people consider the toughest record in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as stunning as his fabled streak is another DiMaggio
statistic that demonstrates his unparalled discipline as a hitter:
In 13 seasons, DiMaggio jolted 361 homers and struck out only 369
times _ an almost unfathomable 1-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you have to remember, Yankee Stadium was the toughest park
around for a right-handed hitter,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 440 feet to straightaway center, 420 to left-center. To
strike out that few times and hit all those homers shows you how
great a ballplayer he was, what kind of hand-eye coordination he
had.''
</P>
<P>
   What an eye. For clothes, for style, for poise, for wives.
Whatever element, if any, was missing to launch DiMaggio's legend
into the stratosphere, his romance and marriage to Marilyn Monroe
took care of that. A baseball god and a movie star, ingrained in
our American heritage.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, to this day, has never denied that the rose placed
daily upon Marilyn Monroe's grave is done so at his request. The
mystique lives. The class. Always.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
