<SLUG> BC-DEVLOPMENT-REPORT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report: Unregulated suburban growth a threat
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Poorly managed growth in suburban counties
around Austin and other major Texas cities threatens public health,
strains roads, causes drainage problems and erodes the small-town
rural character, according to separate reports by UT researchers
and a state House com- mittee.
</P>
<P>
   The problems involve unincorporated areas, which are outside the
jurisdiction of cities and subject to minimal oversight by
counties. The demand for affordable housing near major cities has
led to rapid development in such areas, with suburban counties
expected to grow more rapidly than other counties during the next
25 years. But poor planning and inadequate regulation have resulted
in leaking septic systems, overloaded country roads and difficult
access for ambulances and other emergency vehicles, which sometimes
must travel five miles on substandard driveways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those growth-related problems will only worsen in many
suburban counties ringing major Texas cities such as Austin,
Dallas, Houston and San Antonio,'' said a draft report prepared for
the Capital Area Planning Council, one of 24 regional planning
commissions in the state, by the UT researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The other report, by the House Land and Resource Management
Committee, said unregulated subdividing was initially thought to be
a problem mainly in Hays and Williamson counties because of the
booming economy of nearby Austin. But it now appears to be
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many subdivisions have been developed with lots that do not
meet minimum requirements for the installation of a permitted
septic system,'' the committee's report said. ``This creates a
health risk for the purchaser of the lot, as well as others in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots were sold with drainage problems and flood with
relatively normal rainfall. The lack of access for emergency
vehicles presents a threat to the safety and lives of those
residents. Ultimately, county citizens are left to pick up the tab
for irrresponsible developers.''
</P>
<P>
   Both reports suggest that legislation is needed before the
problems reach crisis proportions. The vice chairman of the House
panel, Rep. Bob Turner, D-Voss, said Friday that he plans to file a
bill on Monday that would plug a loophole allowing developers to
subdivide land for residential and commercial purposes with
virtually no county oversight. He said such development is a
growing problem in his district, including Bandera County,
northwest of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call them high-dollar colonias,'' Turner said, referring to
the term for substandard develop- ments in the Texas-Mexico border
region. ``There's no regulation, no control.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said his bill would address a 1995 court decision
involving Elgin Bank and Travis County. Appellate judges ruled that
the bank did not have to file subdivision blueprints and maps,
known as plats, for a tract of land it was subdividing if it was
not building streets or other public areas. The ruling does not
apply in areas subject to a city's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Many developers, eager to avoid the legal and engineering fees
associated with filing plats, have built without streets by carving
tracts into odd-shaped parcels that resemble a flag atop a pole.
The house or mobile home occupies the flag section, and the pole
section is a driveway leading to an existing public road. Such
subdivisions have numerous closely spaced and parallel driveways
leading to the road.
</P>
<P>
   The flag-lot approach leaves county officials unaware of the
development until bulldozers appear, often too late to ensure
adequate wastewater disposal, drainage, water supply, road
culverts, roads and other essentials.
</P>
<P>
   The UT report, unlike the House committee's report, lists a
variety of more sweeping options, including granting counties
planning and zoning powers in areas of critical concern.
</P>
<P>
   However, even modest efforts to expand counties' regulatory
powers have failed in the past few legislative sessions. There are
nonetheless signs that lawmakers might be more willing in the
upcoming five-month session, which begins Jan. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of the Legislature are being pushed by our
constituency,'' Turner said. ``I really think the time is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Lewis, D-Mauriceville, who filed a bill last session,
agreed. ``I think we'll be able to get a consensus between the
builders and the counties,'' he said. ``It won't be everything
everybody wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said his bill would focus on closing the so-called Elgin
Bank loophole. But a consensus favoring a more sweeping approach is
gradually taking shape among representatives of county, plan- ning
and policy groups, said Betty Voights, executive director of the
Capital Area Planning Council, which sponsored a meeting on the
issue last week.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging consensus is that counties need expanded powers on
what she called ``the big four'' _ water, wastewater, streets and
drainage. Public safety might well be added to the wish list,
Voights said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Seale, executive director of the Texas Association of
Counties, said he is optimistic. ``Plugging the Elgin Bank loophole
would not be enough,'' he said. ``A well-thought-out plan of
development is something commissioners' courts need to take a look
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
