<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heisman to be payoff for Williams' patience
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After Ricky Williams led the nation in rushing and
scoring last season on a 4-7 team, the Texas running back was
tempted to jump to the NFL and its instant riches. But Williams
passed on pro football to pursue a more fitting conclusion to his
college football career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had turned pro last year, I would have always felt like
there was something missing,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   He should get that storybook finish tonight at the Downtown
Athletic Club in New York, where he is expected to receive the 1998
Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who ran for 2,124 yards this season, is a strong
favorite over three quarterbacks: Michael Bishop of Kansas State,
Tim Couch of Kentucky and Cade McNown of UCLA. All will attend the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Williams led the Longhorns to an 8-3 record and a spot in the
Jan. 1 Cotton Bowl against Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   He rushed for 6,279 yards in his career, breaking the Division I
record that had been held by Pittsburgh's Tony Dorsett since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been around a football player that is more
deserving of everything that has come his way,'' Texas coach Mack
Brown said. ``Ricky was the heart and soul of our team. Without him
we wouldn't be 8-3 and wouldn't be in the Cotton Bowl. It has been
my privilege to coach him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the regular season, Williams has been on the
banquet circuit. At Thursday night's ESPN Awards show in Orlando,
he received the Doak Walker Award, which goes to the nation's best
running back, and the Maxwell Award, which goes to the nation's
best player.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has already been named Player of the Year by the Walter
Camp Football Foundation. Twenty-six of the previous 31 winners of
the Camp Award have gone on to win the Heisman, including the last
seven straight. He will be a consensus All-American.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to career yardage, Williams holds 14 other NCAA
records, including rushing TDs (72), points (452) and all-purpose
yards (7,206).
</P>
<P>
   The three quarterbacks who will join him tonight had impressive
statistcs, too. Couch completed 400 of 553 passes for 4,275 yards
and 36 touchdowns for Kentucky. Kansas State's Bishop was
164-for-295 for 2,844 yards and 23 TDs, and ran for 748 yards and
14 TDs). UCLA's McNown was 188-for-323 for 3,130 yards and 23 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   But even Couch says Williams deserved the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``As many times as he carries the ball, he's just as strong in
the fourth quarter as he is in the first quarter,'' Couch said.
``He's an amazing player. I'd give him my vote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
