<SLUG> BC-FBC-MOORE-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. not the place for Holtz
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lou Holtz? At South Carolina? Anyway, that groan you
hear is coming from the vicinity of Knute Rockne's grave.
</P>
<P>
   Either that, or those are the collective sounds of folks who
believe a football coach who leaves Notre Dame for whatever reason
should resemble your average President of the United States after
his final term.
</P>
<P>
   That a former Notre Dame coach should spend the rest of his life
doing absolutely nothing worth mentioning.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get picky, Jimmy Carter works for Habitat For
Humanity, and William Howard Taft became Chief Justice of the
Supreme Court. So let Lou Holtz build houses across the country or
work in a flowing black robe in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is, Holtz should do anything he wants these
days, except coach away from the Golden Dome.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't make sense. Actually, it does, and we'll get to
that after we finish telling you about the illogic here.
</P>
<P>
   When Holtz left Notre Dame two seasons ago, he was only six
victories shy of topping Rockne as the Fighting Irish's winningest
coach. Now Holtz is taking over a South Carolina football program
whose closest thing to Rockne has been nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Despite great facilities, spurred by a wonderful fan base that
pumps nearly as much cash into its program as any in the SEC, South
Carolina isn't Notre Dame. South Carolina isn't even Vanderbilt
during many seasons. The Gamecocks have played football for 106
years, and they are three games under .500 overall. This year's
1-10 flop didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   While Notre Dame recruits nationally, South Carolina depends on
leftovers from a state with only a few prized recruits. Worse, the
bulk of those recruits go either to South Carolina's Great Satan
called Clemson or to traditional powers in the SEC or ACC.
</P>
<P>
   So that brings us to a simple question: Why? After all, Holtz
was a growing star in retirement as a football analyst for CBS.
Money definitely wasn't a factor for Holtz, not with the thousands
he receives from corporations for his motivational talks.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, at nearly 62, and with his wife, Beth, recovering from
throat cancer, you'd think that life for Holtz visiting those plush
golf courses around his Orlando home would be just fine.
</P>
<P>
   The answer here is twofold. First, Holtz obviously didn't leave
Notre Dame on his own after 11 seasons of both triumph and turmoil.
Even now, neither Holtz nor Notre Dame officials will discuss his
abrupt resignation from the Irish beyond the superficial.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Holtz showed he wasn't ready to leave South Bend by
coming to Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   As for the biggest reason for Holtz's return to coaching, we'll
just say that he is suffering from the addiction that often
overcomes athletes, and so is John Robinson. This is the same John
Robinson who was a two-time coach at Southern Cal and once ran the
Los Angeles Rams. He just left retirement to take over the Las
Vegas football program.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask. This addiction for Holtz and Robinson is to
adrenaline. Just as athletes have to play, coaches have to coach _
even if it means doing the unthinkable of going from Notre Dame to
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   No, going from Notre Dame to anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
