<HEADER>
A6145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TV-ROGERS-COLUMN1     12-11 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TV-ROGERS-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walker hints politics, not broadcasting, in his future
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time Herschel Walker saw a Georgia high
school playoff game in person, he was wearing a Johnson County
uniform en route to a state record 3,167 yards rushing and the
Class A championship.
</P>
<P>
   When told that was 19 years ago, he flashed a look of surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like that long. It seems like it was
yesterday,'' said Walker, whose face has not aged since he was the
most sought-after high school football player in America. ``I guess
I've been really blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who lives in Dallas, was back in his home state to serve
as the color commentator on GPTV's coverage of the Class AAA
semifinals at the Georgia Dome. Though Friday's Cairo-Dougherty
game was his first television assignment in the booth, he has
dabbled in the medium.
</P>
<P>
   During his stint with the Minnesota Vikings, Walker said he
produced a television show, and there have been a few instances
when he has ``done some college stuff down on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   However, broadcasting is not on his list of possibilities for
life after football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I'm thinking about doing. I don't watch
enough football to do color,'' Walker said. ``But I'm excited about
coming here to do this. I've been doing a lot with kids in Texas,
California and Minnesota, but I haven't done a lot here in Georgia.
I'd like to start to doing more things in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about four hours before air time, and Walker was relaxing
in the lobby of his hotel. His 6-foot, 220-pound frame showed no
signs of wear and tear after gaining 17,001 all-purpose yards,
fourth highest in NFL history. At 37, Georgia's 1982 Heisman Trophy
winner still looks fit enough to play in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a couple of guaranteed contracts, but I will only play
for a team with a good chance to get to the Super Bowl,'' Walker
said. ``I don't have to play for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   So Walker has spent the season meeting with kids around the
country as part of the Health South Road Show and concentrating on
developing a new aloe-based health drink that he says will be in
Wal-Mart stores by the first of February.
</P>
<P>
   Though Walker owns a couple of businesses, the native of
Wrightsville hinted politics may be the next arena he enters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been people wanting me to run for different stuff
in Texas, but I'm from Georgia. If I ever ran for public office,
and I'm not sure if that's something I will do, I wouldn't run in
Texas, I'd run in Georgia,'' Walker said. ``I'm grateful for the
support I've gotten in Minnesota, Philadelphia and Dallas, but I'm
a Georgia product.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason GPTV was ecstatic to get one of the most
storied figures in Georgia football to participate in its coverage.
However, that didn't necessarily mean he knew a lot of stories
about football in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Dublin, which is next to my hometown, would be
playing. But Cairo knocked them out,'' Walker said. ``And then I
saw they were the Syrupmakers. Have they always been that, or did
they just come up with that name?''
</P>
<P>
   By the kickoff at 6 p.m., it would be safe to say he knew the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
