<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANDERSEN1     12-11 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANDERSEN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'We need this win in the worst way'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kicker Morten Andersen, who is eighth in NFL history
with 257 games played, has played in more Saints-Falcons games than
any other player, kicking 13 seasons for New Orleans and the past
four for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He's been a big factor in several games, as six of his
NFL-record 25 game-winning kicks came against the Falcons when he
played for New Orleans. In his first year with Atlanta, 1995, he
kicked a 21-yarder in overtime to beat the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen spoke with the Journal-Constitution about this game,
and how it's different from others.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What else makes this game special?
</P>
<P>
   A: We need this win in the worst way. It's our last division
game, and it would give us a big step toward winning the division.
That's huge. This game was by far the one (Saints) fans got up for
the most. Other than the division (implications), though, for me,
there's no real special sentimental reason anymore. There was more
emotion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The New Orleans front office felt an average salary of
$1million per year was too much for a kicker. Did you take that
personally when they asked you to take a pay cut (in '95), and how
did you end up with the Falcons?
</P>
<P>
   A: The way I look at it now, it's totally water under the
bridge. They kind of surprised me the night before training camp.
There's a misconception. People think I got released, but I asked
for my release. Several teams called right away (Andersen signed a
day later with the Falcons). The idea of staying in the division
and this part of the country was important. (Former Saints and
Falcons quarterback) Bobby (Hebert) was here, (former Saints and
Falcons running back Craig) Ironhead (Heyward) was here. I would
have a chance to play the Saints twice a year. The team was
competitive at that time. We made the playoffs in 1995 ... and my
agent had a good relationship with the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you remember about the Superdome?
</P>
<P>
   A: It gets very, very loud in there. It's so enormous, but you
still get a good, cozy feel in there. I just like the feel in
there. In many ways, it's home.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The fans there can get a little rough, don't you agree?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, not really. They're loyal, and wanted to win in the worst
way. They were great. I would rather have a fan that really shows
the way he feels. They pay for the ticket, they're allowed to boo
and cheer. As long as it doesn't get violent, I'm all for it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which of your game-winning kicks against the Falcons stands
out most?
</P>
<P>
   A: My second year, (former Saints quarterback) Kenny Stabler
called timeout with about two seconds left at Atlanta-Fulton County
Stadium. I was quite nervous, and as he came off he said, ``Let's
go home, Morten.'' I made the kick (a 35-yarder as time expired for
a 19-17 Saints win), and we went home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
