A6156 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN     12-11 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' DEPTH A DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While coach Steve Lavin whittles down his rotation
in preparation for conference play, the Bruins are wearing down
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Against Oklahoma State, eight Bruins played at least 15 minutes
and two others played at least five. The Cowboys used seven players
extensively and were fatigued in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Oklahoma State coach) Eddie Sutton said to me, `You've got
waves of fresh bodies,''' Lavin said. ``That's how our players used
to feel against Duke or Kentucky or Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin tweaks his rotation based on matchups, practice
performance, feel, fatigue and fouls. If a player doesn't hustle on
defense, he's pulled. If he takes a bad shot, he's pulled. Fatigue?
Out. Foul trouble? Out.
</P>
<P>
   Count on Baron Davis, Earl Watson, JaRon Rush, Travis Reed, Dan
Gadzuric, Jerome Moiso and Matt Barnes being in the top rotation
once Pac-10 play begins Jan. 2 against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The second wave _ Rico Hines, Ryan Bailey and Ray Young _ must
impress in practice and contribute in games to warrant extended
time.
</P>
<P>
   The third wave, Brandon Loyd, Sean Farnham and Todd Ramasar,
will fill specific needs.
</P>
<P>
   In all, nine players are averaging at least 17 minutes. Compare
that to recent seasons, when the Bruins had six or seven top
players and a slew of walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, what a difference,'' Lavin said. ``You don't know what
it's like until you have a team that's 12 deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when J.R. (Henderson) got in foul trouble (at
Duke), we had Rico on Elton Brand. The difference one year later .
. . it was almost comical at times.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Davis update: Davis played 16 minutes against Delaware State,
his first game back from the knee injury, and 19 against Oklahoma
State. Don't expect him to play more than 20-22 minutes today
against Nevada-Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bulky brace on his left leg, Davis' medical team
doesn't want to exhaust his reconstructed anterior cruciate
ligament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may stay at 20 minutes for a while,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stat of the Week: Gadzuric has 10 steals in six games, second
on the team and a surprising figure for a 6-foot-10 center. Why?
Gadzuric has extremely quick feet for his size, the result of years
playing soccer in his native Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric does not have UCLA's longest wingspan, however. That
belongs to forward Jerome Moiso.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has alien-like tentacles,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lineup change?: Rush might rejoin the starting lineup today
after a two-game absence due to back spasms, which limited his
practice availability. Rush's back-strengthening exercises are
slowly reducing the pain and extending his practice time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
