<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      12-11 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMITTEE PASSES 3 IMPEACHMENT COUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Spurning President Clinton's dramatic, last-minute
appeal, the House Judiciary Committee Friday approved the first
impeachment charges against a president since the national upheaval
of the Watergate crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled committee, riven by extraordinary
partisan rancor, recommended removing Clinton from office for two
counts of perjury and one count of obstructing justice for
allegedly engaging in an elaborate effort to conceal his sexual
affair in the White House with a former intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Despite broad public opposition to Clinton's ouster, the somber
committee began casting the historic votes just minutes after the
beleaguered president issued his most contrite apology to date and
said for the first time that he would accept a lesser sanction than
impeachment, such as a censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want the American people to know, what I want the
Congress to know is that I am profoundly sorry for all I have done
wrong in words and deeds,'' Clinton said. ``I never should have
misled the country, the Congress, my friends or my family. Quite
simply, I gave in to my shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Representative Barney Frank, a Newton Democrat, who had
argued the night before for censure rather than impeachment
charges, the president said, ``I would give anything to go back and
undo what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Unswayed, the Judiciary Committee voted along party lines,
21-16, to charge Clinton with perjuring himself before a federal
grand jury investigating the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Article 1 is approved,'' said the chairman, Representative
Henry J. Hyde, at 4:25 p.m., amid the first presidential
impeachment case in a generation and the third in history.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican, Representative Lindsey O. Graham of South
Carolina, broke with the GOP majority, as the committee voted,
20-17, several hours later to approve the second perjury charge:
that Clinton lied under oath in a civil deposition in the sexual
harassment case that Paula Corbin Jones filed against him and
settled last month for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction of justice charge was adopted shortly after 9
p.m., again along strictly partisan lines: 21-16.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the committee is expected to approve a fourth
charge, that Clinton abused his office, and send the impeachment
matter to the full House for a showdown next week _ where the
outcome is too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's last-ditch appeal, committee Republicans said
he deserves the shame of being removed from office because he has
never been forthright about his lies under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the only way we will ever reconcile Bill
Clinton with the law is for us to have the moral courage to find
him guilty of these crimes,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Within and beyond the same stately hearing room where the
Judiciary Committee passed articles of impeachment against
President Richard M. Nixon in 1974, Democrats on the panel
portrayed the charges against Clinton as the product of a partisan
vendetta aimed at reversing the president's election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear for the country,'' Representative William D. Delahunt
of Quincy said in an interview. ``This is the beginning of a de
facto movement toward a parliamentary form of government that will
poison relationships within the institution and divide people in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell
Democrat, emerged sullenly from the hearing room. ``I feel sick at
heart about what this means for the Congress, the country, and the
presidency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the final impeachment vote today, the committee is
expected to reject a Democratic alternative that would censure
Clinton for ``reprehensible conduct.'' The measure would require
Clinton to sign a resolution acknowledging ``he violated the trust
of the American people, lessened their esteem for the office of
president, and dishonored the office which they have entrusted to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who faces the increasing likelihood that the House will
send at least one impeachment charge to the Senate for the first
trial of a president in 130 years, broke his recent silence on the
matter in the final minutes before the Judiciary Committee passed
the first perjury count against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must also be at peace with the fact that the public
consequences of my actions are in the hands of the American people
and their representatives in the Congress,'' Clinton said. ``Should
they determine that my errors of word and deed require their rebuke
and censure, I am ready to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides argued strenuously with Clinton Thursday night
over what he should say in the high-stakes speech and when he
should give it.
</P>
<P>
   Some aides believed Clinton had more to gain by waiting until
after the committee voted and the president returned from a
four-day trip to the Middle East, which begins today. Others argued
that Clinton needed to make a forceful statement aimed at about two
dozen undecided lawmakers before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton broke up the meeting, saying he would think about it
overnight. But then a draft of one of the president's proposed
statements appeared later that night on MSNBC. In it, the president
would call his conduct ``terribly wrong'' and conclude that he may
have ``crossed the line'' in his hairsplitting testimony under
oath.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton blew up over the leak, and White House aides said they
were in the dark about whether Clinton would make a statement until
less than a hour before he delivered it.
</P>
<P>
   The undecided lawmakers are expected to decide Clinton's fate
when the matter is taken up by the full House, probably on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the timing of his remarks, Clinton was given no hope of
persuading committee Republicans to abandon their inexorable push
toward passing impeachment charges. And no member of the GOP
majority on the panel was swayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in his most recent apology, the president continues to
deny the serious criminal acts of perjury, obstruction of justice,
and witness tampering he has committed and to rely upon technical
legal arguments advanced by his attorneys,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Representative Bob Barr of Georgia, saw it, Clinton
``continues to thumb his nose at the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans were no less strident within the towering
hearing room, as they sparred with defiant Democrats for more than
nine hours over the three impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   The count of grand-jury perjury, which committee members in both
parties said is the most likely charge to pass the House, came
under relentless fire from committee Democrats who complained that
the impeachment resolution does not lay out which of Clinton's
statements allegedly constitute perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said Republicans cloaked the allegation in ``deliberate
vagueness and obfuscation'' because they feared the statements
might not be impeachable and because they were wary of a backlash
if they highlighted the salacious nature of the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The statements relate to intimate details of Clinton's sexual
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority knows a losing case when they see one,'' Frank
said. ``They look at Kenneth Starr's three charges, and they say,
`Whoa, we can't defend these,' so they obfuscate and dress them
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans countered that Clinton's allies on the
committee were trying to include the precise statements in the
impeachment resolution so the charges could not be expanded if the
case goes to trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very clever ruse to try to limit the evidence,'' said
Representative F. James Sensenbrenner Jr., a Wisconsin Republican.
</P>
<P>
   As for the perjury charge involving Clinton's deposition in the
Jones case, Graham was the only Republican who agreed with
Democrats that the allegation was not impeachable because a judge
had ruled Lewinsky was not a material witness in the case. Graham
also said he felt uncomfortable about recommending Clinton's
impeachment on the charge because he agreed with the president's
lawyers that Jones's lawyers appeared to ambush him about his
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction of justice charge cites seven instances when
Clinton attempted to ``delay, impede, cover up and conceal''
evidence in the Jones case, particularly in seeking to prevent
discovery of some of the 64 gifts that he and Lewinsky exchanged.
The charge also relates to Clinton's alleged role in helping
Lewinsky find a job in New York at a time when she was developing a
false affidavit to submit in the Jones case that denied her sexual
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During the committee's debate, the White House and the House
minority leader, Richard A. Gephardt, were gearing up for the House
vote next week, hoping to win commitments for a vote on censure.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt was calling Democrats to try to hold the line on
defections and find a way to bring a censure vote to the floor,
said Laura Nichols, his press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton's chief of staff, John Podesta,
reached out to House Speaker-elect Robert L. Livingston for a
censure vote. ``If we were denied that choice, I think it would say
something about the fairness of the process,'' said White House
press secretary Joseph Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston remains publicly uncommitted on whether to allow a
censure vote. But the majority whip, Representative Tom DeLay of
Texas, who is in charge of organizing the House impeachment agenda,
adamantly opposes a vote on censure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 2230EST &QL; 
