r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-7-ELEVEN-SFCHRON &LR;      12-11 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-7-ELEVEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 A Slurpee, Some Jerky, And a Burgundy, Please _ 7-Eleven stores  go
upscale   By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
7-Eleven, the world's largest convenience store chain, is going
upscale. Southland Corp. of Dallas is now pushing premium wines
along with self-serve coffee and the Slurpee at about 3,200 of its
5,600 North American outlets.
</P>
<P>
   New international wine displays carrying 30 different varieties
have been installed recently by the front door of many of
7-Eleven's 1,000 stores in California.
</P>
<P>
   Like other retailers, 7-Eleven has experienced growing consumer
demand for upscale beverages like imported beer and gourmet
coffees. It also is well aware that supermarket wine sales grew 43
percent since 1994, making it the fastest-growing beverage category
after soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   7-Eleven's expanded selection includes some of the best-selling
brands such as Beringer, Bolla, Gallo, Fetzer, Kendall-Jackson,
Korbel and Woodbridge. In addition to $5.99-to-$14.99 price tags (a
bit more than some big stores), they carry the flag of the country
of origin and flowery descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 7-Eleven advises its customers that Andre Sparkling
Wine has ``apple &AMP; pear flavors,'' Beringer Chardonnay has
``buttery flavors, a hint of oak,'' and Gabbiano Chianti is ``rich,
soft &AMP; spicy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The displays include pictograms of suitable food pairings
(like beef or fish) but they don't suggest which wines go best with
7-Eleven staples like beef jerky, hot dogs, doughnuts and potato
chips.
</P>
<P>
   Southland`s wine blitz is ``designed to reflect what our
customers want,'' said Dennis Phelps, 7-Eleven's alcoholic
beverages category manager. The convenience store giant is the
nation's largest vendor of beer, selling more than 30 million cases
a year, but its stores typically have carried only a few wines.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps said that the larger selection plus strategic placement
of Wine Spectator magazine are aimed at shoppers who may not want
to trudge down long aisles and stand in line at the supermarket
when they want to pick up a bottle of wine for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   7-Eleven's selection mirrors U.S. wine consumption patterns.
Seventy percent of the shelf space is devoted to domestic wines, 30
percent to imports. The company won't divulge current wine sales,
but Phelps said the company's goal is ``to triple our wine business
in the next four years.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oakland, 7-Eleven franchise owner Jin An said that wine is
probably his fourth-biggest sales category after gasoline, other
alcohol and beer. He attributes the popularity of premium wines and
micro-brews to his store's location on Piedmont Avenue near the
affluent &LR;   &LR; residents of the Oakland hills. Wine has about a 25
percent profit margin, according to An, which is less than for
Slurpees. (Americans drink more than 10 million of these slushy
drinks each month.)
</P>
<P>
   In October, An's store sold 590 bottles of wine for $3,416 and
the biggest seller was the 187.5-milliliter-sized bottle of
Vendange Chardonnay. An sold 98 of these smaller-than-a-cup
portions for $1.69 each.
</P>
<P>
   Vintners are pleased with 7-Eleven's new commitment to wine.
``This is an opportunity to broaden our market to yet another
distribution channel,'' said Kendall-Jackson spokesman James
Caudill. ``It's meaningful to us that people are looking for
popular wines in popular places.''
</P>
<P>
   The 7-Eleven campaign is another sign of the growing popularity
of wine, according to John De Luca, president of the Wine Institute
in San Francisco. ``People who buy wine are no longer boxed in
certain categories,'' he said. ``Besides food stores and
restaurants, winemakers increasingly sell overseas, by direct
shipment, in warehouse and discount stores and through convenience
stores like 7-Eleven.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
