<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON &LR;      12-11 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Schwab Blocks Some Online Trading  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman and Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. temporarily suspended online trading of some
newly-issued stocks this week on concerns that many customers who
trade volatile, fast-moving stocks via computer don't understand
what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest online broker posted a notice on its
Internet site yesterday saying it wouldn't take electronic orders
for the stock of InfoSpace.com Inc., a Redmond, Wash., Internet
guide scheduled to go public next week. Customers were instructed
to contact Schwab by phone or in person to place orders for the
stock.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, &UR;  &LR; Schwab blocked online trading of Internet America
Inc. and AboveNet Communications Inc., two Internet companies that
went public that day.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco firm also stopped electronic trading that day
of Infinity Broadcasting Corp., the radio company that syndicates
shock jock Howard Stern, which was spun off by parent CBS Corp. in
a public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The broker resumed online trading of the three firms yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Schwab said online trading halts were needed to protect
clients from the huge, lightning-fast price moves that now
routinely happen when hot companies go public.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can either place a ``market order,'' meaning they'll
buy or sell shares at the current price, or a ``limit order,''
meaning they'll only trade shares at a specified price or better.
</P>
<P>
   When orders are placed online, there's no human broker who can
make sure the customers understand the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   As stocks of Internet companies have doubled or tripled and then
fallen back on the day they went public, Schwab said clients _ many
with stars in their eyes _ were often shocked to find they bought
stocks at prices far higher than electronic quotes they received.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Others were irritated when they weren't able to get shares at
all because stocks shot past price limits they set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people put in (market) orders and don't understand when
they end up paying a lot more'' than they expected, said Tracey
Gordon, a Schwab spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   On its customer Web site, Schwab said it blocked orders for
InfoSpace because of ``volatility and fast-market conditions''
which it said ``could result in price quotes significantly
different from the current trading price.''
</P>
<P>
   By routing trades of volatile IPO stocks through a human broker,
Schwab can ensure that customers understand that they may not get
shares at the prices they expect, said Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all to help the customer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts warned that such restrictions could anger clients
who have been led to believe that online trading is the most modern
and efficient way to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could make the customer say, `Maybe this isn't such a
wonderful channel for trading stocks,''' said Piper Jaffray analyst
Stephen Franco.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one Schwab customer who plans to buy InfoSpace shares
said he was furious that he won't be able to do so by computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to hold on the telephone for 20 minutes to get my
order in,'' said Jack Diamond, a 69-year-old Carrollton, Texas,
resident.
</P>
<P>
   Rival online brokers said they don't plan similar halts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pure-play electronic. This is our business model,''
said Lisa Nash, a spokeswoman for Palo Alto's E-Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade, based in Omaha, Neb., telephones clients who order
hot IPOs to make sure they understand the risks, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab is reacting to two related developments that have
profoundly altered retail stock brokerage: the breakneck growth of
online trading and the huge increase in stock volatility,
especially for hot new issues. Individual investors are flocking to
computer-based stock trading, which has gone from insignificant
levels three years ago to an estimated 20 percent of all retail
brokerage transactions today. Online trades represent more than
half of the 121,000 transactions Schwab handles every business day.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' ability to buy shares with a few mouse clicks has
boosted demand for hot IPOs, contributing to wild price swings. For
example, stock in eBay Inc., the Internet swap meet, nearly tripled
on its first day of trading September 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``By suspending trading, maybe they can modulate the
shooting-gallery atmosphere we have online,'' said David Simons,
managing director at Digital Video Investments in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Internet America, AboveNet, theglobe.com, Ticketmaster
Online-CitySearch, uBid, Xoom.com, InfoSpace.com, EarthWeb and
Claimsnet.com have all gone public during the past six weeks,
triggering a surge in online trading.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts speculated Schwab's may be partly motivated by the
strain on its computers triggered by heavy IPO orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect (Schwab is) scared off by the mind-boggling demand
for Internet stocks,'' said a high-placed InfoSpace source.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's average daily trades rose 18 percent in November from
the previous month, coinciding with the latest IPO feeding frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Keynote Systems, a San Mateo company that monitors commercial
Web traffic, noted a dramatic slowdown in Schwab's online
performance over the past month. It took users an average of 78
seconds to access Schwab's commercial home page yesterday
afternoon, compared with 20 seconds the past few weeks and 10
seconds before that, according to Gene Shklar, Keynote's vice
president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, at E-Trade, the second-biggest electronic stock
broker, it took between five and 17 seconds to download information
during test runs over the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's Gordon said online trading restrictions are not a
result of any strain on its computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely not a Web capacity issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a previous attempt to rein in Internet trades, Schwab,
E-Trade and several other online brokers in recent weeks raised
margin requirements _ the amount of cash customers must put up when
they buy stocks with borrowed money _ for Internet-related
companies as Amazon.com, eBay and Yahoo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
