A6172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MEETINGS12-COX     12-11 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schuerholz: Braves may accept higher payroll
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Operating out of a fifth-floor suite at the
Opryland Hotel, the Atlanta Braves front office was to have arrived
in Tennessee in a generous mood, with a bloated payroll that needed
venting.
</P>
<P>
   Just two hours after hitting town, John Schuerholz altered that
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may decide to have a higher payroll,'' said the Braves
general manager, a mighty suggestion from the National League's
reigning payroll kings.
</P>
<P>
   The winter meetings opened Friday and those clubs that are
following the Braves around waiting to see whose contract gets
jettisoned figure to be disappointed. Though the club projected a
$65 million to $68 million payroll in October organizational
meetings, the 1999 payroll currently stands at $72.725 million with
18 players under contract and should exceed $74 million before the
signings are done.
</P>
<P>
   But while Atlanta has had preliminary discussions with several
teams about dealing Ryan Klesko, Schuerholz backed off the
importance of a payroll target and said the team is prepared to
spend more than first budgeted. Atlanta led the NL with a $61
million payroll in 1998 and is close to committing a 21 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the only reason we have to make a deal is we have to
off-load salary, we can do that almost any time, if the players
we're talking about are attractive to other teams. And they would
be,'' Schuerholz said. ``If we did have a particular position that
needed to be filled, if we were absent a second baseman or right
fielder or a shortstop, then we'd be out there to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to make a deal to diminish payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Tampa Bay Devil Rays have sought Klesko, the Boston
Red Sox have a greater need for power and a first baseman to fill
Mo Vaughn's place. Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette is not due
to arrive until today but is expected to speak with Schuerholz
about Klesko. If the Braves want a young outfielder in return,
Boston can offer Trot Nixon or minor leaguers Michael Coleman or
Dernell Stenson.
</P>
<P>
   But Schuerholz sounds in no mood to deal. When the Braves dealt
Denny Neagle last month, the upshoot was the club would plow cash
back into position players. The Otis Nixon signing reflects that
new thinking, even though it leaves the team with three left
fielders (including Gerald Williams), since Brian Jordan will start
daily in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Even at $74 million, the Braves rank far below the AL payroll
leaders. Baltimore is projecting an $80 million payroll, while the
Yankees should reach $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   But those teams waiting for Atlanta to dump a contract may be
waiting come March. Asked what he wanted to do in the next four
days, Schuerholz replied, ``Talk, listen, find out what other
people are doing. You never know when somebody may approach you
with an idea that's interesting. Based on the conversations I've
had with people so far prior to these meetings, I don't expect
anything like that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
