</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-GRAHAM, 12-11 --
Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., makes comments during Friday's
hearings by the House Judiciary Committee. After months of public
wrangling over whether to oust President Clinton, Graham, the
conservative firebrand on the committee with a penchant for
moderation on the impeachment issue, went on the attack. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- MUSICALS-KRIEGER, 12-11 --
Sisters, sisters: Emily Scott Skinner, left, and Alice Ripley in
``Side Show,'' a box office failure. Had the production's creators
crossed into dark territory best left unexplored by the ``light''
musical? (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KATMANDU, Nepal -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- NEPAL-GODDESS, 12-11
-- Rashmila Shakya, 18, stands beside a photo of herself dressed as
the Royal Kumari. Shakaya became Nepal's official living goddess
the day before turning four and her reign lasted until puberty. By
practice, the Kumari has always been chosen from the Shakya caste.
Parents of the current Royal Kumari say the position takes a toll
on the child. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
DISNEY-INTERNET, 12-11 -- Jake Winebaum, 39, trains for marathons
when he is not running Disney's Internet business. A current
colleague, Michael Slade, the chairman of Starwave, the Internet
production company recently bought by Disney, says, ``The best way
to understand Jake is that he's a great athlete. He is very
competitive and wants to win.'' (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SEATTLE -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
BOEING, 12-11 -- As Boeing has faltered, Harry Stonecipher, left,
and Philip Condit have not had a happy year - and the news only
seems to get worse. Earlier this month, the company stunned
investors and its 232,000 employees with the announcement that it
will cut as many as 48,000 jobs by 2001 - and still make only a
negligible profit. (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
ABOUT-CARS-ESCALADE, 12-11 -- The fancy steering wheel is new, but
the Escalade dash is last-generation Chevy truck. The Escalade -
pronounced ESS-kuh-lade and defined by Webster's as ``the act of
scaling or climbing the walls of a fortified place using ladders''
- is the first truck to be produced by Cadillac in its 96 years of
existence. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
ABOUT-CARS-ESCALADE-1, 12-11 -- The Escalade - pronounced
ESS-kuh-lade and defined by Webster's as ``the act of scaling or
climbing the walls of a fortified place using ladders'' - is the
first truck to be produced by Cadillac in its 96 years of
existence. The Escalade's capabilities, like those of most
luxo-barge four-by-fours, will rarely be used to their potential.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WESTON, Conn. -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13
-- BIZ-PROFILE-NIEDERHOFFER, 12-11 -- After losing millions, Victor
Niederhoffer is selling assets. But the money manager, who has a
fondness for The National Enquirer and disdain for shoes, is still
living in his 20,000-square-foot home. (Janet Durrans/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- SCI-MARS, 12-11 -- The Mars
Climate Orbiter approaches Mars in this computer generated image.
The orbiter was launched on Friday on its nine month voyage. The
Orbiter, which will fly around the red planet at an altitude of 260
miles, will serve as a radio-relay station for the Polar Lander,
which will be launched at a later date.(NASA/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-CLINTON-2, 12-11
-- President Clinton leaves the podium after addressing the nation
regarding the developing impeachment proceedings on Friday at the
White House. Clinton expressed ``profound remorse'' over the
nationwide turmoil stemming from his relationship with White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON, -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH, 12-11 --
President Clinton addresses the nation regarding the developing
impeachment proceedings on Friday at the White House. Clinton
expressed ``profound remorse'' over the nationwide turmoil stemming
from his relationship with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) EULESS, Texas -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- BIZ-ONLINE-SHOPPING,
12-11 -- Like millions of other people, Rhonda and Curtis Tallant
have become online shoppers. They like to buy from auction sites
becuase they believe they can get better bargains elsewhere. ``I
can spend an hour at home in my chair and get everything I need,''
says Mrs. Tallant. They are surrounded by booty discovered online.
(Mark Graham/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LONDON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
INVEST-WITH-LOVERING, 12-11 -- For William Lovering, co-manager of
the Bartlett Europe fund, finding the European stocks likely to
benefit the most from the introduction of the euro is like picking
the best-looking from a bowl of cherries. ``The bottoms-up story in
Europe is the changing shape of businesses and balance sheets, and
the recognition that shareholders are important,'' he says.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
COLLEGE-WORK-PROGRAMS, 12-11 -- A cooperative education job helped
propel Julio Bofill to a photography career. At the Copacabana in
Manhattan, he works a party. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PARIS -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
BIZ-FRENCH-OIL-2, 12-11 -- Though Thierry Desmarest, chairman of
Total, says its acquisition of Petrofina will bolster profits, some
analysts have criticized the deal, saying it will add more
``downstream'' oil operations, like gas stations, to Total's mix.
``Over the next five years, our concern was to have our downstream
pole strong enough,'' says Desmarest in his defense. (Owen
Franken/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PARIS -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
BIZ-FRENCH-OIL-1, 12-11 -- Thierry Desmarest, chairman of Total,
says its acquisition of Petrofina will bolster profits. ``It's
important to keep sufficient balance,'' he says. (Owen Franken/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-CLINTON-2, 12-11
-- President Clinton is seen through a window in the Oval Office
decorated with a Christmas wreath on Friday moments before he
addressed the nation regarding the Monica Lewinsky affair. Clinton
expressed ``profound remorse'' over the nationwide turmoil stemming
from his relationship with Lewinsky. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13,
EYEBROW-GURU, 12-11 -- Eliza Petrescu, an eyebrow designer, works
on a client. Petrescu can strip, pluck and prune brows to bonsai
perfection in seven minutes flat. For that skill, her clients are
willing to overlook a manner that can be as sharp as her flashing
metal tweezers. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON-- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-MOOD, 12-11 --
President Clinton shows Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman where
to stand during an event at the White House on Friday announcing
additional U.S. assistance to Central American countries devastated
by Hurricane Mitch. Fourth from right is Salvadoran President
Armando Calderon Sol. Honduran President Carlos Roberto Flores is
third from right. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
