<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 12/11/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- BBO-DIMAGGIO, 12-11 -- Joe
DiMaggio still wears his1936 World Series ring, the one he won his
rookie year with the Yankees. After lapsing into a coma overnight,
Joe DiMaggio revived Friday. But his doctor said DiMaggio's
condition remained very serious and could change at any time. (Fred
R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- OBIT-BRUGGER, 12-11 --
Kenneth Brugger, an amateur naturalist who discovered the wooded
mountain slopes in Mexico where hundreds of millions of North
American monarch butterflies spend the winter, died on Nov. 25 at
his home in Austin, Texas. He was 80. Brugger is seen in a Mexican
forest during a nature walk in 1977. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) HEBRON, West Bank -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- MIDEAST-US, 12-11
-- Palestinian police, one holding the Palestinian flag, react to
the wind stirred up by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's
helicopter as it arrives in Hebron for a meeting. As President
Clinton prepared to fly to the Middle East early Saturday morning,
American officials in Washington and the Middle East scrambled to
cool off tempers and get Palestinians to comply with their Wye
peace accord obligations. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) BLACK HAWK, Colo. -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- GAMBLING-FEUD-2,
12-11 -- A gambler leaves a charter bus in the gambling town of
Black Hawk earlier this week. In this old gold rush landscape,
modern greed over gambling is plunging Black Hawk and the nearby
village of Central City into a municipal feud worthy of the
Hatfields and the McCoys. (KevIn Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) CENTRAL CITY, Colo. -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- GAMBLING-FEUD-1,
12-11 -- A gambler feeds the slots at the Coyote Creek Casino
earlier this week. In this old gold rush landscape, modern greed
over gambling is plunging Central City and the nearby village of
Black Hawk into a municipal feud worthy of the Hatfields and the
McCoys. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-CLINTON-3, 12-11
-- President Clinton leaves the podium after addressing the nation
regarding the developing impeachment proceedings on Friday at the
White House. Clinton expressed ``profound remorse'' over the
nationwide turmoil stemming from his relationship with White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-3, 12-11 -- Rep.
Chuck Schumer, right, talks to fellow members of the House
Judiciary Committee as Rep. Barney Frank looks on during debate on
articles of impeachment against President Clinton on Friday.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-2, 12-11 -- House
Judiciary Committee staff member Shawn Friesen tallies the vote on
the second article of impeachment on Friday. The House Judiciary
Committee voted on articles of impeachment against President
Clinton on grounds of perjury. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- CLINTON-RIGHTS-COX, 12-11
-- Casting the American civil rights movement as part of a broader
global struggle for human rights, President Clinton honored Rep.
John Lewis on Thursday for his lifetime fight against racial
segregation. President Clinton, Lewis, and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton posed for phtographers as Lewis held his award.
(Rick McCay/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ROTHERHAM, England -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- BRITAIN-EURO-2,
12-11 -- Julie Kenney got shops here to trade in ``Rotherham
euros'' for a week in November - more than a month before Europe's
new single currency, the euro, is to be introduced. ``We as
businesses have to be on the inside, playing on the same terms as
everyone else, rather than on the outside looking in,'' says Mrs.
Kenny, managing director of a security company employing 200 people
here. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ROTHERHAM, England -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- BRITAIN-EURO-1,
12-11 -- A ``Rotherham euro.'' On Monday, Jan. 4, Europe's new
single currency, the euro, will be introduced in 11 nations
combining a total of 290 million people. But this old steel town
has already beaten the rest of Europe to the punch: For a week in
November, business leaders introduced a voucher roughly valued at
what one euro was worth at the time. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-BOUCHER, 12-11 --
From left: Julian Epstein, Democratic chief counsel of the House
Judiciary Committee, Rep. Bill Delahunt, Rep. Rick Boucher and Rep.
Thomas Barrett meet before the arrival of White House Counsel
Charles Ruff to testify before the committee on Wednesday. Boucher,
co-author of the Democratic censure measure, has been phoning his
moderate Republican friends to win their support for his
compromise. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- MUSICALS-BISHOP, 12-11 --
Brent Carver as Leo Frank and Carolee Carmello as his wife,
Lucille, in the musical ``Parade.'' The production is not so much a
musical about the Frank case as it is a musical about two
mismatched people - Frank and Lucille - who grow to depend on,
appreciate and eventually love each other because of the Frank
case. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- IMPEACH-GRAHAM, 12-11 --
