crossed into dark territory best left unexplored by the ``light''
musical? (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KATMANDU, Nepal -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- NEPAL-GODDESS, 12-11
-- Rashmila Shakya, 18, stands beside a photo of herself dressed as
the Royal Kumari. Shakaya became Nepal's official living goddess
the day before turning four and her reign lasted until puberty. By
practice, the Kumari has always been chosen from the Shakya caste.
Parents of the current Royal Kumari say the position takes a toll
on the child. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
DISNEY-INTERNET, 12-11 -- Jake Winebaum, 39, trains for marathons
when he is not running Disney's Internet business. A current
colleague, Michael Slade, the chairman of Starwave, the Internet
production company recently bought by Disney, says, ``The best way
to understand Jake is that he's a great athlete. He is very
competitive and wants to win.'' (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SEATTLE -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
BOEING, 12-11 -- As Boeing has faltered, Harry Stonecipher, left,
and Philip Condit have not had a happy year - and the news only
seems to get worse. Earlier this month, the company stunned
investors and its 232,000 employees with the announcement that it
will cut as many as 48,000 jobs by 2001 - and still make only a
negligible profit. (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Dec. 11, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 13 --
ABOUT-CARS-ESCALADE, 12-11 -- The fancy steering wheel is new, but
