<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEMENCY12-COX     12-11 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death penalty filings likely
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With two executions already halted by a
challenge to Texas' secretive clemency process, state officials
braced Friday for the possibility that some of the eight other
convicts now scheduled for lethal injection may file for similar
court orders.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, though, no other challenges were
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly possible,'' said one official. ``And based on
what's happened, if you had an execution date, you'd be stupid not
to file.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for execution is James Meanes, 42, a former Ohio parolee
who is scheduled to die just after 6 p.m. Tuesday for the April
1981 shooting death of an armored-car guard during a million-dollar
heist in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Seven others are scheduled to be executed through April 13.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks of Austin blocked
the executions of convicted murderers Danny Lee Barber and Joseph
Stanley Faulder, a Canadian whose case drew international protest.
Barber was to have been executed Wednesday and Faulder on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's attorneys convinced Sparks that there are enough
questions about the legality of Texas' clemency process that his
death sentence should not have been carried out on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Clemency reviews in Texas are conducted secretly by the
18-member parole board, based on criteria that have never been
specified publicly. Voting also is not done in public.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld Sparks' order in
Barber's case, and the U.S. Supreme Court blocked Faulder's
execution shortly before it was to have taken place.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Tisdale, a spokesman for Attorney General Dan Morales, said
state lawyers are awaiting word on what will happen next with the
challenges filed by Barber and Faulder. He would not speculate on
what broader effects the execution-blocking court orders in those
cases might have.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks has scheduled a Dec. 21 hearing in the Faulder case and
one the following day in Barber's. Tisdale said the state is
confident the clemency system is not legally flawed and will seek
to have Sparks cancel his orders so the executions can be
rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   In stopping the Faulder execution, court filings in Washington
showed Friday, Justice Antonin Scalia gave no timetable for when
the Supreme Court might take further action in the case _ even on
what specific issues it is reviewing.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's attorneys, in filings with the high court last month,
contended that prosecutors illegally withheld evidence during the
trial, that some testimony against Faulder was false and that
Faulder was illegally denied a chance to consult with Canadian
authorities in Texas after his arrest in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   It is that last contention _ that police violated the 1963
Vienna Convention on Consular Relations _ that has drawn much of
the protest in Faulder's case in recent months. Under the treaty,
foreigners jailed in the United States have to be allowed to
contact diplomats from their country.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his arrest, Texas officials have said, Faulder
was carrying a Colorado driver's licence and had applied for one in
Texas. He did not assert his Canadian citizenship until years
later, after he had been imprisoned and was appealing his
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit filed with the Supreme Court, though, Faulder
insists that if he had been told about his right to Canadian
counsel, he would have ``wanted their assistance in understanding
my rights under American law, since the American criminal justice
system was completely strange to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight executions scheduled through April 13, five now
appear likely to be carried out on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of those has two stars ... a system we use to show
they already have gone through the federal habeas process once,''
Tisdale said. ``One star means it's their first time through, and
they're probably not going (to be executed). Two stars and they're
pretty much a goner.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Barber and Faulder had two stars. ``They got lucky,''
Tisdale said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
