<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKE12-COX     12-11 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida lawyers' windfall from tobacco deal more than $3.4
billion
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The lawyers who took on the tobacco
industry on behalf of Florida were vindicated with a historic
windfall Friday when a panel of arbitrators said they were entitled
to more than $3.4 billion in legal fees, or roughly 25 percent of
the state's $13 billion settlement with cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   The award, thought to be the largest legal fee ever paid for a
single case, was lambasted as ``outrageous'' by the tobacco
industry, which chose arbitration as the method for paying its
opponents' legal fees in the national battle over the public costs
of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The three-person panel also awarded $3.3 billion and $1.4
billion, respectively, to lawyers in similar lawsuits in Texas and
Mississippi. The money will be paid over at least 10 years _ and
possibly decades _ from a fund set aside by cigarette makers with a
$500 million annual cap.
</P>
<P>
   Under the industry's agreements with the states, the panel's
decision is final and not subject to appeal _ though industry
lawyers were carefully inspecting the panel's findings Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it shakes the conscience of the courts,'' said Scott
Williams, a spokesman for the industry. ``You can't say the
attorneys in these cases are solely responsible for the result.''
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the panel voted 2-1 for the fees, with panelist
Charles Renfrew dissenting. Renfrew, a retired federal judge chosen
by the industry, said the panel was given too little time to
determine the fees and was hampered because the lawyers did not
keep track of the hours they worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are limits, even in these cases, as to the amount the
attorneys should be paid,'' Renfrew said in his dissent. ``Each of
the three state awards rendered by the majority is clearly
excessive and to me incomprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Siding with the lawyers in Florida's case were panelists Harry
Huge, a lawyer chosen by the trial team; and John Calhoun Wells,
chosen by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without these outside counsel, there would be no multi-billion
dollar settlements for the states to reimburse tobacco-related
health expenses,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's decision was praised by Florida officials and the
state's trial team, who, after more than a year of squabbling, both
got what they wanted in the end: The lawyers were paid a 25 percent
fee, as spelled out in the contract they signed with the state when
they took the case; and the state successfully placed the burden of
paying the lawyers on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the state their money, and now we've been fully
compensated,'' said David Fonvielle, a Tallahassee lawyer on the
trial team. ``How much better can it get for the people of
Florida?''
</P>
<P>
   The trial lawyers said they deserved the fee because they took
on the risk of fighting the previously unstoppable industry. The
lawyers paid their expenses on their own, and had they lost, they
would have received nothing.
</P>
<P>
   As the case plodded toward a 1997 trial date, the lawyers took
more than 200 depositions, attended 150 court hearings, handled
nine appeals and produced more than 500 million pieces of paper.
These details were contained in the lawyers' application to the
arbitrators, along with the fee contract and videotaped interviews
with, among others, Gov. Lawton Chiles and Attorney General Bob
Butterworth.
</P>
<P>
   The state settled with cigarette makers in 1997 for $11 billion
over 25 years, while jury selection was underway in West Palm
Beach. In addition, the state won more than $1.7 billion this year
under a provision that allows Florida to adopt benefits of future
lawsuits. The arbitrators calculated Florida's total settlement as
$13.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Montgomery, a West Palm Beach lawyer who long opposed
arbitration before agreeing to it earlier this month, said the
decision affirms that the fee contract was not excessive, as Palm
Beach County Circuit Judge Harold Cohen had deemed it in a ruling
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery and two other trial lawyers, Bob Kerrigan and Sheldon
Schlesinger , fought for their contract all the way to the Florida
Supreme Court, and Montgomery sued other trial team members, saying
they improperly agreed to go to arbitration on behalf of the whole
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost us an awful lot in aggravation in order to protect our
contract in the first place, but I feel very happy about it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the $3.4 billion exists only on paper, and
several lawyers said they didn't expect to collect that much. How
much they will get per year depends on how many states take part in
arbitration in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette makers have set aside $500 million per year to pay the
legal fees not only for Florida, Mississippi and Texas, but also in
lawsuits filed by 46 other states. Those suits were recently
settled for a combined $206 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As lawyers from those states go through arbitration, more
lawyers will be drawing on the pot, said Joe Rice, a Charleston,
S.C. lawyer involved in the Florida suit and dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers from Florida and Mississippi will first divide $250
million because they settled in 1997. They along with Texas'
lawyers will also share $500 million set aside for this year, with
the amounts dependent upon the size of the state settlements. That
money should be paid by the end of this year, Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the industry's settlement payments to the states, the
legal fees will not be adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's $3.4 billion will be split among 11 law firms, though
a 12th lawyer, Tim Howard of Tallahassee, says he's also entitled
to a share.
</P>
<P>
   Two out-of-state firms involved in about 40 other tobacco
lawsuits will share 46 percent _ $1.56 billion _ of the Florida
fees; the rest will be divided among the lawyers in Florida, with
each firm collecting about 6 percent of the total _ or $204
million.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said his firm must also pay Fred Levin, the Pensacola
lawyer who assembled the trial team and encouraged legislators to
pass the 1994 law that allowed Florida to pursue the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Howard says he, too, should get part of the fee because he also
signed the contract. But the rest of the trial lawyers say he was
their employee. Howard's lawyer recently said Howard will probably
sue the other lawyers to claim his share.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco stock analysts said Friday's announcement won't affect
tobacco companies because of the annual cap. Gary Black, an analyst
with Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. in New York, said he figured the
entire cost of all the settlements, including lawyers' fees, will
cost tobacco companies 43 cents on each pack ofcigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   But the 45-cent-a-pack price hike tobacco firms announced before
Thanksgiving will more than cover the costs, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Major tobacco stocks weren't affected Friday, with Philip Morris
Cos. Inc. (NYSE: MO) closing up 63 cents at $52.94 a share, and RJR
Nabisco Holdings Corp. (NYSE: RN), the parent of R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co., ending the day up 13 cents at $28.31 a share.
</P>
<P>
   How much each tobacco company will contribute to the fees is
based on their market share, Williams said. As of Oct. 31, Philip
Morris held 48.5 percent of the market, followed by RJ Reynolds
with 24.8 percent, and Brown and Williamson with 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide business groups reacted with harsh vitriol. Bill
Herrle, Florida director of the National Federation of Independent
Business, said the award was a dangerous precedent that will
encourage lawyers to pursue needless suits against businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly illustrates the obscene excesses that trial
lawyers are capable of,'' Herrle said. ``They are capable of
destroying an industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The House member charged with crafting last year's ``tort
reform'' bill _ and who ultimately voted against it because of
changes forced on it by leadership _ said business lobbyists are
exaggerating the implications of paying all that money to trial
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers winning the fees were already wealthy enough to make
mischief, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys don't need seed money to do anything,'' said Rep.
Tom Warner, R-Stuart and himself a trial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Fonvielle of the trial team also placed little credence in the
business lobby's rhetoric: ``I guarantee the lobbyists are all
going to be up there (in Tallahassee) fighting over this money that
we got for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Julie Waresh and Shirish Date contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
