<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6190 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-11 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN PANEL VOTES TO IMPEACH CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided, highly partisan House Judiciary
Committee on Friday recommended removing President Clinton from
office, setting up a momentous impeachment vote next week by the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The committee approved three articles of impeachment, two of
them accusing Clinton of lying under oath and another saying he
obstructed justice in an effort to conceal his affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth article, which alleges that Clinton misused his office
in an attempt to cover-up his affair, was scheduled for debate by
the Republican-controlled committee early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The first article was approved as dusk fell on the nation's
capital and less than 10 minutes after Clinton made an
extraordinary, nationally televised plea from the White House for a
punishment less than impeachment, which would lead to a Senate
trial that could end his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never should have misled the country, the Congress, my
friends or my family. Quite simply, I gave into my shame,'' Clinton
said, adding that his fate is in the hands of the public and the
Congress. ``Should they determine that my errors of word and deeds
require their rebuke and censure, I am ready to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's critics, many of them at the forefront of the effort
to drive him from office, were unmoved, and moments later he became
only the third president in U.S. history to be accused by the
Judiciary Committee of an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't even admit what his attorneys have admitted for
him, that he misled the court,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, a Georgia
Republican who 13 months ago, before the Lewinsky affair became
public, called for Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Chabot, an Ohio Republican on the committee, said the
president's effort to woo undecided House members fell short. ``I
don't think this is going to get him off the hook at this late
date,'' Chabot said. ``It's not going to make a significant
difference to any members sitting on the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   When advance word of Clinton's latest mea culpa was whispered to
Judiciary Committee members, most of them hustled out of the
oak-panelled Room 2141 of the Rayburn Office Building and huddled
around television sets to watch the president.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the committee members shuffled back to their
seats in the room where, 24 years earlier, articles of impeachment
were approved to remove President Nixon for his role in the
Watergate scandal. Faced with a certain impeachment vote by the
full House and no support in the Senate, Nixon resigned a week
later.
</P>
<P>
   Much as their predecessors almost a quarter-century ago,
Judiciary Committee members Friday stared straight ahead, most with
no expression, as they responded joylessly when their names were
called by Shawn Friesen, the committee clerk two years out of
college.
</P>
<P>
   The audience sat quietly, reporters scribbled notes and
television cameras panned the committee room as each of the
Republicans responded ``aye'' and the Democrats called out ``no''
as the roll was called.
</P>
<P>
   Friesen counted the votes, then reported: ``Mr. Chairman, there
are 21 aye, 16 nay.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., looked around the room
and asked: ``Have all voted who wish to?'' There was no response.
The Illinois Republican rapped his gavel on the dais and called
out: ``Then Article 1 is agreed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The clock read 4:25 p.m. EST, and Clinton had been formally
accused by the committee of lying to a federal grand jury. The
charge stems from his Aug. 17 testimony before the panel, which was
being used by independent counsel Kenneth Starr to investigate the
president's affair with Lewinsky and attempt to keep it secret.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the committee voted again, and Article 2 was
approved. It accuses Clinton of lying during his Jan. 17 sworn
testimony in the Paula Jones lawsuit. The article of impeachment
was approved 20-17. Rep. Lindsey Graham, a South Carolina
Republican who long has opposed impeachment for lying in a civil
lawsuit, had sided with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   After another three hours of rancorous debate, the committee
approved Article 3 accusing Clinton of obstruction of justice by
allegedly interfering in the Jones lawsuit on several different
occasions. The vote was 21-16, again with all Republicans voting to
impeach and the Democrats voting against.
</P>
<P>
   Article 4, which the committee is scheduled to consider
Saturday, would accuse Clinton of abusing the power of his office
by making false statements to aides, his Cabinet and to the public.
The article also accuses him of misusing his executive privilege in
an effort to keep aides from cooperating with Starr's
investigation. Clinton also is accused in this article of making
false statements in response to inquiries from the Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Chabot said his vote to push for Clinton's removal was made
easier by his behavior. The president ``lied so many times in so
many forums it's really hard to keep track of it all,'' Chabot
said. ``For the children of this nation, this president has to be
impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   By passing the articles, the committee assured that the House _
for only the second time in U.S. history _ will vote on whether to
impeach the president. House members have been alerted by Speaker
Newt Gingrich to return to Washington by midweek to consider
impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   If the full House approves any of the articles recommended by
the Judiciary Committee, Clinton will join Reconstruction-era
President Andrew Johnson as the only chief executives to face
Senate trial on charges of ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' that
could lead to removal from office. Johnson's trial in 1868 ended
with his acquittal, and he continued as president until leaving
office in 1869.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling the prospect that the Senate could be asked to sit as
a jury, with Chief Justice William Rehnquist presiding, Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Minority Leader Thomas A.
Daschle, D-S.D., issued a rare joint statement saying they would
not make any comment ``unless and until the full House, by its
action, makes it clear that this body has a specific constitutional
duty to consider'' the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crucial week for the Clinton presidency and for the
Constitution,'' said Texas Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, one of the
president's most vocal defenders on the committee. ``Contrary to
the will of the American people, the House Republican impeachment
effort is moving ahead like a freight train.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, a California Democrat who whispered ``no''
each time the roll was called, read from a statement that began
with the explanation that she was ``of sound mind, excellent health
and a clear conscience.'' She went on, directing her remarks to her
grandchildren, mother and siblings ``living and dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters asked that history note that she fought against
impeachment. ``Let history treat me kindly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Delahunt, D-Mass., called the move toward
impeachment ``a capital case'' against Clinton. ``This case
involves the death penalty, politically speaking, for the executive
branch of government,'' Delahunt said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
