<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 2309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981211.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6300 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH12-COX     12-11 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 impeachment articles OK'd, go to the House
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman, Ken Foskett and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unswayed by another presidential plea for
forgiveness, the House Judiciary Committee recommended Friday that
President Clinton be removed from office for lying under oath and
obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared in the White House Rose Garden in a last-ditch
attempt to stave off impeachment through a public display of
penitence, saying he would accept ``rebuke and censure'' from the
Congress for his misconduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, at 4:26 p.m., he became the third president to be
charged with an impeachable offense. Somber committee members voted
an article of impeachment charging that he committed perjury in his
Aug. 17 testimony to a federal grand jury investigating his
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-16 vote, like most of the committee's work on
impeachment, was split strictly on party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday, the committee adopted two additional articles of
impeachment. Article 2, accusing Clinton of perjury in his
testimony in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, won
committee approval by a 20-17 vote. Rep. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.)
joined the Democrats in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The third article, passed by a 21-16 party-line vote, charged
that the president obstructed justice in the Jones case and the
grand jury investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will return today to its stately hearing room,
also the scene of impeachment proceedings against President Nixon
24 years ago. The panel will vote on a fourth article accusing
Clinton of abusing the powers of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also will present a proposed resolution of censure,
which the Republican majority is certain to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The House will meet Thursday to debate the impeachment articles,
according to Speaker Newt Gingrich, who is playing virtually no
role in the impeachment in his final weeks as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Livingston (R-La.), Gingrich's presumptive
successor, is waiting for the committee to complete its work before
making a decision about allowing a vote on censure, spokesman Mark
Corallo said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans were acutely aware of the gravity of
their proceedings Friday. They harked back frequently to the
proceedings against Nixon and, less often, to the impeachment of
Andrew Johnson, who was impeached in 1868 but survived his trial in
the Senate by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   While Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) called Friday's first votes
``historic,'' few Republicans appeared to find much joy in their
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am mindful that there are many qualities of Bill Clinton
that I admire, and of even greater significance, that the many
people of my state admire,'' said Rep. Asa Hutchinson (R-Ark.), who
hails from Clinton's home state of Arkansas. ``This is not a
pleasant experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Chabot (R-Ohio) said, ``He lied so many times in so
many forums it's really hard to keep track of it all. For the
children of this nation, this president has to be impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, on the other hand, expressed incredulity that
Clinton's sexual indiscretions would subject him to impeachment.
They complained bitterly that Republicans were accusing Clinton of
perjury without specifying exactly which statements amounted to
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   They insisted in vain that he could not be accused of perjury in
the Jones lawsuit because his statements were not material, meaning
they had nothing to do with the substance of Jones' allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides tried to place the proceedings in context. Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican, countered
Democratic criticisms that impeachment would overturn the results
of the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not reversing any election. Bob Dole will not end up
president of the United States if there is an impeachment,'' Hyde
said. ``We are following a process wisely set down as a check and
balance on executive overreaching, by our Founding Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who was the last to give his opening remarks before the
committee began debating the articles of impeachment, sought to
crystalize the issues before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lying under oath ``cheapens the oath. It is a breach
of promise to tell the truth. It subverts our system of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   He summarized the Democrats' position as the ``so what''
defense, accusing the minority of overlooking the seriousness of
the president's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Berman, a California Democrat, said he believes the
president lied under oath, even if Clinton has yet to say so.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Berman said, ``I don't believe this constitutes or rises
to the level of high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argued that the House is not voting to convict the
president, but merely to send the matter to the Senate, akin to the
proceedings of a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Clinton is impeached, the prospects for his conviction
by the Senate appear remote. It takes two-thirds of the Senate, or
67 senators, to remove the president from office. Republicans hold
55 seats to 45 for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) said the likelihood of Clinton's
acquittal in a Senate trial demonstrates that ``the Republicans are
using impeachment to censure the president because they know the
Senate won't vote him out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barr, exulting in the adoption of three articles late
Friday, said, ``The dynamics can change very quickly. When I first
brought this up a year ago, people said my chances for impeachment
were ... one in 9 million. Now look.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's last-minute apology, which stopped short of
conceding he lied under oath, failed to change any minds on the
committee, even among Republican members who said they were open to
anything new the president might have to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking ...for an admission that he violated the oath,''
Graham said. ``That did not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's a sincere apology, but it's not going to change my
view,'' said Ed Bryant (R-Tenn.).
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, (R-Texas), a strong Clinton
critic, was far less charitable, calling the speech ``an insult to
...the intelligence of all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to make yet another public show of
contrition, this one before his trip to the Middle East, reflected
a growing sense in Washington that he may well suffer the
humiliation of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Six previously undeclared Republicans, including Georgia
Republican Saxby Chambliss, announced their support for impeachment
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King (R-N.Y.), one of a handful of Republicans who
have said they will oppose impeachment, called Clinton's statement
a step in the right direction, but said he would need to do more to
attract uncommitted, mainly moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Charles Schumer of New York warned that the
momentum had swung in favor of impeachment in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that will stop impeachment is a strong reaction
from the American people,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats held out some hope of defeating the fourth article of
impeachment, the one alleging that Clinton abused his powers by
lying to his aides and asserting executive privilege for frivolous
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Pease(R-Ind.) who voted for the three articles,
expressed reservations about some of the other charges against
Clinton. ``Having reviewed and reviewed the material, I do not
believe that all of the allegations presented meet the standard of
being proven by 'clear and convincing evidence,''' Pease said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
