<SLUG> BC-FBC-WILLIAMS-HEISMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS EXPECTED TO CHALLENGE HEISMAN RECORD FOR VICTORY MARGIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ What the 64th Heisman Trophy presentation
lacks in drama, it could compensate with history.
</P>
<P>
   Texas senior running back Ricky Williams is the shoo-in favorite
to become the winner of college football's most prestigious award
in ceremonies tonight (6:30 p.m., ESPN) at New York's Downtown
Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who in his last game became NCAA Division I-A's most
prolific ground gainer, could break another record _ biggest
landslide by a Heisman winner. In 1968, Southern California running
back O.J. Simpson won the Heisman by 1,750 points, the largest
margin in the award's history.
</P>
<P>
   There are 920 Heisman voters _ media members plus all living
former winners. The media ballots are divided among six regions
(Northeast, Mid-Atlantic, Midwest, Far West, Southwest and South),
with 145 media voters in each region.
</P>
<P>
   The voters each list three players; first place is worth three
points, second worth two points and third is worth one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win, I think it would be a great end to my career,''
Williams said yesterday during a news conference in New York. ``I
think the thing that excites me the most about winning an award
like this is the fact that people are giving me credit for having
an impact on my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams could have applied for the NFL draft after last season,
but he returned for his senior season. He said he returned so he
could ``have fun and play football.'' He did that and more.
Williams rushed for 2,124 yards and led Texas to an 8-3 record and
a berth in the Cotton Bowl on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to possibly making history, Williams will be bucking
a recent trend if he wins the Heisman. Preseason favorites
typically don't wind up with the trophy. That happened last year
when Tennessee quarterback Peyton Manning lost to Michigan's
Charles Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for the front-runner to make it because
there are so many people that question it every day,'' Texas coach
Mack Brown said. ``The pressure is just so tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin and the UT campus became awash in Williams T-shirts and
bumper stickers. A song was written about him. And every day at
practice, a billboard on Interstate 35 loomed. It said ``Run,
Ricky, Run'' and kept a running countdown of his pursuit of Tony
Dorsett's career rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pressure about the Heisman at first,'' said
Williams, who set 16 NCAA and 40 school records in his four-year
career. ``Everyone was looking at you and every team was trying to
stop you. But as the season went on, I didn't think about it as
much. I just went out and played hard.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of evidence to safely assume Williams' Heisman
victory:
</P>
<P>
   A weekly poll of 10 Heisman voters conducted by the ``Rocky
Mountain News'' has Williams as the unanimous winner. Just 10
voters of 921, you say? This survey has picked the Heisman winner
each of the last 10 years _ including last season, when Woodson was
the surprise pick over Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has won the Maxwell and Walter Camp awards that are
given each year to college football's top player. Seven of the past
10 years, the winner of the Maxwell has won the Heisman. Nine of
the past 10 years, the winner of the Walter Camp has won the
Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists are quarterbacks _ UCLA's Cade McNown,
Kansas State's Michael Bishop and Kentucky's Tim Couch. The Heisman
has been won by a running back 37 times; quarterbacks have won it
18 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a tremendous injustice if Ricky Williams
doesn't win it,'' Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly deserving of the award,'' said Nebraska coach
Frank Solich, who recruited Mike Rozier, the 1983 Heisman winner.
Williams is ``a great, great football player. I'd be surprised if
he doesn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Williams' competitors for the award are readying concession
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty much over,'' said Couch, the only junior
among the finalists. ``I think they're going to give it to Williams
because he got the record, had a great year and a great career. I'm
just going to go enjoy it. This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity
to go meet these guys, go see New York and the Downtown Athletic
Club and have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps, become a witness to history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
