<HEADLINE>
TOP PITCHER MIGHT PICK TEAM TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The one big prize left from the free-agent
market could be awarded today at baseball's winter meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Scott Boras said yesterday that pitcher Kevin Brown is
close to making a decision on where he'll pitch next year.
Major-league officials said the Baltimore Orioles and Los Angeles
Dodgers appear to be the favorites, but Boras said none of the
teams that have shown interest have been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres, St. Louis Cardinals, Anaheim Angels and
Colorado Rockies are also pursuing Brown, who was 18-7 with a 2.38
earned-run average for the Padres this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and the Orioles are considered the favorites mainly
because they have the financial resources to meet Brown's contract
demands, and they have shown the ability to be competitive every
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Brown is a very special player in a very special market
for premium pitchers,'' Boras said. ``The desire for his services
is not surprising. Everybody knows the value of a No. 1 pitcher.
The premium is Kevin is a pitcher who has taken two good teams
\RFlorida and San Diego\S and put them in the World Series the past
two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras said Brown will definitely receive a six-year contract,
and a seventh guaranteed year is a possibility. That would likely
eliminate the Rockies and Padres, who have said they're not willing
to go that far.
</P>
<P>
   Boras refused to say if Brown would walk away from the
negotiations as the highest-paid player in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn enjoys that status with a
six-year, $80 million contract that averages $13.3 million per
season. Mets catcher Mike Piazza received the highest total package
when he agreed to a seven-year, $91 million deal in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of numbers floating around out there,'' Boras
said. ``We're talking about both the structure of the deal and the
length of the deal and also trying to get a solid definition of the
club's commitment to continue to bring in teammates that would
allow them to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras said he met with all six teams yesterday and has more
meetings scheduled today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had enough communications from teams where we're close
to a decision,'' Boras said.
\Ntagtop:T.R. Sullivan (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
