<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTORNEY-GENERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY IN GOP SAY VACCO SHOULD CONCEDE IN CONTESTED ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-VACCO-LAWYER) 
(bl)  
By JONATHAN P. HICKS   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ State Attorney General Dennis Vacco is coming under
increasing criticism from fellow Republicans as he continues his
fight over last month's election, and some are openly suggesting
that it is time for him to concede _ though he still has Staten
Island Borough President Guy Molinari in his corner _ and to
acknowledge his Democratic rival, Eliot Spitzer, as the next
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial returns show Spitzer with a seemingly insurmountable
lead of 26,000 votes over Vacco. But the Republican incumbent has
refused to concede. His campaign has maintained, among other
things, that tens of thousands of New York City voters cast ballots
illegally, and the campaign has filed lawsuits in state Supreme
Court asking that Vacco be named the winner or that the court
authorize a new election.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco's efforts have drawn sharp condemnation from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of Republican leaders, privately and
publicly, have started to complain that they consider Vacco's
approach to be excessive and that he is harming the image of the
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has gone on too long,'' state Sen. Michael Balboni, a
Republican of Mineola, said Friday. ``There are legitimate concerns
about voter eligibility in any large municipality, and about
rooting out any fraud. But, at this point, to go to this length is
troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   Balboni said that he considered Vacco to be ``a terrific
attorney general,'' but that ``the voters have said differently; he
should move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Several days ago, Gov. George Pataki, also a Republican,
distanced himself from an effort by the Vacco campaign to use New
York City police officers to conduct door-to-door investigations of
more than 103,000 homes in largely minority neighborhoods to
determine the eligibility of people whom the campaign suspected of
having voted fraudulently.
</P>
<P>
   And Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, another Republican, said he would
not order police participation without a court order, and a state
Supreme Court judge insisted that none was forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Board of Elections is scheduled to certify the
election results Tuesday. Monday, one day before the results are to
be certified, representatives of the two campaigns must return to
the state Supreme Court in Albany, and Vacco will be asked to
substantiate his charges of widespread voter fraud in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco's lawyers have contended that he has no plans to concede
and have hinted that the Republican incumbent may pursue further
legal action if Spitzer is certified by the Board of Elections as
the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for him to concede,'' said Molinari, a
Republican. ``No candidate in his right mind should abandon a legal
remedy because some people in the party think he should.''
</P>
<P>
   An upstate Republican mayor, Roy Bernardi of Syracuse, said he
understood how the closeness of the margin could be a source of
frustration to Vacco. ``But I think we need to move on and certify
the election,'' Bernardi said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Vacco campaign's pursuit of police officers to
investigate claims of voter fraud would have a detrimental effect
on the image of Republicans in black and Hispanic communities,
where Spitzer's lead was widest and where much of the investigation
would have been concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have evidence that irregularities are occurring, you
should check the entire system, not just certain neighborhoods,''
Bernardi said. ``The Republican Party needs to reach out more to
the Latino and African-American communities. And this is not
exactly a way to endear the party to those communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vacco's lawyers obtained an order from the state
Supreme Court to keep the offices of the New York City Board of
Elections open Saturday, to enable the campaign's lawyers and
volunteers to examine voter information in an effort to determine
whether voters had cast ballots illegally.
</P>
</TEXT>
