<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VACCO-LAWYER-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY GENERAL'S LAWYER HAS FOUGHT MANY BATTLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-ATTORNEY-GENERAL) 
(lb) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thomas Spargo, the lawyer representing Dennis Vacco,
a Republican, in his struggle to remain state attorney general, has
sometimes done battle with the very party that enlisted him in this
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Among the political figures who have retained Spargo, an expert
on election law, are Ross Perot, the independent presidential
candidate; Jerry Brown, the former governor of California and
sometime presidential contender; Karen Burstein, the Democrat who
ran against Vacco four years ago, and Thomas Golisano, the
Independence Party candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, Spargo succeeded in getting Steve Forbes a
spot on the New York state presidential primary ballot despite
strenuous opposition from supporters of Bob Dole, including Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Until a decade ago, Spargo, now 55, was known as a Republican
loyalist. For 15 years, he was counsel to the Republican State
Committee. That chapter in his life ended after he became a target
of a state commission that was investigating whether he helped
channel nearly $800,000 from a shopping-center developer, Pyramid
Co. of Syracuse, to candidates for the Poughkeepsie Town Board.
</P>
<P>
   From 1985 to 1989, Spargo sought to block the investigation by
filing a series of 16 lawsuits, said Peter Bienstock, who was the
executive director of the New York State Commission on Government
Integrity. Spargo agreed to testify before the commission only
after a judge ordered him arrested for contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   He was never charged with criminal wrongdoing, but the
investigation eventually forced him to give up the party position
and a second job as counsel to the State Senate Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became embarrassing for me and for the party to have its
counsel under this kind of attack,'' Spargo recalled. He said that
the commission took aim at him because of his long service to the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Spargo has been in the news because of Vacco's
continuing effort to challenge the results of the state attorney
general's race. Unofficial results placed Vacco more than 26,000
votes behind his Democratic rival, Eliot Spitzer, but in his latest
legal maneuver, the incumbent attorney general has maintained that
tens of thousands of votes in New York City were fraudulently cast.
</P>
<P>
   Bienstock said that Spargo's tactics in the Vacco case _ keeping
the case going with one legal challenge after another _ mirrored
the strategy he used more than a decade ago in the Poughkeepsie
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He advanced theory after theory after theory,'' Bienstock
said. ``He lost most of the litigation, but it all took time. He
knew that we had a finite life.'' Spargo, however, credits his
lawyers for developing the legal strategy for him.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his reputation as a relentless litigator, Spargo is
popular with other members of the small fraternity of lawyers with
expertise in the arcane New York state election laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an adversary, he's friendly, he's soft-spoken, and you can
rely on his word,'' said state Sen. Martin Connor, D-Brooklyn, a
lawyer for the Spitzer campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Harding, the chairman of the Liberal Party, hired Spargo
to handle Ms. Burstein's petition drive when she sought the
Democratic nomination for state attorney general in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have found him over the years to be exceedingly honorable
both professionally and personally,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Born in Rome, N.Y., Spargo is a former seminarian and army
paratrooper who now lives on a farm in the Albany County community
of East Berne, where he raises pigs and turkeys with his second
wife, MaryAnn Youngs. The couple are home-schooling their two young
children, ages 6 and 7. Spargo has three grown daughters from a
previous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Spargo's law office is about a half-mile away from the farm, in
a barnlike structure he built himself. Since election law is a
seasonal business, he also handles routine legal work like
real-estate closings and wills.
</P>
<P>
   He was not the first lawyer called to handle Vacco's
post-election efforts. Lawrence Mandelker, a New York election
specialist, headed the Republican team that monitored the recount
and the tally of paper ballots. But Mandelker has had nothing to do
with the subsequent legal challenges, prompting speculation in the
Spitzer camp that he was not happy with Vacco's decision to keep
the case going after the recount was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelker, however, said that he had been retained by the
Republican State Committee for the recount only and that Spargo was
Vacco's choice. He pointed out that the judge in the case, Thomas
Keegan of the state Supreme Court, sits in Albany, not far from
Spargo's home.
</P>
<P>
   But Spargo said he thought that Mandelker had dropped out
because of a conflict in his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   He denied another rumor, also spread by Democrats, that he was
trying to get back in the good graces of the Republican Party after
incurring its animosity during the Forbes campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It was much simpler than that, he said. ``They reached out to
me,'' he said, referring to the Vacco campaign, ``and I was
available.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
