r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-CARROLL-STEPHENVI     12-11 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-CARROLL-STEPHENVILLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING ON THE OFFENSIVE WITH FANCY-PASSING QBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Stephenville and Carroll meet today in
a Class 4A Division II high school football semifinal, expect a
wide-open contest. At least that is the safe prediction
Stephenville coach Art Briles made on his radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Briles has his own weekly radio half-hour, just like Chan
Gailey, and that isn't the only big-time feature of the Yellow
Jackets' program.
</P>
<P>
   Briles has constructed one of the most prolific offensive
attacks in Texas high school football history, with an imaginative
playbook including numerous formations and confusing variations.
And Carroll puts points on the board, too, so the meeting between
the traditional powerhouses at 5 p.m. today at Texas Stadium should
be particularly entertaining, unless your preferences lean toward
three yards and a cloud of dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be one heck of a shootout,'' Carroll coach Tom
Rapp agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville (13-1) advanced last week with a 42-21 victory
against Wichita Falls Hirschi. Carroll (13-1) defeated Highland
Park, 28-21. The winner will meet the La Marque-Smithson Valley
winner next week for the 4A Division II championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets' victory against Hirschi was the 11th time
this season they have scored 40 or more points in a game. Included
have been lopsided victories of 65-14 over Granbury, 63-0 over
Joshua, 58-0 over Burleson, 55-6 against Crowley and 50-6 over
Everman. Their only loss was, 40-35, to District 6-4A rival
Brownwood, which lost to Hirschi in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville is beating up on the record books, too.
</P>
<P>
   Senior quarterback Kelan Luker has thrown for 4,073 yards and 43
TDs. Luker is 403 yards away from the state single-season record of
4,476 passing yards set last year by Patrick Hutka of Class 2A
Rogers. Meanwhile, Luker's favorite target, senior end Cody
Cardwell, is logging gaudy numbers of his own. Of Cardwell's 92
receptions, 22 have been for touchdowns, and his 2,061 receiving
yards is a state record. Both are being recruited by SMU, Baylor
and Texas Tech, among other colleges.
</P>
<P>
   But the relentless Yellow Jackets aren't one-dimensional. They
come at you from every possible angle. Luker even caught a
touchdown pass this season. Almost lost in the shuffle is Zac
Hunter, but he shouldn't be. He has 1,526 yards rushing and
averages 11 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They run every formation you can think of,'' Rapp said. ``They
must sit down and draw up offenses when they don't have anything
else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding it all up, Stephenville's offense has gained 7,778 yards
this season _ a staggering 555 yards per game _ which is
threatening Sugar Land's all-time national record of 8,375 total
yards set in 12 games in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll still averages more yards rushing than passing, but Rapp
installed a new offense this year to take better advantage of the
arm of quarterback Nathan Chandler, who has thrown for 2,572 yards.
On the ground, Clay McNutt and runner-receiver Tye Strickland
provide a versatile one-two punch.
</P>
<P>
   McNutt has run for 1,637 yards, while Strickland has 61
receptions and combined rushing and receiving of 1,566 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough adjustment at first, because the offense was
totally new to us,'' Strickland said. ``But now that we're 15 weeks
into the season, we know it so well that when plays are called it's
almost like a reflex action.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has reached the 50-point mark twice this year, and seven
times has reached or exceeded 40 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two traditionally strong teams, and I don't think
either of us are where we're at by mistake,'' Stephenville's Briles
said. ``\RCarroll\S is the best offensive team we've faced this
year. I think it's going be a great game with a great atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   And what did Briles tell his radio audience?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody's going to ask for their money back,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
