<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MEETING-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds pick up Braves toss-out Avery
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Cast adrift after two years in Boston, Steve
Avery returned to the National League on Friday when the Cincinnati
Reds signed the ex-Braves left-hander to a one-year contract worth
up to $1.5 million. Now he can finally wreak revenge on an Atlanta
club that once gave up on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, I just want to take one of those guys deep. That's the
main thing,'' Avery said. ``I might start with (Tom) Glavine. Maybe
I could get all three of them, that would be cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds acted on the recommendation of pitching coach Don
Gullett, who has admired Avery for years. Avery was 10-7 with a
5.02 ERA last year with the Red Sox, but the club declined to pick
up his option and then refused to offer him arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gullett) really thinks he can take Steve and bring him back
to where he was back in his early Atlanta years,'' Cincinnati
general manager Jim Bowden said. ``We think he can get back to 15
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the Braves after the 1996 season, he was 16-13 in
Boston and was limited to 23 starts in 1998 due to a stint in the
minors. Avery, who will turn 29 next April, is destined for the
bottom of the rotation, which currently includes six pitchers.
After ex-Brave Denny Neagle, Pete Harnish and Brett Tomko, Avery
will compete with Dennis Reyes and Jason Bere for one of the final
two spots.
</P>
<P>
   His 1999 deal includes an extra $1 million in incentives by
starting between 20 and 35 games. The contract also includes a
mutual option for the 2000 season that includes a $1 million
buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Brown signing close
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown may have a new team today. Agent Scott Boras met
with Los Angeles general manager Kevin Malone and Baltimore GM
Frank Wren and reported five teams still in the running _ including
San Diego, St. Louis and Colorado _ had increased their offers to
six years. At a minimum $14 million asking price per year, Brown
could fetch a $98 million contract if a team is willing to go to
seven years on a 34-year-old pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty close to making a decision possibly as soon as
(today),'' Boras said.
</P>
<P>
   Boras also said, against much rumoring early in the process,
that the Braves not only never bid but never even inquired about
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Jones moving on
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Braves batting coach Clarence Jones, displaced in the
shuffling of the staff last month, has accepted a coaching job with
the Cleveland Indians. Though offered a spot as hitting coach with
Class AAA Richmond in the Braves organization, Jones took a spot as
outfield coach with the Indians, even though he spent his playing
career as a first baseman. He may wind up a first base coach, as
manager Mike Hargrove continues to arrange his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Inquiring of Hershiser
</P>
<P>
   Though the Braves has maintained their commitment to rookie
Bruce Chen as the newcomer to the rotation next year, the team has
sent out an inquiry to Orel Hershiser, who is still unsigned after
his contract with San Francisco expired. Hershiser, 40, was 11-10
as a Giant and worked 202 innings last year but allowed 200 hits
with a 4.41 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
