<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-11 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6328 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     12-11 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET, SHY DIMAGGIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio, who lay near death Friday night in a Miami-area
hospital, is one of the singular figures of the 20th century
without really trying. Imagine how big he could have been with the
slightest talent for self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   What if he'd had a flashy home run trot, traded forearm bashes
with Charlie Keller or worn his uniform socks differently from the
other Yankees? Then he might have REALLY been somebody.
</P>
<P>
   What if he'd shaved his head, tattooed his biceps or put a gold
stud in one ear? How cool would that have been? It might have been
worth millions to him. He might have gotten his own show on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about a cowboy hat and head-to-toe denim on road trips?
That would have been distinctive. They might have let him cut a
country album or plug a chewing tobacco. He'd have been a legend.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you almost never saw DiMaggio out of a suit and tie.
Who was his fashion coordinator, anyway? Very un-hip.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't one to spit on reporters, wasn't one to brush off
autograph seekers, wasn't one to speak his mind and say the hell
with anybody who didn't like it. That was his problem; he was
always so polite, never asserted his individuality like all the
great athletes today. How'd he expect to make Page 1 that way?
Maybe self-esteem was his problem.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, he never once came into The Jungle, loosened up and
traded gloss with Jim Rome. He totally kissed off the 18-to-35
demographic. Celebrity suicide is what that was.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with DiMaggio, if you want to sum it up, is that his
marriages lasted too long. Five years with Dorothy Arnold and one
year with Marilyn Monroe. These days, anything more than the two
days of Dennis Rodman and Carmen Electra, and the gossip columnists
won't lift a pencil. And as far as we know, he never borrowed one
of Marilyn's dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Guess he didn't want it badly enough. &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Which is the point about Joe DiMaggio, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   He didn't want it badly at all. He never enjoyed his celebrity
as much as the rest of us enjoyed his celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   And that, as we begin to look back, is what lifted the Hall of
Famer known mostly as ``The Yankee Clipper'' but sometimes as ``the
Big Guy'' above all the bad boys and poster boys of the sports
world.
</P>
<P>
   There were ``Mr. Coffee'' commercials and savings-and-loan
commercials and other TV appearances, small movie roles, a couple
of co-written books in the 1940s, golf-tournament and baseball
card-show appearances, and the annual first-ball tosses at Yankee
Stadium. And despite all that you knew, DiMaggio would have been
just as happy if nobody ever recognized him on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he was quoted saying, ``I want to be left
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, at age 84, he was in and out of a coma, fighting
pneumonia nearly two months after having a cancerous tumor removed
from his right lung.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, over the newswires crawled the written appreciations.
Most included the words ``dignity'' and ``grace,'' the DiMaggio
boilerplate. None included the words ``outrageous'' and
``controversial,'' the hallmarks of modern stardom.
</P>
<P>
   I love what Marilyn Monroe said in 1953, describing their first
date: ``He had no line at all. No jokes. He was rather shy and
reserved, but at the same time, warm and friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   I love what DiMaggio did when he was offered $2 million for an
autobiography: He said no, if it meant giving up the details of
their famous relationship.
</P>
<P>
   I love what DiMaggio said about the shyness that defined his
public behavior: ``I'm nervous if I have to make a speech in front
of 10 people.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the anti-Rodman. Thank God someone is.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lipsyte, in The New York Times, recently wrote about
interviewing DiMaggio casually at the Yankees' spring-training camp
in 1967. DiMaggio talked on and on, if only about the art of
judging fly balls. Lipsyte ``took no notes . . . barely breathed,
afraid to break the spell.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, that reminded me of my only contact with DiMaggio, when
he visited the Dodgers' camp in Vero Beach, Fla., about a decade
ago and sat down with writers in the press room.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable? You bet. Like meeting Muhammad Ali, Bill Shoemaker or
the President of the United States. Do I remember what we talked
about? No. And, a Daily News library search shows I wrote nothing
about the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio wasn't there to make headlines, so he said nothing of
news value. DiMaggio wasn't there to promote anything, least of all
himself.
</P>
<P>
   In a world of self-promoters and trendies and ``individuals,''
he stood out because he never tried to be any of those.
</P>
<P>
   Dignity and grace. It's a cliche we don't get to use often
enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
