<HEADER>
A6329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEBATE-2NDLD-     12-11 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEBATE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS AND REPUBLICANS ON PANEL ARE A UNIVERSE APART
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs last 5 grafs to add comments by Rothman, Frank; polishing and
tightening throughout.) (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-CLINTON,
IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-MOOD,
IMPEACH-BOUCHER, IMPEACH-GRAHAM, IMPEACH-AMBITION,
IMPEACH-NETWORKS, IMPEACH-MEDIA, EDIT-IMPEACH) 
(bl) 
By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To one set of lawmakers, the accusations against
President Clinton in the articles of impeachment were models of
coherence and sufficiently precise in detail.
</P>
<P>
   To the other, they were untenably vague word jumbles. ``You've
taken an article of impeachment,'' Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., told
his Republican colleagues, ``and made it a multiple choice test.''
</P>
<P>
   From one side of the aisle, President Clinton's actions fit
perfectly the high standard for impeachment set by the
Constitution. ``William Jefferson Clinton has thrown a gauntlet at
the feet of the Congress,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   From the other side, the charges against Clinton were so poorly
substantiated that the impeachment inquiry had descended ``almost
into the theater of the absurd,'' in the words of Rep. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans and Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee
bickered furiously Friday, studying the same facts and phrases to
draw opposite conclusions, they often seemed not merely to be
worlds apart, but to be occupying alternate universes.
</P>
<P>
   If a cow had lumbered into the hearing room, members of one
party might have called it a horse, members of the other a pig.
</P>
<P>
   But on one somber point, there was consensus. Both Republicans
and Democrats agreed, in grave voices and freighted words, that the
decisions before them were as important as any they would ever
make, and that history would sit in judgment of what they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote says something about us,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., the 74-year-old chairman of the committee. ``We vote for
our honor, which is the only thing we get to take with us to the
grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's hearing presented something of a paradox, colored as it
was by both an acknowledgment of the momentousness of the occasion
and by intense acrimony between Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   While members of both political parties summoned the memories of
famous leaders from George Washington and Daniel Webster to Winston
Churchill and Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., they drew starkly
different inspiration from those ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is a vote of conscience, and I believe it is, it is
going to come down to a Republican conscience versus a Democratic
conscience,'' said Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C. ``And I don't know
how to characterize that. I don't know what that means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suggest that one is not better than the other. I would
suggest that there is a very unique nature about this case that we
need to look at long after this case is over. And only time will
tell who got it right.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the four-hour debate over the first article of
impeachment, charging President Clinton with lying under oath about
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, that incited the most heated
crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   The central disagreement was somewhat technical, over whether
the first article should spell out each statement by Clinton that
Republicans believe constituted perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this, a shell game?'' Frank asked. ``I guess that's
the question _ under which pea is the impeachment? Is it under No.
1, or is it under No. 2, or maybe it's under 3 and 2, or 4 and 1,
or 2 and 3, and how are you going to defend it? I mean, I have to
say, the notion _ and I hope this doesn't go anywhere and I hope we
don't bog the country down _ but I'm almost intrigued here.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., responded:
``What I'm afraid the other side is trying to do is precisely what
they're accusing us of. The other side is trying to trivialize this
matter. And this is not a trivial matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're dealing with today is the fact that the president
of the United States engaged in a scheme, an elaborate scheme, to
lie and to get other people to lie and to hide evidence and get
other people to hide evidence in order to thwart the opportunity of
Paula Jones to bring her civil rights sexual harassment suit in
court and have it properly adjudicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., offered a theory for what she
characterized as her Republican colleagues' refusal to amend the
general language of the first article of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to get any specificity in any of these
referrals,'' Ms. Waters said, ``because the allegations are so
outrageous, so flimsy, so ridiculous, that they dare not put it in
writing, they dare not write it down, because they know that the
American people won't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after today, then all those who have been shopping since
Thanksgiving, all of those who thought that this was going to go
away, all of those who thought somehow it was going to be resolved,
will know exactly what has taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Republican majority on the committee passed the first
article of impeachment and debate proceeded to the second, the
divergence of opinion between Republicans and Democrats was equally
wide.
</P>
<P>
   While the first article charged Clinton with lying under oath to
a federal grand jury, the second concerned the deposition he gave
in Ms. Jones' civil lawsuit, which was initially dismissed, then
appealed and finally settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., said Clinton's denial of sexual
relations with Ms. Lewinsky in his deposition in response to Ms.
Jones' lawsuit did not represent perjury so much as ``the reaction
of a husband and father whose conduct was about to be exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., saw it as ``an act of
wrongdoing meant to deprive another American citizen of her rights
in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steven Rothman, D-N.J., appealed to the members of the
public to make their voices louder and clearer before it was too
late.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people must tell their representatives in
Congress if they don't think this president should be impeached,
because no reasonable burden of proving his guilt has been
established,'' Rothman said in a fiery voice. ``They must stop what
will be one of the saddest moments in American history from taking
place _ the removal of a sitting United States president on no _
with no reasonable proof.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the impassioned oratory were surprising moments
of levity, some of which sneaked up slyly and subtly. At one point
late into the night, when Hyde granted a request from Frank to
interrupt him, Frank said, ``I appreciate your swinging my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, as the familiar details of Clinton's interactions with
Ms. Lewinsky were hashed out anew, Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y.,
sarcastically derided a theory put forward by some investigators
that a stuffed bear Clinton gave Ms. Lewinsky had been a signal to
stand firm against questions about their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bear was a warning from the president that the
stock market was going to tank and she should put her money in
bonds,'' Nadler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-11-98 2353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
