u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-1STLD     12-11 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHISPERING LOUDLY IN EARS OF WAVERING REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Story rewritten throughout.)  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J., Ohio, N.Y., Ark., Calif., Wash., Ga., N.J.,
N.M., La.)  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON,
IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-MOOD,
IMPEACH-BOUCHER, IMPEACH-GRAHAM, IMPEACH-AMBITION,
IMPEACH-WHITEWATER, IMPEACH-MEDIA) 
(lb) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unfazed by the House Judiciary Committee's votes on
Friday, White House allies continued to lobby undeclared
rank-and-file Republicans to oppose impeachment next week on the
House floor, and many of the conflicted lawmakers voiced anguish
over the impending decision.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Geraldine Ferraro, the former congresswoman from
New York and vice presidential candidate, has contacted three House
Republicans _ Tillie Fowler of Florida, Marge Roukema of New Jersey
and Deborah Pryce of Ohio _ to sound out the views of Republican
women in Congress and to urge the lawmakers to oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked what I was thinking,'' Mrs. Fowler said in an
interview, ``and I told her I would vote for impeachment, and she
spent the next 15 minutes telling why that was the wrong decision.
She said it didn't amount to perjury and it wasn't an impeachable
offense. Then she said, a man is a man is a man, and said that
other presidents have done this kind of thing before.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House acknowledged it was deploying its allies in a
full-scale effort to avert impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly talking to friends around the country about
the importance of this matter and how the case that's been made by
the committee doesn't reach the standards of impeachment,'' Joe
Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the White House presses for a censure vote, presidential
aides have contacted 45 possibly wavering Republicans to help
explain the president's defense.
</P>
<P>
   But undeclared Republicans continued to wrestle with the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jay Dickey of Arkansas, the only Republican to vote against
the impeachment inquiry, is still undecided. But the phone calls,
e-mail messages and letters to his offices have intensified greatly
in the last three days, he said, and they run 3-to-1 for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Dickey said, the tone of callers has become much
more threatening. ``Before, people were calling to say, `This is my
opinion,''' he said. ``Now they're saying, `If you don't impeach
him, you'll get a primary challenge.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., who is retiring this year, is
leaning toward voting to impeach on at least the perjury charges.
But he said he had pulled back on his position after listening to
the debate in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's influenced me the most over the last 24 to 48 hours is
the notion that the vote to impeach is a vote to remove,'' Riggs
said. ``Prior to that, I was favorable to the view that impeachment
is censure. I've raised the bar. That's reinforced the gravity of
the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The resistance by House Republican leaders to permit a censure
vote complicates the White House's flat-out campaign to sway dozens
of Republican House moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have been adamant that the full House will
vote next week only on articles of impeachment, not on censure.
Rep. Tom DeLay, the Republican whip, fears that permitting a
censure option would siphon votes away from impeachment. The
leadership strategy is intended to pressure as many as three dozen
undecided Republicans to vote to impeach the president on at least
one count.
</P>
<P>
   It is conceivable that if impeachment failed, Robert Livingston,
the new speaker, would relent and permit a censure vote. But at
that point, with the president out of peril, Democrats who wanted
censure as an alternative might balk, and Republicans who believed
a censure was unconstitutional or a bad precedent would also oppose
it.
</P>
<P>
   The precise dimensions of a censure are still shifting. Several
Democrats and Republicans have discussed including a strong
condemnation of the president's actions, to be signed by Clinton,
and a fine.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win over Republicans, Clinton publicly
acknowledged for the first time on Friday that he would accept a
censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public consequences of my actions are in the hands of the
American people and their representatives in the Congress,''
Clinton said. ``Should they determine that my errors of word and
deed require their rebuke and censure, I am ready to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart refused to parry with reporters over what censure
language the president would accept. ``I'm not going to get into a
negotiating position from here at this podium,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Unmoved by the White House's defense of the president this week
and Clinton's statement, six undeclared Republicans _ Jack Metcalf
of Washington, Saxby Chambliss of Georgia, Ileana Ros-Lehtinen and
Lincoln Diaz-Balart, both of Florida, and Bob Franks and Rodney
Frelinghuysen, both of New Jersey _ announced Friday they would
vote to impeach the president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It is now clear that the president violated both his oath of
office and the oath he took to tell the truth,'' Frelinghuysen said
in a letter to constituents. ``In doing so, Bill Clinton not only
committed perjury, he violated the public trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz-Balart, who an aide said turned down a White House offer on
Thursday to speak to the White House counsel, Charles Ruff, said in
a statement, ``Failure to impeach President Clinton would do grave
harm to the integrity of the judicial system in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leadership aides said they expected two other
undeclared Republicans to announce their support for impeachment in
the next few days: Reps. Joe Skeen of New Mexico and Richard Baker
of Louisiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
