u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RICE-NYT &LR;      12-11 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE STILL PLAYS WELL BUT NO LONGER DOMINATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Steve Young, who will be in the Hall of Fame
with him, says nothing has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who thinks there still isn't greatness there is a
fool,'' the San Francisco quarterback said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mariucci, who has walked a tightrope coaching him, sees a
champion. ``I don't know if there has ever been a better competitor
to play this game,'' the 49ers' coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Owens, whose talent as a receiver may have surpassed his
celebrated teammate's, says there is no question who remains the
best. ``Everything I ever learned came from him,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing but admiration, respect and even awe for Jerry
Rice. But ask almost anyone in the National Football League,
especially on the 49ers, and there is an equally large dose of
carefully chosen words. No one wants to offend perhaps the greatest
receiver in football history. No one wants to state the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   It is this: Rice has become mortal. He is no longer Superman. He
no longer dominates a game or causes defensive coaches to have
sleepless nights.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that should be the end of the story; after all, football
players do age. But Rice, now 36, has not done so gracefully. He
admits that being forced to take a lesser role in an offense where
his name used to be called more times than not has been more
difficult to take than a hit from a 250-pound linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be the season I have to play a different role,''
Rice said recently, standing in the 49ers' locker room. ``You've
got to swallow deep and live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Rice is playing shows how great an athlete he is.
He damaged ligaments in his left knee at the beginning of last
season, which required surgery to repair. Then Rice defied
expectations and returned in December, only to severely damage the
knee again in his first game back.
</P>
<P>
   If Rice were not one of the game's most superbly conditioned
athletes _ his off-season workout program is legendary _
consecutive knee injuries could have ended his career. That
conditioning, as well as great physical skills and mental strength,
made him the focus of the 49ers' West Coast offense for years.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the current problem.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Rice is still an effective player, but
the team has been developing other offensive weapons. Garrison
Hearst has his second straight 1,000-yard rushing season. J.J.
Stokes is a solid possession receiver. Owens is the team's most
dangerous player, a great blend of size and speed. When the Giants
were preparing to play the 49ers earlier this season, they
considered Owens, not Rice, San Francisco's biggest threat.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, 49er officials maintain that it is better to spread
the ball around to all of their offensive stars than to have Rice
as the primary option.
</P>
<P>
   What has become apparent _ and hard to say because for some it
is painful to do so _ is that Rice no longer has the physical
skills to be the offensive focal point. That's because Rice can no
longer run free of coverage the way he once did. And he no longer
makes an abundance of what coaches call y.a.c. yards _ yards after
the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Once a game, Rice could run a 10-yard slant pattern and turn it
into a 60-yard touchdown. Those moments are rare now.
</P>
<P>
   None of this should be surprising, because it would take a
player in his 20s several years to recover from two surgeries on
the same knee.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is what happened during the Nov. 15 game against
Atlanta, when a Falcons player banged his helmet on Rice's other
knee, the healthy one. That has slowed him even more, and against
Carolina on Dec. 6, Rice had five catches for only 36 yards. Owens
and Stokes combined for eight catches for 106 yards and three
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   What has made Rice great throughout his career is his strong
will, as well as his belief that no one is better than he is. No
knee injury will change that, and Rice is not ready to concede
anything. That is what led to his verbal explosion after San
Francisco's 31-20 victory over New Orleans two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rice had three catches for 27 yards that game and was shut out
in the first half for the first time in six years. He was
occasionally used as the third receiver off the bench when the
49ers went to a two-receiver set with Stokes and Owens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just work here,'' he said after the game. ``If nothing is
asked of me, I guess I'm not going to do much. If you ask me if I'm
having a good time, no. Is this something that might make you
retire? Hell, yes. All I know is I'm not having a good time. Maybe
it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   What was puzzling about Rice's comments was that at the time, he
ledthe National Football Conference with 61 catches. According to
the 49ers' coaching statistics, Rice had 121 passes thrown his way
in the first 11 games. Owens and Stokes had 81 and 76,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Rice was blasted by sports columnists across the country for
being selfish. But he said recently: ``I have been around 14 years
and have always been a team player. Why can't I have my own opinion
without getting crucified?''
</P>
<P>
   Rice asked, ``I was unhappy about catching three balls, but who
wouldn't be, as a competitor?''
</P>
<P>
   Rice has complained in the past after games when he felt more
passes should have come his way. To the 49ers, that's as normal as
a fogged-in San Francisco bridge.
</P>
<P>
   After such complaints, more balls usually do go Rice's way in
the following game. But he had only three catches against the
Giants the week after that Saints game.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci and Rice spoke for about 30 minutes after the Saints
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of our conversation was to make sure we kept him
involved, but we also want to keep other guys involved,'' the coach
said. ``We want Jerry fresh for the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem Mariucci faced as a result of Rice's outburst was
this: If he capitulated to his receiver and immediately ordered
more passes thrown his way, it could have weakened him in the eyes
of other players. Mariucci had to take a stance for the good of his
team, which is 10-3 heading into Monday night's game against the
Detroit Lions and still battling for a division title.
</P>
<P>
   Where do things stand now? Rice is being a good citizen. After
other receivers make good catches in practices or games, Rice is
the first to congratulate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to enjoy myself, smile, watch these young guys
make plays and do what I can,'' Rice said. ``I don't want to lower
my standards, but I've got to enjoy football because its going to
end soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Giants, after Owens made a spectacular 79-yard
touchdown catch, Rice ran up to the muscular receiver, hugged him,
and said, ``I remember doing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
