<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-VOODOO-BURNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER CONSPIRACY ALLEGED IN VOODOO RITUAL BURNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A voodoo priest in New Jersey and two other people were indicted
Friday on charges that they conspired to kill a New York woman who
was burned in a religious ritual that she sought as a means of
driving away evil spirits, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Marie DeGraff, 30, of Uniondale, N.Y., a Haitian
immigrant who also uses the first name Sheila, was burned on her
head, face and neck in October 1997 when a cloth doused with a
flammable liquid was placed on her head and ignited, said Ray
Weiss, a spokesman for the Essex County prosecutor's office in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeGraff, a registered nurse and Haitian pop singer, was
hospitalized for three weeks in the burn unit at St. Barnabas
Medical Center in Livingston, N.J., where she received skin grafts,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The voodoo priest, Pierrot Charles, 41, of Irvington, N.J., and
Jean Valme, 36, of Brooklyn, N.Y., who was identified as the
victim's boyfriend, were charged with conspiracy to commit murder,
attempted murder, aggravated assault and criminal restraint, Weiss
said. Carolyn Destin, 39, identified by the authorities as Charles'
common-law wife, was charged with conspiracy to commit murder.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeGraff said last fall that her friends had convinced her
that noises she was hearing in her basement were her father's bad
spirits and that Charles could drive the spirits away. She went to
Irvington, a city with one of the largest populations of Haitian
immigrants in New Jersey, and underwent nine nights of prayer. On
the ninth night, she said, Charles covered her head and body with a
white sheet. Then she heard a whooshing noise and realized she was
on fire, she said. She was injured with second- and third-degree
burns.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges that Charles and Valme did not permit Ms.
DeGraff to seek treatment for the burns for 24 hours, Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment does not specify a motive for attempted murder,
and Weiss refused to elaborate. ``Until this gets to trial, that's
not something that we're at liberty to talk about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Steven Palamara of the Irvington police said he was
unaware of any motive behind the attempted murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   Charles' attorney, James Weinberg, said that's because there was
no motive. He said his client is innocent and that Ms. DeGraff, not
Charles, doused herself with the flammable liquid, a cologne known
as Florida Water that is used in voodoo rituals, and that she
accidentally set herself ablaze when she bumped into a candle.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Ms. DeGraff refused treatment immediately after the
incident, and that someone else finally called an ambulance the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeGraff did not respond to messages left at her home and on
her pager Friday. Attempts to reach Mr. Valme were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg said Ms. DeGraff has filed a civil suit claiming her
injuries were the result of negligence by Charles and Valme. He
said the criminal allegations were contrived to help her win a
settlement in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg also said prosecutors may have felt pressure to file
charges because the case attracted considerable attention and
because of negative connotations associated with voodoo, a mix of
African and Christian religious beliefs originally developed on
slave plantations in Haiti. Ms. DeGraff's lawyer in the civil suit,
Stuart Siegel, said there was no link between the criminal and
civil cases, other than that they stemmed from the same incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
