u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-FUND-INQUIRY-NYT &LR;      12-11 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FUND-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT LAKE OFFICIALS FACE QUERY INTO FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The disclosure of a scholarship fund in
Salt Lake City is generating considerable activity on the shores of
Lake Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Acting with uncommon urgency, the International Olympic
Committee formed a special commission on Friday to investigate
scholarship payments allegedly made to relatives of some IOC
members by Salt Lake City officials during their successful bid to
play host to the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The payments, categorized as a bribe by Mark Hodler, an IOC
member, were made through a privately financed $500,000 fund
beginning in 1991, the year Salt Lake City was beaten by Nagano,
Japan, in the bidding for the 1998 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The four-man ad hoc commission, whose chairman will be Richard
Pound, the IOC vice president, will consider the evidence and
attempt to deliver a ruling. No deadline has been set, but the
commission was already at work Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should say that the executive board takes this matter very
seriously,'' said Pound, a Canadian lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite many requests made in the past or evidence to support
rumors that have been floating around, we've never had anything
come forward,'' he added, in reference to rumblings of attempted
vote-buying by other Olympic cities and aspiring Olympic cities.
``Specific allegations have now been made, and as you can see, the
executive board has acted very quickly to investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound, who had yet to examine any of the related documents,
declined to comment on what action his commission might take. ``We
are not going to make any conclusions or any speculation until we
know what the facts are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Krimsky, the U.S. Olympic Committee deputy
secretary-general, said he believed stripping Salt Lake City of the
Games was ``not even a remote possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please understand that the organization of the Salt Lake
Olympic Committee today is a very different group than it was
during the bid,'' he said. ``There are a couple of carry-overs, but
this is not the same group.''
</P>
<P>
   One holdover is Frank Joklik, the SLOC president, who was
chairman of the executive committee when Salt Lake City
successfully bid in 1995. The bid-committee president, Tom Welch,
resigned from the Salt Lake committee last year.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik was called to a meeting with Juan Antonio Samaranch, the
IOC president, on Friday in Lausanne and furnished documents
relating to the case. ``We intend to be fully cooperative,'' Joklik
said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Joklik and David Johnson, senior vice
president of the Salt Lake committee, who was also part of the team
that bid for the games, met with Pound's new commission. The other
three commission members are Thomas Bach of Germany, Jacques Rogge
of Belgium and Judge Keba Mbaye of Senegal. They and Pound are
among the most influential members of the IOC
</P>
<P>
   The scholarship fund's alleged connection with IOC members was
disclosed by a television station in Salt Lake City two weeks ago.
On Tuesday, officials of the Salt Lake committee announced that 13
individuals were given scholarships or training grants during the
program that operated between 1991 and 1995, when Salt Lake City
was the overwhelming choice to be host to the 2002 Games. Of the 13
individuals who received assistance, six were related to IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   The only relative of an IOC member to have been identified is
Sonia Essomba, the daughter of Rene Essomba of Cameroon, who has
since died. Sonia Essomba was given money to attend American
University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik said earlier this week that the fund was established to
help offer educational and athletic training opportunities to those
from poorer countries. But he said some of those who received
assistance were probably from more privileged backgrounds than most
Africans. Rene Essomba was a prominent Cameroonian physician and
former secretary-general of the National Olympic Committees of
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already stated that I do not regard what was done as
bribery, even though I recognize that there have been perceptions
contrary to that,'' Joklik said Friday. ``I regret those
perceptions but don't feel they are justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Francois Carrard, the IOC director, said this was the most
significant case of alleged ethical misconduct before the committee
since Robert Helmick was accused of conflict of interest in 1991.
Helmick eventually resigned from the IOC and as president of the
U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
