<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NCAA-SEMIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOOSIERS ON BRINK OF FOURTH NATIONAL TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ind., Md.)  (rl) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Indiana was efficient. Stanford was
opportunistic. On Sunday they will play for the men's national
collegiate soccer championship.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana (22-2) set the tempo against Santa Clara in the first
minute Friday, pinning the Broncos in the penalty area. They
continued to dominate for the next 89 minutes and breezed to a 4-0
victory in the opener of the semifinals at the University of
Richmond. The Hoosiers will try to win their fourth title.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford (18-4-2) will try to win its first championship after
defeating Maryland, 1-0, on a fluke goal in the 39th minute. The
score came when Lee Morrison headed Jamie Clark's throw-in from the
left of the goal. A Maryland defender, Beckett Hollenbach, headed
it out but right back to Morrison, who headed the ball back toward
the goal. This time the ball hit the post and fell into the net as
Hollenbach was unable to block it.
</P>
<P>
   In five previous trips to the tournament, Stanford had not won a
game. Now it is in the final. Maryland (16-8) had the territorial
advantage for most of the game, taking 16 shots to Stanford's nine,
and was especially forceful in the second half, when a Maryland
goal was disallowed by the referee, Alex Yvahnenko, because Andy
Hemmerich fouled the Stanford goalkeeper, Adam Zapala.
</P>
<P>
   Judged by Friday's performance of the two finalists, the
Hoosiers must be considered the favorite in Sunday's championship
game, which will be broadcast by ESPN at 2 p.m. All four goals by
Indiana were well executed and delighted the crowd of 17,616.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksei Korol, the crafty striker from the Ukraine, led the
Hoosiers with two goals, with Dema Kovalenko, also from the
Ukraine, and Nick Garcia scoring once each in a game completely
dominated by Indiana, the champion in 1982, 1983 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the opposition was difficult to play against and we
were able to dictate the style,'' said Coach Jerry Yeagley of
Indiana, who avenged semifinal losses to Santa Clara in 1989 and
1991. ``This was our day.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Alexander, Santa Clara's goalkeeper, was hampered by a
right knee injury he suffered in the quarterfinal victory over St.
John's last Saturday, and had to wear a brace.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very focused and we were tentative,'' he said. ``I
don't want to use my knee as an excuse, but we were on our heels
from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mitch Murray of Santa Clara apparently felt Alexander was
probably better on one leg than his backup, Rusty Johnson, who had
played only six minutes all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goalkeeper was not the problem,'' Murray said. ``We
retreated too much and we were not stepping up to the ball. They
physically intimidated us and they're good technically.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hoosiers displayed plenty of skill in all parts of the
field. They varied their attack and exhibited effective finishing
primarily because of Korol, who scored both goals in last Sunday's
elimination of Clemson, which entered the tournament as the
top-seeded team.
</P>
<P>
   Korol scored the first goal in the 20th minute, when he stepped
onto a rebound from a shot by Kovalenko and beat Alexander from 15
yards. Garcia gave the Hoosiers a two-goal lead just over three
minutes later from 16 yards away before Korol scored his second,
five minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalenko's goal with 12 minutes remaining was the first time
Santa Clara (15-5-2) had allowed four goals in a game in six years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
